WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.000
Blackstone Audio presents

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:30.000
UBIC by Philip K. Dick

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:34.000
or Tony Boucher

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:38.000
1.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:43.840
Friends, this is cleanup time and we're discounting all our silent electric UBICs by this

00:00:43.840 --> 00:00:49.600
much money. Yes, we're throwing away the blue book and remember every UBIC on our lot has been used

00:00:49.600 --> 00:00:52.640
only as directed.

00:00:52.640 --> 00:00:59.920
At 3.30 a.m. on the night of June 5, 1992, the top telepath in the Sol system fell off the map

00:00:59.920 --> 00:01:06.080
in the offices of Runciter Associates in New York City. That started vid-phones ringing.

00:01:06.080 --> 00:01:11.760
The Runciter organization had lost track of too many of Hollis's size during the last two months.

00:01:11.760 --> 00:01:15.280
This added disappearance wouldn't do.

00:01:15.280 --> 00:01:20.320
Mr. Runciter, sorry to bother you. The technician in charge of the night shift at the map-room

00:01:20.320 --> 00:01:26.480
coughed nervously as the massive sloppy head of Glenn Runciter swam up to fill the vid-screen.

00:01:27.280 --> 00:01:33.040
We got this news from one of our inersals. Let me look. He fiddled with the disarranged stack

00:01:33.040 --> 00:01:39.040
of tapes from the recorder which monitored incoming messages. Our Miss Dorn reported it.

00:01:39.120 --> 00:01:42.240
As you may recall, she had followed him to Green River, Utah, where...

00:01:43.200 --> 00:01:45.120
sleepily, Runciter grated,

00:01:45.760 --> 00:01:51.920
Who? I can't keep in mind at all times which inersals are following what teap or precog.

00:01:52.640 --> 00:01:56.320
With his hand he smoothed down his ruffled gray mass of wire-like hair,

00:01:56.960 --> 00:02:00.480
skipped the rest and told me which of Hollis's people is missing now.

00:02:01.200 --> 00:02:04.160
Est dole Malapone, the technician said.

00:02:04.160 --> 00:02:07.280
What? Malapone's gone. You kid me.

00:02:07.280 --> 00:02:13.280
I not kid you, the technician assured him. Eddie Dorn and two other inersals followed

00:02:13.280 --> 00:02:19.760
him to a motel named the Bonds of Erotic Polymorphic Experience, a 60-unit subsurface

00:02:19.760 --> 00:02:23.920
structure catering to businessmen and their hookers who don't want to be entertained.

00:02:24.480 --> 00:02:28.720
Edie and her colleagues didn't think he was active, but just beyond the safe side,

00:02:28.720 --> 00:02:32.960
we had one of our own telepaths, Mr. G.G. Ashwood, go in and read him.

00:02:33.920 --> 00:02:37.440
Ashwood found a scramble pattern surrounding Malapone's mind,

00:02:38.240 --> 00:02:42.960
so he couldn't do anything. He therefore went back to Topeka, Kansas,

00:02:42.960 --> 00:02:49.280
where he's currently scouting a new possibility. Runciter, more awake now, had lit a cigarette.

00:02:49.280 --> 00:02:54.480
Chin in hand, he sat propped up somberly, smoke drifting across the scanner of his

00:02:54.480 --> 00:03:00.880
end of the bi-channel circuit. You're sure the teap was Malapone? Nobody seems to know what he looks

00:03:00.880 --> 00:03:06.000
like. He must use a different physiognomic template every month. What about his field?

00:03:06.640 --> 00:03:10.400
We asked Joe Chipp to go in there and run tests on the magnitude and

00:03:10.400 --> 00:03:15.680
minitude of the field being generated there at the Bonds of Erotic Polymorphic Experience Motel.

00:03:16.320 --> 00:03:22.560
Chipp says it registered at its height 68.2 BLR units of telepathic aura,

00:03:23.120 --> 00:03:29.040
which only Malapone, among all known telepaths, can produce. The technician finished,

00:03:29.040 --> 00:03:35.840
so that's where we stuck Malapone's ident flag on the map, and now he—it—is gone.

00:03:36.960 --> 00:03:42.800
Did you look on the floor behind the map? It's gone electronically. The man it represents

00:03:42.800 --> 00:03:47.440
is no longer on Earth, or as far as we can make out on a colony world, either.

00:03:48.320 --> 00:03:54.560
Runciter said, I'll consult my dead wife. It's the middle of the night. The moratoriums are closed

00:03:54.640 --> 00:04:01.680
now—not in Switzerland, Runciter said, with a grimacing smile, as if some repellent midnight

00:04:01.680 --> 00:04:07.360
fluid had crept up into his aged throat. Good eve, Runciter hung up.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:15.360
As owner of the beloved brethren moratorium, Herbert Schoenheit von Vogelsang, of course,

00:04:15.360 --> 00:04:21.280
perpetually came to work before his employees. At this moment, with the chilly, echoing building

00:04:21.280 --> 00:04:26.960
just beginning to stir, a worried-looking clerical individual with nearly opaque glasses and wearing

00:04:26.960 --> 00:04:32.240
a tabby-fur blazer and pointed yellow shoes waited at the reception counter, a claim-check

00:04:32.240 --> 00:04:38.640
stub in his hand. Obviously he had shown up to holiday-greeter relative. Resurrection day,

00:04:38.640 --> 00:04:43.920
the holiday on which half-lifers were publicly honoured, lay just around the corner. The rush

00:04:43.920 --> 00:04:50.320
would soon be beginning. Yes, sir, Herbert said to him with an affable smile.

00:04:50.320 --> 00:04:55.360
I'll take your stub personally. It's an elderly lady, the customer said, about 80,

00:04:55.360 --> 00:05:01.360
very small and whiz-ent, my grandmother. Till only be a moment. Herbert made his way back to the

00:05:01.360 --> 00:05:08.640
coal-pack bins to search out number 3054039B. When he located the correct party, he scrutinised the

00:05:08.640 --> 00:05:16.400
lading report attached. It gave only fifteen days of half-life remaining. Not very much, he reflected.

00:05:16.960 --> 00:05:22.000
Automatically he pressed a portable photo-phazon amplifier into the transparent plastic hull

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:27.760
of the casket, tuned it, listened at the proper frequency for indication of cephalic activity.

00:05:28.400 --> 00:05:30.800
Faintly, from the speaker, a voice said,

00:05:31.360 --> 00:05:38.080
And then Tillie sprained her ankle, and we never thought it'd heal. She was so foolish about it,

00:05:38.080 --> 00:05:44.720
wanted to start walking immediately. Satisfied, he unplugged the amplifier and located the union

00:05:44.720 --> 00:05:51.200
man to perform the actual task of carting 3054039B to the consultation lounge,

00:05:51.760 --> 00:05:54.640
where the customer would be put in touch with the old lady.

00:05:55.360 --> 00:05:59.840
You checked her out, did you? The customer asked as he paid the post-grad's due.

00:06:00.480 --> 00:06:06.080
Personally, Herbert answered, functioning perfectly. He kicked a series of switches,

00:06:06.080 --> 00:06:10.080
then stepped back. Happy resurrection, day, sir. Thank you.

00:06:11.040 --> 00:06:16.320
The customer seated himself facing the casket which steamed in its envelope of cold-pack.

00:06:16.880 --> 00:06:21.520
He pressed an earphone against the side of his head and spoke firmly into the microphone.

00:06:22.240 --> 00:06:26.960
Flora, dear, can you hear me? I think I can hear you already. Flora?

00:06:27.840 --> 00:06:31.680
When I pass, Herbert Shohenheidt von Vogelsang said to himself,

00:06:32.240 --> 00:06:38.560
I think I'll reel my ears to revive me one day a century, that way I can observe the fate of all

00:06:38.560 --> 00:06:45.200
mankind. But that meant a rather high maintenance cost to the heirs, and he knew what that meant.

00:06:45.200 --> 00:06:51.040
Sooner or later they would rebel, have his body taken out of cold-pack, and, God forbid, buried.

00:06:51.920 --> 00:06:57.920
Periel is barbaric, Herbert muttered aloud, remnant of the primitive origins of our culture.

00:06:58.560 --> 00:07:05.520
Yes, sir, his secretary agreed at her typewriter. In the consultation lounge, several customers

00:07:05.600 --> 00:07:11.760
now communed with their half-lifer relations, enwrapped quiet, distributed at intervals each

00:07:11.760 --> 00:07:18.320
with his separate casket. It was a tranquil sight, these faithfuls, coming as they did so regularly

00:07:18.320 --> 00:07:24.240
to pay homage. They brought messages, news of what took place in the outside world. They cheered

00:07:24.240 --> 00:07:31.680
the gloomy half-lifers in these intervals of cerebral activity, and they paid, Herbert Shohenheidt

00:07:31.680 --> 00:07:36.640
von Vogelsang. It was a profitable business, operating a moratorium.

00:07:37.760 --> 00:07:42.880
My dad seems a little frail, a young man said, catching Herbert's attention. I wonder if you

00:07:42.880 --> 00:07:48.480
could take a moment of your time to check him over. I'd really appreciate it. Certainly, Herbert said,

00:07:49.040 --> 00:07:55.040
accompanying the customer across the lounge to his deceased relative. The lading for this one

00:07:55.040 --> 00:08:01.120
showed only a few days remaining. That explained the vitiated quality of celebration. But still,

00:08:01.680 --> 00:08:06.160
he turned up the gain of the proto-phazon amplifier, and the voice from the half-lifer

00:08:06.160 --> 00:08:11.440
became a trifle stronger in the earphone. He's almost at an end, Herbert thought.

00:08:12.160 --> 00:08:18.080
It seemed obvious to him that the son did not want to see the lading, did not actually care to know

00:08:18.080 --> 00:08:24.320
that contact with his dad was diminishing, finally. So, Herbert said nothing. He merely walked off,

00:08:24.320 --> 00:08:29.520
leaving the son to commune. Why tell him that this was probably the last time he would come here?

00:08:30.080 --> 00:08:32.320
He would find out soon enough in any case.

00:08:34.320 --> 00:08:38.720
A truck had now appeared at the loading platform at the rear of the moratorium.

00:08:38.720 --> 00:08:42.720
Two men hopped down from it, wearing familiar pale blue uniforms,

00:08:42.720 --> 00:08:48.000
Atlas interplanetary van and storage, Herbert perceived, delivering another half-lifer who had

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:54.640
just now passed, or here to pick up one which had expired. Lesually, he started in that direction

00:08:54.640 --> 00:08:59.600
to supervise. At that moment, however, his secretary called to him, here, Sean Hight van

00:08:59.600 --> 00:09:04.480
Vogelsang, sorry to break into your meditation, but a customer wishes you to assist in revving up

00:09:04.480 --> 00:09:13.360
his relative. Her voice took on special coloration, as she said. The customer is Mr. Glenn Rumseter,

00:09:13.360 --> 00:09:15.920
all the way here from the North American Confederation.

00:09:16.160 --> 00:09:22.400
A tall elderly man with large hands and a quick, sprightly stride came toward him.

00:09:23.120 --> 00:09:26.480
He wore a very colored Dacron wash and wear suit,

00:09:26.480 --> 00:09:32.960
knit cummerbund, and dip-died cheesecloth cravat. His head, massive like a Tomcat's,

00:09:32.960 --> 00:09:38.320
thrust forward as he peered through slightly protruding, round and warm and highly alert eyes.

00:09:39.200 --> 00:09:43.280
Rumseter kept on his face a professional expression of greeting,

00:09:43.280 --> 00:09:49.840
a fast attentiveness which fixed on Herbert, then almost once strayed past him as if Rumseter

00:09:49.840 --> 00:09:56.080
had already fastened on to future matters. How is Ella? Rumseter boomed, sounding as if he possessed

00:09:56.080 --> 00:10:01.440
a voice electronically augmented, ready to be cranked up for a talk. She's only twenty,

00:10:01.440 --> 00:10:06.880
she ought to be in better shape than you or me. He chuckled, but it had an abstract quality.

00:10:07.440 --> 00:10:15.520
He always smiled and he always chuckled. His voice always boomed, but inside he did not notice

00:10:15.520 --> 00:10:22.880
anyone did not care. It was his body which smiled, nodded and shook hands. Nothing touched his mind,

00:10:22.880 --> 00:10:29.120
which remained remote. A luke but amiable, he propelled Herbert along with him, sweeping his way

00:10:29.120 --> 00:10:34.320
in great strides back into the chilled bins where the half-lifers, including his wife, lay.

00:10:34.720 --> 00:10:40.960
You have not been here for some time, Mr. Rumseter, Herbert pointed out. He could not recall the data

00:10:40.960 --> 00:10:47.360
on Mrs. Rumseter's lading sheet, how much half-life she retained. Rumseter, his wide, flat hand,

00:10:47.360 --> 00:10:50.480
pressing against Herbert's back to urge him along, said,

00:10:50.480 --> 00:10:56.640
This is a moment of importance, one vocal sang. We, my associates and myself, are in a line of

00:10:56.640 --> 00:11:03.360
business that surpasses all rational understanding. I'm not at liberty to make disclosures that this

00:11:03.360 --> 00:11:10.480
time, but we consider matters at present to be ominous, but not, however, hopeless. Despair is

00:11:10.480 --> 00:11:16.080
not indicated, not by any means. Where's Ella? He halted, glanced rapidly about.

00:11:16.080 --> 00:11:22.320
I bring her from the bin to the consultation lounge for you, Herbert said. Customers should

00:11:22.320 --> 00:11:27.280
not be here in the bins. Do you have your numbered claim checked, Mr. Rumseter?

00:11:27.360 --> 00:11:28.000
Mr. Rumseter?

00:11:28.480 --> 00:11:34.320
God no, Rumseter said. I lost it months ago. But you know who my wife is, you can find her.

00:11:34.320 --> 00:11:39.600
Ella Rumseter, about twenty. Brown hair and eyes. He looked around him impatiently.

00:11:40.160 --> 00:11:43.360
Where did you put the lounge? It used to be located where I could find it.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:48.720
Show Mr. Rumseter to the consultation lounge, Herbert said to one of his employees,

00:11:48.720 --> 00:11:53.760
who had come meandering by, curious to see what the world-renowned owner of an anti-sci

00:11:53.760 --> 00:11:58.720
organization looked like. Peering into the lounge, Rumseter said with a version,

00:11:58.720 --> 00:12:04.160
It's fall! I can't talk to Ella in there. He strode after Herbert, who had made for the

00:12:04.160 --> 00:12:10.400
moratorium's files. Mr. Van Vogel sang, he said, overtaking him, and once more dropping his big

00:12:10.400 --> 00:12:16.000
paw onto the man's shoulder. Herbert felt the weight of the hand, its persuading vigor.

00:12:16.560 --> 00:12:22.640
Isn't there a more private sanctum sanctorum for confidential communications? What I have to discuss

00:12:22.640 --> 00:12:27.920
with Ella, my wife, is not a matter which we at Rumseter Associates are ready at this time to

00:12:27.920 --> 00:12:34.000
reveal to the world. Caught up in the urgency of Rumseter's voice and presence, Herbert found

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:40.400
himself readily mumbling, I can make Mrs. Rumseter available to you in one of our offices, sir.

00:12:41.360 --> 00:12:46.880
He wondered what had happened. What pressure had forced Rumseter out of his belly-wick

00:12:46.880 --> 00:12:51.200
to make this belated pilgrimage to the beloved brethren moratorium to

00:12:51.280 --> 00:12:58.000
crank up, as Rumseter crudely phrased it, his half-life or wife, a business crisis of some

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:04.000
sort, he theorized. Ads over TV and in the homeopapes by the various anti-sci prudence

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:10.080
establishments had shrilly squawked their harangues of late. Defend your privacy, the ads

00:13:10.080 --> 00:13:16.160
yammered on the hour from all media. Is the stranger tuning in on you? Are you really alone?

00:13:17.120 --> 00:13:21.120
That for the telepaths, and then the queasy worry about precogs.

00:13:21.760 --> 00:13:26.960
Are your actions being predicted by someone you never met, someone you would not want to meet

00:13:26.960 --> 00:13:32.960
or invite into your home? Terminate anxiety. Contacting your nearest prudence organization

00:13:32.960 --> 00:13:38.080
will first tell you if, in fact, you are the victim of unauthorized intrusions, and then,

00:13:38.080 --> 00:13:42.240
on your instructions, nullify these intrusions at moderate cost to you.

00:13:42.480 --> 00:13:49.840
Prudence organizations. He liked the term. It had dignity, and it was accurate. He knew this

00:13:49.840 --> 00:13:55.200
from personal experience. Two years ago a telepath had infiltrated his moratorium staff,

00:13:55.760 --> 00:14:01.360
for reasons which he had never discovered, to monitor confidences between half-lifers and

00:14:01.360 --> 00:14:08.240
their visitors, probably. Perhaps those are one specific half-lifer. Anyhow, a scout from one of

00:14:08.240 --> 00:14:12.960
the anti-Sci organizations had picked up the telepathic field and he had been notified.

00:14:13.600 --> 00:14:18.960
Upon his signing of a work contract, an anti-telepath had been dispatched, had installed

00:14:18.960 --> 00:14:25.600
himself on the moratorium premises. The telepath had not been located, but it had been nullified,

00:14:25.600 --> 00:14:31.680
exactly as the TV ads promised. And so, eventually, the defeated telepath had gone away.

00:14:32.240 --> 00:14:38.320
The moratorium was now scy-free, and to be sure it stayed so, the anti-Sci Prudence

00:14:38.320 --> 00:14:42.080
organization surveyed his establishment routinely once a month.

00:14:43.040 --> 00:14:48.320
Thanks very much, Mr. Vogelsang, runs to the said, following Herbert through an outer office in which

00:14:48.320 --> 00:14:54.080
clerks worked, to an empty inner room that smelled of drab and unnecessary micro-documents.

00:14:55.120 --> 00:15:00.960
Of course, Herbert thought musingly to himself, and took their word for it that a telepath got in

00:15:00.960 --> 00:15:07.120
here. They showed me a graph they had obtained, citing it as proof. Maybe they faked it,

00:15:07.120 --> 00:15:12.240
made up the graph in their own labs, and I took their word for it that the telepath left.

00:15:12.240 --> 00:15:18.400
He came, he left, and I paid two thousand post-crets. Could the Prudence organizations be,

00:15:18.400 --> 00:15:25.360
in fact, rackets, claiming a need for their services, when sometimes no need actually exists?

00:15:26.320 --> 00:15:29.760
Pondering this, he set off in the direction of the files once more.

00:15:30.400 --> 00:15:34.400
This time, Runciter did not follow him. Instead, he thrashed about,

00:15:34.400 --> 00:15:41.360
noisily making his big frame comfortable in terms of a meager chair. Runciter sighed,

00:15:41.360 --> 00:15:46.080
and it seemed to Herbert suddenly that the massively built old man was tired,

00:15:46.080 --> 00:15:48.240
despite his customary show of energy.

00:15:49.200 --> 00:15:56.160
I guess when you get up into that bracket, Herbert decided, you have to act in a certain way.

00:15:56.160 --> 00:16:00.160
You have to appear more than a human with merely ordinary failings.

00:16:00.800 --> 00:16:07.200
Probably, Runciter's body contained a dozen artefogs, artificial organs grafted into place

00:16:07.200 --> 00:16:14.160
in his physiological apparatus, as the genuine original ones failed. Medical science, he conjectured,

00:16:14.160 --> 00:16:20.160
supplies the material groundwork, and out of the authority of his mind, Runciter supplies the

00:16:20.160 --> 00:16:27.520
remainder. I wonder how old he is, he wondered. Impossible any more to tell by looks, especially

00:16:27.520 --> 00:16:28.320
after ninety.

00:16:29.600 --> 00:16:36.160
A Miss Beeson, he instructed his secretary, have Mrs. Ella Runciter located, and bring me the

00:16:36.160 --> 00:16:42.720
ident number. She is to be taken to Office 2A. He seated himself across from her, busied himself

00:16:42.720 --> 00:16:49.120
with a pinch or two of Fryborg and Trier Prince's snuff, as Miss Beeson began the relatively simple

00:16:49.120 --> 00:16:51.920
job of tracking down Glen Runciter's wife.

00:16:55.040 --> 00:17:00.160
2. The best way to ask for beer is to sing out

00:17:00.160 --> 00:17:06.960
U-BIC, made from select hops, choice water, slow aged for perfect flavour. U-BIC is the nation's

00:17:06.960 --> 00:17:10.720
number one choice in beer, made only in Cleveland.

00:17:12.960 --> 00:17:19.680
Upright in her transparent casket, encased in an effluvium of icy mist, Ella Runciter lay with her

00:17:19.680 --> 00:17:26.880
eyes shut, her hands lifted permanently toward her impassive face. It had been three years since he

00:17:26.880 --> 00:17:33.520
had seen Ella, and of course she had not changed, she never would now, at least not in the outward

00:17:33.600 --> 00:17:40.640
physical way, but with each resuscitation into active half-life, into a return of cerebral activity,

00:17:40.640 --> 00:17:49.120
however short, Ella died somewhat. The remaining time left to her pulse-phased out and ebbed.

00:17:50.400 --> 00:17:56.320
Knowledge of this underwrote his failure to rev her up more often. He rationalized this way,

00:17:56.320 --> 00:18:03.440
that it doomed her, that to activate her constituted a sin against her. As to her own

00:18:03.440 --> 00:18:09.520
stated wishes before her death and in early half-life encounters, this had become handily

00:18:09.520 --> 00:18:15.440
nebulous in his mind. Anyway, he would know better, being four times as old as she.

00:18:16.240 --> 00:18:22.960
What had she wished? To continue to function with him as co-owner of Runciter Associates,

00:18:23.520 --> 00:18:30.400
something vague on that order. Well, he had granted this wish. Now, for example, and six or seven

00:18:30.400 --> 00:18:35.760
times in the past, he did consult her at each crisis of the organization, he was doing so at this

00:18:35.760 --> 00:18:42.480
moment. Damn this earphone arrangement! He grumbled as he fitted the plastic disc against the side

00:18:42.480 --> 00:18:50.400
of his head, and this microphone, all impediments to natural communication. He felt impatient and

00:18:50.400 --> 00:18:55.840
uncomfortable as he shifted about on the inadequate chair which Vogelsang, or whatever his name was,

00:18:55.840 --> 00:19:02.000
had provided him. He watched her rev back into sentience and wished she would hurry, and then

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:08.080
in panic he thought, maybe she isn't going to make it, maybe she's worn out and they didn't tell me,

00:19:08.080 --> 00:19:13.440
or they don't know. Maybe he thought out to get that Vogelsang creature in here to explain,

00:19:13.440 --> 00:19:20.480
maybe something terrible is wrong. Ella, pretty and light-skinned, her eyes, in the days when

00:19:20.480 --> 00:19:27.360
they had been open, had been bright and luminous blue. That would not again occur. He could talk to

00:19:27.360 --> 00:19:32.560
her and hear her answer, he could communicate with her, but he would never again see her with eyes

00:19:32.560 --> 00:19:40.080
opened, nor would her mouth move. She would not smile at his arrival. When he departed, she would not

00:19:40.080 --> 00:19:47.760
cry. Is this worth it, he asked himself? Is this better than the old way, the direct road from

00:19:47.760 --> 00:19:54.480
full life to the grave? I still do have her with me, in a sense, he decided. The alternative

00:19:55.040 --> 00:20:05.120
is nothing. In the earphone, words slow and uncertain form, circular thoughts of no importance,

00:20:05.200 --> 00:20:12.240
fragments of the mysterious dream which she now dwelt in. How did it feel he wondered to be in

00:20:12.240 --> 00:20:18.800
Half-Life? He could never fathom it from what Ella had told him, the basis of it, the experience of

00:20:18.800 --> 00:20:25.760
it couldn't really be transmitted. Gravity, she had told him once, it begins not to affect you,

00:20:25.760 --> 00:20:32.160
and you float more and more. When Half-Life is over, she had said, I think you float out of the

00:20:32.160 --> 00:20:39.360
system, out into the stars. But she did not know either, she only wondered and conjectured,

00:20:39.360 --> 00:20:43.360
she did not however seem afraid, or unhappy, he felt glad of that.

00:20:44.880 --> 00:20:52.960
Hi, Ella, he said clumsily into the microphone. Oh, her answer came, in his ear, she seemed startled,

00:20:53.520 --> 00:20:58.400
and yet, of course, her face remained stable, nothing showed. He looked away.

00:20:58.560 --> 00:21:05.360
Hello, Glenn. She said, with a sort of childish wonder, surprised, taken aback to find him here.

00:21:06.240 --> 00:21:08.000
What? She hesitated.

00:21:08.880 --> 00:21:10.320
How much time has passed?

00:21:11.200 --> 00:21:12.720
Couple years, he said.

00:21:13.600 --> 00:21:14.880
Tell me what's going on.

00:21:15.920 --> 00:21:22.240
Ah, Christ, he said, everything's going to pieces, the whole organization. That's why I'm here,

00:21:22.240 --> 00:21:27.680
you wanted to be brought into major policy planning decisions, and God knows we need that now,

00:21:27.680 --> 00:21:31.840
a new policy, or anyhow, a revamping of our scout structure.

00:21:32.640 --> 00:21:41.680
I was dreaming, Ella said. I saw a smoky red light, a horrible light, and yet I kept

00:21:41.680 --> 00:21:43.840
moving toward it, I couldn't stop.

00:21:44.720 --> 00:21:46.960
Yeah, Runsiter said, nodding.

00:21:46.960 --> 00:21:52.400
The bardo told all, the Tibetan Book of the Dead tells about that. You remember reading that,

00:21:52.400 --> 00:21:55.600
the doctors made you read it when you were—he hesitated.

00:21:56.400 --> 00:21:58.000
Dying, he said then.

00:21:58.880 --> 00:22:02.240
The smoky red light is bad, isn't it? Ella said.

00:22:03.120 --> 00:22:06.880
Yeah, you want to avoid it. He cleared his throat.

00:22:07.840 --> 00:22:13.280
Listen, Ella, we've got problems. You feel up to hearing about it? I mean, I don't want to

00:22:13.280 --> 00:22:17.360
over-tact you or anything. Just say, if you're too tired, or if there's something else you

00:22:17.360 --> 00:22:18.800
want to hear about or discuss.

00:22:19.360 --> 00:22:24.800
It's so weird. I think I've been dreaming all this time since you last talked to me.

00:22:25.600 --> 00:22:32.560
Is it really two years? Do you know, Glen, what I think? I think that other people who are around

00:22:32.560 --> 00:22:39.680
me, we seem to be progressively growing together. A lot of my dreams aren't about me at all.

00:22:40.400 --> 00:22:48.240
Sometimes I'm a man, and sometimes a little boy. Sometimes I'm an old fat woman with varicose veins,

00:22:48.880 --> 00:22:52.800
and I'm in places I've never seen doing things that make no sense.

00:22:52.960 --> 00:22:59.280
Well, like they say, you're heading for a new womb to be born out of. And that smoky red light,

00:22:59.280 --> 00:23:04.960
that's a bad womb. You don't want to go that way. That's a humiliating low sort of womb.

00:23:04.960 --> 00:23:09.600
You're probably anticipating your next life for whatever it is.

00:23:09.600 --> 00:23:15.360
He felt foolish talking like this. Normally he had no theological convictions,

00:23:15.360 --> 00:23:20.960
but the half-life experience was real, and it had made theologians out of all of them.

00:23:23.120 --> 00:23:26.640
Hey, he said, changing the subject. Let me tell you what's happened,

00:23:26.640 --> 00:23:32.160
what made me come here and bother you. Estol Melopone has dropped out of sight.

00:23:33.520 --> 00:23:40.240
A moment of silence, and then Ella laughed. Ha! Who or what is an Estol Melopone?

00:23:40.960 --> 00:23:47.840
There can't be any such thing. The laugh, the unique and familiar warmth of it made his spine

00:23:47.840 --> 00:23:55.040
tremble. He remembered that about her, even after so many years. He had not heard Ella's laugh

00:23:55.040 --> 00:24:03.120
in over a decade. Maybe you've forgotten, he said. Ella said, I haven't forgotten.

00:24:03.120 --> 00:24:08.080
I wouldn't forget an Estol Melopone. Ha! Is it like a Hobbit?

00:24:09.040 --> 00:24:14.720
It's Raymond Hollis's top telepath. We've had at least one inertial sticking close to him ever

00:24:14.720 --> 00:24:20.880
since G.G. Ashwood first scouted him a year and a half ago. We never lose Melopone. We can't afford

00:24:20.880 --> 00:24:27.200
to. Melopone can, when necessary, generate twice the scyfield of any other Hollis employee.

00:24:27.760 --> 00:24:31.360
And Melopone is only one of a whole string of Hollis people who've disappeared.

00:24:32.480 --> 00:24:37.600
Anyhow, disappeared as far as we're concerned. As far as all prudent organizations in the

00:24:37.600 --> 00:24:43.680
society can make out. So I thought, hell, I'll go ask Ella what's up and what we should do.

00:24:43.680 --> 00:24:50.080
Like you specified in your will, remember? I remember. But she sounded remote.

00:24:51.040 --> 00:24:56.080
Step up your ads on TV. Warn people. Tell them.

00:24:57.760 --> 00:25:00.000
Her voice trailed off into silence then.

00:25:01.600 --> 00:25:05.920
This bores you, Runceter said gloomily. No, I—

00:25:07.040 --> 00:25:10.000
She hesitated and he felt her once more drift away.

00:25:10.240 --> 00:25:15.440
Are they all telepaths? She asked after an interval.

00:25:16.400 --> 00:25:22.080
Telepaths and precogs, mostly. They're nowhere on earth. I know that. We've got a dozen

00:25:22.080 --> 00:25:26.880
inactive inertials with nothing to do because the size they've been nullifying aren't around.

00:25:27.520 --> 00:25:32.240
And what worries me even more, a lot more, is that requests for anti-size have dropped,

00:25:32.880 --> 00:25:36.400
which you would expect, given the fact that so many size are missing.

00:25:36.400 --> 00:25:42.320
But I know they're on one single project. I mean, I believe. Anyhow, I'm sure of it.

00:25:42.320 --> 00:25:47.840
Somebody's hired the bunch of them, but only Hollis knows who it is or where it is,

00:25:47.840 --> 00:25:51.840
or what it's all about. He lapsed into brooding silence then.

00:25:53.760 --> 00:25:58.640
How would Ella be able to help him figure it out, he asked himself, stuck here in this casket,

00:25:58.640 --> 00:26:01.840
frozen out of the world? She knew only what he told her.

00:26:02.080 --> 00:26:11.040
Yet he had always relied on her sagacity, that particular female form of it, a wisdom not

00:26:11.040 --> 00:26:17.920
based on knowledge or experience, but on something innate. He had not during the period she had lived

00:26:17.920 --> 00:26:23.600
been able to fathom it. He certainly could not do so now that she lay in chilled immobility.

00:26:24.400 --> 00:26:30.560
Other women he had known, since her death, there had been several, had a little of a trace amounts,

00:26:30.560 --> 00:26:37.920
perhaps, intimations of a greater potentiality which in them never emerged as it had in Ella.

00:26:39.040 --> 00:26:43.760
Tell me, Ella said, what this melapone person is like?

00:26:44.720 --> 00:26:45.680
A screwball.

00:26:46.480 --> 00:26:53.200
Working for money or out of conviction. I always feel wary about that, when they have that sigh

00:26:53.200 --> 00:27:00.480
mystique, that sense of purpose and cosmic identity, like that awful Serapis had. Remember him?

00:27:01.600 --> 00:27:07.360
Serapis isn't around anymore. Hollis allegedly bumped him off because he connived to set up

00:27:07.360 --> 00:27:12.240
his own outfit and competition with Hollis. One of his pre-cogs tipped Hollis off.

00:27:13.120 --> 00:27:19.440
He added, melapone is much tougher on us than Serapis was. When he's hot, it takes three

00:27:19.520 --> 00:27:25.440
inertials to balance his field, and there's no profit in that. We collect, or did collect,

00:27:25.440 --> 00:27:31.680
the same fee we get with one inertial. Because the society has a rate schedule now, which we're bound by.

00:27:32.400 --> 00:27:38.400
He liked the society less each year. It had become a chronic obsession with him. Its uselessness,

00:27:38.400 --> 00:27:45.680
its cost, its vain glory. As near as we can tell, melapone is a money sigh. Does that make you feel

00:27:45.680 --> 00:27:50.880
better? Is that less bad? He waited, but heard no response from her.

00:27:51.920 --> 00:28:02.720
Ella? He said. Silence. Nervously, he said, Hey, hello there, Ella. Can you hear me? Is something wrong?

00:28:03.440 --> 00:28:11.040
Oh, God, he thought she's gone. A pause, and then thoughts materialized in his right ear.

00:28:11.040 --> 00:28:18.400
My name is Jory. Not Ella's thoughts, a different Elan, more vital and yet clumsier,

00:28:18.400 --> 00:28:19.840
without her deft subtlety.

00:28:20.720 --> 00:28:25.120
Get off the line, Runceter said in panic. I was talking to my wife, Ella. Where'd you come from?

00:28:25.760 --> 00:28:31.200
I am Jory, the thoughts came, and no one talks to me. I'd like to visit with you a while, Mr.,

00:28:31.200 --> 00:28:35.040
if that's okay with you. What's your name? Stammering, Runceter said.

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:41.840
I want my wife, Mrs. Ella Runceter. I paid to talk to her, and that's who I want to talk to, not you.

00:28:42.400 --> 00:28:47.280
I know Mrs. Runceter. The thoughts clanged in his ear, much stronger now. She talks to me,

00:28:47.280 --> 00:28:52.400
but it isn't the same as somebody like you talking to me, somebody in the world. Mrs. Runceter is here

00:28:52.400 --> 00:28:58.720
where we are. Doesn't count, because she doesn't know any more than we do. What year is it, Mr.?

00:28:58.720 --> 00:29:03.360
Did they send that big ship to Proxima? I'm very interested in that. Maybe you can tell me.

00:29:03.360 --> 00:29:05.920
And if you want, I can tell Mrs. Runceter later on, okay?

00:29:07.200 --> 00:29:12.400
Runceter popped the plug from his ear, hurriedly set down the earphone and the rest of the gadgetry.

00:29:12.400 --> 00:29:18.400
He left the stale, dust-saturated office and roamed about among the chilling caskets row after row,

00:29:18.400 --> 00:29:24.160
all of them neatly arranged by number. Moratorium employees swam up before him and then vanished

00:29:24.160 --> 00:29:29.680
as he churned on, searching for the owner. Is something the matter, Mr.? Runceter?

00:29:29.760 --> 00:29:33.760
The Von Vogel Sang person said, observing him as he floundered about,

00:29:33.760 --> 00:29:40.720
can I assist you? I got some thing coming in over the wire, Runceter panted, halting,

00:29:40.720 --> 00:29:46.160
instead of Ella. Damn you guys and your shoddy business practices! This shouldn't happen. And

00:29:46.160 --> 00:29:51.280
what does it mean? He followed after the moratorium owner who had already started in the direction

00:29:51.280 --> 00:29:57.680
of Office 2A. If I ran my business this way, did the individual identify himself?

00:29:57.680 --> 00:30:03.360
Yeah, he called himself Jory. Frowning with obvious worry, Von Vogel Sang said,

00:30:03.920 --> 00:30:10.480
that would be Jory Miller. I believe he's located next to your wife in the bin. But I can see it's Ella.

00:30:11.520 --> 00:30:18.560
After prolonged proximity, Von Vogel Sang explained, there is occasionally a mutual osmosis,

00:30:18.560 --> 00:30:25.680
a suffusion between the mentalities of half-lifers. Jory Miller's cephalic activity is particularly

00:30:25.680 --> 00:30:32.400
good. Your wife's is not. That makes for an unfortunately one-way passage of protophasons.

00:30:33.040 --> 00:30:38.960
Can you correct it? Runceter asked hoarsely. He found himself still, spent still, panting and

00:30:38.960 --> 00:30:46.560
shaking. Get that thing out of my wife's mind and get her back. That's your job! Von Vogel

00:30:46.560 --> 00:30:54.080
Sang said in a stilted voice, if this condition persists, your money will be returned to you.

00:30:54.080 --> 00:30:59.840
Who cares about the money? Snot the money! They had reached Office 2A now. Runceter

00:30:59.840 --> 00:31:04.240
unsteadily reseeded himself, his heart laboring so that he could hardly speak.

00:31:04.800 --> 00:31:09.680
If you don't get this Jory person off the line, he half gasped, half snarled,

00:31:09.680 --> 00:31:16.320
I'll sue you! I'll close down this place! Facing the casket Von Vogel Sang pressed the

00:31:16.320 --> 00:31:23.120
audio outlet into his ear and spoke briskly into the microphone. Fees out, Jory. That's a good boy.

00:31:24.080 --> 00:31:29.680
Glancing at Runceter, he said, Jory passed at fifteen. That's why he has so much vitality.

00:31:30.320 --> 00:31:35.120
Actually, this has happened before. Jory has shown up several times where he shouldn't be.

00:31:36.080 --> 00:31:42.800
Once more into the microphone, he said, This is very unfair of you, Jory. Mr. Runceter has come

00:31:42.800 --> 00:31:47.920
a long way to talk to his wife. Don't gem her signal, Jory. That's not nice.

00:31:48.880 --> 00:31:55.200
Appaulon says he listened to the earphone. I know her signal is weak. Again he listened,

00:31:55.200 --> 00:31:59.520
solemn and frog-like. Then removed the earphone and rose to his feet.

00:32:00.400 --> 00:32:04.480
What did he say? Runceter demanded. Will he get out of there and let me talk to Ella?

00:32:05.200 --> 00:32:12.480
Von Vogel Sang said, There's nothing Jory can do. Think of two AM radio transmitters,

00:32:12.480 --> 00:32:19.120
one close by but limited to only five hundred watts of operating power, then another far off,

00:32:19.120 --> 00:32:24.240
but on the same or nearly the same frequency and utilizing five thousand watts.

00:32:25.360 --> 00:32:34.000
When night comes and night, Runceter said, has come, at least for Ella, and maybe himself as well,

00:32:34.560 --> 00:32:40.400
if Hollis' missing teeps, paracinetists, precogs, resurrectors, and animators couldn't be found.

00:32:41.200 --> 00:32:48.160
He had not only lost Ella, he had also lost her advice, Jory having supplanted her before she could

00:32:48.160 --> 00:32:54.960
give it. When we return her to the bin, Von Vogel Sang was blabbing, we won't install her near Jory

00:32:54.960 --> 00:33:01.680
again. In fact, if you are agreeable as to paying the somewhat larger monthly fee, we can place her

00:33:01.680 --> 00:33:08.160
in a high-grade isolated chamber with walls coated and reinforced with Teflon 26 so as to

00:33:08.160 --> 00:33:15.200
inhibit hetero-psychic infusion from Jory or anybody else. Isn't it too late?

00:33:15.200 --> 00:33:19.920
Runceter said, surfacing momentarily from the depression into which this happening had dropped

00:33:19.920 --> 00:33:28.160
him. She may return. Once Jory phases out, plus anyone else who may have gotten into her because

00:33:28.160 --> 00:33:34.320
of her weak in state, she's accessible to almost anyone. Von Vogel Sang chewed his lip palpably

00:33:34.320 --> 00:33:42.720
pondering. She may not like being isolated, Mr. Runceter. We keep the containers, the caskets,

00:33:42.720 --> 00:33:47.680
as they're called by the lay public, close together for a reason, wandering through one

00:33:47.680 --> 00:33:54.240
another's mind, gives those in half-life the only, put her in solitary right now, Runceter broke in.

00:33:54.240 --> 00:34:00.400
Better she be isolated than not exist at all. She exists, Von Vogel Sang corrected.

00:34:00.400 --> 00:34:04.960
She merely can't contact you. There's a difference. Runceter said,

00:34:04.960 --> 00:34:07.680
a metaphysical difference which means nothing to me.

00:34:08.240 --> 00:34:14.880
I will put her in isolation, Von Vogel Sang said, but I think you're right. It's too late.

00:34:15.680 --> 00:34:24.560
Jory has permeated her permanently to some extent, at least I'm sorry. Runceter said harshly, so am I.

00:34:28.080 --> 00:34:28.400
3.

00:34:30.560 --> 00:34:35.280
Instant, you, Bick, has all the fresh flavor of just-brewed drip coffee. Your husband will say,

00:34:35.280 --> 00:34:42.320
Christ, Sally, I used to think your coffee was only so-so, but now, wow! safe when taken as directed.

00:34:44.400 --> 00:34:50.960
Still in gray, pinstripe clown-style pajamas, Joe Chip hazily seated himself at his kitchen table,

00:34:50.960 --> 00:34:55.760
lit a cigarette, and after inserting a dime, twiddled the dial of his recently-rented

00:34:55.760 --> 00:35:02.720
paper machine. Having a hangover, he dialed off interplan news, hovered momentarily at domestic

00:35:02.720 --> 00:35:05.120
news, and then selected gossip.

00:35:06.480 --> 00:35:10.080
Yes, sir, the paper machine said heartily, gossip! Guess what,

00:35:10.080 --> 00:35:14.880
Stanton mech the reclusive interplanetary known speculator and financier is up to it this very

00:35:14.880 --> 00:35:21.680
moment. Its works whizzed, and a scroll of printed matter crept from its slot. The ejected roll,

00:35:21.680 --> 00:35:27.040
a document in four colors, niftly incised with bold type, rolled across the surface of the

00:35:27.040 --> 00:35:34.240
Neoteakwood table and bounced to the floor. His head aching, Chip retrieved it, spread it out flat

00:35:34.240 --> 00:35:42.240
before him. Mick hits World Bank for two-trill, AP London. What could Stanton mech the reclusive

00:35:42.240 --> 00:35:48.400
interplanetarily known speculator and financier be up to? The business community asked itself,

00:35:48.400 --> 00:35:52.960
as rumor leaked out of Whitehall that the dashing but peculiar industrial magnet,

00:35:52.960 --> 00:35:58.080
who once offered to build free of charge a fleet by which Israel could colonize and make fertile

00:35:58.080 --> 00:36:05.120
otherwise desert areas of Mars, had asked for and may possibly receive a staggering and unprecedented

00:36:05.120 --> 00:36:11.680
loan of— This isn't gossip, Joe Chip said to the paper machine. This is speculation about

00:36:11.680 --> 00:36:17.120
fiscal transactions. Today I want to read about which TV star is sleeping with whose drug-addicted

00:36:17.120 --> 00:36:23.360
wife. He had, as usual, not slept well, at least in terms of REM, Rapid Eye Movement Sleep,

00:36:23.920 --> 00:36:30.960
and he had resisted taking a sapirific because, very unfortunately, his week's supply of stimulants

00:36:30.960 --> 00:36:37.600
provided him by the autonomic pharmacy of his Conap building had run out—due, admittedly,

00:36:37.600 --> 00:36:44.240
to his own oral greed, but nonetheless gone. By law he could not approach the pharmacy for more,

00:36:44.800 --> 00:36:51.200
until next Tuesday, two days away, two long days. The paper machine said,

00:36:51.760 --> 00:36:57.760
set the dial for low gossip. He did so, and a second scroll excreted by the paper machine

00:36:57.760 --> 00:37:04.640
without delay emerged. He zombed in on an excellent caricature drawing of Lola Hertzberg writes,

00:37:04.640 --> 00:37:09.840
licked his lips with satisfaction at the naughty exposure of her entire right ear,

00:37:09.840 --> 00:37:15.360
then feasted on the text. Acosted by a cut purse in a fancy New York After Hours

00:37:15.360 --> 00:37:19.920
mowl the other night, Lola Hertzberg, right, bounced a swift right jab off the chops of

00:37:19.920 --> 00:37:24.800
the do-batter, which sent him reeling onto the table where King Egon groat of Sweden,

00:37:24.800 --> 00:37:31.520
and an unidentified miss with astonishingly large—the ring construct of his Conap door jangled.

00:37:32.160 --> 00:37:37.280
Startled, Joe Chip glanced up, found his cigarette attempting to burn the Formica surface of his

00:37:37.280 --> 00:37:42.800
Neoteakwood table, coped with that, then shuffled blearily to the speak tube mounted

00:37:42.800 --> 00:37:48.720
handily by the release bolt of the door. Who is it? he grumbled, checking with his wrist what

00:37:48.720 --> 00:37:55.600
she saw that eight o'clock had not arrived. Probably the rent, robot, he decided, or a creditor.

00:37:56.320 --> 00:38:02.160
He did not trigger off the release bolt of the door. An enthusiastic male voice from the door's

00:38:02.160 --> 00:38:07.120
speaker exclaimed, I know it's early, Joe, but I just hit town. GG Ashwood here. I've got a firm

00:38:07.120 --> 00:38:12.160
prospect that I snared in Topeka. I read this one as magnificent, and I want your confirmation

00:38:12.160 --> 00:38:16.640
before I lay the pitch in Runciter's lap. Anyhow, he's in Switzerland. Chip said,

00:38:17.440 --> 00:38:22.160
I don't have my test equipment in the apt. I'll shoot over to the shop and pick it up for you.

00:38:22.160 --> 00:38:29.600
It's not at the shop. Reluctantly, he admitted, it's in my car. I didn't get around to unloading

00:38:29.600 --> 00:38:35.440
it last night. In actuality, he had been too puzzled on Parapot to get the trunk of his hovercar

00:38:35.440 --> 00:38:42.720
open. Can it wait until after nine, he asked irritably. GG Ashwood's unstable, manic energy

00:38:42.720 --> 00:38:49.280
annoyed him even at noon. This, at seven forty, struck him as downright impossible, worse even

00:38:49.280 --> 00:38:54.400
than a creditor. Chip, dearie, this is a sweet number, a walking symposium of miracles that

00:38:54.400 --> 00:38:58.400
will curl the needles of your gauges and in addition give new life to the firm which it

00:38:58.400 --> 00:39:04.320
badly needs. And furthermore, it's an anti-watt, Joe Chip asked. Telepath?

00:39:04.880 --> 00:39:10.960
I'll lay it on you right out in front, GG Ashwood declared. I don't know. Listen, Chip, Ashwood

00:39:10.960 --> 00:39:15.920
lowered his voice. This is confidential, this particular one. I can't stand down here at the

00:39:15.920 --> 00:39:20.320
gate, gum-flapping away out loud. Somebody might overhear. In fact, I'm already picking up the

00:39:20.320 --> 00:39:26.000
thoughts of some gluque in a ground level apt. He— Okay, Joe Chip said, resigned.

00:39:26.720 --> 00:39:32.000
Once started, GG Ashwood's relentless monologues couldn't be aborted anyhow. He might as well

00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:38.240
listen to it. Give me five minutes to get dressed and find out if I've got any coffee left in the

00:39:38.240 --> 00:39:45.440
apt anywhere. He had a quasi-memory of shopping last night at the con-app supermarket. In particular,

00:39:45.440 --> 00:39:53.200
a memory of tearing out a green ration stamp, which could mean either coffee or tea or cigarettes or

00:39:53.200 --> 00:39:59.520
fancy imported snuff. You'll like her, GG Ashwood stated energetically, although as often happened,

00:39:59.520 --> 00:40:07.120
she's the daughter of a—her. In alarm, Joe Chip said, my apt's unfit to be seen. I'm behind in my

00:40:07.120 --> 00:40:12.320
payments to the building cleanup robots. They haven't been inside here in two weeks. I'll ask her if

00:40:12.320 --> 00:40:18.720
she cares. Don't ask her, I care. I'll test her out down at the shop on Runs at Her's Time.

00:40:19.280 --> 00:40:24.800
I read her mind and she doesn't care. How old is she? Maybe he thought she's only a child.

00:40:25.440 --> 00:40:29.920
Quite a few new and potential inertials were children, having developed their ability in

00:40:29.920 --> 00:40:35.840
order to protect themselves against their psionic parents. How old are you, dear? GG Ashwood asked

00:40:35.840 --> 00:40:41.520
faintly, turning his head away to speak to the person with him. Nineteen, he reported to Joe Chip.

00:40:42.480 --> 00:40:49.920
Well, I shot that. But now he had become curious. GG Ashwood's razzle-dazzle wound up tightness

00:40:49.920 --> 00:40:55.680
usually manifested itself in conjunction with attractive women. Maybe this girl fell into that

00:40:55.680 --> 00:41:03.440
category. Give me fifteen minutes, he told GG. If he worked fast and scoked about in a cleanup

00:41:03.440 --> 00:41:08.720
campaign, and if he missed both coffee and breakfast, he could probably affect a tidy apt by then.

00:41:09.280 --> 00:41:15.200
At least it seemed worth trying. He rang off, then searched in the cupboards of the kitchen for a

00:41:15.200 --> 00:41:21.760
broom, manual, or self-powered, or vacuum cleaner, helium battery, or wall socket. Neither could be

00:41:21.760 --> 00:41:27.280
found. Evidently he had never been issued any sort of cleaning equipment by the building supply

00:41:27.280 --> 00:41:32.800
agency. Hell of a time he thought to find that out. And he had lived here four years.

00:41:33.760 --> 00:41:38.560
Picking up the vid-phone, he dialed two fourteen, the extension for the maintenance circuit of the

00:41:38.560 --> 00:41:45.840
building. Listen, he said, when the homeostatic entity answered, I'm now in a position to divert

00:41:45.840 --> 00:41:51.280
some of my funds in the direction of settling my bill vis-a-vis your cleanup robots. I'd like

00:41:51.280 --> 00:41:55.680
them up here right now to go over my apt. I'll pay the full and entire bill when they're finished.

00:41:56.240 --> 00:41:59.760
Sir, you'll pay your full and entire bill before they start.

00:42:01.040 --> 00:42:06.560
By now he had his billfold in hand. From it he dumped his supply of magic credit keys,

00:42:06.560 --> 00:42:12.480
most of which by now had been voided, probably in perpetuity, his relationship with money and

00:42:12.480 --> 00:42:18.400
the payment of pressing debts being such as it was. I'll charge my overdue bill against my

00:42:18.400 --> 00:42:24.000
triangular magic key, he informed his nebulous antagonist. That will transfer the obligation

00:42:24.080 --> 00:42:27.840
out of your jurisdiction on your books, it'll show as total restitution.

00:42:28.480 --> 00:42:32.960
Plus fines, plus penalties. I'll charge those against my heart-shaped.

00:42:32.960 --> 00:42:37.920
Mr. Chip, the Ferris and Brockman retail credit auditing and analysis agency has published a

00:42:37.920 --> 00:42:45.200
special flyer on you. Our recept slot received it yesterday and it remains fresh in our minds.

00:42:45.840 --> 00:42:52.320
Since July, you've dropped from a triple G status credit-wise to quadruple G. Our department,

00:42:52.960 --> 00:42:58.640
in fact, this entire Conap building is now programmed against an extension of services

00:42:58.640 --> 00:43:05.520
and or credit to such pathetic anomalies as yourself, sir. Regarding you, everything must

00:43:05.520 --> 00:43:11.600
hereafter be handled on a basic cash subfloor. In fact, you'll probably be on a basic cash

00:43:11.600 --> 00:43:18.480
subfloor for the rest of your life. In fact, he hung up and abandoned the hope of enticing and

00:43:18.480 --> 00:43:24.400
or threatening the cleanup robots into entering his muddled apt. Instead, he padded into the

00:43:24.400 --> 00:43:31.360
bedroom to dress. He could do that without assistance. After he had dressed, in a sporty

00:43:31.360 --> 00:43:36.640
maroon wrapper, twinkle-toes turned up shoes and a felt cap with a tassel, he poked around

00:43:36.640 --> 00:43:43.520
hopefully in the kitchen for some manifestation of coffee. None. He then focused on the living

00:43:43.520 --> 00:43:48.480
room and found, by the door leading to the bathroom last night's great cape, every spotty

00:43:48.480 --> 00:43:55.200
blue yard of it, and a plastic bag which contained a half-pound can of authentic Kenya coffee.

00:43:55.920 --> 00:44:01.440
A great treat and one which only while puzzled would he have risen to, especially in view of his

00:44:01.440 --> 00:44:07.360
current abominable financial situation. Back in the kitchen, he fished in his various pockets for a

00:44:07.360 --> 00:44:14.480
dime and with it started up the coffee pot. Sniffing the, to him very unusual smell, he again

00:44:14.480 --> 00:44:19.200
consulted his watch, saw that fifteen minutes had passed. He therefore vigorously strode to the

00:44:19.200 --> 00:44:25.680
apt door, turned the knob and pulled on the release bolt. The door refused to open. It said,

00:44:26.560 --> 00:44:31.120
Five cents, please. He searched his pockets. No more coins, nothing.

00:44:31.760 --> 00:44:36.240
I'll pay you tomorrow, he told the door. Again he tried the knob. Again it remained locked tight.

00:44:37.440 --> 00:44:42.000
What I pay you, he informed it, is in the nature of a gratuity. I don't have to pay you.

00:44:42.560 --> 00:44:47.680
I think otherwise, the door said. Look in the purchase contract you signed when you bought this

00:44:47.680 --> 00:44:53.200
con app. In his desk drawer he found the contract. Since signing it he had found it necessary to

00:44:53.200 --> 00:44:59.200
refer to the document many times. Sure enough, payment to his door for opening and shutting

00:44:59.200 --> 00:45:06.640
constituted a mandatory fee, not a tip. You discover I'm right, the door said. It sounded smug.

00:45:07.840 --> 00:45:12.160
From the drawer beside the sink Joe Chip got a stainless steel knife. With it he began

00:45:12.160 --> 00:45:17.200
systematically to unscrew the bolt assembly of his apt's money-gulping door.

00:45:17.920 --> 00:45:25.120
I'll sue you, the door said, as the first screw fell out. Joe Chip said, I've never been sued by

00:45:25.120 --> 00:45:31.120
a door but I guess I can live through it. A knock sounded on the door. Hey Joe baby, it's me, G.G.

00:45:31.120 --> 00:45:36.480
Ashwood, and I've got it right here with me. Open up. Put a nickel in the slot for me, Joe said.

00:45:36.480 --> 00:45:42.960
The mechanism seems to be jammed on my side. A coin rattled down into the works of the door.

00:45:42.960 --> 00:45:49.280
It swung open and there stood G.G. Ashwood with a brilliant look on his face. It pulsed with sly

00:45:49.280 --> 00:45:55.600
intensity, an erratic gleaming triumph as he propelled the girl forward and into the apt.

00:45:57.920 --> 00:46:04.320
She stood for a moment staring at Joe, obviously no more than 17, slim and copper skinned with

00:46:04.320 --> 00:46:12.640
large dark eyes. My God, he thought she's beautiful. She wore an ersatz canvas work shirt and jeans,

00:46:12.640 --> 00:46:18.640
heavy boots, caked with what appeared to be authentic mud. Her tangle of shiny hair was tied

00:46:18.640 --> 00:46:24.560
back and knotted with a red bandana. Her rolled up sleeves showed tanned, competent arms.

00:46:25.280 --> 00:46:29.520
At her imitation leather belt she carried a knife, a field telephone unit,

00:46:29.520 --> 00:46:35.280
and an emergency pack of rations and water. On her bare dark forearm he made out a tattoo.

00:46:36.080 --> 00:46:39.600
Caveat emtor, it read. He wondered what that meant.

00:46:40.320 --> 00:46:46.400
This is Pat, G.G. Ashwood said, his arm with ostentatious familiarity around the girl's waist.

00:46:46.400 --> 00:46:52.880
Never mind her last name. Square and puffy like an overweight brick, wearing his usual mohair poncho,

00:46:52.880 --> 00:46:58.400
apricot-colored felt hat, argile ski socks, and carpet slippers. He advanced toward Joe Chip,

00:46:58.400 --> 00:47:05.440
self-satisfaction smirking from every molecule in his body. He had found something of value here,

00:47:05.440 --> 00:47:10.640
and he meant to make the most of it. Pat, this is the company's highly skilled first-line electrical

00:47:10.640 --> 00:47:14.320
type tester. Coolly the girl said to Joe Chip,

00:47:15.120 --> 00:47:23.520
is it you that's electrical or your tests? We trade off, Joe said. He felt from all around

00:47:23.680 --> 00:47:29.280
him the miasma of his uncleaned-up apt. It radiated the specter of debris and clutter,

00:47:29.280 --> 00:47:31.280
and he knew that Pat had already noticed.

00:47:32.400 --> 00:47:35.680
Sit down, he said awkwardly. Have a cup of actual coffee.

00:47:36.560 --> 00:47:41.760
Such luxury, Pat said, seating herself at the kitchen table. Reflexively,

00:47:41.760 --> 00:47:44.800
she gathered the week's heap of papes into a neater pile.

00:47:45.760 --> 00:47:48.240
How can you afford real coffee, Mr. Chip?

00:47:49.200 --> 00:47:53.840
G.G. Ashwood said, Joe gets paid a hell of a lot. The firm could not break without him.

00:47:54.560 --> 00:47:57.760
Reaching out, he took a cigarette from the package lying on the table.

00:47:57.760 --> 00:48:04.080
Put it back, Joe Chip said. I'm almost out, and I used up my last green ration stamp on the coffee.

00:48:04.640 --> 00:48:10.400
I paid for the door, G.G. pointed out. He offered the pack to the girl. Joe puts on an act,

00:48:10.400 --> 00:48:16.320
pay no attention. Like, look how he keeps his place. Joe sees creative, all geniuses live like this.

00:48:16.320 --> 00:48:18.560
Where's your test equipment, Joe? We're wasting time.

00:48:19.600 --> 00:48:23.120
To the girl, Joe said, you're dressed oddly.

00:48:24.080 --> 00:48:30.000
I maintained the subsurface vid phone lines at the Topeka Kibbutz, Pat said. Only women can hold

00:48:30.000 --> 00:48:34.880
jobs involving manual labor at that particular Kibbutz. That's why I applied there instead of

00:48:34.880 --> 00:48:43.680
the Wichita Falls Kibbutz. Her black eyes blazed pridefully. Joe said, that inscription on your arm,

00:48:44.320 --> 00:48:51.280
tattoo, is that Hebrew? Latin. Her eyes veiled her amusement. I've never seen an app so cluttered

00:48:51.280 --> 00:48:56.480
with rubbish. Don't you have a mistress? These electrical expert types have no time for

00:48:56.480 --> 00:49:02.400
pterodital, G.G. Ashwood said irritably. Listen, Chip, this girl's parents work for Ray Hollis.

00:49:02.400 --> 00:49:05.120
If they knew she was here, they'd give her a frontal lobotomy.

00:49:06.000 --> 00:49:10.080
To the girl, Joe Chip said, they don't know you have a counter-talent?

00:49:10.880 --> 00:49:17.120
No, she shook her head. I didn't really understand it either until your scout sat down with me in

00:49:17.120 --> 00:49:22.880
the Kibbutz cafeteria and told me. Maybe it's true? She shrugged. Maybe not.

00:49:23.600 --> 00:49:27.280
He said you could show me objective proof of it with your testing battery.

00:49:28.320 --> 00:49:32.240
How would you feel? he asked her, if the tests show that you have it.

00:49:33.280 --> 00:49:37.280
Reflecting, Pat said, it seems so negative.

00:49:38.160 --> 00:49:44.000
I don't do anything. I don't move objects or turn stones into bread or give birth without

00:49:44.000 --> 00:49:51.280
impregnation or reverse the illness process in sick people or read minds or look into the future.

00:49:51.280 --> 00:49:56.720
Not even common talents like that. I just negate somebody else's ability. It seems,

00:49:57.440 --> 00:50:04.320
she gestured, stultifying. As a survival factor for the human race, Joe said,

00:50:04.320 --> 00:50:10.800
it's as useful as the Psi talents, especially for us norms. The anti-Si factor is a natural

00:50:10.800 --> 00:50:17.840
restoration of ecological balance. One insect learns to fly, so another learns to build a web

00:50:17.840 --> 00:50:23.600
to trap him. Is that the same as no flight? Clams develop hard shells to protect them,

00:50:23.600 --> 00:50:27.920
therefore birds learn to fly the clam up high in the air and drop them on a rock.

00:50:27.920 --> 00:50:34.480
In a sense, you're a life form preying on the size. And the size are life forms that

00:50:34.480 --> 00:50:40.320
prey on the norms. That makes you a friend of the norm class. Balance, the full circle,

00:50:40.320 --> 00:50:45.920
predator and prey. It appears to be an internal system and frankly I can't say how it could

00:50:45.920 --> 00:50:53.120
be improved. I might be considered a traitor, Pat said. Does it bother you? It bothers me

00:50:53.120 --> 00:50:58.080
that people will feel hostile toward me. But I guess you can't live very long without arousing

00:50:58.080 --> 00:51:03.440
hostility. You can't please everybody because people want different things. Please one,

00:51:04.080 --> 00:51:09.920
and you displease another. Joe said, what is your anti-talent?

00:51:10.800 --> 00:51:16.320
It's hard to explain. Like I say, G.G. Ashwood said, it's unique. I never heard of it before.

00:51:17.280 --> 00:51:20.960
Which side talent does it counteract? Joe asked the girl.

00:51:22.080 --> 00:51:28.560
Precog, Pat said, I guess. She indicated G.G. Ashwood, who smirked of enthusiasm, had not dimmed.

00:51:29.200 --> 00:51:35.040
Your scout, Mr. Ashwood, explained it to me. I knew I did something funny. I've always had these

00:51:35.040 --> 00:51:40.800
strange periods in my life, starting in my sixth year. I never told my parents because

00:51:40.960 --> 00:51:42.560
I sensed that it would displease them.

00:51:43.360 --> 00:51:48.480
Are they precogs? Joe asked. Yes. You're right, it would have displeased them.

00:51:49.280 --> 00:51:55.280
But if you used it around them even once, they would have known. Didn't they suspect? Didn't

00:51:55.280 --> 00:52:03.280
you interfere with their ability? Pat said, I—she gestured. I think I did interfere,

00:52:03.280 --> 00:52:07.360
but they didn't know it. Her face showed bewilderment.

00:52:08.320 --> 00:52:13.920
Let me explain, Joe said, how the anti-precog generally functions— functions, in fact,

00:52:13.920 --> 00:52:20.160
in every case we know of. The precog sees a variety of futures laid outside by side,

00:52:20.160 --> 00:52:26.480
like cells in a beehive. For him, one has greater luminosity unless he picks.

00:52:27.200 --> 00:52:32.400
Once he has picked it, the anti-precog can do nothing. The anti-precog has to be present

00:52:32.400 --> 00:52:39.200
when the precog is in the process of deciding, not after. The anti-precog makes all futures seem

00:52:39.200 --> 00:52:46.880
equally real to the precog. He aborts his talent to choose, at all. The precog is instantly aware

00:52:46.880 --> 00:52:51.600
when an anti-precog is nearby because his entire relation to the future is altered.

00:52:52.400 --> 00:52:54.960
In the case of telepaths, a similar impairment—

00:52:54.960 --> 00:53:00.400
She goes back in time, G. G. Ashwood said. Joe stared at him.

00:53:01.200 --> 00:53:08.800
Back in time, G. G. repeated, savoring this. His eyes shot shafts of significance to every

00:53:08.800 --> 00:53:14.640
part of Joe Chip's kitchen. The precog affected by her still sees one predominant future,

00:53:14.640 --> 00:53:20.160
like you said, the one luminous possibility, and he chooses it, and he's right. But why is it right?

00:53:20.800 --> 00:53:25.120
Why is it luminous? Because this girl, he shrugged in her direction,

00:53:25.120 --> 00:53:30.720
path controls the future. That one luminous possibility is luminous because she's gone

00:53:30.720 --> 00:53:36.000
into the past and changed it. By changing it, she changes the present, which includes the precog.

00:53:36.000 --> 00:53:40.160
He's affected without knowing it, and his talent seems to work whereas it really doesn't.

00:53:40.160 --> 00:53:45.360
So that's one advantage of her anti-talent over other anti-precog talents. The other,

00:53:45.360 --> 00:53:51.360
and greater, is that she can cancel out the precog's decision after he's made it.

00:53:52.000 --> 00:53:56.160
She can enter the situation later on, and this problem has always hung us up, as you know.

00:53:56.160 --> 00:54:00.080
If we didn't get in there from the start, we couldn't do anything. In a way, we never could

00:54:00.080 --> 00:54:04.560
truly abort the precog ability as we've done with the others, right? Hasn't that been a weak

00:54:04.560 --> 00:54:08.480
link in our services? He eyed Joe Chip expectantly.

00:54:09.120 --> 00:54:12.720
Interesting, Joe said presently.

00:54:13.360 --> 00:54:19.040
Hell, interesting! G.G. Ashwood thrashed about indignantly. This is the greatest anti-talent

00:54:19.040 --> 00:54:22.880
to emerge thus far. In a low voice, Pat said,

00:54:23.760 --> 00:54:29.440
I don't go back in time. She raised her eyes, confronted Joe Chip, half apologetically,

00:54:29.440 --> 00:54:35.840
half belligerently. I do something, but Mr. Ashwood has built it up all out of proportion to reality.

00:54:36.560 --> 00:54:40.160
I can read your mind, G.G. said to her, looking a little nettle.

00:54:40.160 --> 00:54:43.440
I know you can change the past. You've done it. Pat said,

00:54:44.400 --> 00:54:50.480
I can change the past, but I don't go into the past. I don't time travel, as you want your

00:54:50.480 --> 00:54:59.920
tester to think. How do you change the past, Joe asked her. I think about it. One specific

00:54:59.920 --> 00:55:05.680
aspect of it, such as one incident or something somebody said, or a little thing that

00:55:05.680 --> 00:55:11.200
happened that I wish hadn't happened. The first time I did this, as a child, when she was six

00:55:11.200 --> 00:55:15.280
years old, G.G. broke in, living in Detroit with her parents, of course, she broke a ceramic

00:55:15.280 --> 00:55:20.880
antique statue that her father treasured. Didn't your father foresee it, Joe asked her,

00:55:20.880 --> 00:55:26.880
with his precog ability? He foresaw it, Pat answered, and he punished me the week before

00:55:26.880 --> 00:55:33.200
I broke the statue. But he said it was inevitable. You know the precog talent they can foresee,

00:55:33.200 --> 00:55:40.880
but they can't change anything. Then, after the statue did break, after I broke it, I should say,

00:55:41.680 --> 00:55:46.960
I brooded about it, and I thought about that week before it broke, when I didn't get any

00:55:46.960 --> 00:55:53.680
dessert at dinner and had to go to bed at 5 p.m. I thought, Christ, or whatever a kid says,

00:55:53.680 --> 00:55:57.200
isn't there some way these unfortunate events can be averted?

00:55:58.160 --> 00:56:03.840
My father's precog ability didn't seem very spectacular to me, since he couldn't alter events.

00:56:04.560 --> 00:56:11.760
I still feel that way, a sort of contempt. I spent a month trying to will the damn statue back into

00:56:11.760 --> 00:56:18.000
one piece. In my mind, I kept going back to before it broke, imagining what it had looked like,

00:56:18.560 --> 00:56:25.520
which was awful. And then, one morning, when I got up, I even dreamed about it at night.

00:56:26.240 --> 00:56:32.560
There it stood as it used to be. Tensley, she leaned toward Joe Chip. She spoke in a sharp,

00:56:32.560 --> 00:56:40.240
determined voice. But neither of my parents noticed anything. It seemed perfectly normal to them that

00:56:40.240 --> 00:56:46.240
the statue was in one piece. They thought it had always been in one piece. I was the only one who

00:56:46.240 --> 00:56:52.480
remembered. She smiled, leaned back, took another of his cigarettes from the pack, and lit up.

00:56:53.200 --> 00:56:58.160
I'll go get my test equipment from the car, Joe said, starting toward the door.

00:56:59.280 --> 00:57:03.360
Five cents, please. The door said as he seized its knob.

00:57:03.360 --> 00:57:05.760
Pay the door, Joe said to G.G. Ashwood.

00:57:07.920 --> 00:57:12.480
When he had lugged his armload of testing apparatus from the car to his apt, he told

00:57:12.480 --> 00:57:19.680
the firm scout to hit the road. What, G.G. said astounded. But I found her. The bounty is mine.

00:57:19.680 --> 00:57:24.160
I spent almost ten days tracing the field to her. I— Joe said to him,

00:57:24.160 --> 00:57:29.920
I can't test her with your field presence, as you will know. Talent and anti-talent fields

00:57:29.920 --> 00:57:33.760
deform each other. If they didn't, we wouldn't be in this line of business.

00:57:34.320 --> 00:57:40.080
He held out his hand as G.G. got grumpily to his feet. And leave me a couple of nickels,

00:57:40.080 --> 00:57:44.960
so she and I can get out of here. I have changed, Pat murmured, in my purse.

00:57:45.840 --> 00:57:49.680
You can measure the force she creates, G.G. said, by the loss within my field.

00:57:49.680 --> 00:57:54.640
I've seen you do it that way a hundred times. Joe said briefly, this is different.

00:57:55.200 --> 00:57:58.720
I don't have any more nickels, G.G. said. I can't get out.

00:57:59.520 --> 00:58:01.760
Glancing at Joe, then at G.G. Pat said,

00:58:02.400 --> 00:58:06.160
Have on a mine. She tossed G.G. a coin, which he caught

00:58:06.160 --> 00:58:10.720
an expression of bewilderment on his face. The bewilderment then, by degrees,

00:58:10.800 --> 00:58:17.200
changed to a grieved sullenness. You sure shot me down, he said, as he deposited the

00:58:17.200 --> 00:58:21.600
nickel in the door slot. Both of you, he muttered, as the door closed after him.

00:58:21.600 --> 00:58:25.040
I discovered her. This is really a cutthroat business, wouldn't it?

00:58:25.920 --> 00:58:30.960
His voice faded out as the door clamped shut. There was then silence.

00:58:33.120 --> 00:58:38.240
Presently Pat said, When his enthusiasm goes, there isn't much left of him.

00:58:38.320 --> 00:58:45.040
He's okay, Joe said. He felt a usual feeling, guilt, but not very much.

00:58:46.080 --> 00:58:47.440
Anyhow, he did his part.

00:58:48.480 --> 00:58:52.080
Now, it's your turn, Pat said, so to speak.

00:58:52.880 --> 00:58:54.480
May I take off my boots?

00:58:54.480 --> 00:58:59.840
Sure, he said. He began to set up his test equipment, checking the drums, the power supply.

00:58:59.840 --> 00:59:05.040
He started trial motions of each needle, releasing specific surges and recording their effect.

00:59:05.920 --> 00:59:09.600
A shower? She asked as she set her boots neatly out of the way.

00:59:10.800 --> 00:59:16.240
Quarter, he murmured, cost a quarter. He glanced up at her and saw that she had begun

00:59:16.240 --> 00:59:17.600
unbuttoning her blouse.

00:59:18.640 --> 00:59:20.880
I don't have a quarter, he said.

00:59:21.520 --> 00:59:23.600
At the kebutz, Pat said, everything is free.

00:59:24.320 --> 00:59:29.920
Free? He stared at her. That's not economically feasible. How can it operate on that basis

00:59:29.920 --> 00:59:30.880
for more than a month?

00:59:31.760 --> 00:59:35.440
She continued, unperturbedly, unbuttoning her blouse.

00:59:36.560 --> 00:59:40.000
Our salaries are paid in, and we're credited with having done our job.

00:59:40.640 --> 00:59:44.480
The aggregate of our earnings underwrites the kebutz as a whole.

00:59:45.040 --> 00:59:49.200
Actually, the Tipeek at Kebutz has shown a profit for several years.

00:59:49.200 --> 00:59:52.080
We as a group are putting in more than we're taking out.

00:59:53.360 --> 00:59:56.640
Having unbuttoned her blouse, she laid it over the back of her chair.

00:59:57.600 --> 00:59:59.920
Under the blue coarse blouse, she wore nothing.

01:00:00.560 --> 01:00:06.960
And he perceived her breasts, hard and high, held well by the accurate muscles of her shoulders.

01:00:08.400 --> 01:00:11.680
Are you sure you want to do that? he said.

01:00:11.680 --> 01:00:15.200
Take off your clothes, I mean. Pat said.

01:00:16.160 --> 01:00:17.040
You don't remember.

01:00:17.680 --> 01:00:18.800
Remember what?

01:00:18.800 --> 01:00:22.080
My not taking off my clothes. In another present.

01:00:22.640 --> 01:00:26.480
You didn't like that very well, so I eradicated that. Hence this.

01:00:27.360 --> 01:00:28.560
She stood up lightly.

01:00:28.800 --> 01:00:31.360
What did I do? he asked cautiously.

01:00:31.360 --> 01:00:34.720
When you didn't take off your clothes, refused to test you?

01:00:35.760 --> 01:00:39.520
You mumbled something about Mr. Ashwood having overrated my anti-talent.

01:00:40.560 --> 01:00:42.960
Joe said, I don't work that way. I don't do that.

01:00:43.440 --> 01:00:44.000
Here.

01:00:44.880 --> 01:00:49.520
Vending her breasts wagging forward, she rummaged in the pocket of her blouse,

01:00:49.520 --> 01:00:54.800
brought forth a folded sheet of paper which she handed him, from the previous present,

01:00:54.800 --> 01:00:55.600
when I abolished.

01:00:55.600 --> 01:00:58.960
He read it, read his one-line evaluation at the end.

01:00:59.840 --> 01:01:04.240
Anti-Sci-Field generated inadequate, below standard throughout.

01:01:05.040 --> 01:01:08.160
No value against precog ratings now in existence.

01:01:09.200 --> 01:01:13.600
And then the code mark which he employed a circle, with a stroke dividing it,

01:01:13.600 --> 01:01:15.600
do not hire the symbol meant.

01:01:15.600 --> 01:01:18.240
And only he and Glenn Runceter knew that.

01:01:18.240 --> 01:01:20.720
Not even their scouts knew the meaning of the symbol.

01:01:20.720 --> 01:01:23.840
So Ashwood could not have told me.

01:01:23.840 --> 01:01:26.000
So Ashwood could not have told her.

01:01:27.200 --> 01:01:29.200
Silently he returned the paper to her.

01:01:29.200 --> 01:01:31.840
She refolded it and returned it to her blouse pocket.

01:01:33.120 --> 01:01:35.360
Do you need to test me? she asked.

01:01:36.000 --> 01:01:36.960
After seeing that?

01:01:38.720 --> 01:01:44.000
I have a regular procedure, Joe said. Six indices which...

01:01:44.880 --> 01:01:49.600
Pat said, you're a little debt-stricken, ineffective bureaucrat who can't even scrape

01:01:49.600 --> 01:01:52.560
together enough coins to pay his door to let him out of his abut.

01:01:53.520 --> 01:01:56.960
Her tone, neutral but devastating, rebounded in his ears.

01:01:56.960 --> 01:01:59.840
He felt himself stiff and wince and violently flush.

01:02:01.280 --> 01:02:04.240
This is a bad spot, right now, he said.

01:02:04.240 --> 01:02:06.480
I'll be back on my feet financially any day now.

01:02:07.840 --> 01:02:10.080
I can get a loan from the firm if necessary.

01:02:10.640 --> 01:02:14.880
He rose unsteadily, got two cups and two saucers, poured coffee from the coffee pot.

01:02:15.520 --> 01:02:17.120
Sugar, he said, cream?

01:02:18.160 --> 01:02:21.680
Cream. Pat said, still standing barefoot without her blouse.

01:02:22.800 --> 01:02:26.320
He fumbled for the door handle of the refrigerator to get out a carton of milk.

01:02:27.120 --> 01:02:29.840
Ten cents, please, the refrigerator said.

01:02:29.840 --> 01:02:32.640
Five cents for opening my door, five cents for the cream.

01:02:33.280 --> 01:02:36.640
It isn't cream, he said, it's plain milk.

01:02:36.640 --> 01:02:40.000
He continued to pluck futilely at the refrigerator door.

01:02:40.000 --> 01:02:41.680
Just this one time, he said to it.

01:02:41.680 --> 01:02:43.440
I swear to God, I'll pay you back tonight.

01:02:44.240 --> 01:02:48.320
Here, Pat said. She slid a dime across the table, toward him.

01:02:48.720 --> 01:02:53.360
She should have money, she said, as she watched him put the dime in the slot of the refrigerator.

01:02:53.360 --> 01:02:57.200
You're mistress. You really have failed, haven't you?

01:02:57.200 --> 01:02:59.280
I knew it when Mr. Ashwood—

01:02:59.280 --> 01:03:01.920
It isn't, he graded, always like this.

01:03:03.200 --> 01:03:06.080
Do you want me to bail you out of your problems, Mr. Chip?

01:03:07.280 --> 01:03:12.640
Hands in the pockets of her jeans, she regarded him expressionlessly, no emotion clouding her face,

01:03:12.640 --> 01:03:13.520
only alertness.

01:03:13.520 --> 01:03:15.280
You know I can.

01:03:15.280 --> 01:03:18.560
Sit down and write out your evaluation report on me.

01:03:18.560 --> 01:03:20.240
Forget the tests.

01:03:20.240 --> 01:03:21.920
My talent is unique anyway.

01:03:21.920 --> 01:03:24.000
You can't measure the field I produce.

01:03:24.000 --> 01:03:25.200
It's in the past.

01:03:25.200 --> 01:03:31.200
And you're testing me in the present, which simply takes place as an automatic consequence.

01:03:31.200 --> 01:03:32.080
Do you agree?

01:03:33.040 --> 01:03:37.200
He said, let me see that evaluation sheet you have in your blouse.

01:03:37.200 --> 01:03:40.080
I want to look at it one more time before I decide.

01:03:40.560 --> 01:03:44.400
From her blouse she once more brought forth the folded-up yellow sheet of paper.

01:03:44.400 --> 01:03:48.000
She calmly passed it across the table to him and he re-read it.

01:03:48.800 --> 01:03:52.880
My writing, he said to himself, yes, it's true.

01:03:54.160 --> 01:04:00.320
He returned it to her and from the collection of testing items took a fresh clean sheet of the same familiar yellow paper.

01:04:00.320 --> 01:04:08.320
On it he wrote her name, then spurious extraordinarily high test results, and then at last she took a new sheet of paper.

01:04:08.320 --> 01:04:13.760
She took the test results and then at last his conclusions, his new conclusions.

01:04:13.760 --> 01:04:15.920
Has unbelievable power.

01:04:15.920 --> 01:04:21.920
Anti-Sci-Field, unique in scope, can probably negate any assembly of Precog's imaginable.

01:04:23.040 --> 01:04:24.720
After that he scratched a symbol.

01:04:24.720 --> 01:04:27.040
This time two crosses both underlined.

01:04:28.240 --> 01:04:30.160
Pat, standing behind him, watched him right.

01:04:30.160 --> 01:04:31.920
He felt her breath on his neck.

01:04:31.920 --> 01:04:35.120
What do the two underlined crosses mean?

01:04:35.120 --> 01:04:35.920
She asked.

01:04:36.000 --> 01:04:39.600
Hire her, Joe said, at whatever cost required.

01:04:40.480 --> 01:04:40.960
Thank you.

01:04:42.240 --> 01:04:48.320
She dug into her purse, brought out a handful of Pascred bills, selected one and presented it to him, a big one.

01:04:49.120 --> 01:04:50.640
This will help you with expenses.

01:04:51.280 --> 01:04:55.680
I couldn't give it to you earlier before you made your official evaluation of me.

01:04:55.680 --> 01:05:00.880
You would have cancelled very nearly everything and you would have gone to your grave thinking I had bribed you.

01:05:01.760 --> 01:05:05.040
Ultimately you would have even decided that I had no counter-talent.

01:05:06.160 --> 01:05:11.200
She then unzipped her jeans and resumed her quick furtive undressing.

01:05:12.560 --> 01:05:15.040
Joe Chip examined what he had written, not watching her.

01:05:15.840 --> 01:05:19.280
The underlined crosses did not symbolize what he had told her.

01:05:19.280 --> 01:05:21.920
They meant, watch this person.

01:05:21.920 --> 01:05:23.920
She is a hazard to the firm.

01:05:23.920 --> 01:05:25.120
She is dangerous.

01:05:26.560 --> 01:05:29.520
He signed the test paper, folded it and passed it to her.

01:05:29.520 --> 01:05:31.280
She at once put it away in her purse.

01:05:31.600 --> 01:05:33.280
When can I move my things in here?

01:05:33.280 --> 01:05:35.360
She asked as she padded toward the bathroom.

01:05:36.320 --> 01:05:41.520
I consider it mine, as of now since I've already paid you what must be virtually the entire month's rent.

01:05:43.520 --> 01:05:44.640
Any time, he said.

01:05:45.760 --> 01:05:46.640
The bathroom said,

01:05:47.600 --> 01:05:49.600
Get the sense, please, before turning on the water.

01:05:50.800 --> 01:05:54.000
Pat padded back into the kitchen to reach into her purse.

01:05:58.000 --> 01:05:58.160
Four.

01:06:01.520 --> 01:06:06.960
Wild new UBIC salad dressing, not Italian, not French, but an entirely new and different

01:06:06.960 --> 01:06:09.120
taste treat that's waking up the world.

01:06:09.120 --> 01:06:11.760
Wake up to UBIC and be wild.

01:06:11.760 --> 01:06:13.440
Safe when taken as directed.

01:06:14.960 --> 01:06:19.360
Back in New York once more, his trip to the beloved brethren moratorium completed.

01:06:19.920 --> 01:06:25.920
Glenn Runciter landed via a silent and impressive all-electric hired limousine

01:06:25.920 --> 01:06:29.760
on the roof of the central installation of Runciter Associates.

01:06:29.760 --> 01:06:33.440
A descent chute dropped him speedily to his fifth-floor office.

01:06:34.160 --> 01:06:40.160
Presently at 9.30 a.m. local time, he sat in the massive, old-fashioned, authentic,

01:06:40.160 --> 01:06:43.680
walnut-and-leather swivel chair behind his desk,

01:06:43.680 --> 01:06:46.880
talking on the VID phone to his public relations department.

01:06:47.920 --> 01:06:52.400
Tamish, I just now got back from Zurich. I conferred with Ella there.

01:06:53.120 --> 01:06:58.720
Runciter glared at his secretary who had cautiously entered his personal oversized office,

01:06:58.720 --> 01:07:00.080
shutting the door behind her.

01:07:01.120 --> 01:07:03.440
What do you want, Ms. Freck? he asked her.

01:07:04.160 --> 01:07:09.120
Withered, timorous Mrs. Freck, her face dabbed with spots of artificial color

01:07:09.120 --> 01:07:14.080
to compensate for her general ancient grayness, made a gesture of disavowal.

01:07:14.080 --> 01:07:15.760
She had no choice but to bother him.

01:07:16.480 --> 01:07:20.000
Okay, Ms. Freck, he said patiently. What is it?

01:07:20.560 --> 01:07:24.560
A new client, Mr. Runciter. I think you should see her.

01:07:25.280 --> 01:07:29.760
She both advanced toward him and retreated a difficult maneuver which Mrs. Freck alone

01:07:29.760 --> 01:07:33.120
could carry off. It had taken her ten decades of practice.

01:07:33.920 --> 01:07:36.480
As soon as I'm off the phone, Runciter told her.

01:07:37.200 --> 01:07:38.240
Into the phone he said,

01:07:38.960 --> 01:07:44.720
How often do our ads run on primetime TV, planet-wide? Still once every third hour?

01:07:45.440 --> 01:07:50.480
Not quite that, Mr. Runciter. Over the course of a full day, prudence ads appear on the average of

01:07:50.480 --> 01:07:54.640
once every third hour per UHF channel. But the cost of primetime?

01:07:54.640 --> 01:07:59.600
I want them to appear every hour, Runciter said. Ella thinks that would be better.

01:08:00.480 --> 01:08:05.360
On the trip back to the Western Hemisphere, he had decided which of their ads he liked the most.

01:08:06.080 --> 01:08:11.120
You know that recent Supreme Court ruling where a husband can legally murder his wife if he can

01:08:11.120 --> 01:08:16.640
prove she wouldn't under any circumstances give him a divorce? Yes, the so-called I don't care

01:08:16.720 --> 01:08:22.160
what it's called. What matters is that we have a TV ad made up on that already.

01:08:22.160 --> 01:08:24.640
How does that ad go? I've been trying to remember it.

01:08:25.520 --> 01:08:31.600
Tamish said, There's this man, an ex-husband, being tried. First comes a shot of the jury,

01:08:31.600 --> 01:08:36.880
then the judge, then a pan up on the prosecuting attorney cross-examining the ex-husband.

01:08:36.880 --> 01:08:39.600
He says it would seem, sir, that your wife—

01:08:39.600 --> 01:08:44.560
That's right, Runciter said, with satisfaction. He had originally helped write the ad.

01:08:45.200 --> 01:08:51.600
It was, in his opinion, another manifestation of the marvellous multifacetedness of his mind.

01:08:52.800 --> 01:08:57.680
Is it not the assumption, however, Tamish said, that the missing size are at work as a group for

01:08:57.680 --> 01:09:02.880
one of the larger investment houses? Seeing as how this is probably so, perhaps we should stress

01:09:02.880 --> 01:09:08.320
one of our business establishment commercials. Do you perhaps recall this one, Mr. Runciter?

01:09:08.320 --> 01:09:13.040
It shows a husband home from his job at the end of the day. He still has on his electric yellow

01:09:13.040 --> 01:09:18.720
cummerbund, pedal skirt, knee-hugging hose, and military-style visor cap. He seats himself

01:09:18.720 --> 01:09:24.400
wearily on the living-room couch, starts to take off one of his gauntlets, then hunches over, frowns,

01:09:24.400 --> 01:09:30.000
and says, Gosh, Jill, I wish I knew what's been wrong with me lately. Sometimes, with greater

01:09:30.000 --> 01:09:34.960
frequency almost every day, the least little remark at the office makes me think that, well,

01:09:35.600 --> 01:09:41.120
somebody's reading my mind. Then she says, If you're worried about that, why don't we contact

01:09:41.120 --> 01:09:47.040
our nearest Prudence organization? They'll lease us an inertial at prices easy on our budget,

01:09:47.040 --> 01:09:52.240
and then you'll feel like your old self again. Then this great smile appears on his face,

01:09:52.240 --> 01:09:55.440
and he says, Why, this nagging feeling is already—

01:09:56.560 --> 01:09:59.920
Again appearing in the doorway to Runciter's office, Mrs. Frick said,

01:10:00.480 --> 01:10:05.440
Please, Mr. Runciter, her glasses quivered. He nodded.

01:10:06.400 --> 01:10:12.080
I'll talk to you later, Tamish. Anyhow, get hold of the networks and start our material on the

01:10:12.080 --> 01:10:17.440
hour basis as I outlined. He rang off and regarded Mrs. Frick silently.

01:10:18.720 --> 01:10:24.480
I went all the way to Switzerland, he said presently, and had Ella Rouse to get that information,

01:10:24.480 --> 01:10:31.920
that advice. Mr. Runciter is free, Miss Wirt. His secretary tottered to one side,

01:10:32.480 --> 01:10:38.240
and a plump woman rolled into the office. Her head, like a basketball, bobbed up and down.

01:10:38.240 --> 01:10:43.840
Her great round body propelled itself toward a chair, and there at one she seated herself,

01:10:43.840 --> 01:10:50.400
narrow legs dangling. She wore an unfashionable spider silk coat, looking like some

01:10:50.400 --> 01:10:56.000
amiable bug wound up in a cocoon not spun by itself. She looked encased.

01:10:56.720 --> 01:11:02.560
However, she smiled. She seemed fully at ease. In her late forties, Runciter decided,

01:11:02.560 --> 01:11:05.200
passed any period in which she might have had a good figure.

01:11:06.160 --> 01:11:11.520
Ah, Miss Wirt, he said. I can't give you too much time. Maybe you should get to the point.

01:11:11.520 --> 01:11:16.320
What's the problem? In a mellow, merry, incongruous voice,

01:11:16.880 --> 01:11:23.280
Miss Wirt said, We're having little trouble with telepaths. We think so, but we're not sure.

01:11:23.280 --> 01:11:28.240
We maintain a telepath of our own, one we know about, and who's supposed to circulate among

01:11:28.240 --> 01:11:34.800
our employees. If he comes across any size, telepaths, or precogs, any kind, he's supposed to report to

01:11:35.680 --> 01:11:43.440
G.I., Runciter, brightly. To my principle. Late last week he made such a report. We have an

01:11:43.440 --> 01:11:49.840
evaluation done by a private firm on the capacities of the various prudent agencies yours is rated

01:11:49.920 --> 01:11:55.760
foremost. I know that, Runciter said. He had seen the evaluation, as a matter of fact.

01:11:56.480 --> 01:12:01.920
As yet, however, it had brought him little, if any, greater business. But now this.

01:12:02.960 --> 01:12:06.720
How many telepaths, he said, do your man pick up? More than one?

01:12:07.520 --> 01:12:11.760
Two, at least. Possibly more. Possibly, Miss Wirt nodded.

01:12:12.880 --> 01:12:18.800
Here is how we operate, Runciter said. First, we measure the sigh field objectively,

01:12:18.800 --> 01:12:24.640
so we can tell what we're dealing with. That generally takes from one week to ten days, depending

01:12:24.640 --> 01:12:30.560
on Miss Wirt interrupted. My employer wants you to move in your inertials right away without the

01:12:30.560 --> 01:12:36.560
time consuming and expensive formality of making tests. We wouldn't know how many inertials to

01:12:36.560 --> 01:12:44.000
bring in, or what kind, or where to station them. Diffusing a sigh operation has to be done on a

01:12:44.000 --> 01:12:52.240
systematic basis. We can't wave a magic wand or spray toxic fumes into corners. We have to balance

01:12:52.240 --> 01:12:59.680
Hollis' people individual by individual, and anti-talent for every talent. If Hollis has gotten

01:12:59.680 --> 01:13:06.720
into your operation, he's done it the same way, sigh by sigh. One gets into the personnel department,

01:13:06.720 --> 01:13:12.880
hires another. That person sets up a department, or takes charge of a department, and requisitions

01:13:12.960 --> 01:13:19.760
a couple more. Sometimes it takes a month. We can't undo, in twenty-four hours, what they've

01:13:19.760 --> 01:13:26.560
constructed over a long period of time. Big time sigh activity is like a mosaic. They can't afford

01:13:26.560 --> 01:13:32.880
to be impatient, and neither can we. My employer, Miss Wirt said cheerfully, is impatient.

01:13:33.760 --> 01:13:38.960
I'll talk to him. Runciter reached for the VID phone. Who is he, and what's his number?

01:13:39.600 --> 01:13:45.920
You'll deal through me. Maybe I won't deal at all. Why won't you tell me who you represent?

01:13:46.800 --> 01:13:51.040
He pressed a covert button mounted under the rim of his desk. It would bring his resident

01:13:51.040 --> 01:13:56.640
telepath, Nina Freed, into the next office where she could monitor Miss Wirt's thought processes.

01:13:57.680 --> 01:14:01.600
I can't work with these people, he said to himself, if I don't know who they are.

01:14:02.320 --> 01:14:05.600
For all I know, Ray Hollis is trying to hire me.

01:14:06.720 --> 01:14:12.160
You're hidebound, Miss Wirt said. All we're asking for is speed, and we're only asking for that,

01:14:12.160 --> 01:14:18.080
because we have to have it. I can tell you this much. Our operation, which they've infested,

01:14:18.080 --> 01:14:23.760
isn't on earth. From the standpoint of potential yield, as well as from an investment standpoint,

01:14:23.760 --> 01:14:30.160
it's our primary project. My principal has put all his negotiable assets into it.

01:14:30.160 --> 01:14:36.080
Nobody is supposed to know about it. The greatest chalk to us in finding telepaths on the site—

01:14:36.080 --> 01:14:40.720
Excuse me, Consider said. He rose, walked to the office door.

01:14:41.360 --> 01:14:46.640
I'll find out how many people we have about the place who are available for use in this connection.

01:14:47.520 --> 01:14:51.920
Shutting his office door behind him, he looked into each of the adjoining offices until he spied

01:14:51.920 --> 01:14:57.280
Nina Freed. She sat alone in a minor side room, smoking a cigarette and concentrating.

01:14:58.240 --> 01:15:02.720
Find out who she represents, he said to her. And then find out how high they'll go.

01:15:03.600 --> 01:15:09.520
We've got thirty-eight idle inertials, he reflected. Maybe we can dump all of them,

01:15:09.520 --> 01:15:15.520
or most of them, into this. I may finally have found where Hollis's smart-ass talents have

01:15:15.520 --> 01:15:21.920
sneaked off to—the whole goddamn bunch of them. He returned to his own office,

01:15:21.920 --> 01:15:23.760
receded himself behind his desk.

01:15:24.640 --> 01:15:29.840
If telepaths have gotten into your operation, he said to Ms. Wirt, his hands folded before him,

01:15:30.480 --> 01:15:37.360
then you have to face up to and accept the realization that the operation per se is no longer

01:15:37.360 --> 01:15:44.240
secret, independent of any specific technical info they've picked up. So why not tell me what the

01:15:44.240 --> 01:15:50.240
project is? Hesitating, Ms. Wirt said. I don't know what the project is.

01:15:50.800 --> 01:15:52.000
Or where it is?

01:15:52.640 --> 01:15:55.680
No, she shook her head. Runcitor said,

01:15:56.640 --> 01:15:58.240
Do you know who your employer is?

01:15:59.040 --> 01:16:05.440
I work for a subsidiary firm which he financially controls. I know who my immediate employer is.

01:16:05.440 --> 01:16:10.400
That's a Mr. Shepherd Howard. But I've never been told whom Mr. Howard represents.

01:16:11.360 --> 01:16:15.760
If we supply you with the inertials you need, will we know where they're being sent?

01:16:16.480 --> 01:16:17.200
Probably not.

01:16:17.920 --> 01:16:19.200
Suppose we never get them back.

01:16:20.000 --> 01:16:24.160
Why wouldn't you get them back after they've decontaminated our operation?

01:16:24.800 --> 01:16:30.240
Hollis's men, Runcitor said, have been known to kill inertials sent out to negate them.

01:16:30.880 --> 01:16:36.240
It's my responsibility to see that my people are protected. I can't do that if I don't know where

01:16:36.320 --> 01:16:43.360
they are. The concealed micro-speaker in his left ear buzzed, and he heard the faint measured voice

01:16:43.360 --> 01:16:50.800
of Nina Freed audible to him alone. Ms. Wirt represents Stanton Mick. She is his confidential

01:16:50.800 --> 01:16:58.080
assistant. There is no one named Shepherd Howard. The project under discussion exists primarily

01:16:58.080 --> 01:17:04.240
on Luna. It has to do with tech prize, Mick's research facilities, the controlling stock of

01:17:04.240 --> 01:17:10.800
which Ms. Wirt keeps in her name. She does not know any technical details, no scientific evaluations

01:17:10.800 --> 01:17:17.200
or memos or progress reports are ever made available to her by Mr. Mick, and she resents this enormously.

01:17:18.160 --> 01:17:23.360
From Mick's staff, however, she has picked up a general idea of the nature of the project.

01:17:24.400 --> 01:17:30.400
Assuming that her second hand knowledge is accurate, the Luna project involves a radical,

01:17:30.400 --> 01:17:38.320
new, low-cost interstellar drive system approaching the velocity of light, which could be leased to

01:17:38.320 --> 01:17:44.800
every moderately affluent political or ethnological group. Mick's idea seems to be that the drive

01:17:44.800 --> 01:17:52.000
system will make colonization feasible on a mass basic understructure, and hence no longer a monopoly

01:17:52.000 --> 01:17:59.200
of specific governments. Nina Freed clicked off and runs her to lean back in his leather and

01:17:59.200 --> 01:18:05.120
walnut swivel chair to ponder. What are you thinking, Ms. Wirt asked brightly?

01:18:06.240 --> 01:18:13.680
I'm wondering, Runciter said, if you can afford our services. Since I have no test data to go on,

01:18:13.680 --> 01:18:20.240
I can only estimate how many inertials you'll need, but it may run as high as forty.

01:18:21.360 --> 01:18:25.840
He said this knowing that Stanton Mick could afford or could figure out how to get someone

01:18:25.840 --> 01:18:29.280
else to underwrite an unlimited number of inertials.

01:18:30.400 --> 01:18:38.080
Forty, Ms. Wirt echoed. That is quite a few. The more we make you sell, the sooner we can get the

01:18:38.080 --> 01:18:45.200
job done. Since you're in a hurry, we'll move them all in at one time. If you were authorized to sign

01:18:45.200 --> 01:18:51.200
a work contract in the name of your employer, he pointed a steady, unyielding finger at her.

01:18:51.200 --> 01:18:56.960
She did not blink. And you can come up with a retainer now. We could probably accomplish

01:18:56.960 --> 01:19:04.320
this within seventy-two hours. He eyed her, then, waiting. The Micro Speaker in his ear rasped.

01:19:05.200 --> 01:19:10.560
As owner of tech-prize, she is fully bonded. She can legally obligate her firm up to and

01:19:10.560 --> 01:19:16.560
including its total worth. Right now, she is calculating how much this would be if converted

01:19:16.560 --> 01:19:24.560
on today's market. A pause. Several billion pause-creds, she has decided, but she doesn't

01:19:24.560 --> 01:19:29.760
want to do this. She doesn't like the idea of committing herself to both a contract and retainer.

01:19:29.760 --> 01:19:34.240
She would prefer to have Mick's attorneys do that, even if it means several days delay.

01:19:35.600 --> 01:19:42.000
But they're in a hurry, Runster reflected, or so they say. The Micro Speaker said,

01:19:42.720 --> 01:19:47.440
She has an intuition that you know or have guessed whom she represents,

01:19:47.440 --> 01:19:54.080
and she's afraid you'll up your fee accordingly. Mick knows his reputation. He considers himself

01:19:54.080 --> 01:20:00.800
the world's greatest mark. So he negotiates in this manner through someone or some firm as a front.

01:20:01.680 --> 01:20:06.320
On the other hand, they want as many inertials as they can get, and they're resigned to that being

01:20:06.400 --> 01:20:07.600
enormously expensive.

01:20:09.440 --> 01:20:16.320
Forty inertials, Runster said idly. He scratched with his pen at a small sheet of blank paper

01:20:16.320 --> 01:20:26.480
on his desk for just such purposes. Let's see, six times fifty times three times forty.

01:20:27.520 --> 01:20:31.440
Miss Wirt's still smiling, her glazed happy smile waited with visible tension.

01:20:32.400 --> 01:20:37.040
I wonder, he murmured, who paid Hollis to put his employees in the middle of your project?

01:20:38.080 --> 01:20:42.560
That doesn't really matter, does it? Miss Wirt said, what matters is that they're there.

01:20:43.600 --> 01:20:50.560
Runster said, Sometimes one never finds out. But as you say, it's the same as when aunts find

01:20:50.560 --> 01:20:55.760
their way into your kitchen. You don't ask why they're there, you just begin the job of getting

01:20:55.760 --> 01:21:02.080
them back out. He had arrived at a cost figure. It was enormous.

01:21:04.320 --> 01:21:10.160
I'll have to think it over, Miss Wirt said. She raised her eyes from the shocking sight of

01:21:10.160 --> 01:21:16.640
his estimate and half rose to her feet. Is there somewhere, an office, where I can be alone,

01:21:16.640 --> 01:21:23.360
and possibly phone Mr. Howard? Runster, her also rising, said it rare for any prudent

01:21:23.360 --> 01:21:29.280
organization to have that many inertials available at one time. If you wait, the situation will

01:21:29.280 --> 01:21:34.960
change. So if you want them, you'd better act. And you think it would really take that many

01:21:34.960 --> 01:21:40.560
inertials? Taking Miss Wirt by the arm, he led her from his office and down the hall to the firm's

01:21:40.560 --> 01:21:46.800
map room. This shows, he told her, the location of our inertials plus the inertials of other

01:21:46.800 --> 01:21:53.040
prudent organizations. In addition to that, it shows, or tries to show, the location of all

01:21:53.040 --> 01:21:59.680
of Hollis's scy's. He systematically counted the scy ident flags, which one by one had been

01:21:59.680 --> 01:22:04.480
removed from the map. He wound up holding the final one, that of S. Dole, Melopone.

01:22:05.520 --> 01:22:10.960
I know now where they are, he said to Miss Wirt, who had lost her mechanical smile as she

01:22:10.960 --> 01:22:16.880
comprehended the significance of the unpositioned ident flags. Taking hold of her damp hand,

01:22:16.880 --> 01:22:21.760
he deposited Melopone's flag among her damp fingers and closed them around it.

01:22:22.720 --> 01:22:28.480
You can stay here and meditate, he said. There's a vid phone over there, he pointed.

01:22:28.480 --> 01:22:33.120
No one will bother you, I'll be in my office. He left the map room, thinking,

01:22:33.680 --> 01:22:38.080
I really don't know that this is where they are, all those missing scy's, but it's possible.

01:22:39.040 --> 01:22:46.080
And Stanton Mick had waived the routine procedure of making an objective test. Therefore, if he

01:22:46.080 --> 01:22:50.960
wound up hiring inertials which he did not need, it would be his own fault.

01:22:52.640 --> 01:22:57.600
Legalistically speaking, Runster Associates was required to notify the society that some of the

01:22:57.600 --> 01:23:04.240
missing scy's, if not all, had been found, but he had five days in which to file the notification,

01:23:04.240 --> 01:23:10.880
and he decided to wait until the last day. This kind of business opportunity he reflected happens

01:23:10.880 --> 01:23:12.080
once in a lifetime.

01:23:13.360 --> 01:23:18.960
Mrs. Frick, he said, entering her outer office, type up a work contract specifying forty.

01:23:19.920 --> 01:23:27.280
He broke off. Across the room sat two persons. The man, Joe Chipp, looked haggard and hung over

01:23:27.280 --> 01:23:34.480
and more than usually glum. Looked, in fact, about as always, the glumness accepted. But beside him

01:23:34.480 --> 01:23:42.080
lounged a long-legged girl with brilliant tumbling black hair and eyes. Her intense distilled beauty

01:23:42.080 --> 01:23:47.280
illuminated that part of the room, igniting it with heavy sullen fire. It was, he thought,

01:23:47.280 --> 01:23:53.280
as if the girl resisted being attractive, disliked the smoothness of her skin and the sensual,

01:23:53.280 --> 01:24:00.400
swollen dark quality of her lips. She looks, he thought, as if she just now got out of bed,

01:24:00.480 --> 01:24:04.880
still disordered, resentful of the day, in fact of every day.

01:24:06.240 --> 01:24:08.480
Walking over to the two of them, Runciter said,

01:24:09.200 --> 01:24:11.920
I gather G.G. is back from Topeka.

01:24:12.880 --> 01:24:20.320
This is Pat, Joe Chipp said, no last name. He indicated Runciter then sighed. He had a peculiar

01:24:20.320 --> 01:24:27.040
defeated quality hanging over him. And yet, underneath, he did not seem to have given up.

01:24:27.040 --> 01:24:33.440
A vague and ragged hint of vitality lurked behind the resignation. It seemed to Runciter that Joe

01:24:33.440 --> 01:24:40.080
most nearly could be accused of feigning spiritual downfall. The real article, however, was not there.

01:24:41.680 --> 01:24:47.680
Anti-what, Runciter asked the girl, who still sat sprawling in her chair, legs extended.

01:24:47.680 --> 01:24:52.720
The girl murmured, anti-ketogenesis. What does that mean?

01:24:53.680 --> 01:24:59.360
The prevention of ketosis, the girl said remotely, as by the administration of glucose.

01:25:00.640 --> 01:25:07.280
To Joe, Runciter said, explain. Give Mr. Runciter your test, she, Joe said to the girl.

01:25:08.240 --> 01:25:12.080
Sitting up, the girl reached for her purse, rummaged, then produced one of Joe's wrinkled

01:25:12.080 --> 01:25:16.320
yellow score sheets, which she unfolded, glanced at, and passed to Runciter.

01:25:16.480 --> 01:25:23.280
Amazing score, Runciter said. Is she really this good, he asked Joe.

01:25:24.400 --> 01:25:31.600
And then he saw the two underlined crosses, the graphic symbol of indictment, of, in fact, treachery.

01:25:32.640 --> 01:25:35.280
She's the best so far, Joe said.

01:25:36.160 --> 01:25:41.840
Come in my office, Runciter said to the girl. He led the way, and behind him the two of them followed.

01:25:41.840 --> 01:25:46.960
Fat Miss Wirtz, all at once breathless, her eyes rolling, appeared.

01:25:47.600 --> 01:25:52.400
I phoned Mr. Howard, she informed Runciter. He has now given me my instruction. She,

01:25:52.400 --> 01:25:57.520
thereupon, perceived Joe Chip and the girl named Pat. For an instant she hesitated,

01:25:57.520 --> 01:26:02.160
then plunged on. Mr. Howard would like the formal arrangements made right away.

01:26:02.160 --> 01:26:07.120
So may we go ahead now? I've already acquainted you with the urgency, the time factor.

01:26:07.840 --> 01:26:10.560
She smiled, her glassy, determined smile.

01:26:10.560 --> 01:26:16.080
You too, mind-waiting? She asked him. My business with Mr. Rumpsters of a priority nature.

01:26:17.680 --> 01:26:22.800
Glancing at her, Pat laughed. A low, throaty laugh of contempt.

01:26:24.080 --> 01:26:29.680
You'll have to wait, Miss Wirtz. Runciter said. He felt afraid. He looked at Pat,

01:26:29.680 --> 01:26:31.920
then at Joe, and his fear quickened.

01:26:32.880 --> 01:26:38.080
To sit down, Miss Wirtz, he said to her, and indicated one of the outer office chairs.

01:26:38.880 --> 01:26:43.840
Miss Wirtz said, I can tell you exactly, Mr. Runciter, how many inertials we intend to take.

01:26:43.840 --> 01:26:48.000
Mr. Howard feels he can make an adequate determination of our needs, of our problem.

01:26:48.560 --> 01:26:50.000
How many? Runciter asked.

01:26:50.640 --> 01:26:52.160
Eleven, Miss Wirtz said.

01:26:53.360 --> 01:26:57.440
We'll sign the contract in a little while, Runciter said, as soon as I'm free.

01:26:58.240 --> 01:27:02.480
With his big, wide hand, he guided Joe and the girl into his inner office.

01:27:02.480 --> 01:27:04.640
He shut the door behind them and seated himself.

01:27:05.760 --> 01:27:10.560
They'll never make it, he said to Joe, with eleven or fifteen or twenty,

01:27:10.560 --> 01:27:13.920
especially not with Est Dolm Mellopone involved on the other side.

01:27:14.720 --> 01:27:16.720
He felt tired, as well as afraid.

01:27:18.000 --> 01:27:22.800
This is, as I assume, the potential trainee that G.G. scouted in Topeka.

01:27:23.440 --> 01:27:26.720
And you believe we should hire her? Both you and G.G. agree?

01:27:27.520 --> 01:27:29.680
Then we'll hire her, naturally.

01:27:30.560 --> 01:27:34.480
And maybe I'll turn her over to Mick, he said to himself, make her one of the eleven.

01:27:35.520 --> 01:27:40.800
Nobody has managed to tell me yet, he said, which of the sigh talents she counters.

01:27:41.920 --> 01:27:45.040
Mrs. Frick says you flew to Zurich, Joe said.

01:27:45.040 --> 01:27:46.000
What did Ella suggest?

01:27:46.560 --> 01:27:49.920
More ads, Runciter said, on TV every hour.

01:27:50.880 --> 01:27:52.000
Into his intercom, he said,

01:27:52.640 --> 01:27:57.680
Mrs. Frick, draw up an agreement of employment, pre-in-ourselves and a Jane Doe.

01:27:58.240 --> 01:28:02.320
Specify the starting salary that we in the Union agreed on last December.

01:28:02.320 --> 01:28:03.120
Specify-

01:28:03.120 --> 01:28:06.560
What is the starting salary? the girl Pat asked.

01:28:06.560 --> 01:28:11.520
Her voice suffused with sardonic suspicion of a cheap, childish sort.

01:28:12.640 --> 01:28:13.920
Runciter eyed her.

01:28:14.560 --> 01:28:16.080
I don't even know what you can do.

01:28:16.720 --> 01:28:21.440
It's pre-cog, Glen, Joe Chip grated, but in a different way.

01:28:22.400 --> 01:28:27.760
He did not elaborate. He seemed to have run down like an old-time battery-powered watch.

01:28:28.880 --> 01:28:32.000
Is she ready to go to work? Runciter asked Joe.

01:28:32.000 --> 01:28:35.120
Or is this one we have to train and work with and wait for?

01:28:35.840 --> 01:28:39.360
We've got almost forty idle inertials and we're hiring another.

01:28:40.080 --> 01:28:42.400
Forty, lest I suppose eleven.

01:28:42.400 --> 01:28:47.680
Thirty idle employees all drawing full scale while they sit around with their thumbs in their noses.

01:28:48.960 --> 01:28:51.120
I don't know, Joe, I really don't.

01:28:51.680 --> 01:28:53.520
Maybe we ought to fire our scouts.

01:28:54.800 --> 01:28:59.440
Anyway, I think I found the rest of Hollis's size. I'll tell you about it later.

01:29:00.160 --> 01:29:01.280
Into his intercom, he said,

01:29:01.920 --> 01:29:05.520
Specify that we can discharge this Jane Doe without notice,

01:29:05.520 --> 01:29:10.240
without severance, pay or compensation of any kind, nor is she eligible for the first

01:29:10.240 --> 01:29:13.040
ninety days for pension health or sick pay benefits.

01:29:13.920 --> 01:29:14.800
To Pat, he said,

01:29:15.440 --> 01:29:19.680
Starting salary in all cases begins at 400 credits per month,

01:29:19.680 --> 01:29:21.280
figuring on twenty hours a week.

01:29:21.920 --> 01:29:23.680
And you'll have to join a union.

01:29:23.680 --> 01:29:26.400
The Mill, Mine and Smelter Workers Union.

01:29:26.400 --> 01:29:30.880
They're the one that signed up all the Prudence Organization employees three years ago.

01:29:30.880 --> 01:29:32.320
I have no control over that.

01:29:33.280 --> 01:29:38.400
I get more, Pat said, maintaining vid-phone relays at the Topeka Kibbutz.

01:29:38.400 --> 01:29:40.320
Your scout, Mr. Ashwood, said,

01:29:40.320 --> 01:29:43.280
Our scouts lie, Runciter said.

01:29:44.240 --> 01:29:47.600
And in addition, we're not legally bound by anything they say.

01:29:47.600 --> 01:29:49.520
No Prudence Organization is.

01:29:50.480 --> 01:29:55.040
The office door opened and Mrs. Frick crept unsteadily in with the typed-out agreement.

01:29:55.600 --> 01:29:58.960
Thank you, Mrs. Frick, Runciter said, accepting the papers.

01:30:00.160 --> 01:30:04.560
I have a twenty-year-old wife in cold Pat, he said to Joe and Pat.

01:30:04.560 --> 01:30:10.080
A beautiful woman who, when she talks to me, gets pushed out of the way by some weird kid named Jory.

01:30:10.080 --> 01:30:11.760
Then I'm talking to him, not her.

01:30:12.560 --> 01:30:15.280
Ella frozen in half-life and dimming out.

01:30:15.840 --> 01:30:20.480
And that battered crone for my secretary that I have to look at all day long.

01:30:21.920 --> 01:30:26.720
He gazed at the girl, Pat, with her black, strong hair and her sensual mouth.

01:30:27.520 --> 01:30:32.720
In him he felt unhappy cravings arise, cloudy and pointless wants,

01:30:33.520 --> 01:30:36.880
that led nowhere that returned to him empty,

01:30:36.880 --> 01:30:40.240
as in the completion of a geometrically perfect circle.

01:30:41.760 --> 01:30:45.760
I'll sign, Pat said, and reached for the desk pen.

01:30:48.720 --> 01:30:49.040
Five

01:30:50.960 --> 01:30:54.000
Can't make the Frug contest, Helen. Stomach's upset.

01:30:54.000 --> 01:30:58.080
I'll fix you, Ubik. Ubik dropped you back in the thick of things fast.

01:30:58.080 --> 01:31:01.200
Taking his directed, Ubik speeds relief to head and stomach.

01:31:01.200 --> 01:31:05.520
Remember, Ubik is only seconds away. Avoid prolonged use.

01:31:06.240 --> 01:31:12.560
During the long days of forced unnatural idleness, the antitellopath, Tippi Jackson,

01:31:12.560 --> 01:31:18.880
slept regularly until noon. An electrode planted within her brain perpetually stimulated e-rem,

01:31:18.880 --> 01:31:24.320
extremely rapid eye movement, sleep. So while tucked within the percale sheets of her bed,

01:31:24.320 --> 01:31:29.600
she had plenty to do. At this particular moment, her artificially-induced dream state centered

01:31:29.600 --> 01:31:34.160
around the mythical Hollis Functionary endowed with enormous psionic powers.

01:31:34.800 --> 01:31:40.160
Every other inertial in the Sol system had either given up or been melted down into lard.

01:31:40.160 --> 01:31:45.520
By process of elimination, the task of nullifying the field generated by this supernatural entity

01:31:45.520 --> 01:31:46.800
had devolved to her.

01:31:47.440 --> 01:31:51.760
I can't be myself while you're around, her nebulous opponent informed her.

01:31:52.320 --> 01:31:58.160
On his face a feral, hateful expression formed, giving him the appearance of a psychotic squirrel.

01:31:59.040 --> 01:32:00.880
In her dream, Tippi answered,

01:32:00.880 --> 01:32:05.200
Perhaps your definition of your self-system lacks authentic boundaries.

01:32:05.200 --> 01:32:09.680
You've erected a precarious structure of personality on unconscious factors of which

01:32:09.680 --> 01:32:12.400
you have no control. That's why you feel threatened by me.

01:32:12.960 --> 01:32:15.520
Aren't you an employee of a prudence organization?

01:32:15.520 --> 01:32:18.560
The Hollis telepath demanded, looking nervously about.

01:32:19.120 --> 01:32:21.920
If you're the stupendous talent you claim to be,

01:32:21.920 --> 01:32:24.880
Tippi said, you can tell that by reading my mind.

01:32:24.880 --> 01:32:26.880
I can't read anybody's mind.

01:32:26.880 --> 01:32:29.920
The telepath said, My talent is gone.

01:32:29.920 --> 01:32:31.600
I'll let you talk to my brother, Bill.

01:32:31.600 --> 01:32:33.760
Here, Bill, talk to this lady.

01:32:33.760 --> 01:32:34.960
Do you like this lady?

01:32:35.760 --> 01:32:38.800
Bill, looking more or less like his brother, the telepath said,

01:32:38.800 --> 01:32:42.960
I like her fine because I'm a precog and she doesn't post-grip me.

01:32:43.680 --> 01:32:48.640
He shuffled his feet and grinned, revealing great pale teeth as blunt as shovels.

01:32:49.200 --> 01:32:52.560
I then am curtailed of this fair proportion,

01:32:52.560 --> 01:32:55.200
cheated of feature by dissembling nature.

01:32:56.000 --> 01:32:58.400
He paused, wrinkling his forehead.

01:32:58.400 --> 01:33:01.200
How does it go, Matt? he asked his brother.

01:33:01.200 --> 01:33:04.400
Disarmed, unfinished, sent before my time into this

01:33:04.400 --> 01:33:06.800
breeding world scarce half made up.

01:33:06.800 --> 01:33:08.960
Matt, the squirrel-like telepath, said,

01:33:08.960 --> 01:33:10.880
scratching meditatively at his pelt.

01:33:11.440 --> 01:33:13.920
Oh, yeah, Bill the precog nodded.

01:33:13.920 --> 01:33:14.480
I remember.

01:33:15.120 --> 01:33:20.240
And that's solingly and unfashionable that dogs bark at me as I halt by them.

01:33:20.880 --> 01:33:24.320
From Richard the Third, he explained to Tippi,

01:33:24.320 --> 01:33:25.600
both brothers grinned.

01:33:26.240 --> 01:33:30.880
Even their incisors were blunt as if they lived on a diet of uncooked seeds.

01:33:31.520 --> 01:33:33.440
Tippi said, was that mean?

01:33:34.240 --> 01:33:39.040
It means, both Matt and Bill said in unison, that we're gonna get you.

01:33:40.240 --> 01:33:42.320
The vid-phone rang, waking Tippi up.

01:33:43.440 --> 01:33:47.600
Stumbling groggily to it, confounded by floating colored bubbles,

01:33:47.600 --> 01:33:50.080
blinking, she lifted the receiver and said,

01:33:50.080 --> 01:33:53.920
Hello? God, it's late, she thought, seeing the clock.

01:33:54.000 --> 01:33:55.600
I'm turning into a vegetable.

01:33:56.400 --> 01:33:59.120
Glenn Runceter's face emerged on the screen.

01:33:59.120 --> 01:34:00.800
Hello, Mr. Runceter?

01:34:00.800 --> 01:34:03.680
She said, standing out of sight of the phone scanner.

01:34:03.680 --> 01:34:05.360
Has her job turned up for me?

01:34:06.000 --> 01:34:08.320
Ah, Mrs. Jackson, Runceter said.

01:34:08.320 --> 01:34:09.520
I'm glad I caught you.

01:34:10.080 --> 01:34:13.040
The group is forming under Joe Chips in my direction.

01:34:13.040 --> 01:34:14.560
Eleven, in all.

01:34:14.560 --> 01:34:17.120
Major work assignment for those we choose.

01:34:17.120 --> 01:34:21.520
We've been examining everyone's history, and Joe thinks yours looks good,

01:34:21.520 --> 01:34:23.280
and I tend to agree.

01:34:23.280 --> 01:34:25.040
How long will it take you to get down here?

01:34:25.760 --> 01:34:28.480
His tone seemed adequately optimistic,

01:34:28.480 --> 01:34:32.320
but on the little screen his face looked hard-pressed and care-worn.

01:34:33.200 --> 01:34:36.400
Tippi said, for this one, will I be living?

01:34:36.400 --> 01:34:37.440
Yes, you'll have to pack.

01:34:38.000 --> 01:34:41.920
Chidingly, he said, we're supposed to be packed and ready to go at all times.

01:34:41.920 --> 01:34:44.320
That's a rule I don't ever want broken,

01:34:44.320 --> 01:34:47.120
especially in a case like this where there's a time factor.

01:34:47.120 --> 01:34:48.160
I am packed.

01:34:48.800 --> 01:34:51.280
I'll be at the New York office in fifteen minutes.

01:34:51.280 --> 01:34:54.240
All I have to do is leave a note to my husband, who's at work.

01:34:54.240 --> 01:34:55.360
Well, okay.

01:34:55.360 --> 01:34:57.520
Runceter said, looking preoccupied,

01:34:57.520 --> 01:35:00.720
he was probably already reading the next name on his list.

01:35:01.360 --> 01:35:02.720
Goodbye, Mrs. Jackson.

01:35:02.720 --> 01:35:03.520
He rang off.

01:35:04.480 --> 01:35:07.280
That was a strange dream, she thought,

01:35:07.280 --> 01:35:09.440
as she hastily unbuttoned her pajamas

01:35:09.440 --> 01:35:11.520
and hurried back into the bedroom for her clothes.

01:35:12.240 --> 01:35:15.120
What did Bill and Matt say that poetry was from?

01:35:15.840 --> 01:35:19.280
Richard III, she remembered, seeing in her mind

01:35:19.280 --> 01:35:22.960
once more their flat, big teeth, their unformed, knob-like,

01:35:22.960 --> 01:35:26.000
identical heads with tufts of reddish hair growing from them,

01:35:26.000 --> 01:35:27.360
like patches of weeds.

01:35:28.080 --> 01:35:31.120
I don't think I've ever read Richard III, she realized.

01:35:31.680 --> 01:35:35.120
Or if I did, it must have been years ago when I was a child.

01:35:36.000 --> 01:35:40.640
How can you dream lines of poetry you don't know? she asked herself.

01:35:41.840 --> 01:35:46.400
Maybe an actual non-dream telepath was getting at me while I slept,

01:35:46.400 --> 01:35:48.720
or a telepath and a precog working together.

01:35:49.280 --> 01:35:50.800
The way I saw them in my dream.

01:35:51.600 --> 01:35:54.320
It might be a good idea to ask our research department

01:35:54.320 --> 01:35:56.800
whether Hollis does, by any remote chance,

01:35:56.800 --> 01:35:59.520
employ a brother team named Matt and Bill.

01:36:00.640 --> 01:36:05.040
Puzzled and uneasy, she began as quickly as possible to dress.

01:36:07.280 --> 01:36:10.400
Lighting a green, all-Havana-quest-a-ray, Palmer Supreme,

01:36:10.400 --> 01:36:13.200
Glenn runs for the lean-back in his noble chair,

01:36:13.200 --> 01:36:15.280
pressed a button of his intercom and said,

01:36:15.920 --> 01:36:18.000
Make out a bounty-check, Mrs. Frick.

01:36:18.000 --> 01:36:21.440
Payable to G.G. Ashwood for one hundred POSCRADS.

01:36:21.440 --> 01:36:22.880
Yes, Mr. Runciter.

01:36:23.760 --> 01:36:28.640
He watched G.G. Ashwood, who paced with manic restlessness about the big office,

01:36:28.640 --> 01:36:30.960
with its genuine hardwood floor,

01:36:30.960 --> 01:36:34.080
against which G.G.'s feet clacked, irritatingly.

01:36:34.960 --> 01:36:38.640
Joe Chip can't seem to tell me what she does, Runciter said.

01:36:39.280 --> 01:36:41.280
Joe Chip is a grunk, G.G. said.

01:36:42.080 --> 01:36:47.120
How come she—this pat—can travel back into time, and no one else can?

01:36:47.680 --> 01:36:49.680
Now, bet this talent isn't new.

01:36:50.320 --> 01:36:53.280
You scouts probably just missed noticing it up till now.

01:36:54.240 --> 01:36:57.360
Anyhow, it's not logical for a prudent's organization to hire her.

01:36:57.360 --> 01:36:59.440
It's a talent, not an anti-talent.

01:36:59.440 --> 01:37:00.160
We deal in—

01:37:00.160 --> 01:37:02.880
As I explained, and as Joe indicated on the test report,

01:37:02.880 --> 01:37:04.960
it aborts the precogs out of business.

01:37:05.520 --> 01:37:09.600
But that's only a side effect, Runciter pondered moodily.

01:37:10.560 --> 01:37:12.480
Joe thinks she's dangerous.

01:37:12.480 --> 01:37:13.760
I don't know why.

01:37:13.760 --> 01:37:14.800
Did you ask him why?

01:37:15.440 --> 01:37:16.160
Runciter said,

01:37:16.880 --> 01:37:19.120
He mumble the way he always does.

01:37:19.680 --> 01:37:22.080
Joe never has reasons, just hunches.

01:37:22.640 --> 01:37:25.600
On the other hand, he wants to include her in the mick operation.

01:37:26.400 --> 01:37:30.880
He shuffled through, rooted among, and rearranged the personnel department documents

01:37:30.880 --> 01:37:32.000
before him on his desk.

01:37:32.960 --> 01:37:37.520
Ask Joe to come in here so we can see if we've got our group of eleven set up.

01:37:38.320 --> 01:37:39.520
He examined his watch.

01:37:39.520 --> 01:37:41.120
They should be arriving about now.

01:37:41.680 --> 01:37:46.640
I'm going to tell Joe to his face that he's crazy to include this pat Conley girl if she's

01:37:46.640 --> 01:37:48.480
so dangerous, wouldn't you say, Gigi?

01:37:49.280 --> 01:37:50.800
Gigi Ashwood said,

01:37:50.800 --> 01:37:52.000
He's got a thing going with her.

01:37:52.800 --> 01:37:54.160
What sort of thing?

01:37:54.160 --> 01:37:55.520
A sexual understanding.

01:37:56.400 --> 01:37:59.200
Joe has no sexual understanding.

01:37:59.840 --> 01:38:03.760
Nina Fried read his mind the other day, and he's too poor even to—

01:38:04.480 --> 01:38:07.120
He broke off because the office door had opened.

01:38:07.120 --> 01:38:11.520
Mrs. Frick teetered her way in, carrying Gigi's bounty check for him to sign.

01:38:12.240 --> 01:38:15.120
I know why he wants her along on the mick operation,

01:38:15.120 --> 01:38:18.080
Runciter said, as he scratched his signature on the check.

01:38:18.640 --> 01:38:19.840
He can keep an eye on her.

01:38:20.400 --> 01:38:21.280
He's going too.

01:38:21.840 --> 01:38:25.760
He's going to measure the scyfield despite what the client stipulated.

01:38:25.760 --> 01:38:27.600
We have to know what we're up against.

01:38:27.600 --> 01:38:29.200
Thank you, Ms. Frick.

01:38:29.200 --> 01:38:32.240
He waved her away and held the check out to Gigi Ashwood.

01:38:32.800 --> 01:38:36.880
Suppose we don't measure the scyfield, and it turns out to be too intense for our

01:38:36.880 --> 01:38:38.160
inertials. Who gets blamed?

01:38:38.720 --> 01:38:40.080
We do, Gigi said.

01:38:40.720 --> 01:38:42.640
I told him eleven wasn't enough.

01:38:43.440 --> 01:38:45.760
We're supplying our best, we're doing the best we can.

01:38:46.560 --> 01:38:51.200
After all, getting stent and micks patronage is a matter of great importance to us.

01:38:52.160 --> 01:38:59.440
Amazing that someone as wealthy and powerful as mick could be so short-sighted, so goddamn miserly.

01:39:00.240 --> 01:39:02.240
Ms. Frick is Joe out there, Joe Chip.

01:39:02.880 --> 01:39:08.160
Mrs. Frick said, Mr. Chip is in the outer office with a number of other people.

01:39:08.160 --> 01:39:10.320
How many other people, Ms. Frick? Ten or eleven?

01:39:10.960 --> 01:39:13.680
I'd say about that many.

01:39:13.680 --> 01:39:16.320
Mr. Runciter, give or take one or two.

01:39:17.200 --> 01:39:20.560
To Gigi Ashwood, Runciter said, that's the group.

01:39:20.560 --> 01:39:24.080
I want to see them, all of them, together before they leave for Luna.

01:39:24.720 --> 01:39:26.880
To Mrs. Frick, he said, send the men.

01:39:27.520 --> 01:39:30.240
He puffed vigorously on his green-wrapped cigar.

01:39:30.960 --> 01:39:32.240
She gyrated out.

01:39:33.040 --> 01:39:40.000
We know, Runciter said to Gigi, that as individuals they perform well, it's all down here on paper.

01:39:40.000 --> 01:39:42.320
He rattled the documents on his desk.

01:39:42.320 --> 01:39:43.600
But how about together?

01:39:44.160 --> 01:39:47.840
How great a Polly and Cephalic counterfield will they generate together?

01:39:47.840 --> 01:39:50.800
Ask yourself that, Gigi. That is the question to ask.

01:39:51.360 --> 01:39:54.000
I guess time will tell, Gigi Ashwood said.

01:39:54.720 --> 01:39:58.160
I've been in this business a long time, Runciter said.

01:39:58.720 --> 01:40:00.880
From the outer office people began to file in.

01:40:01.440 --> 01:40:05.360
This is my contribution to contemporary civilization.

01:40:06.000 --> 01:40:08.080
That puts it well, Gigi said.

01:40:08.080 --> 01:40:10.240
You're a policeman guarding human privacy.

01:40:10.800 --> 01:40:14.160
You know what Ray Hollis says about us, Runciter said.

01:40:14.720 --> 01:40:16.880
He says we're trying to turn the clock back.

01:40:17.600 --> 01:40:20.720
He eyed the individuals who had begun to fill up his office.

01:40:20.720 --> 01:40:23.680
They gathered near one another, none of them speaking.

01:40:23.680 --> 01:40:24.640
They waited for him.

01:40:25.680 --> 01:40:29.600
What an ill assorted bunch, he thought pessimistically.

01:40:30.240 --> 01:40:34.640
A young string bean of a girl with glasses and straight lemon yellow hair,

01:40:34.640 --> 01:40:39.360
wearing a cowboy hat, black lace mantilla, and Bermuda shorts, that would be Edie Dorn.

01:40:40.320 --> 01:40:43.920
A good-looking older dark woman with tricky deranged eyes,

01:40:43.920 --> 01:40:47.520
who wore a silk sari and nylon obi and bobby socks.

01:40:47.520 --> 01:40:49.280
Francy, something.

01:40:49.280 --> 01:40:52.960
A part-time schizophrenic who imagined that sentient beings from

01:40:52.960 --> 01:40:56.800
beetle Jews occasionally landed on the roof of her conap building.

01:40:59.040 --> 01:41:04.240
A woolly-haired adolescent boy wrapped in a superior and cynical cloud of pride,

01:41:04.240 --> 01:41:08.880
this one in a floral moo-moo and spandex bloomers Runciter had never encountered before.

01:41:09.440 --> 01:41:10.320
And so it went.

01:41:10.320 --> 01:41:13.920
Five females and, he counted, five males.

01:41:14.560 --> 01:41:15.680
Someone was missing.

01:41:15.760 --> 01:41:21.280
Ahead of Joe Chip, the smoldering, brooding girl Patricia Conley entered.

01:41:22.240 --> 01:41:23.520
That made the eleventh.

01:41:23.520 --> 01:41:25.040
The group had all appeared.

01:41:26.080 --> 01:41:28.480
You made good time, Mrs. Jackson.

01:41:28.480 --> 01:41:32.080
He said to the manish, thirty-ish, sand-colored lady wearing

01:41:32.080 --> 01:41:35.280
ear-sets by Cunha trousers and a gray sweatshirt,

01:41:35.280 --> 01:41:39.520
on which had been printed a now faded, full-face portrait of Bertrand Lord Russell.

01:41:40.080 --> 01:41:44.000
You had less time than anybody else in as much as I notified you last.

01:41:44.720 --> 01:41:47.760
Tippi Jackson smiled a bloodless, sand-colored smile.

01:41:48.880 --> 01:41:53.920
Some of you, I know, Runciter said, rising from his chair and indicating with his hands

01:41:53.920 --> 01:41:57.920
that they should find chairs and make themselves comfortable, smoking, if necessary.

01:41:58.640 --> 01:42:03.680
You, Miss Dawn, Mr. Chip and I chose you first because of your top notch activity

01:42:03.680 --> 01:42:08.560
vis-à-vis Est-dol-Mellaphone, whom you eventually lost through no fault of your own.

01:42:09.280 --> 01:42:10.800
Thank you, Mr. Runciter.

01:42:11.360 --> 01:42:14.960
Edie Dawn said in a wispy, shy trickle of a voice.

01:42:14.960 --> 01:42:17.760
She blushed and stared wide-eyed at the far wall.

01:42:18.640 --> 01:42:24.320
It's good to be a part of this new undertaking, she added, with undernourished conviction.

01:42:25.280 --> 01:42:29.520
Which one of you is Al Hammond? Runciter asked, consulting his documents.

01:42:30.480 --> 01:42:37.040
An excessively tall, stoop-shouldered negro with a gentle expression on his elongated face

01:42:37.040 --> 01:42:38.960
made a motion to indicate himself.

01:42:39.680 --> 01:42:44.400
I've never met you before, Runciter said, reading the material from Al Hammond's file.

01:42:44.960 --> 01:42:50.400
You rate highest among our anti-precogs. I should, of course, have gotten around meeting you.

01:42:50.400 --> 01:42:55.120
How many of the rest of you are anti-precog? Three additional hands appeared.

01:42:55.680 --> 01:43:00.640
The four of you, Runciter said, will undoubtedly get a great bloop out of meeting and working

01:43:00.640 --> 01:43:06.560
with G. G. Ashwood's most recent discovery, who aborts pre-cogs on a new basis.

01:43:07.600 --> 01:43:12.080
Perhaps Ms. Connolly herself will describe it to us, he nodded toward Pat,

01:43:13.600 --> 01:43:18.800
and found himself standing before Shop Window on Fifth Avenue, a rare coin shop.

01:43:19.440 --> 01:43:24.320
He was studying an uncirculated U.S. gold dollar and wondering if he could afford to

01:43:24.320 --> 01:43:29.520
add it to his collection. What collection, he asked himself, startled.

01:43:30.080 --> 01:43:35.760
I don't collect coins. What am I doing here? And how long have I been wandering around window

01:43:35.760 --> 01:43:40.080
shopping when I ought to be in my office supervising? He could not remember what he

01:43:40.080 --> 01:43:46.560
generally supervised, a business of some kind, dealing in people with ability, special talents.

01:43:47.120 --> 01:43:53.200
He shut his eyes, trying to focus his mind. No, I had to give that up, he realized.

01:43:53.920 --> 01:44:00.240
Because of a coronary, last year I had to retire. But I was just there, he remembered,

01:44:00.240 --> 01:44:05.600
only a few seconds ago, in my office, talking to a group of people about a new project.

01:44:06.320 --> 01:44:13.280
He shut his eyes. It's gone, he thought, desidly. Everything I built up.

01:44:15.680 --> 01:44:20.720
When he opened his eyes he found himself back in his office. He faced G. G. Ashwood, Joe Chip,

01:44:20.720 --> 01:44:25.760
and a dark, intensely attractive girl whose name he did not recall.

01:44:26.720 --> 01:44:32.160
Other than that his office was empty, which, for reasons he did not understand,

01:44:32.160 --> 01:44:33.280
struck him as strange.

01:44:34.640 --> 01:44:38.640
Mr. Runciter, Joe Chip said, I'd like you to meet Patricia Conley.

01:44:39.280 --> 01:44:43.120
The girl said, How nice to be introduced to you at last, Mr. Runciter.

01:44:43.680 --> 01:44:48.160
She laughed, and her eyes flashed exultantly. Runciter did not know why.

01:44:48.480 --> 01:44:52.720
Joe Chip realized she's been doing something.

01:44:53.600 --> 01:44:57.920
Pat, he said aloud, I can't put my finger on it, but things are different.

01:44:58.560 --> 01:45:04.960
He gazed, wonderingly, around the office. It appeared, as it had always, too loud a carpet,

01:45:04.960 --> 01:45:11.120
too many unrelated art objects, on the walls, original pictures of no artistic merit, whatever.

01:45:11.840 --> 01:45:17.280
Glenn Runciter had not changed. Shaggy and gray, his face wrinkled broodingly.

01:45:17.280 --> 01:45:21.520
He returned. Joe's stare. He seemed too perplexed.

01:45:22.240 --> 01:45:25.440
Over by the window, G. G. Ashwood, wearing his customary,

01:45:25.440 --> 01:45:29.680
natty birchbark pantaloons, hemp rope belt, peek-a-boo see-through top,

01:45:29.680 --> 01:45:35.600
and train engineer's tall hat, shrugged indifferently. He obviously saw nothing wrong.

01:45:35.600 --> 01:45:38.640
Nothing is different, Pat said.

01:45:39.280 --> 01:45:45.360
Everything is different, Joe said to her. You must have gone back into time and put us on a different

01:45:45.360 --> 01:45:50.320
track. I can't prove it, and I can't specify the nature of the changes.

01:45:50.880 --> 01:45:55.200
No domestic quarreling on my time, Runciter said, frowningly.

01:45:56.480 --> 01:46:02.400
Joe, taken aback, said, domestic quarreling? He saw then, on Pat's finger, the ring.

01:46:03.120 --> 01:46:08.400
Rot Silver and Jade, he remembered helping her pick it out two days, he thought, before we got

01:46:08.400 --> 01:46:15.680
married. That was over a year ago, despite how bad off I was financially. That, of course,

01:46:15.680 --> 01:46:22.000
is changed now. Pat, with her salary and her money-minding propensity, fixed that, for all time.

01:46:23.360 --> 01:46:29.520
Anyhow, to continue, Runciter said. We must each of us ask ourselves why Stanton

01:46:29.520 --> 01:46:33.520
Mick took his business to a prudence organization other than ours.

01:46:34.320 --> 01:46:38.240
Logically, we should have gotten a contract. We're the finest in the business, and we're

01:46:38.240 --> 01:46:44.880
located in New York, where Mick generally prefers to deal. Do you have any theory, Mrs. Chip?

01:46:44.880 --> 01:46:48.160
He looked, hopefully, in Pat's direction. Pat said,

01:46:48.800 --> 01:46:50.960
Do you really want to know, Mr. Runciter?

01:46:51.520 --> 01:46:54.480
Yes, he nodded vigorously. I'd very much like to know.

01:46:55.440 --> 01:46:57.040
I did it, Pat said.

01:46:57.840 --> 01:47:01.280
How? With my talent? Runciter said,

01:47:01.280 --> 01:47:04.000
What talent? You don't have a talent. You're Joe Chip's wife.

01:47:04.880 --> 01:47:07.120
At the window, G.G. Ashwood said,

01:47:07.120 --> 01:47:08.880
You came in here to meet Joe and me for lunch.

01:47:09.680 --> 01:47:15.520
She has a talent, Joe said. He tried to remember, but already it had become foggy.

01:47:15.520 --> 01:47:18.400
The memory dimmed, even as he tried to resurrect it.

01:47:18.960 --> 01:47:22.320
A different time track, he thought, the past.

01:47:23.280 --> 01:47:26.800
Other than that, he could not make it out. There, the memory ended.

01:47:27.760 --> 01:47:33.120
My wife, he thought, is unique. She can do something no one else on earth can do.

01:47:34.240 --> 01:47:37.680
In that case, why isn't she working for Runciter's associates?

01:47:38.640 --> 01:47:39.680
Something is wrong.

01:47:40.720 --> 01:47:42.880
Have you measured it? Runciter asked him.

01:47:42.880 --> 01:47:46.720
I mean, that's your job. Your sound is if you have. Your sound sure of yourself.

01:47:47.680 --> 01:47:53.040
I'm not sure of myself, Joe said. But I am sure about my wife, he said to himself.

01:47:53.840 --> 01:47:58.640
I'll get my test gear, he said, and we'll see what sort of a fuel she creates.

01:47:58.640 --> 01:48:01.440
Oh, come on, Joe, Runciter said angrily.

01:48:01.440 --> 01:48:05.760
If your wife has a talent or an anti-talent, you would have measured it at least a year ago.

01:48:05.760 --> 01:48:10.160
You wouldn't be discovering it now. He pressed a button on his desk intercom.

01:48:10.720 --> 01:48:14.560
Personnel, do we have a file on Mrs. Chip, Patricia Chip?

01:48:15.520 --> 01:48:17.120
After a pause, the intercom said,

01:48:17.840 --> 01:48:20.800
No file on Mrs. Chip under her maiden name, perhaps?

01:48:21.760 --> 01:48:24.720
Conley, Joe said. Patricia Conley.

01:48:25.520 --> 01:48:26.480
Again, a pause.

01:48:27.520 --> 01:48:33.120
On Amos, Patricia Conley, we have two items, an initial scout report by Mr. Ashwood,

01:48:33.120 --> 01:48:35.200
and then test findings by Mr. Chip.

01:48:36.000 --> 01:48:40.480
From the slot of the intercom, reproves of the two documents slowly dribbled forth

01:48:40.480 --> 01:48:42.160
and dropped to the surface of the desk.

01:48:42.160 --> 01:48:46.400
Examin' Joe Chip's findings, Runciter said, scowling,

01:48:46.400 --> 01:48:48.960
Joe, you better look at this, come here.

01:48:49.520 --> 01:48:53.040
He jabbed a finger at the page, and Joe, coming over beside him,

01:48:53.040 --> 01:48:55.520
saw the twin underlined crosses.

01:48:56.400 --> 01:48:58.800
He and Runciter glanced at each other, then at Pat.

01:48:59.920 --> 01:49:02.560
I know what it reads, Pat said, levelly.

01:49:03.200 --> 01:49:06.880
Unbelievable power, anti-Sci-Field, unique in scope.

01:49:07.680 --> 01:49:11.840
She concentrated, trying visibly to remember the exact wording.

01:49:12.560 --> 01:49:13.520
Can probably—

01:49:14.160 --> 01:49:17.440
We did get the Mick contract, Runciter said to Joe Chip.

01:49:18.080 --> 01:49:23.200
I had a group of eleven in-nursals in here, and then I suggested to her—

01:49:23.920 --> 01:49:27.920
Joe said that she showed the group what she could do, so she did.

01:49:28.560 --> 01:49:31.920
She did exactly that, and my evaluation was right.

01:49:32.560 --> 01:49:36.000
With his fingertip he traced the symbols of danger at the bottom of the sheet.

01:49:36.720 --> 01:49:38.560
My own wife, he said.

01:49:39.440 --> 01:49:42.160
I'm not your wife, Pat said. I changed that, too.

01:49:42.800 --> 01:49:44.560
Do you want to go back the way it was?

01:49:44.560 --> 01:49:46.640
With no changes, not even in details?

01:49:47.440 --> 01:49:49.440
That won't show your in-nursals much.

01:49:50.160 --> 01:49:55.440
On the other hand, they're unaware, anyhow, unless some of them have retained a vestigial memory,

01:49:55.440 --> 01:49:56.480
as Joe has.

01:49:57.280 --> 01:49:59.120
By now, though, it should have phased out.

01:50:00.240 --> 01:50:04.880
Runciter said, bitingly, I'd like the Mick contract back, that much at least.

01:50:05.520 --> 01:50:08.960
When I scouted them, G.G. Ashwood said, I scouted them.

01:50:08.960 --> 01:50:10.160
He had become gray.

01:50:11.280 --> 01:50:14.240
Yes, you really bring in the talent, Runciter said.

01:50:15.200 --> 01:50:19.120
The intercom buzzed, and the quaking, elderly voice of Mrs. Frick grasped.

01:50:19.120 --> 01:50:23.680
A group of our in-nursals are waiting to see you, Mr. Runciter.

01:50:24.320 --> 01:50:28.800
They say you sent for them in connection with a new joint work project.

01:50:28.800 --> 01:50:30.000
Are you free to see them?

01:50:30.640 --> 01:50:32.240
Send them in, Runciter said.

01:50:33.040 --> 01:50:33.600
Pat said,

01:50:34.320 --> 01:50:35.600
I'll keep this ring.

01:50:36.480 --> 01:50:41.600
She displayed the silver and jade wedding ring, which in another time-track she and Joe had picked

01:50:41.600 --> 01:50:46.320
out. This much of the alternate world she had elected to retain.

01:50:47.200 --> 01:50:51.440
He wondered what if any legal basis she had kept in addition.

01:50:51.440 --> 01:50:52.880
None, he hoped.

01:50:53.440 --> 01:50:56.400
Wisely, however, he said nothing better not even to ask.

01:50:58.320 --> 01:51:02.000
The office door opened, and in pairs the in-nursals entered.

01:51:02.000 --> 01:51:07.040
They stood uncertainly for a moment, and then began seating themselves, facing Runciter's desk.

01:51:07.680 --> 01:51:12.480
Runciter eyed them, then poured among the rat's nest of documents on his desk.

01:51:12.480 --> 01:51:16.960
Obviously, he was trying to determine whether Pat had changed in any way the composition of the group.

01:51:17.840 --> 01:51:20.720
Edidorn, Runciter said, yes, you're here.

01:51:20.720 --> 01:51:23.680
He glanced at her, then at the man beside her.

01:51:23.680 --> 01:51:25.520
Hammond, okay, Hammond.

01:51:26.080 --> 01:51:28.560
Tippi Jackson, he peered inquiringly.

01:51:29.120 --> 01:51:32.160
I made it as quick as I could, Mrs. Jackson said.

01:51:32.160 --> 01:51:34.160
You didn't give me much time, Mr. Runciter.

01:51:35.120 --> 01:51:37.200
John illed, Runciter said.

01:51:38.320 --> 01:51:42.000
The adolescent boy with the tousaled woolly hair grunted in response.

01:51:42.800 --> 01:51:46.560
His arrogance, Joe noted, seemed to have receded.

01:51:46.560 --> 01:51:50.800
The boy now seemed introverted and even a little shaken.

01:51:50.800 --> 01:51:53.920
It would be interesting, Joe thought, to find out what he remembers.

01:51:54.560 --> 01:51:58.080
What all of them individually and collectively remember.

01:51:59.120 --> 01:52:01.680
Francesca Spanish, Runciter said.

01:52:02.320 --> 01:52:07.280
The luminous gypsy-like dark woman radiating a peculiar jangle-tautness spoke up.

01:52:08.080 --> 01:52:12.320
During the last few minutes, Mr. Runciter, while we waited in your outer office,

01:52:12.320 --> 01:52:15.280
mysterious voices appeared to me and told me things.

01:52:16.080 --> 01:52:20.080
You're Francesca Spanish, Runciter asked her patiently.

01:52:20.080 --> 01:52:22.320
He looked more than usually tired.

01:52:22.320 --> 01:52:25.600
I am, I have always been, I will always be.

01:52:25.600 --> 01:52:28.160
This Spanish's voice rang with conviction.

01:52:28.160 --> 01:52:30.400
May I tell you what the voices revealed to me?

01:52:31.280 --> 01:52:36.000
Possibly later, Runciter said, passing on to the next personnel document.

01:52:36.000 --> 01:52:39.120
It must be said, Miss Spanish declared vibrantly.

01:52:40.160 --> 01:52:41.680
All right, Runciter said.

01:52:41.680 --> 01:52:44.160
We'll take a break for a couple of minutes.

01:52:44.720 --> 01:52:48.480
He opened a drawer of his desk, got out one of his amphetamine tablets,

01:52:48.480 --> 01:52:49.600
took it without water.

01:52:50.640 --> 01:52:54.560
Let's hear what the voices revealed to you, Miss Spanish.

01:52:54.560 --> 01:52:56.240
He glanced toward Joe, shrugging.

01:52:56.960 --> 01:53:02.240
Someone, Miss Spanish said, just now moved us, all of us, into another world.

01:53:02.240 --> 01:53:07.440
We inhabited it, lived in it, as citizens of it, and then a vast,

01:53:07.440 --> 01:53:12.640
all-encompassing spiritual agency restored us to this, our rightful universe.

01:53:13.680 --> 01:53:18.080
That would be Pat, Joe Chip said, Pat Conley, who just joined the firm today.

01:53:19.760 --> 01:53:23.120
Tito Apostos, Runciter said, you're here?

01:53:23.120 --> 01:53:26.240
He craned his neck, peering about the room at the seated people.

01:53:27.200 --> 01:53:31.680
A bald-headed man, wagging a goatish beard, pointed to himself.

01:53:31.680 --> 01:53:34.880
He wore old-fashioned, hip-hugging, gold-lamé trousers,

01:53:34.880 --> 01:53:37.840
yet somehow created a stylish effect.

01:53:37.840 --> 01:53:42.080
Perhaps the egg-sized buttons of his kelp-green midi-blouse helped.

01:53:42.080 --> 01:53:46.960
In any case, he exuded a grand dignity, a loftiness, surpassing the average.

01:53:46.960 --> 01:53:48.080
Joe felt impressed.

01:53:49.040 --> 01:53:51.120
Don Denny, Runciter said.

01:53:51.920 --> 01:53:52.800
Right here, sir.

01:53:53.360 --> 01:53:57.360
A confident baritone like that of a Siamese cat declared,

01:53:57.360 --> 01:54:01.200
it arose from within a slender, earnest-looking individual

01:54:01.200 --> 01:54:04.720
who sat bolt upright in his chair, his hands on his knees.

01:54:05.440 --> 01:54:10.880
He wore a polyestered dirndl, his long hair in a snood, cowboy chaps

01:54:10.880 --> 01:54:13.840
with simulated silver stars and sandals.

01:54:13.840 --> 01:54:19.200
You're an anti-animator, Runciter said, reading the appropriate sheet,

01:54:19.200 --> 01:54:20.480
the only one we use.

01:54:20.480 --> 01:54:24.400
To Joe, he said, I wonder if we'll need him.

01:54:24.400 --> 01:54:28.160
Maybe we should substitute another anti-telepath, the more of those, the better.

01:54:28.880 --> 01:54:32.560
Joe said, we have to cover everything, since we don't know what we're getting into.

01:54:33.120 --> 01:54:34.240
I guess so.

01:54:34.240 --> 01:54:35.520
Runciter nodded.

01:54:35.520 --> 01:54:37.280
Okay, Sammy Mundo.

01:54:38.320 --> 01:54:42.640
A weak-nosed young man, dressed in a maxi-skirt with an undersized,

01:54:42.640 --> 01:54:48.320
melon-like head, stuck his hand up in a spasmodic, wobbling, tick-like gesture.

01:54:48.880 --> 01:54:52.880
As if Joe thought the anemic body had done it by itself.

01:54:52.880 --> 01:54:55.120
He knew this particular person.

01:54:55.120 --> 01:54:58.640
Mundo looked years younger than his chronological age,

01:54:58.640 --> 01:55:03.440
both mental and physical growth processes had ceased for him long ago.

01:55:04.160 --> 01:55:06.800
Technically, Mundo had the intelligence of a raccoon.

01:55:07.520 --> 01:55:12.000
He could walk, eat, bathe himself, even after a fashion talk.

01:55:12.640 --> 01:55:16.240
His anti-telepathic ability, however, was considerable.

01:55:16.240 --> 01:55:19.200
Once alone, he had blanked out S. D. Melapone.

01:55:19.760 --> 01:55:23.520
The firm's house magazine had rambled on about it for months afterward.

01:55:24.640 --> 01:55:26.400
Oh, yes, Runciter said.

01:55:27.040 --> 01:55:29.040
Now we come to Wendy Wright.

01:55:30.400 --> 01:55:34.720
As always, when the opportunity arose, Joe took a long, astute look,

01:55:35.280 --> 01:55:39.920
at the girl whom, if he could have managed it, he would have had, as is mistress, or even better,

01:55:39.920 --> 01:55:40.480
his wife.

01:55:41.440 --> 01:55:47.120
It did not seem possible that Wendy Wright had been born out of blood and internal organs,

01:55:47.120 --> 01:55:48.000
like other people.

01:55:48.800 --> 01:55:54.640
In proximity to her, he felt himself to be a squat, oily, sweating, uneducated,

01:55:54.640 --> 01:55:58.240
nerd whose stomach rattled and whose breath wheezed.

01:55:58.960 --> 01:56:03.040
Near her, he became aware of the physical mechanisms which kept him alive.

01:56:03.680 --> 01:56:09.680
Within him, machinery, pipes, and valves, and gas compressors, and fan belts had to

01:56:09.680 --> 01:56:13.200
chug away at a losing task, a labor ultimately doomed.

01:56:14.080 --> 01:56:18.480
Seeing her face, he discovered that his own consisted of garish mask.

01:56:19.280 --> 01:56:23.440
Noticing her body made him feel like a low-class wind-up toy.

01:56:24.240 --> 01:56:28.400
All her colors possessed a subtle quality, indirectly lit.

01:56:29.200 --> 01:56:34.960
Her eyes, those green and tumbled stones, looked impassively at everything.

01:56:34.960 --> 01:56:38.480
He had never seen fear in them, or aversion or contempt.

01:56:38.480 --> 01:56:40.400
What she saw, she accepted.

01:56:41.360 --> 01:56:47.200
Generally, she seemed calm, but more than that, she struck him as being durable,

01:56:48.000 --> 01:56:54.080
untroubled, and cool, not subject to wearer, to fatigue, or to physical illness and decline.

01:56:55.200 --> 01:56:59.840
Probably she was twenty-five or six, but he could not imagine her looking younger,

01:56:59.840 --> 01:57:02.160
and certainly she would never look older.

01:57:02.160 --> 01:57:06.000
She had too much control over herself and outside reality for that.

01:57:06.240 --> 01:57:10.960
I'm here, Wendy said, with soft tranquility.

01:57:12.240 --> 01:57:13.280
Runceter nodded.

01:57:14.000 --> 01:57:16.160
Okay, that leaves Fred Zafsky.

01:57:16.880 --> 01:57:22.400
He fixed his gaze on a flabby, big-footed, middle-aged, unnatural-looking individual,

01:57:22.400 --> 01:57:27.440
with pasted-down hair, muddy skin, plus a peculiar protruding Adam's apple.

01:57:28.000 --> 01:57:32.320
Clad for this occasion in a shift dress, the color of a baboon's ass.

01:57:32.320 --> 01:57:33.120
That must be you.

01:57:33.920 --> 01:57:36.480
There you are, Zafsky agreed and sniggered.

01:57:36.480 --> 01:57:37.360
How about that?

01:57:38.320 --> 01:57:40.720
Christ, Runceter said, shaking his head.

01:57:42.000 --> 01:57:46.640
Well, we have to include one anti-paraconet assist to be safe and your it.

01:57:47.200 --> 01:57:50.960
He tossed down his documents and looked about for his green cigar.

01:57:50.960 --> 01:57:51.840
To Joe, he said,

01:57:52.560 --> 01:57:55.680
That's the group, plus you and me.

01:57:55.680 --> 01:57:57.680
Any last-minute changes you want to make?

01:57:58.320 --> 01:57:59.840
I'm satisfied, Joe said.

01:58:00.800 --> 01:58:05.200
You suppose this bunch of inertials is the best combination we can come up with?

01:58:05.200 --> 01:58:06.880
Runceter eyed him intently.

01:58:08.000 --> 01:58:09.120
Yes, Joe said.

01:58:09.680 --> 01:58:12.160
And it's good enough to take on Hollis's size?

01:58:12.960 --> 01:58:14.080
Yes, Joe said.

01:58:15.520 --> 01:58:17.200
But he knew otherwise.

01:58:17.760 --> 01:58:20.000
It was not something he could put his finger on.

01:58:20.000 --> 01:58:22.160
It certainly was not rational.

01:58:22.160 --> 01:58:27.040
Potentially the counter-fueled capacity of the eleven inertials had to be considered enormous,

01:58:27.120 --> 01:58:30.960
and yet, Mr. Chip, can I have a second of your time?

01:58:31.680 --> 01:58:35.840
Mr. Postos bald-headed and bearded his gold-lamé trousers glittering

01:58:35.840 --> 01:58:37.200
plucked at Joe Chip's arm.

01:58:38.000 --> 01:58:41.120
Could I discuss an experience I had late last night?

01:58:41.920 --> 01:58:48.080
In a hypnagogic state, I seem to have contacted one or possibly two of Mr. Hollis's people,

01:58:48.960 --> 01:58:53.120
telepath evidently operating in conjunction with one of their precogs.

01:58:53.760 --> 01:58:55.840
Do you think I should tell Mr. Runceter?

01:58:55.840 --> 01:58:56.640
Is it important?

01:58:57.840 --> 01:59:00.160
Hesitating, Joe Chip looked toward Runceter.

01:59:00.800 --> 01:59:05.040
Seated in his worthy beloved chair, trying to relight his all-Havana cigar,

01:59:05.040 --> 01:59:06.960
Runceter appeared terribly tired.

01:59:06.960 --> 01:59:09.040
The wattles of his face sagged.

01:59:10.320 --> 01:59:11.600
No, Joe said.

01:59:12.480 --> 01:59:13.040
Let it go.

01:59:14.480 --> 01:59:18.320
Ladies and gentlemen, Runceter said, raising his voice above the general noise.

01:59:18.880 --> 01:59:22.000
We're leaving now for Luna, you eleven inertials.

01:59:22.640 --> 01:59:26.800
Joe Chip and myself and our client's rep, so worked.

01:59:26.800 --> 01:59:29.600
Fourteen of us in all will use our own ship.

01:59:30.320 --> 01:59:34.400
He got out his round gold anachronistic pocket watch and studied it.

01:59:35.040 --> 01:59:36.000
Three-thirty.

01:59:36.000 --> 01:59:39.520
Prattfall, too, will take off from the main roof field at four.

01:59:40.160 --> 01:59:43.680
He snapped his watch shut and returned it to the pocket of his silk sash.

01:59:44.400 --> 01:59:48.560
Well, Joe, he said, we're in this for better or worse.

01:59:49.680 --> 01:59:53.360
I wish we had a resident precog who could take a look ahead for us.

01:59:54.320 --> 01:59:58.080
Both his face and the tone of his voice drooped with worry,

01:59:58.080 --> 02:00:03.040
and the care is the irreversible burden of responsibility and age.

02:00:06.560 --> 02:00:06.880
Six.

02:00:08.800 --> 02:00:12.080
We wanted to give you a shave like no other you ever had.

02:00:12.080 --> 02:00:15.520
We said it's about time a man's face got a little loving.

02:00:15.520 --> 02:00:19.520
We said with you, big, self-winding Swiss chromium never-ending blade,

02:00:19.520 --> 02:00:22.080
the days of scrape, scrape are over.

02:00:22.720 --> 02:00:25.120
So try you, Bick, and be loved.

02:00:26.000 --> 02:00:29.600
Warning, use only as directed and with caution.

02:00:32.000 --> 02:00:38.560
Welcome to Luna, so Burt said cheerfully, her jolly eyes enlarged by her red-frame triangular glasses.

02:00:39.200 --> 02:00:43.440
Via myself, Mr. Howard says hello to each and every one of you,

02:00:43.440 --> 02:00:47.680
and most especially to Mr. Glenn Runceter for making his organization,

02:00:47.680 --> 02:00:50.560
and you people in particular, available to us.

02:00:51.360 --> 02:00:56.240
This subsurface hotel suite, decorated by Mr. Howard's artistically talented sister,

02:00:56.240 --> 02:01:02.000
Lada, lies just three hundred linear yards from the industrial and research facilities,

02:01:02.560 --> 02:01:05.840
which Mr. Howard believes to have been infiltrated.

02:01:06.400 --> 02:01:09.040
Your joint presence in this room, therefore,

02:01:09.040 --> 02:01:13.840
should already be inhibiting the psionic capabilities of Hollis's agents,

02:01:13.840 --> 02:01:15.920
a thought pleasing to all of us.

02:01:16.720 --> 02:01:18.320
She paused, looked over them all.

02:01:18.960 --> 02:01:20.000
Are there any questions?

02:01:21.120 --> 02:01:24.400
Tinkering with his test gear, Joe Chip ignored her.

02:01:24.400 --> 02:01:29.440
Despite their client's stipulation, he intended to measure the surrounding psionic field.

02:01:29.440 --> 02:01:33.280
During the hour-long trip from Earth, he and Glenn Runceter had decided on this.

02:01:34.320 --> 02:01:35.680
I have a question.

02:01:36.240 --> 02:01:38.800
Fred Zafke said, raising his hand, he giggled.

02:01:38.800 --> 02:01:39.920
Raise the bathroom.

02:01:40.880 --> 02:01:43.040
You would each be given a miniature map,

02:01:43.120 --> 02:01:45.760
Zoërt said, on which this is indicated.

02:01:46.400 --> 02:01:51.120
She nodded to a drab female assistant who began passing out brightly-colored glossy paper maps.

02:01:51.840 --> 02:01:55.200
This suite, she continued, is complete with the kitchen,

02:01:55.200 --> 02:01:59.520
all of the appliances of which are free, rather than coin-operated.

02:01:59.520 --> 02:02:04.640
Obviously outright blatant expense has been incurred in the constructing of this living unit,

02:02:04.640 --> 02:02:08.240
which is ample enough for twenty persons, possessing, as it does,

02:02:08.240 --> 02:02:15.360
its own self-regulating air, heat, water, and unusually varied food supply, plus closed-circuit

02:02:15.360 --> 02:02:19.440
TV and high-fidelity polyphonic, photograph sound system.

02:02:19.440 --> 02:02:24.160
The two latter facilities, however, unlike the kitchen, being coin-operated,

02:02:24.720 --> 02:02:29.280
to aid you in utilizing these recreation facilities, a change-making machine has

02:02:29.280 --> 02:02:30.560
been placed in the game room.

02:02:31.920 --> 02:02:36.560
My map, Al Hammond said, shows only nine bedrooms.

02:02:37.280 --> 02:02:41.200
Each bedroom, Ms. Wert said, contains two bunk-type beds,

02:02:41.200 --> 02:02:43.280
hence eighteen accommodations in all.

02:02:43.920 --> 02:02:50.080
In addition, five of the beds are double, assisting those of you who wish to sleep with each other

02:02:50.080 --> 02:02:51.280
during your stay here.

02:02:51.280 --> 02:02:56.880
I have a rule, Runceter said irritably, about my employees sleeping with one another.

02:02:57.840 --> 02:03:00.640
For or against, Zoërt inquired,

02:03:00.640 --> 02:03:05.040
Against! Runceter crumpled up his map and dropped it to the metal-heated floor.

02:03:05.680 --> 02:03:07.360
I'm not accustomed to being told.

02:03:07.840 --> 02:03:11.600
But you will not be staying here, Mr. Runceter, Ms. Wert pointed out.

02:03:12.160 --> 02:03:15.680
Aren't you returning to Earth as soon as your employees begin to function?

02:03:16.400 --> 02:03:18.800
She smiled her professional smile at him.

02:03:20.000 --> 02:03:21.760
Runceter said to Joe Chip,

02:03:21.760 --> 02:03:24.080
You're getting any readings as to the sigh-field?

02:03:24.880 --> 02:03:29.600
First, Joe said, I have to obtain a reading on the counter-field our initials are generating.

02:03:29.600 --> 02:03:31.840
You should have done that on the trip, Runceter said.

02:03:32.480 --> 02:03:34.720
Are you attempting to take measurements?

02:03:34.720 --> 02:03:36.480
Ms. Wert inquired alertly.

02:03:37.040 --> 02:03:40.480
Mr. Howard expressly contraindicated that, as I explained.

02:03:41.280 --> 02:03:43.920
We're taking a reading anyway, Runceter said.

02:03:44.480 --> 02:03:45.360
Mr. Howard,

02:03:45.360 --> 02:03:48.560
This isn't Statenmick's business, Runceter told her.

02:03:49.680 --> 02:03:51.760
To her drab assistant, Ms. Wert said,

02:03:52.320 --> 02:03:54.880
Would you ask Mr. Mick to come down here, please?

02:03:55.760 --> 02:03:59.440
The assistant screwed it off in the direction of the syndrome of elevators.

02:04:00.080 --> 02:04:03.680
Mr. Mick will tell you himself, Ms. Wert said to Runceter.

02:04:04.320 --> 02:04:09.280
Meanwhile, please, do nothing. I ask you kindly to wait until he arrives.

02:04:10.240 --> 02:04:13.440
I have a reading now, Joe said to Runceter.

02:04:13.440 --> 02:04:15.360
On our own field, it's very high.

02:04:16.160 --> 02:04:18.000
Probably because of Pat, he decided.

02:04:18.560 --> 02:04:20.880
Much higher than I would have expected, he said.

02:04:21.600 --> 02:04:25.040
Why are they so anxious for us not to take readings, he wondered.

02:04:25.040 --> 02:04:28.480
It's not a time factor now, our initials are here and operating.

02:04:29.360 --> 02:04:32.000
Are there closets? Tiffy Jackson asked,

02:04:32.000 --> 02:04:34.480
Where we can put away our clothes I'd like to unpack.

02:04:35.120 --> 02:04:39.680
Each bedroom, Ms. Wert said, has a large closet, coin-operated,

02:04:39.680 --> 02:04:43.600
and to start you all off, she produced a large plastic bag.

02:04:43.600 --> 02:04:46.080
Here is a complimentary supply of coins.

02:04:46.640 --> 02:04:50.240
She handed the rolls of dimes, nickels, and quarters to John Ild,

02:04:50.240 --> 02:04:54.000
which you distribute these equally, a gesture of goodwill by Mr. Mick.

02:04:54.880 --> 02:05:00.960
Edidorn asked, Is there a nurse or doctor in this settlement?

02:05:01.520 --> 02:05:06.400
Sometimes I develop psychosomatic skin rashes when I'm hard at work.

02:05:06.400 --> 02:05:12.160
A cortisone base, it usually helps me, but in the hurry I forgot to bring some along.

02:05:12.960 --> 02:05:16.320
The industrial research installations adjoining these living quarters,

02:05:16.320 --> 02:05:19.760
Ms. Wert said, keep several doctors on standby,

02:05:19.760 --> 02:05:23.440
and in addition there is a small medical ward with beds for the ill.

02:05:24.560 --> 02:05:27.440
Kind operated, Sammy Mundo inquired.

02:05:28.240 --> 02:05:31.840
All our medical care, Ms. Wert said, is free.

02:05:32.560 --> 02:05:35.680
But the burden of proof that he is genuinely ill

02:05:35.680 --> 02:05:38.320
rests on the shoulders of the alleged patient.

02:05:39.040 --> 02:05:43.920
She added, All medication dispensing machines, however, are coin-operated.

02:05:43.920 --> 02:05:48.080
I might say in regard to this that you will find in the game room of this suite

02:05:48.080 --> 02:05:52.640
a tranquilizer dispensing machine, and if you wish we can probably have

02:05:52.640 --> 02:05:56.960
one of the stimulant dispensing machines moved in from the adjoining installations.

02:05:57.760 --> 02:06:01.440
What about hallucinogens, Francesca Spanish inquired.

02:06:02.000 --> 02:06:07.280
When I'm at work, I function better if I can get an air-god-based psychedelic drug.

02:06:07.280 --> 02:06:11.440
It causes me to actually see who I'm up against, and I find that helps.

02:06:12.640 --> 02:06:18.160
Ms. Wert said, Our Mr. Mick disapproves of all the air-god-based hallucinogenic agents.

02:06:18.160 --> 02:06:19.920
He feels they live at toxic.

02:06:20.720 --> 02:06:26.160
If you have brought any with you, you're free to use them, but we will not dispense any.

02:06:26.800 --> 02:06:28.400
Although I understand we have them.

02:06:29.600 --> 02:06:33.520
Since when, Don Denny said to Francesca Spanish,

02:06:33.520 --> 02:06:38.080
did you begin to need psychedelic drugs in order to hallucinate your whole life's

02:06:38.080 --> 02:06:39.920
awaking hallucination?

02:06:40.720 --> 02:06:46.160
Unfazed, Francesca said, Two nights ago I received a particularly impressive visitation.

02:06:46.800 --> 02:06:49.520
I'm not surprised, Don Denny said.

02:06:49.520 --> 02:06:52.800
A throne of precogs and telepaths descended from a ladder,

02:06:52.800 --> 02:06:57.360
spun a finest natural hemp to the balcony outside my window.

02:06:57.360 --> 02:07:01.920
They dissolved a passageway through the wall and manifested themselves around my bed,

02:07:01.920 --> 02:07:04.000
waking me up with their chatter.

02:07:04.000 --> 02:07:09.040
They quoted poetry and languid prose from old-time books, which delighted me.

02:07:09.040 --> 02:07:13.680
They seemed so, she'd groped for the word, sparkling,

02:07:14.400 --> 02:07:16.000
one of them who called himself Bill.

02:07:16.640 --> 02:07:19.040
Wait a minute, Tito Apostos said.

02:07:19.040 --> 02:07:20.880
I had a dream like that too.

02:07:20.880 --> 02:07:21.680
He turned to Joe.

02:07:22.240 --> 02:07:24.880
Remember, I told you just before we left earth.

02:07:24.880 --> 02:07:26.960
His hands convulsed excitedly.

02:07:26.960 --> 02:07:27.440
Didn't I?

02:07:28.240 --> 02:07:31.200
I dreamed that too, Tippie Jackson said.

02:07:31.200 --> 02:07:33.760
Bill and Matt, they said they were going to get me.

02:07:34.800 --> 02:07:38.560
His face twisting with abrupt darkness runs to the said to Joe,

02:07:38.560 --> 02:07:39.600
You should have told me.

02:07:40.480 --> 02:07:42.480
At the time, Joe said, You.

02:07:43.280 --> 02:07:44.320
He gave up.

02:07:44.320 --> 02:07:45.440
You looked tired.

02:07:45.440 --> 02:07:47.040
You had other things on your mind.

02:07:47.840 --> 02:07:50.320
Francesca said sharply, It wasn't a dream.

02:07:50.320 --> 02:07:52.320
It was an authentic visitation.

02:07:52.320 --> 02:07:53.760
I can distinguish the difference.

02:07:54.880 --> 02:07:56.640
Sure you can, Francie.

02:07:56.640 --> 02:07:57.520
Don Denny said.

02:07:57.520 --> 02:07:58.480
He winked at Joe.

02:07:59.440 --> 02:08:01.520
I had a dream, John Ilde said.

02:08:01.520 --> 02:08:03.200
But it was about hover cars.

02:08:03.200 --> 02:08:05.280
I was memorizing their license plate numbers.

02:08:05.280 --> 02:08:07.360
I memorized sixty-five and I still remember them.

02:08:07.360 --> 02:08:08.000
Want to hear them?

02:08:08.720 --> 02:08:11.680
I'm sorry, Glenn, Joe Chip said to Runceter.

02:08:12.160 --> 02:08:14.640
I thought only a postos experienced it.

02:08:14.640 --> 02:08:15.920
I didn't know about the others.

02:08:16.960 --> 02:08:20.560
The sound of elevator doors sliding side made him pause.

02:08:20.560 --> 02:08:22.000
He and the others turned to look.

02:08:23.200 --> 02:08:25.760
Potbellied, squat and thick-legged,

02:08:25.760 --> 02:08:28.720
Stanton Mick preambulated toward them.

02:08:28.720 --> 02:08:31.840
He wore fuchsia petal pushers, pink yuck fur slippers,

02:08:31.840 --> 02:08:33.920
a snakeskin sleeveless blouse,

02:08:33.920 --> 02:08:37.360
and a ribbon in his waist-length dyed white hair.

02:08:38.160 --> 02:08:40.080
His nose, Joe thought,

02:08:40.080 --> 02:08:44.720
looks like a rubber bulb of a New Delhi taxi horn, soft and squeezable.

02:08:45.360 --> 02:08:48.880
And loud, the loudest noise he thought that I have ever seen.

02:08:50.400 --> 02:08:53.840
Hello, all you top anti-size?

02:08:53.840 --> 02:08:54.880
Stanton Mick said,

02:08:54.880 --> 02:08:56.800
extending his arms in fulsome greeting.

02:08:57.360 --> 02:08:59.360
The exterminators are here.

02:08:59.360 --> 02:09:01.600
By that, I mean, yourselves.

02:09:02.160 --> 02:09:05.760
His voice had a squeaky, penetrating castrato quality to it.

02:09:05.760 --> 02:09:09.520
An unpleasant noise that one might expect to hear, Joe Chip thought,

02:09:09.520 --> 02:09:11.120
from a hive of metal bees.

02:09:11.840 --> 02:09:15.440
The plague, in the form of various psionic riff-rath,

02:09:15.440 --> 02:09:20.480
descended upon the harmless, friendly, peaceful world of Stanton Mick.

02:09:20.480 --> 02:09:23.360
What a day that was for us in Mickville,

02:09:23.360 --> 02:09:27.520
as we call our attractive and appetizing lunar settlement here.

02:09:28.160 --> 02:09:32.400
You have, of course, already started work, as I knew you would.

02:09:32.400 --> 02:09:36.160
That's because your tops in your field has everyone realizes,

02:09:36.160 --> 02:09:38.160
when Runciter Associates is mentioned.

02:09:38.720 --> 02:09:43.760
I'm already delighted at your activity, with one small exception,

02:09:43.760 --> 02:09:47.760
that I perceive your tester there, dingling with his equipment.

02:09:47.760 --> 02:09:50.640
Taster, will you look my way when I'm speaking to you?

02:09:52.720 --> 02:09:55.840
Joe shut off his polygraphs and gauges, killed the power supply.

02:09:56.560 --> 02:09:58.560
Do I have your attention now?

02:09:58.560 --> 02:09:59.760
Stanton Mick asked him.

02:10:00.480 --> 02:10:01.680
Yes, Joe said.

02:10:02.400 --> 02:10:04.640
Leave your equipment on, Runciter ordered him.

02:10:04.640 --> 02:10:07.440
You're not an employee of Mr. Mick, you're my employee.

02:10:08.240 --> 02:10:10.560
It doesn't matter, Joe said to him.

02:10:10.560 --> 02:10:14.400
I've already gotten a reading on the side field being generated in this vicinity.

02:10:14.960 --> 02:10:16.240
He had done his jobs.

02:10:16.240 --> 02:10:18.320
Stanton Mick had been too slow in arriving.

02:10:19.040 --> 02:10:21.360
How great is their field, Runciter asked him.

02:10:22.080 --> 02:10:25.360
Joe said, there is no field.

02:10:26.160 --> 02:10:27.840
Our inertials are nullifying it.

02:10:27.840 --> 02:10:29.120
Our counterfield is greater.

02:10:29.680 --> 02:10:30.720
No, Joe said.

02:10:30.720 --> 02:10:35.760
As I said, there is no side field of any sort within range of my equipment.

02:10:35.760 --> 02:10:40.160
I pick up our own field, so as far as I can determine my instruments are functioning,

02:10:40.160 --> 02:10:42.080
I consider that an accurate feedback.

02:10:42.640 --> 02:10:47.920
We're producing 2,000 BLR units fluctuating upward to 2,100 every few minutes.

02:10:47.920 --> 02:10:52.160
Probably it will gradually increase by the time our inertials have been functioning together,

02:10:52.160 --> 02:10:53.040
say, 12 hours.

02:10:53.040 --> 02:10:56.880
It may reach as high as, I don't understand, Runciter said.

02:10:56.880 --> 02:10:59.680
All the inertials now were gathering around Joe Chip.

02:11:00.240 --> 02:11:04.320
Don Denny picked up one of the tapes which had been excreted by the polygraph,

02:11:04.320 --> 02:11:08.640
examining the unwavering line, then handed the tape to Tiffy Jackson.

02:11:09.200 --> 02:11:14.160
One by one, the other inertials examined it silently, then looked toward Runciter.

02:11:14.880 --> 02:11:16.480
To Stanton Mick, Runciter said,

02:11:17.120 --> 02:11:22.400
Where'd you get the idea that Psy said infiltrated your operations here on Luna?

02:11:22.400 --> 02:11:25.360
And why didn't you want us to run our normal tests?

02:11:25.360 --> 02:11:27.520
Did you know we would get this result?

02:11:28.400 --> 02:11:30.720
Obviously he knew, Joe Chip said.

02:11:31.280 --> 02:11:32.400
He felt sure of it.

02:11:33.440 --> 02:11:36.240
Rapid agitated activity crossed Runciter's face.

02:11:36.240 --> 02:11:41.360
He started to speak to Stanton Mick, then changed his mind and said to Joe in a low voice,

02:11:41.360 --> 02:11:42.560
Let's get back to earth.

02:11:42.560 --> 02:11:44.480
Let's get our inertials right out of here now.

02:11:45.920 --> 02:11:47.440
Allowed to the others, he said,

02:11:47.440 --> 02:11:48.400
Collect your possessions.

02:11:48.400 --> 02:11:49.760
We're flying back to New York.

02:11:49.760 --> 02:11:52.320
I want all of you in the ship within the next 15 minutes.

02:11:52.320 --> 02:11:54.240
Any of you who aren't in it will be left behind.

02:11:54.880 --> 02:11:57.200
Joe, get all that junk of yours together in one heap.

02:11:57.200 --> 02:11:58.880
I'll help you lug it to the ship if I have to.

02:11:59.440 --> 02:12:01.360
Anyhow, I want it out of here and you with it.

02:12:01.920 --> 02:12:04.000
He turned in Mick's direction once again.

02:12:04.560 --> 02:12:06.560
His face puffy with anger.

02:12:06.560 --> 02:12:07.520
He started to speak.

02:12:08.240 --> 02:12:13.760
Squeaking in his metal insect voice, Stanton Mick floated to the ceiling of the room,

02:12:13.760 --> 02:12:16.640
his arms protruding disdendately and rigidly.

02:12:17.280 --> 02:12:22.400
Mr. Runciter, don't let your thalamus override your cerebral cortex.

02:12:22.480 --> 02:12:25.200
This matter calls for discretion, not haste.

02:12:25.200 --> 02:12:30.880
Calm your people down and let's huddle together and in effect mutually understand.

02:12:32.080 --> 02:12:34.320
His rotund colorful body bobbed about,

02:12:34.320 --> 02:12:37.200
twisting in a slow transversal rotation,

02:12:37.200 --> 02:12:40.800
so that now his feet rather than his head extended in Runciter's direction.

02:12:41.760 --> 02:12:43.760
I've heard of this, Runciter said to Joe.

02:12:43.760 --> 02:12:45.600
It's a self-destruct humanoid bomb.

02:12:45.600 --> 02:12:47.040
Help me get everybody out of here.

02:12:47.040 --> 02:12:48.320
They just now put it on auto.

02:12:48.320 --> 02:12:49.440
That's why it floated upward.

02:12:50.240 --> 02:12:51.760
The bomb exploded.

02:12:52.800 --> 02:12:55.200
Smoke billowing in ill-smelling masses,

02:12:55.200 --> 02:12:57.520
which plung to the ruptured walls and floor,

02:12:57.520 --> 02:13:01.600
sank and obscured the prone twitching figure at Joe Chip's feet.

02:13:01.600 --> 02:13:03.280
In Joe's ear Don Denny was yelling,

02:13:03.280 --> 02:13:06.800
They killed Runciter, Mr. Chip, that's Mr. Runciter.

02:13:06.800 --> 02:13:08.720
In his excitement he stammered.

02:13:08.720 --> 02:13:11.680
Who else, Joe said, thickly trying to breathe.

02:13:11.680 --> 02:13:14.080
The accurate smoke constricted his chest,

02:13:14.080 --> 02:13:16.880
his head rang from the concussion of the bomb,

02:13:16.880 --> 02:13:19.040
and feeling an oozing warmth on his neck,

02:13:19.040 --> 02:13:21.520
he found that a flying shard had lacerated him.

02:13:22.240 --> 02:13:24.960
Wendy Wright, indistinct, although close by, said,

02:13:24.960 --> 02:13:27.120
I think everyone else is hurt but alive.

02:13:27.840 --> 02:13:30.640
Bending down the side Runciter, Edie Doran said,

02:13:30.640 --> 02:13:33.360
Could we get an animator from Ray Hollis?

02:13:33.360 --> 02:13:35.120
Her face looked crushed in and pale.

02:13:35.920 --> 02:13:37.920
No, Joe said. He too bent down.

02:13:38.480 --> 02:13:40.400
You're wrong, he said to Don Denny.

02:13:40.400 --> 02:13:41.200
He's not dead.

02:13:41.840 --> 02:13:44.560
But on the twisted floor Runciter lay dying.

02:13:45.120 --> 02:13:47.920
In two minutes, three minutes, Don Denny would be correct.

02:13:48.480 --> 02:13:50.640
Listen, everybody, Joe said aloud,

02:13:50.720 --> 02:13:54.000
Since Mr. Runciter is injured, I'm now in charge temporarily,

02:13:54.000 --> 02:13:55.680
anyhow, until we can get back to Terra.

02:13:56.480 --> 02:13:59.200
Assuming, Al Hammond said, we get back at all,

02:13:59.920 --> 02:14:02.960
with a folded handkerchief he patted a deep cut over his right eye.

02:14:03.840 --> 02:14:06.240
How many of you have hand weapons, Joe asked.

02:14:06.800 --> 02:14:09.840
The inertials continue to mill without answering.

02:14:09.840 --> 02:14:12.320
I know it's against society rules, Joe said,

02:14:12.320 --> 02:14:14.000
but I know some of you carry them.

02:14:14.000 --> 02:14:16.560
Forget the illegality, forget everything you've ever learned

02:14:16.560 --> 02:14:19.040
pertaining to inertials on the job carrying guns.

02:14:19.840 --> 02:14:21.440
After a pause, Tippi Jackson said,

02:14:22.000 --> 02:14:24.000
Mine is with my things in the other room.

02:14:24.960 --> 02:14:27.920
Mine is here with me, Tito Apostos said.

02:14:27.920 --> 02:14:31.280
He already held in his right hand an old-fashioned lead-slug pistol.

02:14:31.840 --> 02:14:33.680
If you have guns, Joe said,

02:14:33.680 --> 02:14:36.080
and they're in the other room where you left your things, go get them.

02:14:36.800 --> 02:14:38.800
Six inertials started toward the door.

02:14:39.440 --> 02:14:41.600
To Al Hammond and Wendy Wright, who remained,

02:14:41.600 --> 02:14:44.160
Joe said, We've got to get Runciter into cold pack.

02:14:44.800 --> 02:14:48.080
There are cold pack facilities on the ship, Al Hammond said.

02:14:48.080 --> 02:14:50.080
Then we'll lug him there, Joe said.

02:14:50.080 --> 02:14:52.240
Hammond, take one end and I'll lift up the other.

02:14:52.240 --> 02:14:56.160
Apostos, you go ahead of us and shoot any of Hollis's employees who try to stop us.

02:14:57.040 --> 02:15:00.240
John Ill, returning from the next room with the laser tube, said,

02:15:00.240 --> 02:15:02.160
You think Hollis is in here with Mr. Mick?

02:15:03.280 --> 02:15:05.040
With him, Joe said, or by himself,

02:15:05.760 --> 02:15:07.680
we may never have been dealing with Mick.

02:15:07.680 --> 02:15:09.520
It may have been Hollis from the start.

02:15:10.400 --> 02:15:14.640
Amazing, he thought that the explosion of the human-eyed bomb didn't kill the rest of us.

02:15:15.440 --> 02:15:17.280
He wondered about zoe Wirt.

02:15:17.360 --> 02:15:19.520
Evidently, she had gotten out before the blast.

02:15:19.520 --> 02:15:20.800
He saw no sign of her.

02:15:21.520 --> 02:15:23.600
I wonder what her reaction was, he thought,

02:15:23.600 --> 02:15:26.240
when she found out she wasn't working for Stanton Mick,

02:15:26.240 --> 02:15:31.520
that her employer, her real employer, had hired us, brought us here to assassinate us.

02:15:32.640 --> 02:15:35.760
Probably have to kill her too, just to be on the safe side.

02:15:35.760 --> 02:15:37.680
She certainly won't be of any more use.

02:15:37.680 --> 02:15:39.680
In fact, she'll be a witness to what happened.

02:15:40.720 --> 02:15:43.200
Now, Al Hammond, the other inertials, returned.

02:15:43.200 --> 02:15:45.280
They waited for Joe to tell them what to do.

02:15:45.280 --> 02:15:49.120
Considering their situation, the eleven inertials seemed reasonably self-possessed.

02:15:50.080 --> 02:15:53.520
If we can get Runciter into co-pack soon enough, Joe explained,

02:15:53.520 --> 02:15:58.320
as he and Al Hammond carried their apparently dying employer toward the elevators,

02:15:58.320 --> 02:16:00.640
he can still run the firm the way his wife does.

02:16:01.200 --> 02:16:03.120
He stabbed the elevator button with his elbow.

02:16:03.680 --> 02:16:07.200
There's really very little chance, he said, that the elevator would come.

02:16:07.200 --> 02:16:10.160
They probably cut off all power at the same moment as the blast.

02:16:10.880 --> 02:16:12.960
The elevator, however, did appear.

02:16:12.960 --> 02:16:15.760
With haste, he and Al Hammond carried Runciter aboard it.

02:16:16.320 --> 02:16:18.880
Three of you who have guns, Joe said, come along with us.

02:16:18.880 --> 02:16:19.600
The rest of you—

02:16:19.600 --> 02:16:20.800
The hell with that!

02:16:20.800 --> 02:16:22.000
Sammy Mundo said,

02:16:22.000 --> 02:16:25.840
We don't want to be stuck down here waiting for the elevators to come back.

02:16:25.840 --> 02:16:27.600
It may never come back.

02:16:27.600 --> 02:16:30.080
He started forward, his face constricted with panic.

02:16:30.640 --> 02:16:33.440
Joe said harshly, Runciter goes first.

02:16:33.440 --> 02:16:37.840
He touched the button, and the doors shut, enclosing him, Al Hammond, Tito Apostos,

02:16:37.840 --> 02:16:40.800
Wendy Wright, Don Denney, and Glenn Runciter.

02:16:41.520 --> 02:16:44.880
It has to be done this way, he said to them, as the elevator ascended,

02:16:44.880 --> 02:16:47.520
and anyhow, if Hollis's people are waiting, they'll get us first.

02:16:48.320 --> 02:16:50.560
Except that they probably don't expect us to be armed.

02:16:51.280 --> 02:16:53.520
There is that law, Don Denney put in.

02:16:54.240 --> 02:16:57.920
See if he's dead yet, Joe said to Tito Apostos.

02:16:57.920 --> 02:17:00.160
Vending Apostos examined the inert body.

02:17:00.720 --> 02:17:05.360
Still some shallow respiration, he said presently, so we still have a chance.

02:17:05.920 --> 02:17:08.480
Yes, a chance, Joe said.

02:17:09.040 --> 02:17:14.240
He remained numb, as he had been both physically and psychologically since the blast.

02:17:14.240 --> 02:17:18.640
He felt cold and torpid, and his eardrums appeared to be damaged.

02:17:19.200 --> 02:17:21.280
Once we're back in our own ship, he reflected,

02:17:21.280 --> 02:17:25.520
after we get Runciter into the cold pack, we can send out an assist call back to New York,

02:17:25.520 --> 02:17:29.200
to everyone at the firm, in fact, to all the Prudence organizations.

02:17:29.840 --> 02:17:32.320
If we can't take off, they can come to get us.

02:17:33.520 --> 02:17:35.360
But in reality, it wouldn't work that way.

02:17:35.920 --> 02:17:38.880
Because by the time someone from the society got to Luna,

02:17:38.880 --> 02:17:43.200
everyone trapped subsurface in the elevator shaft and aboard the ship would be dead.

02:17:43.760 --> 02:17:45.600
So there really was no chance.

02:17:46.560 --> 02:17:47.920
Tito Apostos said,

02:17:47.920 --> 02:17:50.000
You could have let more of them into the elevator.

02:17:50.000 --> 02:17:51.760
We could have squeezed the rest of the women in.

02:17:52.400 --> 02:17:55.600
He glared at Joe, accusing Lee, his hands shaking with agitation.

02:17:56.640 --> 02:18:00.320
We'll be more exposed to assassination than they will, Joe said.

02:18:00.320 --> 02:18:04.400
Hollis will expect any survivors of the blast to make use of the elevator, as we're doing.

02:18:04.480 --> 02:18:06.560
That's probably why they left the power on.

02:18:06.560 --> 02:18:08.240
They know we have to get back to our ship.

02:18:08.960 --> 02:18:12.720
Wendy Wright said, You already told us that, Joe.

02:18:12.720 --> 02:18:15.280
I'm trying to rationalize what I'm doing, he said,

02:18:15.280 --> 02:18:16.720
leaving the rest of them down there.

02:18:17.440 --> 02:18:20.560
What about that new girl's talent, Wendy said?

02:18:20.560 --> 02:18:24.720
That sullen, dark girl with the disdainful attitude pat something.

02:18:25.360 --> 02:18:28.720
You could have had her go back into the past before Runciter's injury.

02:18:28.720 --> 02:18:30.000
She could have changed all this.

02:18:30.000 --> 02:18:31.520
Did you forget about her ability?

02:18:32.320 --> 02:18:34.240
Yes, Joe said tightly.

02:18:34.880 --> 02:18:37.280
He had in the aimless, smoky confusion.

02:18:37.920 --> 02:18:40.720
Let's go back down, Tito Apostos said.

02:18:40.720 --> 02:18:44.000
Like you say, Hollis's people be waiting for us at ground level.

02:18:44.000 --> 02:18:46.560
Like you said, we're more danger by—

02:18:46.560 --> 02:18:48.720
We're at the surface, Don Denney said.

02:18:48.720 --> 02:18:49.760
The elevator stopped.

02:18:50.640 --> 02:18:53.680
When and stiff, he licked his lips apprehensively,

02:18:53.680 --> 02:18:56.080
as the doors automatically slid aside.

02:18:58.000 --> 02:19:02.160
They faced a moving sidewalk that led upward to a concourse,

02:19:02.240 --> 02:19:04.960
at the end of which, beyond air-membrane doors,

02:19:04.960 --> 02:19:07.760
the base of their upright ship could be distinguished,

02:19:07.760 --> 02:19:09.440
exactly as they had left it.

02:19:10.080 --> 02:19:12.640
And no one stood between them and it.

02:19:12.640 --> 02:19:14.640
Peculiar, Joe Chip thought.

02:19:15.280 --> 02:19:18.560
Were they sure the exploding humanoid bomb would get us all?

02:19:19.520 --> 02:19:22.240
Something in the way they planned it must have gone wrong.

02:19:22.800 --> 02:19:27.120
First in the blast itself, then in their leaving the power on,

02:19:27.120 --> 02:19:28.800
and now this empty corridor.

02:19:29.760 --> 02:19:33.760
I think, Don Denney said, as Al Hammond and Joe carried Runceter

02:19:33.760 --> 02:19:35.760
from the elevator and onto the moving sidewalk,

02:19:36.320 --> 02:19:39.440
the fact that the bomb floated to the ceiling fouled them up.

02:19:40.000 --> 02:19:42.080
It seemed to be a fragmentation type,

02:19:42.080 --> 02:19:44.880
and most of the flak hit the walls above our heads.

02:19:45.440 --> 02:19:48.960
I think it never occurred to them that any of us might survive.

02:19:48.960 --> 02:19:50.720
That would be why they left the power on.

02:19:51.360 --> 02:19:54.640
Well, thank God it floated up then, Wendy Wright said.

02:19:55.280 --> 02:19:57.280
Good Lord, it's chilly.

02:19:57.280 --> 02:20:00.400
The bomb must have put this place's heating system out of action.

02:20:00.960 --> 02:20:02.240
She trembled visibly.

02:20:03.120 --> 02:20:06.480
The moving sidewalk carried them forward with shattering slowness.

02:20:06.480 --> 02:20:09.200
It seemed to Joe that five or more minutes passed

02:20:09.200 --> 02:20:12.720
before the sidewalk evicted them at the two-stage air membrane doors.

02:20:13.280 --> 02:20:16.720
The crawl forward in some ways seemed to him the worst part

02:20:16.720 --> 02:20:20.880
of everything which had happened, as if Hollis had arranged this purposely.

02:20:22.320 --> 02:20:26.000
Wait! a voice called from behind them, footstep, sounded,

02:20:26.000 --> 02:20:28.880
and Tito Apostos turned, his gun raised, then lowered.

02:20:29.680 --> 02:20:33.200
The rest of them, Don Denney said to Joe, who could not turn around,

02:20:33.200 --> 02:20:36.000
he and Al Hammond had begun maneuvering Runsterter's body

02:20:36.000 --> 02:20:38.400
through the intricate system of the air membrane doors.

02:20:39.040 --> 02:20:40.880
They're all there, it's okay.

02:20:40.880 --> 02:20:42.880
With his gun he waved them toward him.

02:20:42.880 --> 02:20:43.360
Come on!

02:20:44.640 --> 02:20:47.760
The connecting plastic tunnels still link their ship with the concourse.

02:20:47.760 --> 02:20:51.200
Joe heard the characteristic dull clunk under his feet,

02:20:51.200 --> 02:20:53.840
and wondered, are they letting us go?

02:20:53.920 --> 02:20:55.040
Joe?

02:20:55.040 --> 02:20:57.440
Or he thought, are they waiting for us in the ship?

02:20:58.160 --> 02:21:02.560
It's as if he thought some malicious force is playing with us,

02:21:03.120 --> 02:21:06.960
letting a scamper in Twitter like Debrained Mice, we amuse it,

02:21:06.960 --> 02:21:08.720
our efforts entertain it.

02:21:09.440 --> 02:21:12.800
And when we get just so far, its fist will close around us

02:21:12.800 --> 02:21:17.040
and drop our squeezed remains, like Runsterter's, onto the slow-moving floor.

02:21:18.000 --> 02:21:21.360
Denney, he said, you go into the ship first, see if they're waiting for us.

02:21:22.160 --> 02:21:23.840
And if they are, Denney said.

02:21:24.640 --> 02:21:27.280
Then you come back, Joe said, bitingly, and tell us,

02:21:27.280 --> 02:21:29.200
and we give up, and then they kill the rest of us.

02:21:30.000 --> 02:21:33.920
Wendy Wright said, ask Pat whatever her name is to use her ability.

02:21:34.480 --> 02:21:36.640
Her voice was low, but insistent.

02:21:36.640 --> 02:21:37.440
Please, Joe.

02:21:38.240 --> 02:21:41.200
Let's try to get into the ship, Tito Apostos said.

02:21:41.200 --> 02:21:43.440
I don't like that girl, I don't trust her talent.

02:21:44.160 --> 02:21:47.120
You don't understand her or it, Joe said.

02:21:48.080 --> 02:21:51.600
He watched skinny, small, Don Denney scamper up the tunnel,

02:21:51.600 --> 02:21:55.440
fiddle with the switching arrangement which control the entrance port of the ship,

02:21:55.440 --> 02:21:57.200
then disappear inside.

02:21:58.400 --> 02:22:00.640
You'll never come back, he said, panting.

02:22:00.640 --> 02:22:03.040
The weight of Glenn Runsterter seemed to have grown.

02:22:03.040 --> 02:22:04.400
He could hardly hold on to him.

02:22:05.040 --> 02:22:08.160
Let's set Runsterter down here, he said to Al Hammond.

02:22:08.720 --> 02:22:11.680
Together the two of them lowered Runsterter to the floor of the tunnel.

02:22:12.560 --> 02:22:16.080
For an old man, he's heavy, Joe said, standing erect again.

02:22:16.800 --> 02:22:19.120
To Wendy, he said, I'll talk to Pat.

02:22:19.840 --> 02:22:24.000
The others had caught up now, all of them crowded agitatedly into the connecting tunnel.

02:22:24.560 --> 02:22:28.960
What a fiasco, he gasped, instead of what we hoped to be our big enterprise.

02:22:29.600 --> 02:22:30.320
You never know.

02:22:30.880 --> 02:22:32.560
Hollis really got us this time.

02:22:33.120 --> 02:22:35.280
Emotion pat up beside him.

02:22:35.280 --> 02:22:39.520
Her face was smudged and her synthetic sleeveless blouse had been ripped.

02:22:39.520 --> 02:22:44.320
The elastic band, which, fashionably, compressed her breasts, could be seen,

02:22:44.320 --> 02:22:48.560
it had elegant embossed pale pink fleur de l'î, imprinted on it,

02:22:48.560 --> 02:22:53.440
and for no logical reason the perception of this unrelated, meaningless sense datum

02:22:53.440 --> 02:22:54.720
registered in his mind.

02:22:55.760 --> 02:22:59.920
Listen, he said to her, putting his hand on her shoulder and looking into her eyes.

02:22:59.920 --> 02:23:01.840
She calmly returned his gaze.

02:23:02.640 --> 02:23:07.840
Can you go back to a time before the bomb was detonated and restore Glenn Runsterter?

02:23:08.640 --> 02:23:10.800
It's too late now, Pat said.

02:23:10.800 --> 02:23:11.120
Why?

02:23:11.680 --> 02:23:12.560
That's it.

02:23:12.560 --> 02:23:14.160
Too much time has passed.

02:23:14.160 --> 02:23:15.600
I would have had to do it right away.

02:23:16.160 --> 02:23:17.280
Why didn't you?

02:23:17.280 --> 02:23:19.280
Wendy Wright asked her with hostility.

02:23:19.920 --> 02:23:21.680
Swinging her gaze, Pat eyed her.

02:23:22.320 --> 02:23:23.760
Did you think of it?

02:23:23.760 --> 02:23:24.800
If you did, you didn't say.

02:23:24.800 --> 02:23:25.440
Nobody said.

02:23:26.320 --> 02:23:30.400
You don't feel any responsibility, then, Wendy said, for Runsterter's death,

02:23:30.400 --> 02:23:32.080
when your talent could have obviated it.

02:23:32.960 --> 02:23:34.000
Pat laughed.

02:23:35.280 --> 02:23:37.760
Returning from the ship, Don Denney said, it's empty.

02:23:38.560 --> 02:23:40.880
Okay, Joe said, motioning to Al Hammond.

02:23:40.880 --> 02:23:42.720
Let's get him into the ship and into cold pack.

02:23:43.360 --> 02:23:46.800
He and Al once more picked up the dense heart to manage body.

02:23:46.800 --> 02:23:48.640
They continued on into the ship.

02:23:48.640 --> 02:23:52.320
The inertial scrambled and shoved around him eager for sanctuary.

02:23:52.320 --> 02:23:57.840
He experienced the pure physical emanation of their fear, the field surrounding them,

02:23:57.840 --> 02:23:58.880
and himself, too.

02:23:59.440 --> 02:24:03.680
The possibility that they might actually leave Luna alive made them more,

02:24:03.680 --> 02:24:05.040
rather than less desperate.

02:24:05.040 --> 02:24:07.760
Their stunned resignation had now completely gone.

02:24:08.640 --> 02:24:09.760
Where's the key?

02:24:09.760 --> 02:24:15.520
John Ild shrilled in Joe's ear as he and Al Hammond stumbled groggily toward the cold pack chamber.

02:24:15.520 --> 02:24:16.720
He plucked at Joe's arm.

02:24:16.720 --> 02:24:17.760
The key, Mr. Chip!

02:24:18.800 --> 02:24:22.560
Al Hammond explained, the ignition key for the ship.

02:24:22.560 --> 02:24:24.640
Runsterter must have it on him.

02:24:24.640 --> 02:24:26.640
Get it before we drop him into the cold pack,

02:24:26.640 --> 02:24:28.880
because after that we won't be able to touch him.

02:24:29.760 --> 02:24:32.960
Digging in Runsterter's various pockets, Joe found a leather key case.

02:24:32.960 --> 02:24:34.240
He passed it to John Ild.

02:24:34.880 --> 02:24:36.480
Now we can put him into cold pack?

02:24:36.480 --> 02:24:38.080
He said with savage anger.

02:24:38.080 --> 02:24:40.640
Come on, Hammond, for Christ's sake, help me get him into the pack.

02:24:41.600 --> 02:24:45.280
But we didn't move swiftly enough, he said to himself, it's all over, we failed.

02:24:46.000 --> 02:24:48.880
Well, he thought wearily, so it goes.

02:24:50.320 --> 02:24:52.400
The initial rockets came on with a roar.

02:24:52.400 --> 02:24:57.680
The ship shuddered as, at the control console, four of the initials haltingly collaborated

02:24:57.680 --> 02:25:00.800
in the task of programming the computerized command receptors.

02:25:01.680 --> 02:25:07.200
Why did they let us go, Joe asked himself, as he and Al Hammond stood Runsterter's lifeless or

02:25:07.200 --> 02:25:11.920
apparently lifeless body upright in the floor-to-ceiling cold pack chamber.

02:25:11.920 --> 02:25:16.080
Automatic clamps closed about Runsterter's thighs and shoulders supporting him,

02:25:16.080 --> 02:25:19.440
while the cold, glistening with its own simulated life,

02:25:19.440 --> 02:25:22.800
sparkled and shone dazzling Joe Chipp and Al Hammond.

02:25:23.440 --> 02:25:25.200
I don't understand it, he said.

02:25:26.080 --> 02:25:27.840
They fouled up, Hammond said.

02:25:28.400 --> 02:25:31.040
They didn't have any backup planned behind the bomb,

02:25:31.600 --> 02:25:34.480
like the bomb plotters who tried to kill Hitler.

02:25:34.480 --> 02:25:38.000
When they saw the explosion go off in the bunker hall of them assumed,

02:25:38.560 --> 02:25:41.840
before the cold kills us, Joe said, let's get out of this chamber.

02:25:42.400 --> 02:25:47.280
He prodded Hammond ahead of him, once outside the two of them together twisted the locking

02:25:47.280 --> 02:25:48.160
wheel into place.

02:25:49.200 --> 02:25:55.360
God, what a feeling, he said, to think that a force like that preserves life of a sort.

02:25:56.640 --> 02:26:01.360
Francie, Spanish, her long braids scorched, halted him as he started toward the four

02:26:01.360 --> 02:26:02.160
section of the ship.

02:26:02.720 --> 02:26:05.680
Is there a communication circuit in the cold pack? she asked.

02:26:05.680 --> 02:26:07.760
Can we consult with Mr. Runsterter now?

02:26:08.400 --> 02:26:11.200
No consultation, Joe said, shaking his head.

02:26:11.200 --> 02:26:16.720
No earphone, no microphone, no photophasons, no half-life, not until we get back to earth

02:26:16.720 --> 02:26:18.240
and transfer him to a moratorium.

02:26:19.120 --> 02:26:23.120
Then how can we tell if we froze him soon enough? Don Denney asked.

02:26:23.120 --> 02:26:24.320
We can't, Joe said.

02:26:24.880 --> 02:26:28.800
His brain may have deteriorated, Sammy Mundo said, grinning.

02:26:28.800 --> 02:26:29.440
He giggled.

02:26:30.160 --> 02:26:31.440
That's right, Joe said.

02:26:31.440 --> 02:26:34.960
We may never hear the voice or the thoughts of Glenn Runsterter again.

02:26:34.960 --> 02:26:37.680
We may have to run Runsterter associates without him.

02:26:37.680 --> 02:26:39.920
We may have to depend on what's left of Ella.

02:26:39.920 --> 02:26:44.480
We may have to move our offices to the beloved brethren moratorium at Zurich and operate out

02:26:44.480 --> 02:26:44.880
of there.

02:26:45.520 --> 02:26:49.760
He seated himself in an aisle seat where he could watch the four inertials haggling over

02:26:49.760 --> 02:26:51.280
the correct way to direct the ship.

02:26:52.240 --> 02:26:57.360
Some nambulantly engulfed by the dull dreary ache of shock,

02:26:58.000 --> 02:27:00.320
he got out a bent cigarette and lit it.

02:27:01.600 --> 02:27:07.280
The cigarette, dry and still, broke apart as he tried to hold it between his fingers.

02:27:07.280 --> 02:27:08.560
Strange, he thought.

02:27:09.520 --> 02:27:12.400
The bomb blast, Al Hammond said noticing.

02:27:12.960 --> 02:27:13.440
The heat.

02:27:14.560 --> 02:27:15.680
Did it age us?

02:27:16.240 --> 02:27:18.160
Wendy asked from behind Hammond.

02:27:18.160 --> 02:27:20.720
She stepped past him and seated herself beside Joe.

02:27:21.520 --> 02:27:22.880
I feel old.

02:27:22.880 --> 02:27:24.080
I am old.

02:27:24.080 --> 02:27:26.000
Your package of cigarettes is old.

02:27:26.000 --> 02:27:26.960
We're all old.

02:27:27.440 --> 02:27:29.280
As of today because of what has happened.

02:27:30.240 --> 02:27:32.640
This was a day for us like no other.

02:27:34.080 --> 02:27:37.520
With dramatic energy, the ship rose from the surface of Luna,

02:27:38.080 --> 02:27:41.760
carrying with it absurdly the plastic connective tunnel.

02:27:44.960 --> 02:27:45.360
7.

02:27:47.200 --> 02:27:51.840
Perk up pouting household surfaces with new miracle u-bick, the easy to apply

02:27:51.840 --> 02:27:57.440
extra shiny non-stick plastic coating, entirely harmless if used as directed,

02:27:57.440 --> 02:28:00.640
saves endless scrubbing, glides you right out of the kitchen.

02:28:02.640 --> 02:28:05.680
Our best move, Joe Chiff said, seems to be this.

02:28:05.680 --> 02:28:06.800
We landed Zurich.

02:28:07.360 --> 02:28:12.720
He picked up the microwave audio phone provided by Runceter's expensive, well-appointed ship,

02:28:12.720 --> 02:28:14.960
and dialed the regional code for Switzerland.

02:28:15.840 --> 02:28:20.400
By putting him in the same moratorium as Ella, we can consult both of them simultaneously.

02:28:20.400 --> 02:28:23.360
They can be linked up electronically to function in unison.

02:28:24.240 --> 02:28:26.800
Proto-phazonically, Don Denny corrected.

02:28:27.680 --> 02:28:31.280
Joe said, do any of you know the name of the manager of the beloved brethren moratorium?

02:28:32.000 --> 02:28:35.040
Herbert Soundtane, Tippie Jackson said, a German name.

02:28:35.840 --> 02:28:41.040
Wendy Rye Pondering said, Herbert, Schoenheit von Vogelsang.

02:28:41.040 --> 02:28:44.640
I remember it because Mr. Runceter once told me it means

02:28:44.640 --> 02:28:47.520
Herbert, the beauty of the song of birds.

02:28:48.320 --> 02:28:51.520
I wish I had been named that. I remember thinking that at the time.

02:28:52.240 --> 02:28:54.720
Yucca Mariam, Tito Apostos said.

02:28:55.360 --> 02:29:01.680
I'm going to marry Joe Chiff, Wendy said, in a somber, introspective voice with childlike gravity.

02:29:02.480 --> 02:29:07.760
Oh, Pat Connelly said. Her light-saturated black eyes ignited.

02:29:08.400 --> 02:29:09.280
Are you really?

02:29:10.960 --> 02:29:14.000
Can you change that, too, Wendy said, with your talent?

02:29:14.960 --> 02:29:18.080
Pat said, I'm living with Joe. I'm his mistress.

02:29:18.800 --> 02:29:23.040
Under our arrangement I pay his bills. I paid his front door this morning to let him out.

02:29:23.040 --> 02:29:25.120
Without me he'd still be in his con-app.

02:29:26.800 --> 02:29:31.200
And I'd trip to Luna, Al Hammond said, would not have taken place.

02:29:31.920 --> 02:29:34.880
He eyed Pat a complex expression on his face.

02:29:35.600 --> 02:29:41.440
Perhaps not today, Tippie Jackson pointed out, but eventually, what difference does it make?

02:29:42.160 --> 02:29:47.200
Anyhow, I think that's fine for Joe to have a mistress who pays his front door.

02:29:47.840 --> 02:29:53.920
She nudged Joe on the shoulder, her face beaming with what struck Joe as salacious approval,

02:29:54.480 --> 02:29:58.400
a sort of vicarious enjoying of his private personal activities.

02:29:59.120 --> 02:30:03.440
In Mrs. Jackson, a voyeur dwelt beneath her extroverted surface.

02:30:04.640 --> 02:30:07.120
Give me the ship's overall phone book, he said.

02:30:07.120 --> 02:30:09.200
I'll notify the moratorium to expect us.

02:30:09.920 --> 02:30:12.800
He studied his wristwatch ten more minutes of flight.

02:30:13.520 --> 02:30:17.120
Here's the phone book, Mr. Chet, John Yield said after a search.

02:30:17.120 --> 02:30:20.960
He handed him the heavy square box with its keyboard and micro scanner.

02:30:21.760 --> 02:30:27.920
Joe typed out, Swiss, then Zure, then Bulved Breath Mora.

02:30:28.880 --> 02:30:33.920
Like Hebrew, Pat said from behind him, semantic condensations.

02:30:34.960 --> 02:30:38.880
The micro scanner whisked back and forth, selecting and discarding.

02:30:38.960 --> 02:30:44.080
At last its mechanism popped up a punch card which Joe fed into the phone's receptor slot.

02:30:44.720 --> 02:30:46.160
The phone said, tinnily,

02:30:46.800 --> 02:30:48.080
This is a recording.

02:30:48.640 --> 02:30:50.320
It expelled the punch card vigorously.

02:30:50.880 --> 02:30:53.680
The number which you have given me is obsolete.

02:30:53.680 --> 02:30:56.080
If you need assistance, place a red card in—

02:30:57.120 --> 02:30:59.360
What's the date on that phone book?

02:30:59.360 --> 02:31:02.880
Joe asked Yield, who was returning it to its handy storage shelf.

02:31:03.520 --> 02:31:06.320
Yield examined the information stamped on the rear of the box.

02:31:07.040 --> 02:31:08.880
1990, two years old.

02:31:10.240 --> 02:31:12.800
That can't be, Edidorn said.

02:31:12.800 --> 02:31:15.520
This ship didn't exist two years ago.

02:31:15.520 --> 02:31:17.680
Everything on it and in it is new.

02:31:19.120 --> 02:31:22.240
Tito Apostos said maybe runs to the curfew corners.

02:31:22.800 --> 02:31:24.240
Not at all, Edid said.

02:31:24.240 --> 02:31:28.320
He lavished care, money, and engineering skill on Prattfall, too.

02:31:28.880 --> 02:31:30.960
Everybody who ever worked for him knows that.

02:31:31.520 --> 02:31:33.280
This ship is his pride and joy.

02:31:33.840 --> 02:31:35.680
Was his pride and joy?

02:31:35.680 --> 02:31:37.120
Francie Spanish corrected.

02:31:37.680 --> 02:31:39.520
I'm not ready to admit that, Joe said.

02:31:40.320 --> 02:31:43.120
He fed a red card into the phone's receptor slot.

02:31:43.120 --> 02:31:47.440
Give me the current number, the beloved brethren Moratorium in Zurich, Switzerland, he said.

02:31:48.000 --> 02:31:53.120
To Francie Spanish, he said this ship is still his pride and joy because he still exists.

02:31:54.080 --> 02:31:57.840
A card punched into significance by the phone leapt out.

02:31:57.840 --> 02:32:00.240
He transferred it to its receptor slot.

02:32:00.240 --> 02:32:04.720
This time the phone's computerized workings responded without irritation.

02:32:04.720 --> 02:32:08.640
On the screen, a shallow, conniving face formed.

02:32:08.640 --> 02:32:12.800
That of the unctuous, busy body who ran the beloved brethren Moratorium.

02:32:12.800 --> 02:32:14.800
Joe remembered him with dislike.

02:32:15.760 --> 02:32:18.160
I am Herbert Schoenheit von Vogelsang.

02:32:18.160 --> 02:32:19.840
Have you come to me in your grief, sir?

02:32:20.400 --> 02:32:24.000
May I take your name and address where it happened that we got cut off?

02:32:24.560 --> 02:32:26.480
The Moratorium owner poised himself.

02:32:27.200 --> 02:32:28.880
Joe said there's been an accident.

02:32:28.960 --> 02:32:35.920
What we deem an accident, von Vogelsang said, is ever yet the display of God's handiwork.

02:32:36.560 --> 02:32:41.200
In a sense, all life could be called an accident, and yet, in fact,

02:32:41.200 --> 02:32:44.800
I don't want to engage in a theological discussion, Joe said, not at this time.

02:32:45.520 --> 02:32:51.840
This is the time out of all times when the consolations of theology are most soothing.

02:32:52.480 --> 02:32:54.480
Is the deceased a relative?

02:32:54.480 --> 02:32:55.760
Our employer, Joe said.

02:32:56.240 --> 02:32:58.800
Glenn Runciter of Runciter Associates, New York.

02:32:58.800 --> 02:33:00.240
You have his wife, Ella, there.

02:33:00.800 --> 02:33:02.400
They'll be landing in eight or nine minutes.

02:33:02.400 --> 02:33:05.200
Can you have one of your transport coal-pack vans waiting?

02:33:05.760 --> 02:33:07.520
He is in coal-pack now?

02:33:08.560 --> 02:33:09.760
No, Joe said.

02:33:09.760 --> 02:33:12.880
He's warming himself on the beach at Tampa, Florida.

02:33:13.600 --> 02:33:16.800
I assume your amusing response indicates yes.

02:33:17.760 --> 02:33:21.520
Have a van at the Zurich spaceport, Joe said, and rang off.

02:33:22.480 --> 02:33:26.240
Look who we've got to deal through, he reflected from now on.

02:33:27.360 --> 02:33:31.440
We'll get Ray Hollis, he said to the inertials grouped around him.

02:33:32.560 --> 02:33:36.400
Get him instead of Mr. Vogelsang? Sammy Mundo asked.

02:33:37.200 --> 02:33:41.760
Get him in the manner of getting him dead, Joe said, for bringing this about.

02:33:42.880 --> 02:33:48.160
Glenn Runciter, he thought, frozen upright in a transparent plastic casket ornamented with

02:33:48.160 --> 02:33:53.360
plastic rose buds. Wakened into half-life activity one hour a month.

02:33:53.920 --> 02:33:56.800
Deteriorating, weakening, growing dim.

02:33:56.800 --> 02:34:00.400
Christ, he thought savagely, of all the people in the world.

02:34:00.400 --> 02:34:02.720
Man that vital and vitalic.

02:34:03.840 --> 02:34:07.280
Anyhow, Wendy said, he'll be closer to Ella.

02:34:08.160 --> 02:34:11.440
In a way, Joe said, I hope we got him into the coal-pack too.

02:34:12.480 --> 02:34:14.400
He broke off not wanting to say it.

02:34:14.400 --> 02:34:19.840
I don't like moratoriums, he said. Or moratorium owners.

02:34:19.840 --> 02:34:22.800
I don't like Herbert, Sean Hyde, when Vogelsang.

02:34:22.800 --> 02:34:24.960
Why does Runciter prefer Swiss moratoriums?

02:34:24.960 --> 02:34:26.800
What's the matter with a moratorium in New York?

02:34:27.600 --> 02:34:30.560
It is a Swiss invention, Edie Dorn said.

02:34:31.120 --> 02:34:36.480
And according to impartial surveys, the average length of half-life of a given individual in

02:34:36.480 --> 02:34:42.320
a Swiss moratorium is two full hours greater than an individual in one of ours.

02:34:42.320 --> 02:34:44.320
The Swiss seem to have special knack.

02:34:45.040 --> 02:34:50.240
The UN ought to abolish half-life, Joe said, as interfering with the natural process of the

02:34:50.240 --> 02:34:54.080
cycle of birth and death. Markingly, Al Hammond said,

02:34:54.720 --> 02:35:00.480
if God approved of half-life, each of us would be born in a casket filled with dry eyes.

02:35:01.680 --> 02:35:04.000
At the control console, Don Denney said,

02:35:04.560 --> 02:35:08.800
we're now under the jurisdiction of the Zurich Microwave transmitter.

02:35:08.800 --> 02:35:09.680
It'll do the rest.

02:35:10.480 --> 02:35:12.640
He walked away from the console, looking glum.

02:35:13.840 --> 02:35:15.840
Cheer out, Edie Dorn said to him.

02:35:16.560 --> 02:35:20.720
To be brutally harsh about it, consider how lucky all of us are.

02:35:20.720 --> 02:35:25.760
We might be dead now, either by the bomb or by being lasered down after the blast.

02:35:26.320 --> 02:35:30.320
It'll make you feel better once we land. We'll be so much safer on earth.

02:35:31.840 --> 02:35:35.680
Joe said, the fact that we had to go to Luna should have tipped us off.

02:35:36.640 --> 02:35:38.720
Should have tipped Runciter off, he realized.

02:35:39.280 --> 02:35:42.880
Because of that loophole in the law dealing with civil authority on Luna,

02:35:42.880 --> 02:35:48.000
Runciter always said, be suspicious of any job order requiring us to leave earth.

02:35:48.000 --> 02:35:49.760
If he were alive, he'd be saying it now.

02:35:50.400 --> 02:35:53.600
Especially don't bite if it's Luna where they want us.

02:35:53.600 --> 02:35:56.000
Too many prudent organizations have bitten on that.

02:35:57.200 --> 02:36:01.760
If he does revive at the moratorium, he thought that'll be the first thing he says.

02:36:01.760 --> 02:36:04.560
I always was suspicious of Luna, he'll say.

02:36:05.600 --> 02:36:08.240
But not quite suspicious enough.

02:36:08.880 --> 02:36:11.280
The job was too much of a plumb he couldn't resist it.

02:36:12.000 --> 02:36:15.920
And so with that bait they got him, as he always knew they would.

02:36:17.200 --> 02:36:21.040
The ship's retro jets triggered off by the Zurich microwave transmitter

02:36:21.040 --> 02:36:23.040
rumbled on, the ship shuttered.

02:36:23.920 --> 02:36:25.520
Joe, Tito Apostos said.

02:36:26.160 --> 02:36:28.960
You're gonna have to tell Ella about Runciter, you realize that.

02:36:29.680 --> 02:36:33.440
I've been thinking about it, Joe said, since we took off and started back.

02:36:33.440 --> 02:36:41.280
The ship, slowing radically, prepared by means of its various homeostatic servo-assist systems to land.

02:36:42.160 --> 02:36:45.920
And in addition, Joe said, I have to notify the society as to what's happened.

02:36:46.480 --> 02:36:50.640
They'll rake us over the coals, they'll point out right away that we walked into it like sheep.

02:36:51.600 --> 02:36:55.040
Sammy Mando said, but the society's our friend.

02:36:56.160 --> 02:37:01.200
Nobody, Al Hammond said, after a fiasco like this is our friend.

02:37:03.760 --> 02:37:09.600
A solar battery powered chopper marked beloved brethren moratorium waited at the edge of the Zurich field.

02:37:10.240 --> 02:37:16.560
Beside it stood a beetle-like individual, wearing a continental outfit, tweed toga, loafers,

02:37:16.560 --> 02:37:19.920
crimson sash, and a purple airplane propeller beanie.

02:37:20.560 --> 02:37:29.520
The proprietor of the moratorium minced toward Joe Chip, his gloved hand extended as Joe stepped from the ship's ramp onto the flat ground of earth.

02:37:30.000 --> 02:37:38.000
Not exactly a trip replete with joy, I would judge by your appearance, one vocal sang said, as they briefly shook hands.

02:37:38.560 --> 02:37:42.000
May my workmen go aboard your attractive ship and begin to—

02:37:42.000 --> 02:37:44.560
Yes, Joe said, go aboard and get him.

02:37:45.520 --> 02:37:50.240
Hands in his pockets he meandered toward the field's coffee shop, feeling completely glum.

02:37:51.520 --> 02:37:55.200
All standard operating procedure from now on, he realized.

02:37:55.840 --> 02:37:58.240
We got back to earth, Hollis didn't get us.

02:37:58.720 --> 02:37:59.520
We're lucky.

02:38:00.000 --> 02:38:04.480
The lunar operation, the whole awful, ugly, rat-trap experience, is over.

02:38:05.440 --> 02:38:10.640
And a new phase begins, one which we have no direct power over.

02:38:11.200 --> 02:38:15.680
I sense, please, the door of the coffee shop said, remaining shut before him.

02:38:16.480 --> 02:38:19.840
He waited until a couple passed by him on their way out.

02:38:20.240 --> 02:38:24.240
Neatly, he squeezed by the door, made it to a vacant stool, and seated himself.

02:38:24.240 --> 02:38:28.240
Hunched over, his hands locked together before him on the counter, he read the menu.

02:38:28.800 --> 02:38:30.160
Coffee, he said.

02:38:31.120 --> 02:38:31.920
May my sugar?

02:38:32.320 --> 02:38:35.440
The speaker of the shop's ruling monad, Turret, asked.

02:38:35.840 --> 02:38:36.320
Both.

02:38:37.120 --> 02:38:46.640
The little window opened, a cup of coffee, two tiny paper-wracked sacks of sugar, and a test tube-like container of cream slid forward and came to rest before him on the counter.

02:38:47.200 --> 02:38:50.000
One international pause-cred, please, the speaker said.

02:38:51.120 --> 02:38:55.920
Joe said, charge this to the account of Glenn Runciter of Runciter Associates, New York.

02:38:56.880 --> 02:38:59.120
Insert the proper credit card, the speaker said.

02:38:59.920 --> 02:39:03.680
They haven't let me carry around a credit card in five years, Joe said.

02:39:03.680 --> 02:39:05.920
I'm still paying off what I charged back in—

02:39:05.920 --> 02:39:08.080
One pause-cred, please, the speaker said.

02:39:08.080 --> 02:39:10.320
It began to tick ominously.

02:39:10.320 --> 02:39:13.200
Or in ten seconds I will notify the police.

02:39:13.920 --> 02:39:16.560
He passed the pause-cred over, the ticking stopped.

02:39:16.560 --> 02:39:20.080
We can do without your kind, the speaker said.

02:39:20.640 --> 02:39:27.600
One of these days, Joe said wrathfully, people like me will rise up and overthrow you, and the end of tyranny by the homeostatic machine will have arrived.

02:39:27.600 --> 02:39:32.400
The day of human values and compassion and simple warmth will return.

02:39:32.400 --> 02:39:37.280
And when that happens, someone like myself who has gone through an ordeal, will return.

02:39:37.680 --> 02:39:49.680
And when that happens, someone like myself who has gone through an ordeal, and who genuinely needs hot coffee to pick him up and keep him functioning when he has to function, will get the hot coffee, whether he happens to have a pause-cred readily available or not.

02:39:49.680 --> 02:40:01.680
He lifted the miniature picture of cream, then set it down, and furthermore, your cream or milk or whatever it is is sour.

02:40:03.040 --> 02:40:04.560
The speaker remained silent.

02:40:05.520 --> 02:40:07.920
Aren't you going to do anything? Joe said.

02:40:07.920 --> 02:40:10.000
You had plenty to say when you wanted a pause-cred.

02:40:11.200 --> 02:40:15.280
The pay door of the coffee shop opened, and Al Hammond came in.

02:40:15.280 --> 02:40:17.840
He walked over to Joe and seated himself beside him.

02:40:18.720 --> 02:40:21.680
The moratorium has runciter and their chopper.

02:40:21.680 --> 02:40:25.040
They're ready to take off, and they want to know if you intend to ride with them.

02:40:25.760 --> 02:40:26.960
Joe said, look at this cream.

02:40:27.600 --> 02:40:28.960
He held up the picture.

02:40:28.960 --> 02:40:32.640
In it, the fluid plastered the sides in dense clots.

02:40:33.200 --> 02:40:36.800
This is what you get for a pause-cred in one of the most modern technologically advanced

02:40:36.800 --> 02:40:37.520
cities on earth.

02:40:38.240 --> 02:40:43.520
I'm not leaving here until this place makes an adjustment, either returning my pause-cred

02:40:43.520 --> 02:40:47.520
or giving me a replacement picture of fresh cream so I can drink my coffee.

02:40:48.720 --> 02:40:52.160
Putting his hand on Joe's shoulder, Al Hammond studied him.

02:40:52.960 --> 02:40:53.920
What's the matter, Joe?

02:40:54.560 --> 02:40:59.600
First my cigarette, Joe said, then the two-year-old obsolete phone book in the ship,

02:40:59.600 --> 02:41:02.080
and now they're serving me weak old sour cream.

02:41:02.080 --> 02:41:03.120
I don't get it, Al.

02:41:04.160 --> 02:41:09.200
Drink the coffee black, Al said, and get over to the chopper so they can take

02:41:09.200 --> 02:41:10.800
runsciter to the moratorium.

02:41:11.520 --> 02:41:14.240
The rest of us will wait in the ship until you come back,

02:41:14.960 --> 02:41:18.720
and then we'll head for the nearest society office and make a full report to them.

02:41:20.160 --> 02:41:24.880
Joe picked up the coffee cup and found the coffee cold, inert, and ancient.

02:41:25.520 --> 02:41:27.840
A scummy mold covered the surface.

02:41:27.840 --> 02:41:30.000
He set the cup back down in revulsion.

02:41:30.000 --> 02:41:31.360
What's going on, he thought.

02:41:32.080 --> 02:41:33.120
What's happening to me?

02:41:34.000 --> 02:41:37.760
His revulsion became all at once a weird, nebulous panic.

02:41:38.640 --> 02:41:43.200
Come on, Joe, now set his hand closing firmly around Joe's shoulder.

02:41:43.200 --> 02:41:45.440
Forget the coffee, it isn't important.

02:41:45.440 --> 02:41:47.840
What matters is getting runsciter to—

02:41:47.840 --> 02:41:49.600
You know who gave me that pause-cred?

02:41:49.600 --> 02:41:51.360
Joe said, Pat Conley.

02:41:52.160 --> 02:41:55.040
And right away I did what I always do with money.

02:41:55.040 --> 02:41:59.200
I frittered it away on nothing, on last year's cup of coffee.

02:42:00.160 --> 02:42:03.600
He got down from the stool, urged off it by Al Hammond's hand.

02:42:04.720 --> 02:42:06.960
How about coming with me to the moratorium?

02:42:06.960 --> 02:42:11.040
I need backup help, especially when I go to confer with Ella.

02:42:12.000 --> 02:42:12.720
What should we do?

02:42:12.720 --> 02:42:14.080
Blame it on runsciter?

02:42:14.080 --> 02:42:16.800
Say, it was his decision for us all to go to Luna?

02:42:16.800 --> 02:42:17.600
That's the truth.

02:42:18.560 --> 02:42:20.800
Maybe we should tell her something else.

02:42:20.800 --> 02:42:26.480
Tell her his ship crashed, or he died of natural causes.

02:42:27.360 --> 02:42:31.040
But runsciter will eventually be linked up to her, Al said,

02:42:31.040 --> 02:42:32.400
and he'll tell her the truth.

02:42:33.040 --> 02:42:34.640
So you have to tell her the truth.

02:42:36.000 --> 02:42:38.400
They left the coffee shop and made their way to the chopper,

02:42:38.400 --> 02:42:40.800
belonging to the beloved brethren moratorium.

02:42:41.920 --> 02:42:45.680
Maybe I'll let runsciter tell her, Joe said as they boarded.

02:42:45.680 --> 02:42:46.480
Why not?

02:42:46.480 --> 02:42:50.400
It was his decision for us to go to Luna, let him tell her himself,

02:42:50.400 --> 02:42:52.000
and he's used to talking to her.

02:42:52.560 --> 02:42:53.680
Ready, gentlemen?

02:42:53.760 --> 02:42:56.720
Van Vogelsang inquired seated at the controls of the chopper.

02:42:57.360 --> 02:43:02.160
Shall we wind our doorful steps in the direction of Mr. Runciter's final home?

02:43:03.200 --> 02:43:06.960
Joe groaned and stared out through the window of the chopper,

02:43:06.960 --> 02:43:11.040
fixing his attention on the buildings that made up the installations of Zurich Field.

02:43:11.840 --> 02:43:14.000
Yeah, take off, Al said.

02:43:15.280 --> 02:43:20.080
As the chopper left the ground, the moratorium owner pressed a button on his control panel.

02:43:20.080 --> 02:43:23.200
Throughout the cabin of the chopper, from a dozen sources,

02:43:23.200 --> 02:43:27.360
the sound of Beethoven's miscellaneous rolled forth sonorously,

02:43:27.360 --> 02:43:32.720
the many voices saying, Agnus de Chitolis Picatamuni,

02:43:32.720 --> 02:43:37.840
over and over again accompanied by an electronically augmented symphony orchestra.

02:43:39.120 --> 02:43:44.240
Did you know that Tascanini used to sing along with the singers when he conducted an opera?

02:43:44.240 --> 02:43:44.720
Joe said.

02:43:45.760 --> 02:43:50.160
That in his recording of Traviati you can hear him during the Arias Emperor Lybera.

02:43:50.960 --> 02:43:52.720
I didn't know that, Al said.

02:43:53.440 --> 02:43:59.600
He watched the sleek sturdy connex of Zurich move by below a dignified and stately procession,

02:43:59.600 --> 02:44:01.920
which Joe also found himself watching.

02:44:02.960 --> 02:44:05.200
Liberemé domine, Joe said.

02:44:06.000 --> 02:44:06.960
What does that mean?

02:44:06.960 --> 02:44:10.480
Joe said, it means God have mercy on me.

02:44:10.480 --> 02:44:11.200
Don't you know that?

02:44:11.760 --> 02:44:12.800
Doesn't everybody know that?

02:44:13.840 --> 02:44:16.240
What made you think of it, Al said?

02:44:16.240 --> 02:44:17.040
The music!

02:44:17.040 --> 02:44:18.080
The goddamn music!

02:44:18.720 --> 02:44:21.120
To Von Vogel saying, he said, turn the music off.

02:44:21.120 --> 02:44:22.320
Rensseldur can't hear it.

02:44:22.320 --> 02:44:24.640
I'm the only one who can hear it, and I don't feel like hearing it.

02:44:25.520 --> 02:44:27.600
To Al, he said, you don't want to hear it, do you?

02:44:28.240 --> 02:44:30.640
Al said, calm down, Joe.

02:44:32.400 --> 02:44:37.280
We're carrying a dead employer to a place called the Beloved Brethren Moratorium, Joe said,

02:44:37.280 --> 02:44:38.480
and he says, calm down.

02:44:39.360 --> 02:44:41.520
You know, Rensseldur didn't have to go with us to Luna.

02:44:41.520 --> 02:44:44.080
He could have dispatched us and stayed in New York.

02:44:44.080 --> 02:44:49.040
So now the most life-loving, full-living man I ever met has been—

02:44:49.760 --> 02:44:54.240
Your dark-skinned companion's advice is good, the moratorium owner chimed in.

02:44:54.800 --> 02:44:57.840
What advice, Joe said, to calm yourself.

02:44:58.640 --> 02:45:02.000
Von Vogel saying, open the glove compartment of the chopper's control panel.

02:45:02.000 --> 02:45:04.880
He handed Joe a merry, multi-colored box.

02:45:04.880 --> 02:45:06.720
Chew one of these, Mr. Chip?

02:45:07.680 --> 02:45:11.120
Tranquillizing gum, Joe said, accepting the box.

02:45:11.840 --> 02:45:13.280
Reflexively, he opened it.

02:45:13.920 --> 02:45:16.480
Peach-flavored, tranquilizing gum.

02:45:17.600 --> 02:45:20.320
To Al, he said, do I have to take this?

02:45:21.120 --> 02:45:22.720
You should, Al said.

02:45:23.760 --> 02:45:28.560
Joe said, Rensseldur would never have taken a tranquilizer under circumstances of this sort.

02:45:28.560 --> 02:45:31.600
Glenn Rensseldur never took a tranquilizer in his life.

02:45:32.560 --> 02:45:33.920
You know what I realize now, Al?

02:45:34.480 --> 02:45:38.080
He gave his life to save ours in an indirect way.

02:45:38.800 --> 02:45:40.400
Very indirect, Al said.

02:45:41.600 --> 02:45:42.720
Here we are, he said.

02:45:43.280 --> 02:45:47.360
The chopper had begun to descend toward a target painted on a flat roof field below.

02:45:48.080 --> 02:45:51.440
You think you can compose yourself? he asked Joe.

02:45:51.440 --> 02:45:54.960
I can compose myself, Joe said, when I hear Rensseldur's voice again.

02:45:54.960 --> 02:45:58.160
When I know some form of life, half-life is still there.

02:45:59.280 --> 02:46:03.360
The moratorium owner said cheerily, I wouldn't worry on that score, Mr. Chip.

02:46:03.360 --> 02:46:06.480
We generally obtain an adequate protophasonic flow.

02:46:06.480 --> 02:46:11.760
At first, it is later when the half-life period has expended itself,

02:46:11.760 --> 02:46:17.360
that the heartache arises but with sensible planning that can be forestalled for many years.

02:46:18.160 --> 02:46:22.960
He shut off the motor of the chopper, touched a stud which caused the cabin door to slide back.

02:46:22.960 --> 02:46:26.080
Welcome to the beloved Brezhwin moratorium, he said.

02:46:26.640 --> 02:46:29.440
He ushered the two of them out onto the roof field.

02:46:29.440 --> 02:46:34.560
My personal secretary, Miss Viesen, will escort you to the consultation lounge.

02:46:34.560 --> 02:46:40.000
If you will vase there, being subliminally influenced into peace of soul by the colors

02:46:40.000 --> 02:46:45.280
and textures surrounding you, I will have Mr. Rensseldur brought in as soon as my technicians

02:46:45.280 --> 02:46:46.640
established contact with him.

02:46:47.360 --> 02:46:50.320
I want to be present at the whole process, Joe said.

02:46:50.320 --> 02:46:52.160
I want to see your technicians bring him back.

02:46:53.280 --> 02:46:58.720
To Al, the moratorium owner said, maybe as his friend you can make him understand.

02:46:59.520 --> 02:47:02.400
We have to wait in the lounge, Joe, Al said.

02:47:03.280 --> 02:47:04.640
Joe looked at him fiercely.

02:47:05.280 --> 02:47:06.960
Uncle Tom, he said.

02:47:07.920 --> 02:47:10.880
All the moratoriums work this way, Al said.

02:47:11.600 --> 02:47:13.120
Come on with me to the lounge.

02:47:14.080 --> 02:47:16.560
How long will it take, Joe asked the moratorium owner.

02:47:17.280 --> 02:47:20.400
We'll know one way or another within the first fifteen minutes.

02:47:20.400 --> 02:47:22.560
If we haven't gotten a measurable signal by then.

02:47:23.120 --> 02:47:25.520
You're only going to try for fifteen minutes, Joe said.

02:47:25.520 --> 02:47:28.800
To Al, he said, they're only going to try for fifteen minutes to bring back a man

02:47:28.800 --> 02:47:30.560
greater than all of us put together.

02:47:31.040 --> 02:47:33.280
He felt like crying, allowed.

02:47:33.280 --> 02:47:34.960
Come on, he said to Al.

02:47:34.960 --> 02:47:35.760
Let's—

02:47:35.760 --> 02:47:38.880
You come on, Al repeated, to the lounge.

02:47:40.560 --> 02:47:42.480
Joe followed him into the lounge.

02:47:43.520 --> 02:47:47.520
Cigarette, Al said, seating himself on a synthetic buffalo hide-couch.

02:47:47.520 --> 02:47:48.960
He held his pack up to Joe.

02:47:49.760 --> 02:47:51.920
They're stale, Joe said.

02:47:51.920 --> 02:47:54.400
He didn't need to take one to touch one to know that.

02:47:55.280 --> 02:47:56.800
Yeah, so they are.

02:47:57.360 --> 02:47:58.880
Al put the pack away.

02:47:58.880 --> 02:47:59.680
How did you know?

02:48:00.480 --> 02:48:01.120
He waited.

02:48:01.280 --> 02:48:06.080
You get discouraged easier than any one I ever ran into.

02:48:06.880 --> 02:48:08.320
We're lucky to be alive.

02:48:08.320 --> 02:48:11.200
It could be us, all of us, in that cold pack there.

02:48:11.840 --> 02:48:16.000
And Ronseter sitting out here in this lounge with these nutty colors.

02:48:16.560 --> 02:48:17.520
He looked at his watch.

02:48:18.480 --> 02:48:22.480
Joe said, all the cigarettes in the world are stale.

02:48:23.680 --> 02:48:24.960
He examined his own watch.

02:48:25.760 --> 02:48:26.400
Ten after.

02:48:27.360 --> 02:48:30.400
He pondered having many disjointed and unconnected,

02:48:30.400 --> 02:48:31.520
brooding thoughts.

02:48:31.520 --> 02:48:38.800
They swam through him like silvery fish, fears and mild dislikes and apprehensions,

02:48:38.800 --> 02:48:43.120
and all the silvery fish recirculating to begin once more as fear.

02:48:44.320 --> 02:48:47.760
If Ronseter were alive, he said, sitting out here in this lounge,

02:48:47.760 --> 02:48:49.040
everything would be OK.

02:48:49.040 --> 02:48:51.200
I know it, but I don't know why.

02:48:52.320 --> 02:48:55.600
He wondered what was at this moment going on between the

02:48:55.600 --> 02:48:58.720
moratorium's technicians and the remains of Glenn Ronseter.

02:48:59.840 --> 02:49:02.240
Do you remember dentists? he asked Al.

02:49:03.360 --> 02:49:05.760
I don't remember, but I know what they were.

02:49:06.320 --> 02:49:07.680
People's teeth used to decay.

02:49:08.240 --> 02:49:10.000
I realized that, Al said.

02:49:10.640 --> 02:49:14.400
My father told me what it used to feel like waiting in a dentist's office.

02:49:14.400 --> 02:49:17.280
Every time the nurse opened the door, you thought, it's happening.

02:49:17.280 --> 02:49:18.960
The thing I've been afraid of all my life.

02:49:20.000 --> 02:49:23.200
And that's what you feel now? Al asked.

02:49:23.280 --> 02:49:25.040
I feel Christ.

02:49:25.040 --> 02:49:28.960
Why doesn't that half-wit sap who runs this place come in here and say he's alive,

02:49:28.960 --> 02:49:32.240
Ronseter's alive, or else he's not?

02:49:32.800 --> 02:49:34.640
One way or another, yes or no?

02:49:35.840 --> 02:49:37.600
It's almost always, yes.

02:49:37.600 --> 02:49:41.520
Statistically, as Volkosang said, in this case it'll be no.

02:49:42.080 --> 02:49:43.920
You have no way of knowing that.

02:49:44.640 --> 02:49:49.040
Joe said, I wonder if Ray Hollis has an outlet here in Zurich.

02:49:49.840 --> 02:49:50.800
Of course he has.

02:49:51.360 --> 02:49:55.280
But by the time you get a precog in here, we'll already know anyhow.

02:49:56.080 --> 02:49:58.160
I'll phone up a precog, Joe said.

02:49:58.160 --> 02:49:59.600
I'll get one on the line right now.

02:50:00.160 --> 02:50:02.800
He started to his feet wondering where he could find a bid phone.

02:50:03.440 --> 02:50:04.240
Give me a quarter.

02:50:04.800 --> 02:50:05.840
Al shook his head.

02:50:06.880 --> 02:50:09.920
In a manner of speaking, Joe said, you're my employee.

02:50:10.480 --> 02:50:12.720
You have to do what I say or I'll fire you.

02:50:13.280 --> 02:50:16.080
As soon as Ronseter died, I took over management of the firm.

02:50:16.080 --> 02:50:18.240
I've been in charge since the bomb went off.

02:50:18.240 --> 02:50:21.600
It was my decision to bring him here and it's my decision to rent the use of a

02:50:21.600 --> 02:50:23.040
precog for a couple of minutes.

02:50:23.040 --> 02:50:24.480
Let's have the quarter.

02:50:24.480 --> 02:50:25.600
He held out his hand.

02:50:26.720 --> 02:50:32.320
Ronseter so shits, Al said, being run by a man who can't keep fifty cents on him.

02:50:33.040 --> 02:50:34.000
Here's a quarter.

02:50:34.560 --> 02:50:36.480
He got it from his pocket, tossed it to Joe.

02:50:37.440 --> 02:50:39.840
When you make out my paycheck, add it on.

02:50:41.440 --> 02:50:45.600
Joe left the lounge and wandered down a corridor, rubbing his forehead blearily.

02:50:46.320 --> 02:50:51.200
This is an unnatural place, he thought, halfway between the world and death.

02:50:52.160 --> 02:50:54.800
I am head of Ronseter associates now, he realized.

02:50:55.360 --> 02:50:59.760
Except for Ella, who isn't alive and can only speak if I visit this place and have her revived.

02:51:00.480 --> 02:51:05.520
I know the specifications in Glenn Ronseter's will, which now have automatically gone into

02:51:05.520 --> 02:51:06.160
effect.

02:51:06.160 --> 02:51:11.120
I'm supposed to take over until Ella, or Ella and he if he can be revived,

02:51:11.120 --> 02:51:13.040
decide on someone to replace him.

02:51:13.040 --> 02:51:15.680
They have to agree, both wills make that mandatory.

02:51:16.560 --> 02:51:20.000
Maybe he thought they'll decide I can do it on a permanent basis.

02:51:21.760 --> 02:51:23.680
That'll never come about, he realized.

02:51:24.240 --> 02:51:27.760
Not for someone who can't manage his own personal fiscal responsibilities.

02:51:28.560 --> 02:51:32.400
That's something else Hollis's precog would know, he realized.

02:51:33.280 --> 02:51:37.600
I can find out from them whether or not I'll be upgraded to director of the firm.

02:51:37.600 --> 02:51:40.000
That would be worth knowing, along with everything else.

02:51:40.640 --> 02:51:42.400
And I have to hire the precog anyhow.

02:51:43.280 --> 02:51:49.360
Which way to a public vid-phone, he asked a uniformed employee of the moratorium,

02:51:49.360 --> 02:51:50.960
the employee he pointed.

02:51:50.960 --> 02:51:55.440
Thanks, he said, and wandered on, coming at last to the pay-vid-phone.

02:51:56.000 --> 02:51:59.840
He lifted the receiver, listened for the dial tone, and then dropped in the quarter,

02:51:59.840 --> 02:52:00.880
which Al had given him.

02:52:01.600 --> 02:52:05.600
The phone said, I'm sorry sir, but I can't accept obsolete money.

02:52:06.320 --> 02:52:09.680
The quarter clattered out at the bottom of the phone and landed at his feet,

02:52:09.680 --> 02:52:11.200
expelled in disgust.

02:52:11.840 --> 02:52:15.840
What do you mean, he said, stooping awkwardly to retrieve the coin,

02:52:15.840 --> 02:52:18.800
since when is a North American confederation quarter obsolete?

02:52:19.600 --> 02:52:21.920
I am sorry sir, the phone said.

02:52:21.920 --> 02:52:25.680
The coin which you put into me was not a North American confederation quarter,

02:52:25.680 --> 02:52:30.320
but a recalled issue of the United States of America's Philadelphia Mint.

02:52:30.320 --> 02:52:33.040
It is of merely numismatical interest now.

02:52:34.320 --> 02:52:39.200
Joe examined the quarter and saw on its tarnished surface

02:52:39.200 --> 02:52:41.840
the vast relief profile of George Washington.

02:52:42.960 --> 02:52:49.360
And the date, the coin was forty years old, and as the phone had said, long ago recalled.

02:52:50.720 --> 02:52:55.840
Having difficulties, sir, a moratorium employee asked, walking over pleasantly,

02:52:55.840 --> 02:52:58.560
I saw the phone expel your coin, may I examine it?

02:52:59.120 --> 02:53:01.760
He held out his hand and Joe gave him the U.S. quarter.

02:53:02.720 --> 02:53:07.280
I will trade you a current Swiss ten-franc token for this, which the phone will accept.

02:53:08.000 --> 02:53:09.520
Fine, Joe said.

02:53:09.520 --> 02:53:12.400
He made the trade, dropped the ten-franc piece into the phone,

02:53:12.400 --> 02:53:15.200
and dialed Hollis's international toll-free number.

02:53:17.280 --> 02:53:21.120
Hollis' talents, a polished female voice said in his ear,

02:53:21.120 --> 02:53:26.080
and on the screen a girl's face modified by artificial beauty aids of an advanced nature

02:53:26.080 --> 02:53:27.120
manifested itself.

02:53:28.000 --> 02:53:31.520
Oh, Mr. Chip, the girl said, recognizing him.

02:53:31.520 --> 02:53:33.920
Mr. Hollis left word with us that you'd call.

02:53:33.920 --> 02:53:35.760
We'd been expecting you all afternoon.

02:53:35.760 --> 02:53:38.480
Pre-cogs, Joe thought.

02:53:39.520 --> 02:53:43.760
Mr. Hollis, the girl said, instructed us to put your call through to him.

02:53:43.760 --> 02:53:46.480
He wants to handle your needs personally.

02:53:46.480 --> 02:53:48.960
Would you hold on a moment while I put you through?

02:53:48.960 --> 02:53:53.440
So just a moment, Mr. Chip, the next voice you hear will be Mr. Hollis's god-willing.

02:53:54.240 --> 02:53:55.600
Her face vanished.

02:53:55.600 --> 02:53:57.680
He confronted a blank gray screen.

02:53:59.520 --> 02:54:04.720
A grim blue face, with recessive eyes, swam into focus.

02:54:04.720 --> 02:54:08.400
A mysterious countenance floating without neck or body.

02:54:09.120 --> 02:54:12.000
The eyes reminded him of flawed jewels.

02:54:12.000 --> 02:54:14.880
They shone, but the faceting had gone wrong.

02:54:14.880 --> 02:54:17.680
The eyes scattered light in irregular direction.

02:54:18.720 --> 02:54:20.320
Hello, Mr. Chip.

02:54:21.680 --> 02:54:24.160
So this is what he looks like, Joe thought.

02:54:24.160 --> 02:54:27.760
Photographs hadn't caught this, the imperfect planes and surfaces,

02:54:27.760 --> 02:54:31.120
as if the whole brittle edifice had once been dropped, had broken,

02:54:31.120 --> 02:54:34.320
and then been reglueed, but not quite as before.

02:54:34.880 --> 02:54:40.640
The society, Joe said, will receive a full report on your murder of Glenn Runciter.

02:54:41.360 --> 02:54:42.800
They own a lot of legal talent.

02:54:42.800 --> 02:54:44.560
You'll be in court the rest of your life.

02:54:45.520 --> 02:54:48.000
He waited for the face to react, but it did not.

02:54:49.040 --> 02:54:53.280
We know you did it, he said, and felt the futility of it,

02:54:53.280 --> 02:54:55.200
the pointlessness of what he was doing.

02:54:56.320 --> 02:55:00.960
As to the purpose of your call, Hollis said, in a slithering voice,

02:55:00.960 --> 02:55:03.680
which reminded Joe of snakes crawling over one another,

02:55:04.240 --> 02:55:08.880
Mr. Runciter will not, shaking Joe hung up the receiver.

02:55:10.320 --> 02:55:12.800
He walked back up the corridor along which he had come.

02:55:12.800 --> 02:55:16.800
He reached the lounge once more, where Al Hammond sat morosely picking

02:55:16.800 --> 02:55:19.040
apart a dry as dust former cigarette.

02:55:19.920 --> 02:55:23.440
There was a moment of silence, and then Al raised his head.

02:55:25.120 --> 02:55:26.800
It's no, Joe said.

02:55:28.320 --> 02:55:31.440
Vogel Sang came around looking for you, Al said.

02:55:32.240 --> 02:55:36.080
He acted very strange, and it was obvious what's been going on back there.

02:55:36.800 --> 02:55:39.280
Six will get you eight, he's afraid to tell you outright.

02:55:40.000 --> 02:55:44.720
He'll probably go through a long routine, but it'll boil down, like you said,

02:55:44.720 --> 02:55:46.000
it'll boil down to no.

02:55:47.280 --> 02:55:49.440
So, what now?

02:55:50.560 --> 02:55:51.120
He waited.

02:55:52.560 --> 02:55:54.800
Now we get Hollis, Joe said.

02:55:55.840 --> 02:55:57.040
We won't get Hollis.

02:55:57.760 --> 02:55:58.480
The society!

02:55:59.200 --> 02:56:00.080
He broke off.

02:56:00.080 --> 02:56:04.960
The owner of the moratorium had sidled into the lounge, looking nervous and haggard,

02:56:04.960 --> 02:56:09.280
but attempting at the same time to emit an aura of detached or steer prowess.

02:56:10.320 --> 02:56:11.520
We did what we could.

02:56:12.160 --> 02:56:16.240
At such low temperatures, the flow of current is virtually unimpeded.

02:56:16.240 --> 02:56:20.160
There's no perceptible resistance at minus 150 G.

02:56:21.040 --> 02:56:26.160
The signal should have bounced out clear and strong, but all we got from the amplifier was

02:56:26.160 --> 02:56:27.440
a 60-cycle hum.

02:56:28.720 --> 02:56:33.680
Remember, however, that we did not supervise the original cold pack installation.

02:56:33.680 --> 02:56:34.800
Bear that in mind.

02:56:35.760 --> 02:56:36.320
Al said,

02:56:37.040 --> 02:56:38.080
We have it in mind.

02:56:38.880 --> 02:56:41.520
He rose stiffly to his feet and stood facing Joe.

02:56:42.880 --> 02:56:43.920
I guess that's it.

02:56:44.880 --> 02:56:46.480
I'll talk to Ella, Joe said.

02:56:47.120 --> 02:56:48.320
Now, Al said,

02:56:48.960 --> 02:56:51.200
You better wait until you know what you're going to say.

02:56:52.080 --> 02:56:54.800
Tell her to morrow, go home, and get some sleep.

02:56:54.800 --> 02:56:59.040
To go home, Joe said, is to go home to Pat Connolly.

02:56:59.040 --> 02:57:00.960
I'm in no shape to cope with her, either.

02:57:02.080 --> 02:57:04.720
Take a hotel room here in Zurich.

02:57:04.720 --> 02:57:06.240
Al said, Disappear.

02:57:07.360 --> 02:57:11.040
I'll go back to the ship, tell the others, and report to the society.

02:57:11.040 --> 02:57:13.120
You can delegate it to me in writing.

02:57:13.920 --> 02:57:15.680
To Von Vogelsang, he said,

02:57:15.680 --> 02:57:17.440
Bring us a pen and a sheet of paper.

02:57:18.480 --> 02:57:20.720
You know who I feel like talking to, Joe said,

02:57:20.720 --> 02:57:24.000
As the moratorium owner scuttled off in search of pen and paper.

02:57:25.120 --> 02:57:26.240
Wendy, right.

02:57:26.960 --> 02:57:27.920
She'll know what to do.

02:57:27.920 --> 02:57:29.200
I value her opinion.

02:57:30.080 --> 02:57:31.440
Why is that, I wonder.

02:57:31.440 --> 02:57:32.400
I barely know her.

02:57:33.520 --> 02:57:37.360
He noticed then that subtle background music hung over the lounge.

02:57:37.360 --> 02:57:39.280
It had been there all this time.

02:57:39.280 --> 02:57:40.720
The same as on the chopper.

02:57:40.720 --> 02:57:44.000
Dei siirei dei is illa, the voices sang darkly.

02:57:44.000 --> 02:57:48.480
Solvet seiclum infavila testedavit comsibila.

02:57:49.120 --> 02:57:50.800
The very requiem, he realized.

02:57:51.360 --> 02:57:53.520
Von Vogelsang probably personally,

02:57:53.520 --> 02:57:58.560
with his own two hands, switched it on at 9 a.m. every morning when he arrived for work.

02:57:59.920 --> 02:58:03.120
Once you get to your hotel room, Al said,

02:58:03.120 --> 02:58:05.920
I could probably talk Wendy right into showing up there.

02:58:06.720 --> 02:58:08.560
That would be immoral, Joe said.

02:58:09.440 --> 02:58:11.360
What? Al stared at him.

02:58:11.360 --> 02:58:16.000
At a time like this, when the whole organization is about to sink into oblivion,

02:58:16.000 --> 02:58:17.600
unless you can pull yourself together,

02:58:18.400 --> 02:58:21.360
anything that'll make you function is desirable.

02:58:21.360 --> 02:58:22.880
In fact, necessary.

02:58:23.760 --> 02:58:28.000
Go back to the phone, call a hotel, come back here and tell me the name of the hotel,

02:58:28.000 --> 02:58:30.960
and that all our money is worthless, Joe said.

02:58:30.960 --> 02:58:32.320
I can't operate the phone.

02:58:32.880 --> 02:58:37.360
Now, unless I can find a coin collector who trade me another Swiss 10-frank piece of current issue.

02:58:38.480 --> 02:58:40.080
Jesus! Al said.

02:58:40.080 --> 02:58:42.960
He let out his breath in a groaning sigh and shook his head.

02:58:43.600 --> 02:58:45.840
Is it my fault, Joe said?

02:58:45.840 --> 02:58:48.480
Did I make that quarter you gave me obsolete?

02:58:48.480 --> 02:58:49.360
He felt anger.

02:58:50.240 --> 02:58:51.760
In some weird way.

02:58:51.760 --> 02:58:53.360
Al said, yes, it is your fault.

02:58:53.920 --> 02:58:54.960
But I don't know how.

02:58:55.760 --> 02:58:57.440
Maybe one day I'll figure it out.

02:58:58.400 --> 02:59:00.400
Okay, we'll both go back to Prattfall, too.

02:59:00.400 --> 02:59:03.360
You can pick Wendy right up there and take her to the hotel with you.

02:59:04.240 --> 02:59:08.240
Cuantos tremor es futuras, the voices sang.

02:59:08.240 --> 02:59:13.920
Cuando yur ex es venturas, cunta stricte discusuros.

02:59:15.360 --> 02:59:16.800
What'll I pay the hotel with?

02:59:16.800 --> 02:59:18.960
They won't take our money any more than the phone will.

02:59:20.240 --> 02:59:23.200
Cursing, Al yanked out his wallet, examined the bills in it.

02:59:24.080 --> 02:59:26.080
These are old, but still in circulation.

02:59:26.640 --> 02:59:28.480
He inspected the coins in his pockets.

02:59:29.040 --> 02:59:31.200
These aren't in circulation.

02:59:31.200 --> 02:59:33.360
He tossed the coins to the carpet of the lounge,

02:59:33.360 --> 02:59:35.680
ridding himself as the phone had in disgust.

02:59:36.320 --> 02:59:37.600
Take these bills.

02:59:37.600 --> 02:59:39.360
He handed the paper currency to Joe.

02:59:39.920 --> 02:59:42.240
There's enough there for the hotel room for one night,

02:59:42.240 --> 02:59:44.240
dinner and a couple of drinks for each of you.

02:59:44.240 --> 02:59:47.440
I'll send a ship from New York tomorrow to pick you and her up.

02:59:48.000 --> 02:59:49.760
I'll pay you back, Joe said.

02:59:50.400 --> 02:59:53.040
As Protem Director of Runciter Associates,

02:59:53.040 --> 02:59:54.320
I'll draw a higher salary.

02:59:54.960 --> 02:59:57.920
I'll be able to pay all my debts off, including the back taxes,

02:59:57.920 --> 03:00:01.840
penalties and fines which the income tax people without Pat Connolly,

03:00:01.840 --> 03:00:02.880
without her help.

03:00:03.440 --> 03:00:05.360
I can throw her out now, Joe said.

03:00:06.160 --> 03:00:07.680
Al said, I wonder.

03:00:08.240 --> 03:00:09.520
This is a new start for me.

03:00:10.080 --> 03:00:11.120
A new lease on life.

03:00:12.000 --> 03:00:14.160
I can run the firm, he said to himself.

03:00:14.160 --> 03:00:16.080
Certainly I won't make the mistake that Runciter made.

03:00:16.640 --> 03:00:20.800
Hollis, posing as Stanton Mick, won't lure me and my inertials off Earth,

03:00:20.800 --> 03:00:22.000
where we can be gotten at.

03:00:23.040 --> 03:00:27.440
In my opinion, Al said hollily, you have a will to fail.

03:00:28.240 --> 03:00:32.400
No combination of circumstances, including this, is going to change that.

03:00:33.040 --> 03:00:36.800
What I actually have, Joe said, is a will to succeed.

03:00:37.360 --> 03:00:41.440
Glenn Runciter saw that, which is why he specified in his will that I take over

03:00:41.440 --> 03:00:44.880
in the event of his death and the failure of the beloved brethren moratorium

03:00:44.880 --> 03:00:50.240
to revive him into half-life, or any other reputable moratorium as specified by me.

03:00:51.120 --> 03:00:53.200
Within him his confidence rose.

03:00:53.760 --> 03:00:58.480
He saw now the manifold possibilities ahead as clearly as if he had pre-cog abilities.

03:00:59.520 --> 03:01:03.600
And then he remembered Pat's talent, what she could do to pre-cogs,

03:01:03.600 --> 03:01:05.840
to any attempt to foresee the future.

03:01:06.800 --> 03:01:14.880
Tuber Mirum Spargin Sonum, the voices sang, per se putre regionim cogit omnis antithronum.

03:01:14.960 --> 03:01:20.720
Reading his expression, Al said, you're not going to throw her out, not with what she can do.

03:01:21.680 --> 03:01:26.480
I'll rent a room at the Zurich Roots Hotel, Joe decided, as per your outline proposal.

03:01:27.360 --> 03:01:33.120
But he thought, Al's right, it won't work. Pat, or even something worse, will move in and destroy me.

03:01:33.760 --> 03:01:40.480
I'm doomed in the classic sense. An image thrust itself into his agitated fatigued mind,

03:01:41.120 --> 03:01:47.120
a bird caught in cobwebs. Age hung about the image, and this frightened him.

03:01:47.120 --> 03:01:52.400
This aspect of it seemed literal and real. And he thought prophetic,

03:01:53.280 --> 03:02:00.400
but he could not make out exactly how. The coins, he thought, out of circulation rejected by the

03:02:00.400 --> 03:02:07.680
phone, collectors items, like ones found in museums. Is that it? Hard to say, he really didn't know.

03:02:07.680 --> 03:02:16.720
More's to pay, but the voices sang, et natura com risurgit crittura yudicanti responsura.

03:02:17.360 --> 03:02:18.880
They sang on and on.

03:02:22.240 --> 03:02:29.680
Eight. If money worries have you in the cellar, go visit the lady at Ubic Savings and Loan.

03:02:29.680 --> 03:02:34.160
She'll take the frets out of your debts. Suppose, for example, you borrow 59

03:02:34.160 --> 03:02:38.000
Pascrades on an interest-only loan. Let's see, that adds up to...

03:02:40.000 --> 03:02:45.680
Daylight rattled through the elegant hotel room, uncovering stately shapes, which Joe Chip

03:02:45.680 --> 03:02:52.720
blinkingly saw were articles of furnishings. Great hand-printed drapes of a neo-silk screen sort,

03:02:53.280 --> 03:02:58.400
that depicted man's assent from the unicellular organisms of the Cambrian period

03:02:58.400 --> 03:03:02.080
to the first heavier-than-air flight at the beginning of the 20th century.

03:03:02.640 --> 03:03:06.880
A magnificent pseudo-mahogany dresser, four variegated,

03:03:06.880 --> 03:03:14.000
crypto-chrome-plated reclining chairs. He groggily admired the splendor of the hotel room,

03:03:15.120 --> 03:03:20.000
and then he realized with a tremor of keen disappointment that Wendy had not come knocking

03:03:20.000 --> 03:03:24.640
at the door, or else he had not heard her he had been sleeping too deeply.

03:03:25.920 --> 03:03:30.640
Thus the new empire of his hegemony had vanished in the moment it had begun.

03:03:32.080 --> 03:03:38.240
With numbing gloom, a remnant of yesterday pervading him, he lurched from the big bed,

03:03:38.240 --> 03:03:45.600
found his clothes and dressed. It was cold, unusually so, he noticed that and pondered on it.

03:03:46.240 --> 03:03:49.120
Then he lifted the phone receiver and dialed for room service.

03:03:50.560 --> 03:03:54.640
Pay him back, if at all possible, the receiver declared in his ear.

03:03:55.280 --> 03:04:00.000
First, of course, it has to be established whether Stanton Mick actually involved himself,

03:04:00.640 --> 03:04:07.440
or if a mere homo-simulacric substitute was in action against us, and if so, why, and if not,

03:04:07.440 --> 03:04:14.800
then how—the voice droned on, speaking to itself, and not to Joe. It seemed as unaware of him as if

03:04:14.800 --> 03:04:20.480
he did not exist. From all our previous reports, the voice declared, it would appear that Mick

03:04:20.480 --> 03:04:26.560
acts generally in a reputable manner, and in accord with legal and ethical practices established

03:04:26.560 --> 03:04:32.080
throughout the system, in view of this— Joe hung up the phone and stood,

03:04:32.080 --> 03:04:38.560
dizzily swaying, trying to clear his head. Answered his voice. Beyond any doubt.

03:04:39.600 --> 03:04:41.680
He again picked up the phone, listened once more.

03:04:42.240 --> 03:04:47.200
Laws sued by Mick, who can afford and is accustomed to litigation of that nature.

03:04:47.760 --> 03:04:53.840
Our own legal staff certainly should be consulted before we make a formal report to this society.

03:04:53.840 --> 03:04:59.280
It would be liable, if made public, and grounds for a suit claiming false arrest if—

03:04:59.280 --> 03:05:05.280
RUNCENOR! Joe said. He said it loudly. Unable to verify, probably, for at least—

03:05:06.560 --> 03:05:07.280
Joe hung up.

03:05:08.800 --> 03:05:11.440
I don't understand this, he said to himself.

03:05:13.280 --> 03:05:18.240
Going into the bathroom, he splashed icy water on his face, combed his hair with a sanitary,

03:05:18.480 --> 03:05:24.800
free hotel comb. Then, after meditating for a time, shaved with the sanitary free hotel

03:05:24.800 --> 03:05:31.600
throwaway razor. He slapped sanitary free hotel aftershave onto his chin, neck, and jaws, unwrapped

03:05:31.600 --> 03:05:39.200
the sanitary free hotel glass, and drank from it. Did the moratorium finally manage to revive him?

03:05:39.200 --> 03:05:46.400
He wondered. And wired him up to my phone? RUNCENOR! As soon as he came around would want to talk to me,

03:05:46.400 --> 03:05:54.720
probably before anyone else. But if so, why can't he hear me back? Why does it consist of one-way

03:05:54.720 --> 03:05:58.800
transmission only? Is it only a technical defect which will clear up?

03:06:00.320 --> 03:06:03.680
Returning to the phone, he picked up the receiver once more with the idea of calling

03:06:03.680 --> 03:06:10.080
the beloved brethren moratorium. Not the ideal person to manage the firm in view of his confused

03:06:10.080 --> 03:06:12.320
personal difficulties, particularly—

03:06:13.600 --> 03:06:19.360
I can't call, Joe realized. He hung up the receiver. I can't even get room service.

03:06:21.200 --> 03:06:26.560
In a corner of the large room a chime sounded, and a tinkling mechanical voice called

03:06:26.560 --> 03:06:32.720
Ammure Free Homeopapemachine, a service supplied exclusively by all the fine roots hotels throughout

03:06:32.720 --> 03:06:38.080
Earth and the colonies, simply dialed the classification of news that you wish, and in a

03:06:38.080 --> 03:06:42.480
matter of seconds I'll speedily provide you with a fresh, up-to-the-minute, homeopape,

03:06:43.040 --> 03:06:47.920
tailored to your individual requirements, and let me repeat at no cost to you.

03:06:49.040 --> 03:06:52.480
Okay, Joe said, and crossed the room to the machine.

03:06:53.360 --> 03:06:59.280
Maybe by now he reflected news of Runceter's murder has gotten out. The news media cover

03:06:59.280 --> 03:07:06.080
all admissions to moratoriums routinely. He pressed the button marked High Type Interplan Info.

03:07:06.640 --> 03:07:11.840
At once the machine began to clank out a printed sheet which he gathered up as fast as it emerged.

03:07:13.120 --> 03:07:19.040
No mention of Runceter. Too soon? Or had the society managed to suppress it?

03:07:20.080 --> 03:07:24.960
Or Al, he thought, maybe Al slipped a few pause crats to the owner of the moratorium.

03:07:26.080 --> 03:07:30.880
But he himself had all of Al's money. Al couldn't buy off anybody to do anything.

03:07:31.840 --> 03:07:37.520
A knock sounded on the hotel room door. Putting down the homeopape, Joe made his way cautiously

03:07:37.520 --> 03:07:42.000
to the door, thinking, it's probably Pat Conley. She's trapped me here.

03:07:43.120 --> 03:07:47.120
On the other hand, it might be someone from New York here to pick me up and take me back there.

03:07:47.920 --> 03:07:53.920
Theoretically, he conjectured, it could even be Wendy. But that did not seem likely, not now,

03:07:53.920 --> 03:07:59.360
not this late. It could also be an assassin dispatched by Hollis.

03:08:00.080 --> 03:08:05.280
He could be killing us off one by one. Joe opened the door.

03:08:06.800 --> 03:08:12.800
Quivering with unease, ringing his pulpy hands together, Herbert Schoenheit von Vogelsang stood

03:08:12.800 --> 03:08:19.280
in the doorway, mumbling, I just don't understand it, Mr. Schip. We've worked all night in relays.

03:08:19.280 --> 03:08:24.640
They just are not getting a single spark. And yet we ran an electroencephalograph,

03:08:24.640 --> 03:08:31.120
and the Gram showed faith but unmistakable cerebral activity. So, after life is there,

03:08:31.120 --> 03:08:36.800
but we still can't seem to tap it. We've got probes at every part of the cortex now.

03:08:37.760 --> 03:08:43.360
I don't know what else we can do, sir. Is there measurable brain metabolism, Joe asked?

03:08:43.360 --> 03:08:48.480
Yes, sir. We called in an outside expert from another moratorium, and he detected it using

03:08:48.480 --> 03:08:54.400
his own equipment. It's a normal amount, too, just what you'd expect immediately after death.

03:08:55.520 --> 03:09:01.040
How did you know where to find me, Joe asked? We called Mr. Hammond in New York.

03:09:01.040 --> 03:09:06.640
Then I tried to call you here at your hotel, but your phone has been busy all morning.

03:09:07.200 --> 03:09:09.680
That's why I found it necessary to come here in person.

03:09:10.720 --> 03:09:14.400
It's broken, Joe said, the phone. I can't call out, either.

03:09:15.280 --> 03:09:20.960
The moratorium owner said, Mr. Hammond tried to contact you, too, with no success.

03:09:20.960 --> 03:09:25.680
He asked me to give you a message from him, something he wants you to do here in Zurich

03:09:25.680 --> 03:09:30.480
before you start back to New York. He wants to remind me, Joe said, to consult Ella,

03:09:31.360 --> 03:09:36.000
to tell her about her husband's unfortunate, untimely death.

03:09:37.440 --> 03:09:41.520
Can I borrow a couple of passcreds from you, Joe said, so I can eat breakfast?

03:09:42.480 --> 03:09:48.160
Mr. Hammond warned me that you would try to borrow money from me. He informed me that he

03:09:48.160 --> 03:09:53.200
already provided you with sufficient funds to pay for your hotel room plus a round of drinks,

03:09:53.200 --> 03:09:58.480
as well as Al based his estimate on the assumption that I would rent a more modest room than this.

03:09:58.480 --> 03:10:02.160
However, nothing smaller than this was available, which Al did not foresee.

03:10:02.960 --> 03:10:06.800
You can add it on to the statement which you will be presenting to Runciter Associates

03:10:06.800 --> 03:10:12.640
at the end of the month. I am, as Al probably told you, now acting director of the firm.

03:10:13.520 --> 03:10:17.920
You're dealing with a positive thinking powerful man here who has worked his way

03:10:17.920 --> 03:10:24.640
step by step to the top. I could, as you must well realize, reconsider our basic policy decision

03:10:24.640 --> 03:10:30.560
as to which moratorium we wish to patronize. We might, for example, prefer one nearer New York.

03:10:32.000 --> 03:10:35.920
Grumpily Von Vogelsang reached within his tweed toga and brought out an

03:10:36.320 --> 03:10:39.040
ersatz alligator skin wallet which he dug into.

03:10:39.920 --> 03:10:43.440
It's a harsh world we're living in, Joe said, accepting the money.

03:10:43.440 --> 03:10:49.040
The rule is dog eat dog. Mr. Hammond gave me further information to pass on to you.

03:10:49.600 --> 03:10:54.560
The ship from your New York office will arrive in Zurich two hours from now, approximately.

03:10:55.200 --> 03:11:01.600
Fine, Joe said. In order for you to have ample time to confer with Ella Runciter, Mr. Hammond

03:11:01.600 --> 03:11:07.760
will have the ship pick you up as a moratorium. In view of this, Mr. Hammond suggests that I

03:11:07.760 --> 03:11:12.080
take you back to the moratorium with me. My chopper is parked on the hotel roof.

03:11:14.000 --> 03:11:17.680
Al Hammond said that, that I should return to the moratorium with you?

03:11:18.320 --> 03:11:25.120
That's right, Von Vogelsang nodded. A tall, stoop-shouldered negro about 30 years old,

03:11:25.120 --> 03:11:29.760
with gold cap front teeth each with an ornamental design, the one on the left of heart,

03:11:29.760 --> 03:11:35.840
the next club, the one on the right, a diamond. The man who came with us from Zurich field

03:11:35.840 --> 03:11:42.080
yesterday who waited with you at the moratorium. Joe said, did he have on green felt knickers,

03:11:42.080 --> 03:11:46.720
gray golf socks, badger hide, open midriff blouse, and imitation patent leather pumps?

03:11:47.440 --> 03:11:51.200
I couldn't see what he wore. I just saw his face on the vid screen.

03:11:52.240 --> 03:11:56.160
Did he convey any specific cold words so I could be sure it was him?

03:11:57.120 --> 03:12:03.360
The moratorium owner peeved said, I don't understand the problem, Mr. Chip. The man who

03:12:03.360 --> 03:12:07.920
talked to me on the vid phone from New York is the same man you had with you yesterday.

03:12:07.920 --> 03:12:11.600
I can't take a chance, Joe said, on going with you, on getting into your chopper.

03:12:12.160 --> 03:12:15.920
Maybe Ray Hollis sent you. It was Ray Hollis who killed Mr. Runciter.

03:12:16.800 --> 03:12:22.720
His eyes like glass buttons Von Vogelsang said, did you inform the Prudence Society of this?

03:12:23.280 --> 03:12:28.720
We will. We'll get around to it in due time. Meanwhile, we have to watch out that Hollis

03:12:28.720 --> 03:12:33.040
doesn't get the rest of us. He intended to kill us too, there on Luna.

03:12:33.600 --> 03:12:39.360
You need protection, the moratorium owner said. I suggest you go immediately to your phone and

03:12:39.360 --> 03:12:44.720
call the Zurich police. They'll assign a man to cover you until you leave for New York, and as

03:12:44.720 --> 03:12:51.120
soon as you arrive in New York, my phone, as I said, is broken. All I get on it is the voice of

03:12:51.120 --> 03:12:56.640
Glenn Runciter. That's why no one could reach me. Really? How very unusual.

03:12:57.440 --> 03:13:00.960
The moratorium owner undulated past him into the hotel room.

03:13:01.680 --> 03:13:05.200
May I listen? He picked up the phone receiver, questioningly.

03:13:05.920 --> 03:13:11.600
One poskred, Joe said. Digging into the pockets of his tweed toga, the moratorium owner fished

03:13:11.600 --> 03:13:17.680
out a handful of coins, his airplane propeller beanie whirred irritably, as he handed three

03:13:17.680 --> 03:13:23.680
of the coins to Joe. I'm only charging you what they ask around here for a cup of coffee, Joe said.

03:13:23.680 --> 03:13:28.640
This ought to be worth at least that much. Thinking that, he realized that he had had no

03:13:28.640 --> 03:13:33.920
breakfast and that he would be facing Ella in that condition. Well, he could take an amphetamine

03:13:33.920 --> 03:13:40.240
instead. The hotel probably provided them free as a courtesy. Holding, the phone receiver tightly

03:13:40.240 --> 03:13:46.640
against his ear, Von Vogelsang said, I don't hear anything, not even a dial tone.

03:13:48.240 --> 03:13:55.520
Now I hear a little static, as if from a great distance, very faint. He held the receiver out

03:13:55.520 --> 03:14:03.360
to Joe, who took it and also listened. He too heard only the far-off static from thousands

03:14:03.360 --> 03:14:11.520
of miles away, he thought. Eerie. As perplexing in its own way as the voice of Runciter, if

03:14:11.520 --> 03:14:16.960
that was what it had been. I'll return your poskred, he said, hanging up the receiver.

03:14:16.960 --> 03:14:21.440
Never mind, Von Vogelsang said. But you didn't get to hear his voice.

03:14:22.080 --> 03:14:25.360
Let's return to the moratorium, as you, Mr. Hammond, requested.

03:14:26.320 --> 03:14:33.680
Joe said, Al Hammond is my employee. I make policy. I think I'll return to New York before I talk to

03:14:33.680 --> 03:14:38.640
Ella. In my opinion, it's more important to frame our formal notification to the society.

03:14:38.640 --> 03:14:43.840
When you talk to Al Hammond, did he say whether all the inertials left Zurich with him? Oh, but

03:14:43.840 --> 03:14:49.360
the girl who spends the nights with you here in the hotel? Puzzled, the moratorium owner looked

03:14:49.360 --> 03:14:54.800
around the room, obviously wondering where she was. His peculiar face fused over with concern.

03:14:55.520 --> 03:14:56.400
Isn't she here?

03:14:57.840 --> 03:15:05.280
Which girl was it? Joe asked. His morale already low plunged into the blackest depths of his mind.

03:15:06.320 --> 03:15:12.560
Mr. Hammond didn't say. He assumed you'd know. It would have been indiscreet for him to tell me

03:15:12.560 --> 03:15:20.720
her name considering the circumstances didn't shebe. Nobody showed up. Which had it been? Pat Conley?

03:15:20.720 --> 03:15:27.120
Or Wendy? He prowled about the hotel room reflexively working off his fear. I hoped to God he thought

03:15:27.120 --> 03:15:34.960
that it was Pat. In the closet, Von Vogelsang said. What? He stopped pacing. Maybe you ought to look

03:15:34.960 --> 03:15:42.240
in there. These more expensive suites have extra large closets. Joe touched the stud of the closet

03:15:42.640 --> 03:15:48.400
door. Its spring-loaded mechanism sent it flying open. On the floor of the closet,

03:15:48.400 --> 03:15:55.840
a huddled heap dehydrated, almost mummified, lay curled up. Decaying shreds of what seemingly had

03:15:55.840 --> 03:16:02.480
once been cloth covered most of it, as if it had by degrees over a long period of time retracted

03:16:03.120 --> 03:16:09.360
into what remained of its garments. Bending, he turned it over. It weighed only a few pounds.

03:16:09.360 --> 03:16:16.000
At the push of his hand, its limbs folded out into thin bony extensions that rustled like paper.

03:16:17.040 --> 03:16:24.560
Its hair seemed enormously long, wiry and tangled. The black cloud of hair obscured its face.

03:16:25.520 --> 03:16:32.480
He crouched, not moving, not wanting to see who it was. In a strangled voice Von Vogelsang rasped.

03:16:33.280 --> 03:16:39.040
That's old, completely dried out, like it's been here for centuries.

03:16:40.000 --> 03:16:41.840
I'll go downstairs and tell the manager.

03:16:42.880 --> 03:16:49.360
It can't be an adult woman, Joe said. This could only be the remnants of a child that was just too

03:16:49.360 --> 03:16:56.000
small. It can't be either Pat or Wendy, he said, and lifted the cloudy hair away from its face.

03:16:56.960 --> 03:17:03.040
It's like it was in a kiln, he said, at a very high temperature for a long time.

03:17:04.000 --> 03:17:06.480
The blast, he thought, the severe heat from the bomb.

03:17:07.680 --> 03:17:13.280
He stared silently, then, at the shriveled, heat-darkened little face,

03:17:14.400 --> 03:17:18.400
and knew who this was with difficulty he recognized her.

03:17:19.680 --> 03:17:20.560
Wendy Wright

03:17:20.560 --> 03:17:26.240
Sometimes, during the night, he reasoned, she had come into the room and then

03:17:27.040 --> 03:17:32.720
some process had started in on her or around her. She had sensed it, and had crept off,

03:17:32.720 --> 03:17:39.120
hiding herself in the closet so he wouldn't know. In her last few hours of life, or perhaps minutes,

03:17:39.120 --> 03:17:44.560
he hoped it was only minutes. This had overtaken her, but she had made no sound. She hadn't

03:17:44.560 --> 03:17:49.760
awakened him. Or he thought she tried, and she couldn't do it, couldn't attract my attention.

03:17:51.200 --> 03:17:55.520
Maybe it was after that, after trying and failing to wake me, that she crawled into this closet.

03:17:56.320 --> 03:17:58.640
I prayed to God, he thought, that it happened fast.

03:17:59.920 --> 03:18:03.840
You can't do anything for her, he asked when Vogel sang, at your moratorium?

03:18:04.480 --> 03:18:10.400
Not this late. There wouldn't be any residual half-life left, not with this complete deterioration.

03:18:11.040 --> 03:18:18.240
Is she the girl? Yes, he said, nodding. You better leave this hotel right now,

03:18:18.240 --> 03:18:24.560
for your own safety. Hulles, it is hulles, isn't it? We'll do this to you too.

03:18:25.920 --> 03:18:30.480
My cigarettes, Joe said, dried out. The two-year-old phone book on the ship.

03:18:31.280 --> 03:18:38.960
The soured cream and coffee with scum on it, mold on it. The antiquated money. The common thread, age.

03:18:39.040 --> 03:18:43.680
She said that, back on Luna, after we made it up to the ship. She said, I feel old.

03:18:44.960 --> 03:18:49.200
He pondered trying to control his fear. It had begun now to turn into terror.

03:18:49.200 --> 03:18:53.920
But the voice on the phone, he thought, Runceter's voice, what did that mean?

03:18:54.960 --> 03:19:00.720
He saw no underlying pattern, no meaning. Runceter's voice on the Vid phone fitted no theory,

03:19:00.720 --> 03:19:02.400
which he could summon up or imagine.

03:19:02.400 --> 03:19:11.600
Radiation, Van Valkelsang said. It would seem to me that she was exposed to extensive radioactivity,

03:19:11.600 --> 03:19:15.760
probably some time ago, an enormous amount of it, in fact.

03:19:17.280 --> 03:19:22.240
Joe said, I think she died because of the blast, the explosion that killed Runceter.

03:19:23.360 --> 03:19:29.680
Cobalt particles, he said to himself. Hot dust that settled on her and which she inhaled.

03:19:30.640 --> 03:19:35.600
But then we're all going to die this way. It must have settled on all of us.

03:19:35.600 --> 03:19:39.520
I have it in my own lungs. So does Al. So do the other inertials.

03:19:40.400 --> 03:19:43.120
There's nothing that can be done in that case. It's too late.

03:19:44.320 --> 03:19:48.240
We didn't think of that, he realized. It didn't occur to us that the explosion

03:19:48.240 --> 03:19:53.520
consisted of a micronic nuclear reaction. No wonder Hollis allowed us to leave.

03:19:54.480 --> 03:20:00.640
And yet that explained Wendy's death and it explained the dried out cigarettes,

03:20:00.640 --> 03:20:05.280
but not the phone book, not the coins, not the corruption of the cream and coffee.

03:20:06.400 --> 03:20:11.600
Nor did it explain Runceter's voice, the yammering monologue on the hotel room's Vid phone,

03:20:12.240 --> 03:20:17.920
which ceased when Van Valkelsang lifted the receiver, when someone else tried to hear it,

03:20:17.920 --> 03:20:18.720
he realized.

03:20:19.040 --> 03:20:23.120
I've got to get back to New York, he said to himself. All of us who were there on Luna,

03:20:23.120 --> 03:20:27.040
all of us who were present when the bomb blast went off, we have to work this out together.

03:20:27.040 --> 03:20:33.120
In fact, it's probably the only way it can be worked out. Before the rest of us die,

03:20:33.120 --> 03:20:38.800
one by one, the way Wendy did. Or in a worse way, if that's possible.

03:20:40.080 --> 03:20:44.720
Have the hotel management send a polyethylene bag up here, he said to the moratorium owner.

03:20:44.720 --> 03:20:47.040
I'll put her in it and take her with me to New York.

03:20:48.720 --> 03:20:53.280
Isn't this a matter for the police? A horrible murder like this, they should be informed.

03:20:53.840 --> 03:20:55.280
Joe said, just get me the bag.

03:20:56.160 --> 03:21:01.280
All right, it's your employee. The moratorium owner started off down the hall.

03:21:02.080 --> 03:21:04.720
Was, once, Joe said, not any more.

03:21:05.840 --> 03:21:11.600
It would have to be her first, he said to himself. But maybe in a sense that's better.

03:21:12.720 --> 03:21:16.400
Wendy, he thought, I'm taking you with me, taking you home.

03:21:16.480 --> 03:21:19.120
But not as he had planned.

03:21:22.640 --> 03:21:27.280
To the other inertial seated around the massive genuine oak conference table,

03:21:27.280 --> 03:21:30.720
Al Hammond said, breaking abruptly into the joint silence,

03:21:31.520 --> 03:21:37.200
Joe should be back any time now. He looked at his wristwatch to make certain it appeared to have

03:21:37.200 --> 03:21:43.440
stopped. Meanwhile, Pat Connolly said, I suggest we watch the late afternoon news on TV.

03:21:44.160 --> 03:21:47.200
To see if Hollis has leaked out the news of Runceter's death.

03:21:48.000 --> 03:21:54.560
It wasn't in the paper today, Edie Dorn said. The TV news is much more recent, Pat said.

03:21:55.280 --> 03:22:00.400
She handed Al a fifty cent piece, with which to start up the TV set, mounted behind curtains

03:22:00.400 --> 03:22:05.440
at the far end of the conference room. An impressive 3D color polyphonic mechanism,

03:22:05.440 --> 03:22:07.680
which had been a source of pride to Runceter.

03:22:08.480 --> 03:22:11.680
Want me to put it in the slot for you, Mr. Hammond?

03:22:12.160 --> 03:22:13.760
Sammy Mundo asked eagerly.

03:22:14.480 --> 03:22:20.320
Okay, Al said. Broodingly he tossed the coin to Mundo, who caught it and trotted toward the set.

03:22:21.520 --> 03:22:27.840
Restlessly, Walter W. Wales, Runceter's attorney, shifted about in his chair, fiddled with his fine

03:22:27.840 --> 03:22:32.320
veined aristocratic hands at the clasp block of his briefcase, and said,

03:22:33.280 --> 03:22:38.800
You people should not have left, Mr. Chip and Zurich. We can do nothing until he arrives here,

03:22:38.880 --> 03:22:44.400
and it's extremely vital that all matters pertaining to Mr. Runceter's will be expedited.

03:22:45.360 --> 03:22:51.360
You've read the will, Al said, and so has Joe Chip. We know who Runceter wanted to take over

03:22:51.360 --> 03:22:59.520
management of the firm. But from a legal standpoint, Wales began, it won't take much longer, Al said,

03:22:59.520 --> 03:23:06.560
brusquely. With his pen he scratched random lines along the borders of the list he had made.

03:23:07.200 --> 03:23:10.720
Preoccupied, he embroidered the list, then read it once again.

03:23:11.840 --> 03:23:21.680
Stale cigarettes, out-of-date phone book, obsolete money, putrified food, add on match folder.

03:23:23.200 --> 03:23:29.120
I'm going to pass this list around the table once more, he settled out, and see if this time

03:23:29.120 --> 03:23:35.600
anyone can spot a connective link between these five occurrences. Look, whatever you want to call

03:23:35.680 --> 03:23:38.720
them, these five things that are—he gestured.

03:23:39.600 --> 03:23:46.800
I wrong, John Ilde said. Pat Connolly said, It's easy to see the connective between the first four,

03:23:46.800 --> 03:23:52.720
but not the match folder, that doesn't fit in. Let me see the match folder again, Al said,

03:23:52.720 --> 03:23:57.440
reaching out his hand. Pat gave him the match folder, and once again he read the ad.

03:23:58.560 --> 03:24:02.320
Amazing opportunity for advancement to all who can qualify.

03:24:03.200 --> 03:24:08.000
Mr. Glenn Runceter of the beloved brethren moratorium of Zurich, Switzerland, doubled his

03:24:08.000 --> 03:24:14.000
income within a week of receiving our free shoe kit, with detailed information as to how you also

03:24:14.000 --> 03:24:19.840
can sell our authentic simulated leather loafers to friends, relatives, business associates.

03:24:20.400 --> 03:24:24.720
Mr. Runceter, although helplessly frozen in Colpac, earned four hundred—

03:24:25.840 --> 03:24:31.360
Al stopped reading. He pondered, meanwhile picking at a lower tooth with his thumbnail.

03:24:32.080 --> 03:24:38.720
Yes, he thought this is different, this ad. The others consist of obsolescence and decay,

03:24:38.720 --> 03:24:45.600
but not this. I wonder, he settled out, What would happen if we answered this match folder ad?

03:24:46.240 --> 03:24:48.800
It gives a box number into Moines, Iowa.

03:24:49.520 --> 03:24:54.560
We'd get a free shoe kit, Pat Connolly said, with detailed information as to how we too can

03:24:54.560 --> 03:24:59.520
maybe—Al interrupted—we'd find ourselves in contact with Glenn Runceter.

03:25:00.480 --> 03:25:03.520
Everyone at the table, including Walter W. Well, stared at him.

03:25:04.320 --> 03:25:08.880
I mean it, he said. Here he handed the match folder to Tippi Jackson.

03:25:09.520 --> 03:25:10.480
Write him, Stan Mell.

03:25:11.200 --> 03:25:13.360
And say what? Tippi Jackson asked.

03:25:14.160 --> 03:25:16.720
Just fill out the coupon, Al said.

03:25:17.280 --> 03:25:18.720
To Edie Doran, he said,

03:25:18.720 --> 03:25:23.360
Are you absolutely sure you've had that match folder in your purse since late last week?

03:25:23.920 --> 03:25:25.920
Or could you have picked it up somewhere today?

03:25:26.880 --> 03:25:31.440
Edie Doran said, I put several match folders into my purse on Wednesday.

03:25:32.080 --> 03:25:36.960
As I told you, this morning on my way here, I happened to notice this one as I was lighting a

03:25:36.960 --> 03:25:42.800
cigarette. It definitely has been in my purse from before we went to Luna, from several days before.

03:25:43.840 --> 03:25:46.480
Put that ad on it? John Ilde asked her.

03:25:47.120 --> 03:25:50.880
I never noticed what the match folder said before. I only noticed this today.

03:25:51.920 --> 03:25:54.320
I can't say anything about it before. Who can?

03:25:55.280 --> 03:25:57.360
Nobody can, Don Denny said.

03:25:57.920 --> 03:26:02.720
What do you think, Al? A gag by Runciter? Did he have them printed up before his death?

03:26:03.440 --> 03:26:09.360
Or Hollis, maybe as a sort of grotesque joke, knowing that he was going to kill Runciter,

03:26:09.360 --> 03:26:13.920
that by the time we noticed the match folder, Runciter would be in cold pack and Zurich like

03:26:13.920 --> 03:26:20.480
the match folder says. Tito Apostos said, How would Hollis know we take Runciter to Zurich and not

03:26:20.480 --> 03:26:27.520
to New York? Because Elle is there, Don Denny answered. At the TV set, Sammy Mundo stood silently

03:26:27.520 --> 03:26:32.800
inspecting the fifty cent piece which Al had given him. His underdeveloped pale forehead had

03:26:32.800 --> 03:26:39.440
wrinkled up into a perplexed frown. What's the matter, Sam? Al said. He felt himself tense up

03:26:39.440 --> 03:26:41.360
inwardly. He foresaw another happening.

03:26:41.600 --> 03:26:48.320
Isn't Walt Denny's head supposed to be on the fifty cent piece, Sammy said?

03:26:49.200 --> 03:26:54.720
Either Disney's, Al said, or if it's an older one than Fidel Castro's, let's see it.

03:26:55.600 --> 03:27:00.960
Another obsolete coin, Pat Connolly said, as Sammy carried the fifty cent piece to Al.

03:27:02.320 --> 03:27:09.280
No, Al said, examining the coin. It's last year's perfectly good, date-wise, perfectly acceptable,

03:27:09.280 --> 03:27:12.880
any machine in the world would take it. The TV set would take it.

03:27:14.160 --> 03:27:17.920
Then what's the matter? Edie Dorn asked timidly.

03:27:18.880 --> 03:27:25.280
Exactly what Sam said, Al answered. It has the wrong head on it. He got up, carried the

03:27:25.280 --> 03:27:30.400
coin over to Edie, deposited it in her moist open hand. Who does it look like to you?

03:27:31.760 --> 03:27:35.600
After a pause, Edie said, I don't know.

03:27:36.240 --> 03:27:42.800
Sure you know, Al said. Okay, Edie said, sharply goaded into replying against her will. She pushed

03:27:42.800 --> 03:27:46.240
the coin back at him, ridding herself of it with a shiver of aversion.

03:27:47.360 --> 03:27:51.360
It's runciner, Al said to all of them seated around the big table.

03:27:52.960 --> 03:28:00.000
After a pause, Tippi Jackson said, add that to your list. Her voice was barely audible.

03:28:00.320 --> 03:28:06.640
I see two processes at work, Pat said presently, as Al receded himself and began to make the

03:28:06.640 --> 03:28:13.120
addendum on his piece of paper. One, a process of deterioration. That seems obvious, we agree on that.

03:28:14.000 --> 03:28:16.640
Raising his head, Al said to her, what's the other?

03:28:17.360 --> 03:28:23.600
I'm not quite sure, Pat hesitated. Something to do with Runciter. I think we should look at

03:28:23.600 --> 03:28:28.160
all our other coins and paper money too. Let me think a little longer.

03:28:28.160 --> 03:28:34.480
One by one, the people at the table got out their wallets, purses, rummaged in their pockets.

03:28:35.520 --> 03:28:39.600
I have a five-pause cred note, John Ilde said, with a beautiful,

03:28:39.600 --> 03:28:45.680
steel-engraving portrait of Mr. Runciter. The rest—he took a long look at what he held.

03:28:46.400 --> 03:28:51.280
They're normal, they're okay. Do you want to see the five-pause cred note, Mr. Hammond?

03:28:52.080 --> 03:28:57.840
Al said, I've got two of them already. Who else? He looked around the table. Six hands had gone up.

03:28:58.560 --> 03:29:03.600
Eight of us, he said, have what I guess we should call Runciter money, now, to some extent.

03:29:04.320 --> 03:29:09.200
Probably by the end of the day all the money will be Runciter money. Or give it two days.

03:29:10.240 --> 03:29:15.040
Anyhow, Runciter money will work. It'll start machines and appliances, and we can pay our debts

03:29:15.040 --> 03:29:22.640
with it. Maybe not, Don Denney said. Why do you think so? This is what you call Runciter money,

03:29:22.640 --> 03:29:26.720
he tapped a bill he held. Is there any reason why the bank should honor it?

03:29:26.720 --> 03:29:31.120
It's not legitimate issue. The government didn't put it out. It's funny money. It's not real.

03:29:32.240 --> 03:29:37.760
Okay, Al said reasonably. Maybe it's not real. Maybe the banks will refuse it. But that's not

03:29:37.760 --> 03:29:46.960
the real question. The real question, Pat Connolly said, is what does this second process consist of?

03:29:46.960 --> 03:29:53.920
These manifestations of Runciter. That's what they are, Don Denney nodded. Manifestations of Runciter.

03:29:53.920 --> 03:30:01.200
That's the second process, along with the decay. Some coins get obsolete. Others show up with Runciter's

03:30:01.200 --> 03:30:07.680
portrait or bust on them. You know what I think? I think these processes are going in opposite

03:30:07.680 --> 03:30:13.520
directions. One is a going away, so to speak, a going out of existence. That's process one.

03:30:14.160 --> 03:30:22.160
The second process is a coming into existence, but of something that's never existed before.

03:30:22.240 --> 03:30:26.240
Wish fulfillment, Eddydorn said faintly.

03:30:26.240 --> 03:30:35.600
Pardon, Al said. Maybe these are things Runciter wished for, Eddys said. To have his portrait on

03:30:35.600 --> 03:30:40.720
legal tender on all our money, including metal coins, it's grandiose.

03:30:42.800 --> 03:30:45.920
Tito Apostos said, but matchfolders.

03:30:46.800 --> 03:30:50.160
I guess not, Eddys agreed. That's not very grandiose.

03:30:51.120 --> 03:30:57.120
The firm already advertises on matchfolders, Don Denney said, and on TV and in the PAPES and MAGS

03:30:57.120 --> 03:31:02.800
and with Junk Mail. Our PR department handles all that. Generally, Runciter didn't give a

03:31:02.800 --> 03:31:06.880
damn about that end of the business, and he certainly didn't give a damn about matchfolders.

03:31:07.440 --> 03:31:14.160
If this were some sort of materialization of his psyche, he'd expect his face to appear on TV.

03:31:15.120 --> 03:31:17.280
Not on money or matchfolders.

03:31:18.560 --> 03:31:21.520
Maybe it is on TV, Al said.

03:31:21.520 --> 03:31:24.000
That's right, Pat Connolly said. We haven't tried it.

03:31:24.000 --> 03:31:25.840
None of us have had time to watch TV.

03:31:26.880 --> 03:31:31.360
Sammy, Al said, handing him back the fifty-cent piece. Go turn the TV set on.

03:31:32.240 --> 03:31:37.760
I don't know if I want to look, Eddys said, as Sammy Mundo dropped the coin into the slot and

03:31:37.760 --> 03:31:43.280
stood off to one side, jiggling the tuning knobs. The door of the room opened.

03:31:43.280 --> 03:31:46.400
Joe Chip stood there, and Al saw his face.

03:31:47.680 --> 03:31:52.240
Shut the TV set off, Al said, and got to his feet. Everyone in the room watched as he walked

03:31:52.240 --> 03:31:57.600
toward Joe. What happened, Joe? He said. He waited. Joe said nothing.

03:31:58.400 --> 03:31:59.040
What's the matter?

03:32:00.400 --> 03:32:04.000
I chartered a ship to bring me back here, Joe said huskily.

03:32:04.640 --> 03:32:09.840
You and Wendy? Joe said, Write out a check for the ship. It's on the roof. I don't have enough

03:32:09.840 --> 03:32:15.440
money for it. To Walter W. Wells, Al said, Are you able to disperse funds?

03:32:16.160 --> 03:32:19.520
For something like that, I can. I'll go settle with the ship.

03:32:20.080 --> 03:32:25.200
Taking his briefcase with him, Wells left the room. Joe remained in the doorway, again silent.

03:32:25.200 --> 03:32:28.480
He looked a hundred years older than when Al had last seen him.

03:32:29.680 --> 03:32:33.920
In my office. Joe turned away from the table. He blinked, hesitated.

03:32:34.880 --> 03:32:40.880
I don't think you should see. The man from the moratorium was with me when I found her.

03:32:40.880 --> 03:32:44.160
He said he couldn't do anything. It had been too long. Years.

03:32:45.680 --> 03:32:50.880
Years? Al said, chilled. Joe said, We'll go down to my office.

03:32:51.920 --> 03:32:55.040
He led Al out of the conference room into the hall to the elevator.

03:32:56.000 --> 03:33:00.640
On the trip back here, the ship fed me tranquilizers. That's part of the bill.

03:33:01.600 --> 03:33:07.760
Actually, I feel a lot better. In a sense, I don't feel anything. It must be the tranquilizers.

03:33:08.720 --> 03:33:14.480
I guess when they wear off, I'll feel it again. The elevator came. Together, they descended,

03:33:14.480 --> 03:33:18.640
neither of them saying anything until they reached the third floor where Joe had his office.

03:33:19.760 --> 03:33:24.560
I don't advise you to look. Joe unlocked his office, led Al inside.

03:33:25.280 --> 03:33:28.320
It's up to you. If I got over it, you probably will.

03:33:29.120 --> 03:33:30.720
He switched on the overhead lighting.

03:33:32.400 --> 03:33:41.440
After pause, Al said, Lord God, don't open it, Joe said. I'm not going to open it.

03:33:42.400 --> 03:33:47.920
This morning or last night, evidently, it happened early before she even reached my room.

03:33:49.040 --> 03:33:55.440
We, that moratorium owner and I, found bits of cloth in the corridor leading to my door,

03:33:55.440 --> 03:33:58.640
but she must have been all right, or nearly all right, when she crossed the lobby.

03:33:59.200 --> 03:34:04.400
Anyhow, nobody noticed anything. And in a big hotel like that, they keep somebody watching.

03:34:05.040 --> 03:34:10.960
And the fact that she managed to reach my room—yeah, that indicates she must have been at least able

03:34:10.960 --> 03:34:16.960
to walk, that seems probable, anyhow—Joe said, I'm thinking about the rest of us.

03:34:17.680 --> 03:34:23.440
In what way? The same thing happening to us. How could it? How could it happen to her?

03:34:24.000 --> 03:34:30.080
Because of the blast. We're going to die like that, one after another, one by one,

03:34:30.080 --> 03:34:35.760
until none of us are left, until each of us is ten pounds of skin and hair in a plastic bag,

03:34:35.760 --> 03:34:43.120
with a few dried-up bones thrown in. All right, Al said, there's some force at work,

03:34:43.120 --> 03:34:50.480
producing rapid decay. It's been at work since—or started with—the blast there on Luna. We already

03:34:50.480 --> 03:34:57.120
knew that. We also know, or think we know, that another force, a contra-force, is at work,

03:34:57.680 --> 03:35:04.560
moving things in an opposite direction. Something connected with Ronsova. A money's beginning

03:35:04.560 --> 03:35:10.960
to have his picture on it. A match-folder—he was on my VIT phone, Joe said, at the hotel.

03:35:11.760 --> 03:35:17.600
On it? How? I don't know. He just was. Not on the screen, not the video part, only his voice.

03:35:18.560 --> 03:35:22.640
What'd he say? Nothing in particular. Al studied him.

03:35:23.760 --> 03:35:30.160
Could he hear you? He asked, finally. No. I tried to get through. It was one way entirely. I was

03:35:30.160 --> 03:35:36.640
listening in, and that was all. So that's why I couldn't get through to you. That's why, Joe nodded.

03:35:37.520 --> 03:35:41.920
We were trying the TV when you showed up. You realize there's nothing in the

03:35:41.920 --> 03:35:49.840
papes about his death. Or a mess. He did not like the way Joe Chipp looked, old, small,

03:35:49.840 --> 03:35:52.880
and tired, he reflected. If this is how it begins?

03:35:53.760 --> 03:35:58.560
We've got to establish contact with Ronsova, he said to himself. Being able to hear him

03:35:58.560 --> 03:36:04.240
isn't enough. Evidently, he's trying to reach us. But if we're going to live through this,

03:36:04.800 --> 03:36:11.520
we'll have to reach him. Joe said, picking him up on TV isn't going to do us any good.

03:36:12.000 --> 03:36:16.080
It'll just be like the phone all over again, unless he can tell us how to communicate back.

03:36:16.960 --> 03:36:20.480
Maybe he can tell us. Maybe he knows. Maybe he understands what's happened.

03:36:21.920 --> 03:36:25.280
He would have to understand what's happened to himself, which is something we don't know.

03:36:26.240 --> 03:36:31.360
In some sense, Al thought he must be alive, even though the moratorium failed to rouse him.

03:36:31.360 --> 03:36:35.200
Obviously, the moratorium owner did his best with a client of this much importance.

03:36:36.160 --> 03:36:40.160
Did Von Vogelang hear him on the phone? He asked Joe.

03:36:40.960 --> 03:36:47.280
He tried to hear him, but all he got was silence and static, apparently, from a long way off.

03:36:47.280 --> 03:36:55.120
I heard it too. Nothing. The sound of absolute nothing. A very strange sound.

03:36:56.160 --> 03:36:59.840
I don't like that, Al said. He was not sure why.

03:37:00.800 --> 03:37:06.160
I'd feel better about it if Von Vogelang had heard it too. At least that way we could be sure it was

03:37:06.160 --> 03:37:11.840
there that it wasn't an hallucination on your part. Or for that matter he thought on all our parts,

03:37:11.840 --> 03:37:17.680
as in the case of the match-folder. But some of the happenings had definitely not been hallucinations.

03:37:18.240 --> 03:37:25.600
Machines had rejected antiquated coins. Objective machines geared to react only to physical properties.

03:37:26.480 --> 03:37:30.400
No psychological elements came into play there. Machines could not imagine.

03:37:32.000 --> 03:37:38.320
I'm leaving this building for a while, Al said. Think of a city or town at random,

03:37:38.320 --> 03:37:43.360
one that none of us have anything to do with, one where none of us ever go or have ever gone.

03:37:44.640 --> 03:37:50.000
Baltimore, Joe said. Okay. I'm going to Baltimore. I'm going to see if a store picked at random

03:37:50.080 --> 03:37:55.840
will accept runs at a currency. Buy me some new cigarettes, Joe said. Okay. I'll do that too.

03:37:55.840 --> 03:37:59.680
I'll see if cigarettes in a random store in Baltimore have been affected. I'll check other

03:37:59.680 --> 03:38:04.480
products as well. I'll make random samplings. Do you want to come with me or do you want to go

03:38:04.480 --> 03:38:11.760
upstairs and tell them about Wendy? Joe said, I'll go with you. Maybe we should never tell them about

03:38:11.760 --> 03:38:17.600
her. I think we should, Joe said, since it's going to happen again. It may happen before we get back.

03:38:17.600 --> 03:38:23.360
It may be happening now. Then we better get our trip to Baltimore over as quickly as possible.

03:38:23.360 --> 03:38:27.200
Al said. He started out of the office. Joe Chip, follow.

03:38:30.400 --> 03:38:38.640
9. My hair is so dry, so unmanageable. What's a girl to do? Simply rub in creamy

03:38:38.640 --> 03:38:44.560
ubeck hair conditioner. In just five days you'll discover new body in your hair, new glossiness,

03:38:44.640 --> 03:38:49.600
and ubeck hairspray used as directed is absolutely safe.

03:38:51.520 --> 03:38:56.960
They selected the Lucky People supermarket on the periphery of Baltimore. At the counter, Al said to

03:38:56.960 --> 03:39:04.000
the autonomic computerized checker, give me a pack of Paul Mauls. Wings are cheaper, Joe said.

03:39:04.640 --> 03:39:07.840
Irritated Al said. They don't make wings anymore. They haven't for years.

03:39:08.640 --> 03:39:13.360
They make them, Joe said, but they don't advertise. It's an honest cigarette that claims nothing.

03:39:13.440 --> 03:39:16.960
To the checker, he said, change that from Paul Mauls to wings.

03:39:18.160 --> 03:39:20.800
The pack of cigarettes slid from the chute and on to the counter.

03:39:21.600 --> 03:39:27.680
95 cents, the checker said. Here's a 10-postgrad bill. Al fed the bill to the checker,

03:39:27.680 --> 03:39:30.640
whose circuits at once whirred as it scrutinized the bill.

03:39:31.440 --> 03:39:37.520
Your change, sir, the checker said. It deposited a neat heap of coins and bills before Al.

03:39:38.160 --> 03:39:39.280
Please move along now.

03:39:40.480 --> 03:39:46.240
So, Runsitter Money is acceptable, Al said to himself, as he and Joe got out of the way of

03:39:46.240 --> 03:39:52.320
the next customer, a heavy-set old lady wearing a blueberry-colored cloth coat and carrying a Mexican

03:39:52.320 --> 03:40:00.080
rope shopping bag. Cautiously, he opened the pack of cigarettes. The cigarettes crumbled between

03:40:00.080 --> 03:40:07.120
his fingers. It would have proved something, Al said, if this had been a pack of Paul Mauls.

03:40:07.200 --> 03:40:12.160
I'm getting back in line. He started to do so and then discovered that the heavy-set old lady

03:40:12.160 --> 03:40:15.600
in the dark coat was arguing violently with the automatic checker.

03:40:16.400 --> 03:40:22.480
It was dead! she asserted shrilly. By the time I got it home, here, you can have it back!

03:40:22.480 --> 03:40:28.080
She set a pot on the counter. It contained, Al saw, a lifeless plant, perhaps an azalea,

03:40:28.080 --> 03:40:30.880
in its moribund state it showed a few features.

03:40:31.600 --> 03:40:36.320
I can't give you a refund, the checker answered. No warranty goes with the plant life,

03:40:36.400 --> 03:40:40.240
which we sell. Buyer beware, is our rule. Please move along now.

03:40:40.960 --> 03:40:45.440
And the Saturday evening post, the old lady said, that I picked up from your newsstand.

03:40:45.440 --> 03:40:50.560
It was over a year old. What's the matter with you? And the Martian Grubworm TV dinner!

03:40:51.120 --> 03:40:54.000
Next customer, the checker said, it ignored her.

03:40:55.120 --> 03:40:59.840
Al got out of line. He roamed about the premises until he came to the cartons of cigarettes.

03:40:59.840 --> 03:41:04.080
Every conceivable brand stacked to heights of eight feet or more.

03:41:04.880 --> 03:41:06.640
Pick a carton, he said to Joe.

03:41:07.360 --> 03:41:10.080
Dominoes, Joe said, did the same price as wings?

03:41:10.080 --> 03:41:14.560
Christ, don't pick an off brand! Pick something like Winston's or Kool's!

03:41:15.200 --> 03:41:16.800
He himself yanked out a carton.

03:41:17.520 --> 03:41:20.240
It's empty. He shook it. I can tell by the weight.

03:41:21.040 --> 03:41:26.240
Something, however, inside the carton bounced about. Something weightless and small.

03:41:26.880 --> 03:41:28.720
He tore the carton open and looked within it.

03:41:28.800 --> 03:41:31.280
A scrawled note.

03:41:32.320 --> 03:41:34.800
In handwriting familiar to him and to Joe.

03:41:35.520 --> 03:41:37.760
He lifted it out and together they both read it.

03:41:38.960 --> 03:41:46.080
Essential, I get in touch with you. Situation, serious, and certainly will get more so as time goes on.

03:41:46.720 --> 03:41:52.960
There are several possible explanations which I'll discuss with you. Anyhow, don't give up.

03:41:53.520 --> 03:41:58.480
I'm sorry about Wendy Wright. In that connection, we did all we could.

03:41:59.680 --> 03:42:06.320
Al said, so he knows about Wendy. Well, maybe that means it won't happen again to the rest of us.

03:42:07.440 --> 03:42:12.160
A random carton of cigarettes, Joe said, at a random store in a city picked at random,

03:42:12.160 --> 03:42:16.080
and we find a note directed at us from Glenn Runciter.

03:42:17.120 --> 03:42:19.520
What do the other cartons have in them? The same note?

03:42:20.320 --> 03:42:24.080
He lifted down a carton of L&M's, shook it, then opened it.

03:42:24.080 --> 03:42:27.760
Ten packs of cigarettes plus ten more below them. Absolutely normal.

03:42:28.800 --> 03:42:33.440
Or is it, Al asked himself. He lifted out one of the packs.

03:42:34.240 --> 03:42:37.760
You can see they're okay, Joe said. He pulled out a carton from the middle of the stacks.

03:42:37.760 --> 03:42:41.520
This one is full, too. He did not open it. Instead, he reached for another,

03:42:41.520 --> 03:42:44.000
and then another. All had packs of cigarettes in them,

03:42:44.960 --> 03:42:48.320
and all crumbled into fragments between Al's fingers.

03:42:49.120 --> 03:42:52.320
I wonder how he knew we'd come here, Al said.

03:42:52.960 --> 03:42:57.840
And how he knew we'd try that one particular carton. It made no sense.

03:42:58.720 --> 03:43:01.920
And yet here, too, the pair of opposing forces were at work.

03:43:01.920 --> 03:43:05.360
Decay versus Runciter, Al said to himself.

03:43:06.240 --> 03:43:09.440
Throughout the world, perhaps throughout the universe.

03:43:10.080 --> 03:43:15.840
Maybe the sun will go out, Al conjectured, and Glenn Runciter will place a substitute sun in

03:43:15.840 --> 03:43:22.000
its place, if he can. Yes, he thought that's the question. How much can Runciter do?

03:43:23.360 --> 03:43:26.720
Put another way, how far can the process of Decay go?

03:43:26.800 --> 03:43:32.320
Let's try something else, Al said. He walked along the aisle, passed cans, packages, and boxes,

03:43:32.320 --> 03:43:36.400
coming at last to the appliance center of the store. There, on impulse, he picked up an

03:43:36.400 --> 03:43:42.640
expensive German-made tape recorder. This looks all right, he said to Joe, who had followed him.

03:43:42.640 --> 03:43:48.000
He picked up a second one still in its container. Let's buy this, and take you back to New York

03:43:48.000 --> 03:43:52.240
with us. Don't you want to open it, Joe said, and try it out before you buy it?

03:43:52.880 --> 03:43:59.360
I think I already know what we'll find, Al said, and it's something we can't test out here.

03:43:59.920 --> 03:44:02.000
He carried the tape recorder toward the check stand.

03:44:03.280 --> 03:44:07.760
Back in New York at Runciter Associates, they turned the tape recorder over to the firm's shop.

03:44:08.640 --> 03:44:13.280
Fifteen minutes later, the shop foreman, having taken apart the mechanism, made his report.

03:44:14.320 --> 03:44:21.680
All the moving parts in the tape transport stage are worn. The rubber drive tire has flat spots on it.

03:44:22.480 --> 03:44:28.080
Pieces of rubber are all over the insides. The brakes for high-speed wind and rewind are virtually

03:44:28.080 --> 03:44:35.680
gone. It needs cleaning and lubricating throughout its scene. Plenty of use. In fact, I would say

03:44:35.680 --> 03:44:42.800
it needs a complete overhaul, including new belts. Al said, several years of use, possibly,

03:44:42.800 --> 03:44:49.920
how long you had it? I bought it today, Al said. That is impossible, the shop foreman said. Or if

03:44:50.000 --> 03:44:56.400
you did, they sold you. I know what they sold me, Al said. I knew when I got it before I opened the

03:44:56.400 --> 03:45:02.640
carton. To Joe, he said, a brand new tape recorder completely worn out, bought with funny money

03:45:02.640 --> 03:45:08.240
that the store is willing to accept. Worthless money, worthless article purchased. It has

03:45:09.360 --> 03:45:15.280
a sort of logic to it. This is not my day, the shop foreman said. This morning, when I got up,

03:45:15.280 --> 03:45:20.880
my parrot was dead. Dead of what, Joe asked? I don't know, just dead, stiff as a board.

03:45:21.680 --> 03:45:26.240
The shop foreman waggled a bony finger at Al. I'll tell you something you don't know about your

03:45:26.240 --> 03:45:32.400
tape recorder. It isn't just worn out. It's 40 years obsolete. They don't use rubber drive tires

03:45:32.400 --> 03:45:38.240
anymore, or belt-run transports. You'll never get parts for it unless somebody hand makes them.

03:45:38.800 --> 03:45:42.640
And it wouldn't be worth it. The damn thing is antiquated. Junk it. Forget about it.

03:45:43.600 --> 03:45:50.800
You're right, Al said. I didn't know. He accompanied Joe out of the shop and into the corridor.

03:45:51.760 --> 03:45:56.240
Now we're talking about something other than the K. This is a different matter.

03:45:57.360 --> 03:46:01.840
And we are going to have trouble finding edible food anywhere of any kind.

03:46:02.800 --> 03:46:06.720
How much of the food sold in supermarkets will be good after that many years?

03:46:06.880 --> 03:46:12.480
The canned goods, Joe said. And I saw a lot of canned goods at that supermarket in Baltimore.

03:46:13.040 --> 03:46:19.280
And now we know why, Al said. 40 years ago, supermarkets sold a far greater proportion

03:46:19.280 --> 03:46:24.880
of their commodities in cans rather than frozen. That may turn out to be our sole source. You're

03:46:24.880 --> 03:46:31.920
right. He cogitated. But in one day it's jumped from two years to 40 years. By this time tomorrow,

03:46:32.000 --> 03:46:38.080
maybe a hundred years. And no food is edible a hundred years after it's packaged cans or otherwise.

03:46:38.960 --> 03:46:42.880
Chinese eggs, Joe said. Thousand-year-old eggs that they bury in the ground.

03:46:43.840 --> 03:46:48.640
And it's not just us, Al said. That old woman in Baltimore, it's affecting what she bought to

03:46:48.640 --> 03:46:54.400
her zalia. Is the whole world going to starve because of a bomb blast on Luna? He asked himself.

03:46:54.400 --> 03:46:57.600
Why is everyone involved instead of just us?

03:46:58.240 --> 03:47:04.000
Joe said, here comes Be Quiet a second, Al said. I have to think something out.

03:47:05.120 --> 03:47:12.720
Maybe Baltimore is only there when one of us goes there. And the lucky people supermarket,

03:47:12.720 --> 03:47:20.160
as soon as we left, it passed out of existence. It could still be that only we who own Luna are

03:47:20.160 --> 03:47:26.320
really experiencing this. A philosophical problem of no importance or meaning, Joe said,

03:47:26.320 --> 03:47:33.200
and incapable of being proved one way or the other. Al said costically, it would be important

03:47:33.200 --> 03:47:40.240
that that old lady in the blueberry cloth coat and all the rest of them. Here's the shop foreman,

03:47:40.240 --> 03:47:45.440
Joe said. I'd just been looking at the instruction manual, the shop foreman said.

03:47:45.440 --> 03:47:50.160
They came with your tape recorder. He held the booklet out to Al, a complicated expression on

03:47:50.160 --> 03:47:56.160
his face. Take a look. All at once he grabbed it back. I'll have to save you the trouble of reading.

03:47:56.160 --> 03:48:00.320
Look here on the last page where it tells who made the damn thing and where to send it for factory

03:48:00.320 --> 03:48:09.360
repairs. Made by Runciter of Zurich. Al read aloud. And a maintenance station in the North American

03:48:09.360 --> 03:48:16.480
Confederation in Des Moines. The same as on the match folder. He passed the booklet to Joe and said,

03:48:17.200 --> 03:48:22.160
we're going to Des Moines. This booklet is the first manifestation that links the two locations.

03:48:22.160 --> 03:48:27.440
I wonder why Des Moines, he said to himself. Can you recall, he said to Joe,

03:48:27.440 --> 03:48:34.400
any connection that Runciter ever had during his lifetime with Des Moines? Joe said Runciter was

03:48:34.400 --> 03:48:39.360
born there. He spent his first 15 years there. Every once in a while he used to mention it.

03:48:40.160 --> 03:48:46.400
So now, after his death, he's gone back there in some manner or other.

03:48:46.480 --> 03:48:51.920
Runciter is in Zurich, he thought, and also in Des Moines. In Zurich he has measurable brain

03:48:51.920 --> 03:48:56.960
metabolism. His physical half-life body is suspended in Colpac in the beloved brethren

03:48:56.960 --> 03:49:04.240
moratorium. And yet he can't be reached. In Des Moines he has no physical existence. And yet,

03:49:04.240 --> 03:49:11.040
evidently, there, contact can be established. In fact, by such extensions as this instruction

03:49:11.120 --> 03:49:17.600
booklet has been established, at least in one direction from him to us. And meanwhile,

03:49:17.600 --> 03:49:25.760
he thought, our world declines, turns back onto itself, bringing to the surface past phases

03:49:25.760 --> 03:49:31.360
of reality. By the end of the week we may wake up and find ancient clanging streetcars moving

03:49:31.360 --> 03:49:38.240
down Fifth Avenue. Trolley Dodgers, he thought, and wondered what that meant. An abandoned verbal

03:49:38.320 --> 03:49:44.720
term rising from the past. A hazy, distant emanation in his mind, canceling out current reality.

03:49:46.160 --> 03:49:51.200
Even this indistinct perception, still only subjective, made him uneasy. It had already

03:49:51.200 --> 03:49:56.160
become too real. An entity which he had never known about before this moment.

03:49:56.960 --> 03:50:03.040
Trolley Dodgers, he said, allowed. A hundred years ago, at least, obsessively, the term

03:50:03.120 --> 03:50:07.120
remained lodged within awareness. He could not forget it.

03:50:07.120 --> 03:50:13.600
How come you know that? the shop foreman asked. Nobody knows that anymore. That's the old name

03:50:13.600 --> 03:50:17.360
for the Brooklyn Dodgers. He eyed Al's suspiciously.

03:50:19.280 --> 03:50:23.520
Joe said, we better go upstairs and make sure they're all right before we take off for Des Moines.

03:50:24.240 --> 03:50:29.680
If we don't get to Des Moines soon, Al said, it may turn out to be an all-day trip or even a

03:50:29.680 --> 03:50:36.080
two-day trip. As methods of transportation devolve, he thought, from rocket propulsion to jet,

03:50:36.080 --> 03:50:41.520
from jet to piston-driven aircraft, then surface travel as the cold-fed steam train,

03:50:41.520 --> 03:50:47.760
horse-grown cart. But it couldn't regress that far, he said to himself. And yet we've already

03:50:47.760 --> 03:50:53.280
got on our hands a forty-year-old tape recorder run by rubber drive-tire and belts. Maybe it could

03:50:53.280 --> 03:50:58.640
really be. He and Joe walked rapidly to the elevator. Joe pressed the button and they waited,

03:50:58.640 --> 03:51:03.120
both of them, on edge, saying nothing, both withdrew into their own thoughts.

03:51:04.000 --> 03:51:09.200
The elevator arrived clatteringly. The racket awoke Al from his introspection. Reflexively,

03:51:09.200 --> 03:51:16.320
he pushed aside the iron grill safety door and found himself facing an open cage with polished

03:51:16.320 --> 03:51:22.800
brass fittings suspended from a cable. A dull-eyed, uniformed operator sat on a stool working the

03:51:22.800 --> 03:51:29.280
handle. He gazed at them with indifference. It was not indifference, however, that Al felt.

03:51:30.080 --> 03:51:35.120
Don't get in, he said to Joe, holding him back. Look at it and think. Try to remember the elevator

03:51:35.120 --> 03:51:40.240
we rode in earlier today. The hydraulic-powered, closed, self-operated, absolutely silent.

03:51:41.280 --> 03:51:48.080
He ceased talking because the elderly clanking contraption had dimmed. And in its place the

03:51:48.080 --> 03:51:53.760
familiar elevator resumed its existence. And yet he sensed the presence of the other, older

03:51:53.760 --> 03:52:00.000
elevator. It lurked at the periphery of his vision. As if ready to ebb forward as soon as he and Joe

03:52:00.000 --> 03:52:07.680
turned their attention away, it wants to come back. He realized. It intends to come back. We can

03:52:07.680 --> 03:52:14.000
delay it temporarily a few hours, probably at the most. The momentum of the retrograde force

03:52:14.320 --> 03:52:20.000
is increasing. Archaic forms are moving toward domination more rapidly than we thought. It's

03:52:20.000 --> 03:52:25.280
now a question of a hundred years at one swing. The elevator we just now saw must have been a century

03:52:25.280 --> 03:52:33.040
old. And yet he thought we seemed able to exert some control over it. We did force the actual

03:52:33.040 --> 03:52:39.920
contemporary elevator back into being. If all of us stay together, if we function as an entity of

03:52:39.920 --> 03:52:47.360
not two but twelve minds, what did you see, Joe was saying to him, that made you tell me not to

03:52:47.360 --> 03:52:55.360
get in the elevator? Al said, didn't you see the old elevator, open-caged brass from around 1910,

03:52:56.000 --> 03:53:04.160
with the operator sitting on his stool? No, Joe said. Did you see anything? This, Joe gestured,

03:53:04.160 --> 03:53:08.960
the normal elevator I see every day when I come to work. I saw what I always see, what I see now.

03:53:10.000 --> 03:53:12.720
He entered the elevator, turned and stood facing Al.

03:53:14.480 --> 03:53:22.720
Then our perceptions are beginning to differ, Al realized. He wondered what that meant.

03:53:24.160 --> 03:53:31.840
It seemed ominous. He did not like it at all. In its dire obscure way, it seemed to him potentially

03:53:31.840 --> 03:53:38.800
the most deadly change since Runciter's death. They were no longer regressing at the same rate,

03:53:38.880 --> 03:53:45.440
and he had an acute, intuitive intimation that Wendy Wright had experienced exactly this before

03:53:45.440 --> 03:53:53.600
her death. He wondered how much time he himself had left. Now he became aware of an insidious

03:53:53.600 --> 03:53:59.440
seeping cooling off, which at some earlier and unremembered time had begun to explore him,

03:53:59.440 --> 03:54:06.400
investigating him as well as the world around him. It reminded him of their final minutes on Luna.

03:54:07.360 --> 03:54:13.520
The chill debased the surfaces of objects. It warped, expanded,

03:54:13.520 --> 03:54:17.840
showed itself as bulb-like swellings that sighed audibly and popped.

03:54:18.640 --> 03:54:23.840
Into the manifold open wounds, the cold drifted all the way down into the heart of things,

03:54:23.840 --> 03:54:30.720
the core which made them live. What he saw now seemed to be a desert of ice from which stark

03:54:30.800 --> 03:54:37.120
boulders jutted. A wind spewed across the plain which reality had become. The wind congealed

03:54:37.120 --> 03:54:42.960
into deeper ice, and the boulders disappeared for the most part, and darkness presented itself off

03:54:42.960 --> 03:54:48.320
at the edges of his vision. He caught only a meager glimpse of it. But he thought this is

03:54:48.320 --> 03:54:54.960
projection on my part. It isn't the universe which is being entombed by layers of wind, cold,

03:54:54.960 --> 03:55:02.480
darkness, and ice. All this is going on within me. And yet I seem to see it outside,

03:55:02.480 --> 03:55:09.040
straining, she thought. Is the whole world inside me engulfed by my body? When did that happen?

03:55:10.240 --> 03:55:15.680
It must be a manifestation of dying, he said to himself. The uncertainty which I feel, the slowing

03:55:15.680 --> 03:55:23.680
down into entropy, that's the process. And the ice which I see is the result of the success of

03:55:23.680 --> 03:55:30.000
the process. When I blink out, he thought the whole universe will disappear. But what about the

03:55:30.000 --> 03:55:37.040
various lights which I should see, the entrances to new wombs? Where, in particular, is the red smoky

03:55:37.040 --> 03:55:43.280
light of fornicating couples, and the dull dark light signifying animal greed, all I can make out,

03:55:43.280 --> 03:55:49.040
he thought, is encroaching darkness, and utter loss of heat, a plain which is cooling off,

03:55:49.120 --> 03:55:55.200
abandoned by its sun. This can't be normal death, he said to himself. This is unnatural.

03:55:55.200 --> 03:55:59.760
The regular momentum of dissolution has been replaced by another factor imposed upon it,

03:55:59.760 --> 03:56:06.720
a pressure arbitrary and forced. Maybe I can understand it, he thought.

03:56:07.920 --> 03:56:13.360
If I can just lie down and rest. If I can get enough energy to think.

03:56:13.760 --> 03:56:18.560
What's the matter, Joe asked, as together they ascended in the elevator.

03:56:19.600 --> 03:56:25.440
Nothing, Al said curtly. They may make it, he thought. But I'm not going to.

03:56:26.800 --> 03:56:29.920
He and Joe continued on up in empty silence.

03:56:32.000 --> 03:56:35.360
As he entered the conference room, Joe realized that Al was no longer with him,

03:56:35.360 --> 03:56:39.760
turning, he looked back down the corridor, he made out Al standing alone, not coming any farther.

03:56:40.320 --> 03:56:43.920
What's the matter, he asked again. Al did not move.

03:56:43.920 --> 03:56:46.560
Are you all right, Joe asked, walking back toward him.

03:56:47.520 --> 03:56:50.240
I feel tired, Al said.

03:56:51.360 --> 03:56:58.400
You don't look good, Joe said, feeling deeply uneasy. Al said, I'm going to the man's room.

03:56:59.200 --> 03:57:04.640
You go ahead and join the others, make sure they're okay. I'll be along pretty soon.

03:57:05.600 --> 03:57:08.800
He started vaguely away. He seemed now confused.

03:57:09.600 --> 03:57:15.680
I'll be okay, he said. He moved along the corridor haltingly, as if having difficulty

03:57:15.680 --> 03:57:19.760
seeing his way. I'll go with you, Joe said, to make sure you get there.

03:57:20.800 --> 03:57:27.920
Maybe if I splash some warm water on my face, Al said. He found the toll-free door to the men's

03:57:27.920 --> 03:57:33.840
room, and with Joe's help opened it and disappeared inside. Joe remained in the corridor.

03:57:34.400 --> 03:57:38.880
Some things that matter with him, he said to himself. Seeing the old elevator made a change

03:57:38.880 --> 03:57:42.560
in him. He wondered why. Al reappeared.

03:57:43.680 --> 03:57:46.240
What is it, Joe said, seeing the expression on his face?

03:57:47.280 --> 03:57:53.520
Take a look at this, Al said. He led Joe into the men's room and pointed at the far wall.

03:57:54.400 --> 03:58:00.720
Graffiti, he said. You know, words scrawled like you find all the time in a men's room.

03:58:01.440 --> 03:58:06.640
Read it. In crayon or purple ballpoint pen ink, the words read,

03:58:07.440 --> 03:58:14.400
Jump in the urinal and stand on your head. I'm the one that's alive. You're all dead.

03:58:15.920 --> 03:58:20.240
Is it Runciter's writing? Al asked. Do you recognize it?

03:58:21.040 --> 03:58:24.560
Yes, Joe said nodding. It's Runciter's writing.

03:58:25.680 --> 03:58:33.120
So now we know the truth, Al said. Is it the truth? Al said, sure. Obviously.

03:58:34.400 --> 03:58:37.760
What a hell of a way to learn it. From the wall of a men's room.

03:58:38.880 --> 03:58:41.360
He felt bitter resentment rather than anything else.

03:58:43.440 --> 03:58:49.760
That's how graffiti is, harsh and direct. We might have watched the TV and listened to the

03:58:49.760 --> 03:58:57.360
vid phone and read the papes for months forever, maybe without finding out, without being told

03:58:57.360 --> 03:59:01.920
straight to the point like this. So I said, but we're not dead except for Wendy.

03:59:02.800 --> 03:59:09.280
We're in half life. Probably still on platform two. We're probably on our way back to earth from

03:59:09.280 --> 03:59:16.960
Luna after the explosion that killed us. Killed us, not Runciter. And he's trying to pick up the

03:59:17.040 --> 03:59:23.760
flow of proto-phazons from us. So far he's failed. We're not getting across from our world to his,

03:59:23.760 --> 03:59:30.000
but he's managed to reach us. We're picking him up everywhere, even places we choose at random.

03:59:30.640 --> 03:59:37.680
His presence is invading us on every side, him and only him, because he's the sole person trying to

03:59:37.680 --> 03:59:42.400
he and only he, Joe interrupted. Instead of him, you said him.

03:59:43.200 --> 03:59:49.280
I'm sick, Al said. He started water running in the base and began splashing it onto his face.

03:59:49.280 --> 03:59:54.800
It was not hot water, however, Joe saw. In the water, fragments of ice crackled and splintered.

03:59:55.600 --> 04:00:02.320
You go back to the conference room. I'll be along when I feel better, assuming I ever do feel better.

04:00:03.120 --> 04:00:05.360
I think I ought to stay here with you, Joe said.

04:00:05.360 --> 04:00:07.760
No, god damn it. Get out of here.

04:00:08.400 --> 04:00:13.280
His face gray and filled with panic. Al shoved him toward the door of the men's room.

04:00:13.280 --> 04:00:17.920
He propelled Joe out into the corridor. Go on, make sure they're all right.

04:00:18.640 --> 04:00:22.240
Al retreated back into the men's room, clutching at his own eyes.

04:00:22.240 --> 04:00:27.120
Bent over, he disappeared from view as the door swung shut. Joe hesitated.

04:00:28.560 --> 04:00:32.000
Okay, he said. I'll be in the conference room with them.

04:00:33.040 --> 04:00:34.640
He waited, listening, hurt nothing.

04:00:35.600 --> 04:00:39.440
Al? He said. Christ, he thought this is terrible.

04:00:39.440 --> 04:00:41.200
Something is really the matter with him.

04:00:42.560 --> 04:00:46.320
I want to see with my own eyes, he said, pushing against the door, that you're all right.

04:00:47.440 --> 04:00:54.800
In a low, calm voice, Al said, is too late, Joe. Don't look.

04:00:55.360 --> 04:00:59.360
The men's room had become dark. Al evidently had managed to turn the light off.

04:00:59.360 --> 04:01:05.680
You can't do anything to help me. He said in a weak but steady voice,

04:01:06.640 --> 04:01:12.240
we shouldn't have separated from the others. That's why it happened to Wendy.

04:01:13.200 --> 04:01:20.240
You can stay alive at least for a while if you go find them and stick with them.

04:01:21.120 --> 04:01:27.040
Tell them that. Make sure all of them understand. Do you understand?

04:01:27.760 --> 04:01:33.680
Joe reached for the light switch. A blow, feeble, and weightless cuffed his hand in the darkness,

04:01:33.680 --> 04:01:37.520
terrified he withdrew his hand, shocked by the impotence of Al's punch.

04:01:38.080 --> 04:01:42.160
It told him everything. He no longer needed to see.

04:01:44.160 --> 04:01:50.480
I'll go join the others, he said. Yes, I understand. Does it feel very bad?

04:01:51.680 --> 04:01:54.800
Silence. And then a listless voice whispered.

04:01:55.760 --> 04:02:00.400
No. It doesn't feel very bad. I just—

04:02:01.680 --> 04:02:04.960
The voice faded out. Once more, only silence.

04:02:06.960 --> 04:02:12.480
Maybe I'll see you again some time, Joe said. He knew it was the wrong thing to say.

04:02:12.480 --> 04:02:16.720
It horrified him to hear himself prattle out such an inanity, but it was the best he could do.

04:02:18.000 --> 04:02:22.800
Let me put it another way, he said, but he knew Al could no longer hear him.

04:02:22.880 --> 04:02:27.520
I hope you feel better, he said. I'll check back after I tell him about the writing on the wall

04:02:27.520 --> 04:02:31.920
in there. I'll tell him not to come in here and look at it, because it might—

04:02:32.560 --> 04:02:38.720
He tried to think it out, say it right. They might bother you, he finished.

04:02:39.920 --> 04:02:40.800
No response.

04:02:42.320 --> 04:02:48.160
Well, so long, Joe said, and left the darkness of the men's room.

04:02:48.320 --> 04:02:51.600
He walked unsteadily down the corridor back to the conference room,

04:02:51.600 --> 04:02:58.000
halting a moment he took a deep, irregular breath, and then pushed open the conference room door.

04:02:59.360 --> 04:03:03.760
The TV set mounted in the far wall blared out a detergent commercial.

04:03:04.320 --> 04:03:09.200
On the great color 3D screen, a housewife critically examined a synthetic otter-pelt

04:03:09.200 --> 04:03:14.560
towel, and in a penetrating, shrill voice declared it unfit to occupy a place.

04:03:14.560 --> 04:03:20.560
The screen then displayed her bathroom, and picked up graffiti on her bathroom wall, too,

04:03:20.560 --> 04:03:23.120
the same familiar scroll, and this time reading,

04:03:23.120 --> 04:03:30.480
Lean over the bowl and then take a dive. All of you are dead. I am alive.

04:03:31.920 --> 04:03:35.520
Only one person in the big conference room watched, however.

04:03:36.080 --> 04:03:42.080
Joe stood alone in a room, and the other one stood alone in the room.

04:03:42.880 --> 04:03:49.760
Joe stood alone in an otherwise empty room. The others, the entire group of them, had gone.

04:03:51.600 --> 04:03:58.880
He wondered where they were, and if he would live long enough to find them, it did not seem likely.

04:04:02.080 --> 04:04:07.440
10. Has perspiration odor taken you out of the swim?

04:04:07.440 --> 04:04:13.360
10-day ubeck deodorant spray or ubeck roll-on ends worry of offending, brings you back where

04:04:13.360 --> 04:04:19.040
the happening is, safe when used as directed in a conscientious program of body hygiene.

04:04:20.960 --> 04:04:25.280
The television announcer said, and now back to Jim Hunter and the news.

04:04:26.000 --> 04:04:29.600
On the screen, the sunny, hairless face of the newscaster appeared.

04:04:30.400 --> 04:04:35.120
Glenn Runciter came back today to the place of his birth, but it was not the kind of return

04:04:35.120 --> 04:04:40.320
which glattened anyone's heart. Yesterday, tragedy struck at Runciter Associates,

04:04:40.320 --> 04:04:46.320
probably the best known of Earth's many prudent organizations. In a terrorist blast at an undisclosed

04:04:46.320 --> 04:04:52.560
subsurface installation on Luna, Glenn Runciter was mortally wounded and died before his remains

04:04:52.560 --> 04:04:57.600
could be transferred to Colpac. Brought to the beloved brethren moratorium in Zurich,

04:04:57.600 --> 04:05:03.360
every effort was made to revive Runciter to half-life but in vain. In acknowledgement of defeat,

04:05:03.360 --> 04:05:08.480
these efforts have now ceased, and the body of Glenn Runciter has been returned here to Des Moines,

04:05:08.480 --> 04:05:14.480
where it will lie in state at the simple shepherd mortuary. The screen showed an old-fashioned white

04:05:14.480 --> 04:05:20.720
wooden building with various persons roaming about outside. I wonder who authorized the transfer to

04:05:20.720 --> 04:05:27.120
Des Moines, Joe Chipp said to himself. It was the sad but inexorably dictated decision by the

04:05:27.120 --> 04:05:32.640
wife of Glenn Runciter, the newscaster's voice continued, which brought about this final chapter,

04:05:32.640 --> 04:05:38.160
which we are now viewing. Mrs. Ella Runciter herself in Colpac, whom it had been hoped her

04:05:38.160 --> 04:05:44.080
husband would join, revived to face this calamity. Mrs. Runciter learned this morning of the fate

04:05:44.080 --> 04:05:49.760
which had overtaken her husband and gave the decision to abandon efforts to awaken belated

04:05:49.760 --> 04:05:54.880
half-life in the man whom she had expected to merge with, a hope disappointed by reality.

04:05:55.840 --> 04:06:00.480
A still photo of Ella taken during her lifetime appeared briefly on the TV screen.

04:06:01.280 --> 04:06:06.960
In solemn ritual, the newscaster continued, grieving employees of Runciter Associates

04:06:06.960 --> 04:06:12.240
assembled in the chapel of the simple shepherd mortuary, preparing themselves as best they could

04:06:12.240 --> 04:06:19.120
under the circumstances to pay last respects. The screen now showed the roof field of the mortuary.

04:06:19.120 --> 04:06:24.800
A parked upended ship opened its hatch, and men and women emerged. A microphone extended by a

04:06:24.880 --> 04:06:26.080
newsman halted them.

04:06:27.280 --> 04:06:31.760
Tell me, sir, a newsmanish voice said, in addition to working for Glenn Runciter,

04:06:31.760 --> 04:06:36.880
did you and these other employees also know him personally, know him not as a boss, but as a man?

04:06:37.840 --> 04:06:42.720
Blinking like a light-blinded owl, Don Denney said into the extended microphone,

04:06:43.520 --> 04:06:49.040
we all knew Glenn Runciter as a man, as a good individual and a citizen whom we could trust.

04:06:49.040 --> 04:06:51.280
I know I speak for the others when I say this.

04:06:52.080 --> 04:06:57.040
Are all of Mr. Runciter's employees, or perhaps I should say former employees here, Mr. Denney?

04:06:58.000 --> 04:07:03.600
Many of us are here, Don Denney said. Mr. Len Niggleman, Prudent Society Chairman,

04:07:03.600 --> 04:07:07.920
approached us in New York and informed us that he had heard of Glenn Runciter's death.

04:07:08.560 --> 04:07:12.720
He informed us that the body of the deceased was being brought here to Des Moines. He said,

04:07:12.720 --> 04:07:16.800
we ought to come here, and we agreed. So he brought us in his ship. This is his ship.

04:07:17.440 --> 04:07:20.240
Denney indicated the ship out of which he and the others had stepped.

04:07:21.120 --> 04:07:26.240
We appreciated him notifying us of the change of location, from the moratorium in Zurich to the

04:07:26.240 --> 04:07:32.560
mortuary here. Several of us are not here, however, because they weren't at the firm's New York

04:07:32.560 --> 04:07:38.480
offices. I refer in particular to inertials Al Hammond and Wendy Wright and the firm's field

04:07:38.480 --> 04:07:44.880
testemister Chip. The whereabouts of the three of them is unknown to us, but perhaps along with,

04:07:44.880 --> 04:07:49.280
yes, the news announcer with the microphone said, perhaps they will see this telecast,

04:07:49.280 --> 04:07:54.720
which is being beamed by satellite over all the earth, and will come here to Des Moines for

04:07:54.720 --> 04:08:00.320
this tragic occasion, as I am sure, and as you undoubtedly are sure, Mr. Runciter and also

04:08:00.320 --> 04:08:05.920
Mrs. Runciter would want them to. And now, back to Jim Hunter at Newsroom Central.

04:08:07.200 --> 04:08:12.880
Jim Hunter, reappearing on the screen, said, Ray Hollis, whose sionically talented personnel

04:08:12.880 --> 04:08:17.920
are the object of inertial nullification, and hence the target of the Prudence organizations,

04:08:17.920 --> 04:08:23.040
said today in a statement released by his office that he regretted the accidental death of Glen

04:08:23.040 --> 04:08:28.080
Runciter and would, if possible, attend the funeral services in Des Moines. It may be,

04:08:28.080 --> 04:08:32.480
however, that Len Niggleman, representing the Prudence Society, as we told you earlier,

04:08:32.480 --> 04:08:36.800
will ask that he be barred in view of the implication on the part of some Prudence

04:08:36.800 --> 04:08:42.160
organization spokesman that Hollis originally reacted to news of Runciter's death with ill

04:08:42.160 --> 04:08:47.920
disguised relief. Newscaster Hunter paused, picked up a sheet of paper, and said,

04:08:48.640 --> 04:08:55.120
Turning now to other news! With his foot, Joe Chipp tripped the pedal which controlled the TV set,

04:08:55.120 --> 04:08:58.400
the screen faded, and the sound ebbed into silence.

04:08:59.760 --> 04:09:03.920
This doesn't fit in with the graffiti on the bathroom walls, Joe reflected.

04:09:04.800 --> 04:09:10.320
Maybe Runciter is dead, after all. The TV people think so, Ray Hollis thinks so,

04:09:10.320 --> 04:09:16.160
so does Len Niggleman. They all consider him dead. And all we have that says otherwise is the

04:09:16.160 --> 04:09:21.040
two rhymed couplets, which could have been scrolled by anyone, despite what Al thought.

04:09:22.320 --> 04:09:28.400
The TV screen relit, much to his surprise. He had not repressed the pedal switch,

04:09:28.400 --> 04:09:34.080
and in addition it changed channels. Images flitted past of one thing and then another,

04:09:34.080 --> 04:09:38.960
until at last the mysterious agency was satisfied. The final image remained.

04:09:39.920 --> 04:09:42.000
The face of Glenn Runciter.

04:09:43.040 --> 04:09:47.920
Tired of lazy taste buds, Runciter said in his familiar gravelly voice,

04:09:47.920 --> 04:09:54.720
as boil cabbage taken over your world of food, that same old stale, flat, Monday morning odor,

04:09:54.720 --> 04:10:00.960
no matter how many dimes you put into your stove. Ubic changes all that. Ubic wakes up,

04:10:00.960 --> 04:10:05.840
food flavor puts hearty taste back where it belongs and restores fine food smell.

04:10:06.640 --> 04:10:10.480
On the screen a brightly colored spray can replaced Glenn Runciter.

04:10:11.280 --> 04:10:17.680
One invisible puff puff whisk of economically priced Ubic banishes compulsive obsessive fears

04:10:17.680 --> 04:10:22.480
that the entire world is turning into clotted milk worn out tape recorders and obsolete iron

04:10:22.480 --> 04:10:28.160
cage elevators, plus other further as yet unglimbsed manifestations of decay.

04:10:28.960 --> 04:10:35.040
You see, world deterioration of this regressive type is a normal experience of many half lifers,

04:10:35.040 --> 04:10:39.360
especially in the early stages when ties to the real reality are still very strong.

04:10:40.160 --> 04:10:46.800
A sort of lingering universe is retained as a residual charge, experienced as a pseudo environment,

04:10:46.800 --> 04:10:52.960
but highly unstable and unsupported by any ergic substructure. This is particularly true when

04:10:52.960 --> 04:10:58.160
several memory systems are fused, as in the case of you people. But with today's new,

04:10:58.160 --> 04:11:01.680
more powerful than ever, Ubic, all this is changed.

04:11:02.800 --> 04:11:09.840
Dazed, Joe seated himself, his eyes fixed on the screen. A cartoon fairy zipped airily in spirals,

04:11:09.840 --> 04:11:15.280
squirting Ubic here and there. A hard-eyed housewife with big teeth and horses chin replaced the

04:11:15.280 --> 04:11:20.880
cartoon fairy. In a brassy voice she bellowed, I came over to Ubic after trying week out of date

04:11:20.880 --> 04:11:26.960
reality supports. My pots and pans were turning into heaps of rust. The floors of my conap were

04:11:26.960 --> 04:11:32.720
sagging. My husband Charlie put his right foot through the bedroom door. But now I use economical,

04:11:32.720 --> 04:11:39.280
new, powerful today's Ubic. And with miraculous results, look at this refrigerator. On the screen

04:11:39.280 --> 04:11:44.640
appeared an antique turret-top GE refrigerator. Why, it's devolved back eighty years.

04:11:45.520 --> 04:11:51.440
Sixty-two years, Joe corrected reflexively. But now, look at it, the housewife continued

04:11:51.520 --> 04:11:57.200
squirting the old turret-top with her spray can of Ubic. Sparkles of magic light lit up in a

04:11:57.200 --> 04:12:03.200
nimble surrounding the old turret-top. And in a flash, a modern six-door pay refrigerator replaced

04:12:03.200 --> 04:12:09.600
it in splendid glory. Yes, Runceter's dark voice resumed, by making use of the most advanced

04:12:09.600 --> 04:12:15.520
techniques of present-day science, the reversion of matter to earlier forms can be reversed,

04:12:15.520 --> 04:12:21.760
and at a price any conap owner can afford. Ubic is sold by leading home art stores throughout

04:12:21.760 --> 04:12:28.640
earth. Do not take internally. Keep away from open flame. Do not deviate from printed procedural

04:12:28.640 --> 04:12:35.040
approaches as expressed on label. So look for it, Joe. Don't just sit there. Go out and buy a can of

04:12:35.040 --> 04:12:40.240
Ubic and spray it all around you night and day. Standing up, Joe said loudly,

04:12:40.880 --> 04:12:46.720
You know I'm here. Does that mean you can hear and see me? Of course I can't hear you and see you.

04:12:47.280 --> 04:12:52.960
This commercial message is on videotape. I recorded it two weeks ago, specifically twelve

04:12:52.960 --> 04:12:58.640
days before my death. I knew the bomb blast was coming. I made use of pre-cog talents.

04:12:59.600 --> 04:13:05.440
Then you are really dead. Of course I'm dead. Didn't you watch the telecast from Des Moines

04:13:05.440 --> 04:13:11.840
just now? I know you did because my pre-cog saw that too. What about the graffiti on the men's room

04:13:11.840 --> 04:13:18.800
wall? Runciter from the audio system of the TV set boomed. Another deterioration phenomenon.

04:13:19.360 --> 04:13:24.240
Go buy a can of Ubic and it'll stop happening to you. All those things will cease.

04:13:25.360 --> 04:13:34.000
Al thinks we're dead, Joe said. Al is deteriorating. Runciter laughed a deep re-echoing pulsation

04:13:34.080 --> 04:13:40.960
that made the conference room vibrate. Look, Joe, I recorded this goddamn TV commercial to assist you,

04:13:40.960 --> 04:13:45.920
to guide you. You in particular, because we've always been friends. And I knew you'd be very

04:13:45.920 --> 04:13:52.000
confused, which is exactly what you are right now. Totally confused. Which isn't very surprising,

04:13:52.000 --> 04:13:58.080
considering your usual condition. Anyhow, try to hang on. Maybe once you get to Des Moines and

04:13:58.080 --> 04:14:03.680
see my body lying in state, you'll calm down. What's this Ubic, Joe asked?

04:14:04.240 --> 04:14:08.400
I think, though, it's too late to help, Al. Joe said,

04:14:09.440 --> 04:14:15.600
what is Ubic made of? How does it work? As a matter of fact, Al probably induced the writing on the

04:14:15.600 --> 04:14:21.120
men's room wall. You wouldn't have seen it except for him. You really are on videotape, aren't you?

04:14:21.120 --> 04:14:26.720
Joe said, you can't hear me. It's true. Runciter said, and in addition, Al...

04:14:27.360 --> 04:14:31.920
rats. Joe said in weary disgust. It was no use, he gave up.

04:14:33.120 --> 04:14:37.520
The horse-jawed housewife returned to the TV screen, winding up the commercial. Her voice,

04:14:37.520 --> 04:14:42.960
softer now, she trilled. If the home art store that you patronize doesn't yet carry Ubic,

04:14:42.960 --> 04:14:49.040
return to your con app, Mr. Chip, and you'll find a free sample has arrived by mail. A free

04:14:49.120 --> 04:14:54.400
introductory sample, Mr. Chip, that will keep you going until you can buy a regular size can.

04:14:55.280 --> 04:15:01.920
She then faded out. The TV set became opaque and silent. The process that had turned it on

04:15:02.480 --> 04:15:03.600
had turned it back off.

04:15:06.240 --> 04:15:13.680
So, I'm supposed to blame Al, Joe thought. The idea did not appeal to him. He sensed the peculiarity

04:15:13.680 --> 04:15:21.360
of the logic. It's perhaps deliberate misdirectedness. Al the fall guy, Al made into the patsy.

04:15:21.360 --> 04:15:29.840
Everything explained in terms of Al. Senseless, he said to himself. And had Runciter been able

04:15:29.840 --> 04:15:36.000
to hear him, had Runciter only pretended to be on videotape? For a time during the commercial,

04:15:36.000 --> 04:15:41.760
Runciter had seemed to respond to his questions. Only at the end had Runciter's words become

04:15:41.760 --> 04:15:47.120
malappropriate. He felt all at once like an ineffectual moth fluttering at the window

04:15:47.120 --> 04:15:53.920
pain of reality dimly seeing it from outside. A new thought struck him, an eerie idea.

04:15:54.480 --> 04:16:00.160
Suppose Runciter had made the videotape recording under the assumption, based on inaccurate pre-cog

04:16:00.160 --> 04:16:05.200
information, that the bomb blast would kill him and leave the rest of them alive.

04:16:06.160 --> 04:16:11.600
The tape had been made honestly, but mistakenly. Runciter had not died. They had died.

04:16:11.600 --> 04:16:17.440
As the graffiti on the men's room wall had said, and Runciter still lived. Before the bomb blast,

04:16:17.440 --> 04:16:21.520
he had given instructions for the tape commercial to be played at this time, and the network had

04:16:21.520 --> 04:16:27.200
done so. Runciter, having failed to countermand his original order, that would explain the disparity

04:16:27.200 --> 04:16:31.920
between what Runciter had said on the tape and what he had written on the bathroom walls.

04:16:32.720 --> 04:16:38.800
It would, in fact, explain both. Which, as far as he could make out, no other explanation would.

04:16:39.760 --> 04:16:45.200
Unless Runciter was playing a sardonic game with them, trifling with them, first leading them in

04:16:45.200 --> 04:16:51.680
one direction then the other, an unnatural and gigantic force haunting their lives, emanating

04:16:51.680 --> 04:16:56.560
either within the living world or the half-life world. Or, he thought, suddenly perhaps both.

04:16:57.440 --> 04:17:01.840
In any case, controlling what they experienced, or at least a major part of it,

04:17:02.800 --> 04:17:09.360
perhaps not the decay he decided, not that. But why not? Maybe he thought that, too.

04:17:10.320 --> 04:17:13.360
But Runciter wouldn't admit it. Runciter and ubiquity.

04:17:14.240 --> 04:17:20.720
Ubiquity, he realized all at once. That's the derivation of the made-up word, the name of Runciter's

04:17:20.720 --> 04:17:27.280
alleged spray can product. Which probably did not even exist. It was probably a further hoax to

04:17:27.280 --> 04:17:34.320
bewilder them that much more. And in addition, if Runciter were alive, then not one, but two

04:17:34.320 --> 04:17:39.840
Runciter's existed. The genuine one in the real world who was striving to reach them,

04:17:40.400 --> 04:17:45.360
and the phantasmagoric Runciter who had become a corpse in this half-life world,

04:17:45.360 --> 04:17:52.160
the body lying in state in Des Moines, Iowa. And to carry the logic of this out to its full extent,

04:17:52.160 --> 04:17:57.760
other persons here, such as Ray Hollis and Len Nigelman, were also phantasmagoria,

04:17:58.400 --> 04:18:01.680
while their authentic counterparts remained in the world of the living.

04:18:03.040 --> 04:18:08.880
Very confusing, Joe Chipp said to himself. He did not like it at all.

04:18:09.840 --> 04:18:15.440
Granted, it had a satisfying symmetrical quality, but on the other hand, it struck him as untidy.

04:18:16.400 --> 04:18:22.400
I'll zip over to my conapt. He decided to pick up the free sample of UBIC, then head for Des Moines.

04:18:23.040 --> 04:18:28.720
After all, that's what the TV commercial urged me to do. I'll be safer carrying a can of UBIC

04:18:28.720 --> 04:18:35.200
with me, as the ad pointed out in its own jingly, clever way. One has to pay attention to such

04:18:35.200 --> 04:18:43.040
admonitions, he realized, if one expects to stay alive, or half alive, whichever it is.

04:18:45.440 --> 04:18:50.880
Taxi let him off on the roof field of his conapt building. He descended by moving ramp and arrived

04:18:50.880 --> 04:18:56.480
at his own door, with a coin that someone had given him, Al or Pat. He could not knowingly remember.

04:18:56.480 --> 04:19:02.720
He opened the door and entered. The living room smelled faintly of burned grease, an odor he had

04:19:02.720 --> 04:19:08.320
not come across since childhood. Going into the kitchen, he discovered the reason his stove had

04:19:08.320 --> 04:19:14.720
reverted back to an ancient buck natural gas model, with clogged burners and encrusted oven door,

04:19:14.720 --> 04:19:21.680
which did not close entirely. He gazed at the old, much used stove dully, then discovered that the

04:19:21.680 --> 04:19:27.200
other kitchen appliances had undergone similar metamorphoses. The homeopaped machine had vanished

04:19:27.200 --> 04:19:32.880
entirely. The toaster had dissolved sometime during the day and reformed itself as a rubbishy,

04:19:32.880 --> 04:19:37.840
quaint, non-automatic model, not even pop-up, he discovered, as he poked bleakly at it.

04:19:38.640 --> 04:19:43.760
The refrigerator that greeted him was an enormous, belt-driven model, a relic that had floated into

04:19:43.760 --> 04:19:49.520
being from God knew what distant past. It was even more obsolete than the turret-top G.E.

04:19:49.520 --> 04:19:55.440
shown in the TV commercial. The coffee-pot had undergone the least change. As a matter of fact,

04:19:55.440 --> 04:20:00.480
in one respect, it had improved. It lacked the coin slot, operating obviously toll-free.

04:20:01.200 --> 04:20:07.360
This aspect was true of all the appliances, he realized. All that remain, anyhow.

04:20:07.920 --> 04:20:12.160
Like the homeopaped machine, the garbage disposal unit had entirely vanished.

04:20:12.720 --> 04:20:18.320
He tried to remember what other appliances he had owned, but already memory had become vague.

04:20:18.320 --> 04:20:24.800
He gave up and returned to the living-room. The TV set had receded back a long way.

04:20:24.800 --> 04:20:30.320
He found himself confronted by a dark wood cabinet at Waterkent-tuned radio-frequency,

04:20:30.320 --> 04:20:34.480
old-time AM radio, complete with antenna and ground wires.

04:20:34.480 --> 04:20:40.880
God in heaven, he said to himself, appalled. But why hadn't the TV set reverted instead to

04:20:40.880 --> 04:20:46.320
formless metals and plastics? Those, after all were its constituents,

04:20:46.320 --> 04:20:53.840
it had been constructed out of them, not out of an earlier radio. Perhaps this weirdly verified

04:20:53.840 --> 04:21:00.880
a discarded ancient philosophy that of Plato's ideal objects, the universals which in each class

04:21:00.880 --> 04:21:08.000
were real. The form TV set had been a template imposed as a successor to other templates,

04:21:08.000 --> 04:21:13.280
like the procession of frames in a movie sequence. Prior forms, he reflected, must

04:21:13.280 --> 04:21:21.680
carry on an invisible residual life in every object. The past is latent, is submerged, but

04:21:21.680 --> 04:21:27.840
still there, capable of rising to the surface once the later imprinting, unfortunately, and

04:21:27.840 --> 04:21:36.960
against ordinary experience, vanished. The man contains not the boy, but earlier men, he thought.

04:21:37.680 --> 04:21:45.280
History began a long time ago. The dehydrated remnants of Wendy, the procession of forms that

04:21:45.280 --> 04:21:52.480
normally takes place, that procession ceased. And the last form wore off with nothing subsequent,

04:21:52.480 --> 04:21:58.880
no newer form, no next stage of what we see as growth to take its place. This must be what we

04:21:58.880 --> 04:22:06.320
experience as old age. From this absence comes degeneration and senility. Only in this instance,

04:22:06.320 --> 04:22:13.040
it happened abruptly in a matter of hours. But this old theory didn't Plato think that

04:22:13.040 --> 04:22:19.360
something survived the decline, something inner, not able to decay? The ancient dualism, body

04:22:19.360 --> 04:22:25.600
separated from soul, the body ending, as Wendy did, and the soul out of its nest, the bird,

04:22:25.600 --> 04:22:33.200
flown elsewhere. Maybe so, he thought. To be reborn again as the Tibetan book of the dead says,

04:22:33.280 --> 04:22:40.960
it really is true. Christ, I hope so. Because in that case, we all can meet again. In, as in

04:22:40.960 --> 04:22:46.320
Winnie the Pooh, another part of the forest, where a boy and his bear will always be playing,

04:22:47.280 --> 04:22:54.240
a category he thought imperishable, like all of us. We will all wind up with Pooh in a clearer,

04:22:54.240 --> 04:23:02.160
more durable new place. For curiosity's sake, he turned on the prehistoric radio set. The yellow

04:23:02.160 --> 04:23:09.200
celluloid dial glowed. The set gave off a loud sixty-cycle hum, and then amid static and squeals,

04:23:09.200 --> 04:23:15.680
a station came on. Time for Pepper Young's family, the announcer said, and organ music gurgled.

04:23:16.240 --> 04:23:21.840
Brought to you by Myle Cammay, the soap of beautiful women. Yesterday, Pepper discovered

04:23:21.840 --> 04:23:28.160
that the labor of months had come to an unexpected end due to the— Joe shut the radio off at that

04:23:28.160 --> 04:23:34.720
point—a pre-World War II soap opera, he said to himself, marveling. Well, it followed the logic

04:23:34.720 --> 04:23:40.880
of the former versions taking place in this, the dying half-world, or whatever it was.

04:23:42.160 --> 04:23:47.040
Looking around the living room, he discovered a baroque-legged, glass-topped coffee table,

04:23:47.040 --> 04:23:53.600
on which a copy of Liberty Magazine rested, also pre-World War II. The magazine featured a serial

04:23:53.680 --> 04:24:00.320
entitled, Lightning in the Night, a Futuristic Fantasy Supposing an Atomic War. He turned the

04:24:00.320 --> 04:24:06.560
pages numbly, then studied the room as a whole, seeking to identify other changes. The tough,

04:24:06.560 --> 04:24:12.880
neutral-colored floor had become wide, softwood boards, in the center of the room a faded Turkish

04:24:12.880 --> 04:24:19.280
rug lay impregnated with years of dust. One single picture remained on the wall,

04:24:19.280 --> 04:24:24.880
a glass-covered frame print in monochrome showing a dying Indian on horseback. He had never seen

04:24:24.880 --> 04:24:31.200
it before, it stirred no memories, and he did not care for it one bit. The vid-phone had been

04:24:31.200 --> 04:24:37.040
replaced by a black hook-style upright telephone, pre-dial. He lifted the receiver from the hook

04:24:37.040 --> 04:24:40.960
and heard a female voice saying, Hammer, please. At that he hung up.

04:24:42.800 --> 04:24:48.400
The thermostatically controlled heating system had evidently departed. At one end of the living

04:24:48.400 --> 04:24:54.080
room he perceived a gas heater, complete with large tin flue running up the wall almost to the

04:24:54.080 --> 04:25:00.240
ceiling. Going into the bedroom he looked in the closet, rummage, then assembled an outfit. Black

04:25:00.240 --> 04:25:06.000
oxfords, wool socks, knickers, blue cotton shirt, camel's hair, sports coat, and golf cap.

04:25:06.720 --> 04:25:12.000
For more formal wear he laid out on the bed a pinstripe, blue-black double-breasted suit,

04:25:12.000 --> 04:25:16.800
suspenders, wide floral necktie, and white shirt with celluloid collar.

04:25:16.880 --> 04:25:22.800
Jeez, he said to himself in dismay, as in the closet he came across a golf bag with assorted

04:25:22.800 --> 04:25:28.960
clubs. What a relic! Once more he returned to the living room. This time he noticed the spot where

04:25:28.960 --> 04:25:34.480
his polyphonic audio components had formerly been assembled. The multiplex FM tuner, the high

04:25:34.480 --> 04:25:40.320
hysteresis turntable and weightless tracking arm, speakers, horns, multi-track amplifier,

04:25:40.320 --> 04:25:47.680
all had vanished. In their place a tall tan wooden structure greeted him. He made out the crank

04:25:47.680 --> 04:25:53.760
handle and did not need to lift the lid to know what his sound system now consisted of. Bamboo

04:25:53.760 --> 04:25:59.920
needles, a pack of them on the bookcase beside the Victrola, and a 10-inch 78-speed black label

04:25:59.920 --> 04:26:05.920
Victor record of Ray Noble's orchestra playing Turkish delight. So much for his tape and LP

04:26:06.000 --> 04:26:11.200
collection. And by tomorrow he would probably find himself equipped with a cylinder phonograph

04:26:11.200 --> 04:26:16.240
screw-driven, and to play on it a shouted recitation of the Lord's Prayer.

04:26:17.920 --> 04:26:23.120
A fresh-looking newspaper lying at the far end of the overstuffed sofa attracted his attention.

04:26:23.120 --> 04:26:30.240
He picked it up and read the date. Tuesday, September 12, 1939. He scanned the headlines.

04:26:30.880 --> 04:26:35.840
French claim Siegfried Line Dented report gains in area near Sarbrookin.

04:26:35.840 --> 04:26:38.480
Major battle said to be shaping up along western front.

04:26:39.520 --> 04:26:44.240
Interesting, he said to himself, World War II had just begun and the French thought they were

04:26:44.240 --> 04:26:51.440
winning it. He read another headline. Polish report claims German forces halted. Say, invaders throw

04:26:51.440 --> 04:26:57.840
new forces into battle without new gains. The newspaper had cost three cents. That

04:26:57.920 --> 04:27:02.480
interested him, too. What could you get now for three cents, he asked himself.

04:27:03.040 --> 04:27:08.080
He tossed the newspaper back down and marveled once again at its freshness, a day or so old,

04:27:08.080 --> 04:27:15.280
he guessed. No more than that. So I now have a time-fix. I know precisely how far back the regression

04:27:15.280 --> 04:27:20.720
has carried. Wandering about the con app, searching out the various changes, he found

04:27:20.720 --> 04:27:26.480
himself facing a chest of dresser drawers in the bedroom. On the top rested several framed glass

04:27:26.480 --> 04:27:34.960
covered photographs. All were of Runceter. But not the Runceter he knew. These were of a baby,

04:27:34.960 --> 04:27:40.560
a small boy, then a young man. Runceter, as he had once been, but still recognizable.

04:27:41.200 --> 04:27:46.480
Getting out his wallet, he found only snapshots of Runceter. None of his family, none of friends,

04:27:46.480 --> 04:27:52.880
Runceter, everywhere. He returned the wallet to his pocket, then realized with a jolt that it had

04:27:52.880 --> 04:27:59.440
been made of natural cowhide, not plastic. Well, that fitted. In the old days there had been organic

04:27:59.440 --> 04:28:05.760
leather available. So what, he said to himself, bringing the wallet out once more, he somberly

04:28:05.760 --> 04:28:13.280
scrutinized it. He rubbed the cowhide and experienced a new tactile sensation, a pleasant one,

04:28:13.280 --> 04:28:19.440
infinitely superior to plastic, he decided. Back in the living room again he poked about searching

04:28:19.440 --> 04:28:24.720
for the familiar mail slot, the recessed wall cavity, which should have contained today's mail.

04:28:24.720 --> 04:28:31.840
It had vanished. It no longer existed. He pondered, trying to envision old-time mail practices

04:28:32.640 --> 04:28:42.000
on the floor outside the con-app door. No. In a box of some kind. He recalled the term mail box.

04:28:42.880 --> 04:28:49.360
Okay, it would be in the mail box. But where had mail boxes been located? At the main entrance

04:28:49.440 --> 04:28:56.160
of the building? That dimly seemed right. He would have to leave his con-app. The mail would be found

04:28:56.160 --> 04:29:02.800
on the ground floor twenty stories below. Five cents, please, his front door said when he tried to open it.

04:29:03.760 --> 04:29:09.840
One thing anyhow hadn't changed. The toll door had an innate stubbornness to it. Probably it

04:29:09.840 --> 04:29:15.040
would hold out after everything else. After everything except it had long since reverted,

04:29:15.120 --> 04:29:19.600
perhaps in the whole city, if not the whole world. He paid the door a nickel,

04:29:19.600 --> 04:29:22.960
hurried down the hall to the moving ramp which he had used only minutes ago.

04:29:23.760 --> 04:29:28.240
The ramp, however, had now reverted to a flight of inert concrete stairs.

04:29:28.960 --> 04:29:36.800
Twenty flights down, he reflected. Step by step. Impossible! No one could walk down that many

04:29:36.800 --> 04:29:42.640
stairs. The elevator. He started toward it, then remembered what had happened to Al. Suppose this

04:29:42.640 --> 04:29:48.720
time I see what he saw, he said to himself. An old iron cage hanging from a wire cable operated by

04:29:48.720 --> 04:29:55.600
a senile borderline moron wearing an official elevator operator's cap. Not a vision of 1939,

04:29:55.600 --> 04:30:00.960
but a vision of 1909. A regression much greater than anything I've run into so far.

04:30:02.080 --> 04:30:07.280
Better not to risk it. Better to take the stairs. Resigned, he began to descend.

04:30:08.000 --> 04:30:12.080
He had gotten almost halfway down when something ominous flicked alive in his brain.

04:30:12.720 --> 04:30:18.240
There was no way by which he could get back up, either to his conapt or to the roof field where

04:30:18.240 --> 04:30:23.120
the taxi waited. Once on the ground floor he would be confined there. Maybe forever.

04:30:24.160 --> 04:30:28.480
Unless the spray can of Ubeck was potent enough to restore the elevator or the moving ramp.

04:30:29.600 --> 04:30:35.680
Surface travel, he said to himself. What the hell will that consist of by the time I get down their

04:30:35.680 --> 04:30:42.480
train? Covered wagon? Clattering down two steps at a time, he morosely continued his descent

04:30:42.480 --> 04:30:48.160
too late now to change his mind. When he reached the ground level, he found himself confronted by

04:30:48.160 --> 04:30:54.400
a large lobby, including a marble top table, very long, on which two ceramic vases of flowers,

04:30:54.400 --> 04:31:01.600
evidently iris, rested. Four wide steps led down to the curtain front door. He grasped the faceted

04:31:01.600 --> 04:31:07.840
glass knob of the door and swung it open. More steps, and on the right a row of locked brass

04:31:07.840 --> 04:31:13.840
mailboxes, each with a name, each requiring a key. He had been right. This was as far as the mail was

04:31:13.840 --> 04:31:19.040
brought. He located his own box, finding a strip of paper at the bottom of it, reading Joseph Chip,

04:31:19.040 --> 04:31:24.720
2075, plus a button which, when pressed, evidently rang upstairs in his conapt.

04:31:24.960 --> 04:31:33.600
The key. He had no key, or did he? Fishing in his pockets, he discovered a ring on which several

04:31:33.600 --> 04:31:39.520
diversely shaped metal keys dangled. Perplexed, he studied them, wondering what they were for.

04:31:40.480 --> 04:31:45.440
The lock on the mailbox seemed unusually small. Obviously, it took a similar size key.

04:31:45.440 --> 04:31:50.960
Selecting the most meager key on the ring, he inserted it in the lock of the mailbox, turned it.

04:31:51.040 --> 04:31:54.640
The brass door of the box fell open. He peered inside.

04:31:55.840 --> 04:32:02.000
Within the box lay two letters, and a square package wrapped in brown paper sealed with brown tape.

04:32:02.720 --> 04:32:09.440
Purple, three-cent stamps with a portrait of George Washington. He paused to admire these unusual

04:32:09.440 --> 04:32:14.480
memorabilia from the past, and then, ignoring the letters, tore open the square package,

04:32:14.480 --> 04:32:20.000
finding it rewardingly heavy. But he realized suddenly it's the wrong shape for a spray can.

04:32:20.000 --> 04:32:25.600
It's not tall enough. Fear touched him. What if it was not a free sample of Ubeck?

04:32:26.240 --> 04:32:30.720
It had to be. It just had to be. Otherwise, al, all over again.

04:32:31.520 --> 04:32:36.640
Morserta et Horacerta, he said to himself, as he dropped the brown paper wrappings and

04:32:36.640 --> 04:32:42.720
examined the paste-board container within. Ubeck, liver, and kidney bomb.

04:32:43.680 --> 04:32:49.520
Inside the container, he found a blue glass jar with a large lid. The label read,

04:32:49.520 --> 04:32:56.400
Directions for Use. This unique analgesic formula, developed over a period of 40 years by Dr.

04:32:56.400 --> 04:33:02.640
Edward Sondbar, is guaranteed to end forever, annoying getting up at night. You will sleep

04:33:02.640 --> 04:33:08.400
peacefully for the first time and with superlative comfort. Merely dissolve a teaspoonful of Ubeck

04:33:08.400 --> 04:33:14.800
liver and kidney bomb in a glass of warm water and drink immediately one half hour before retiring.

04:33:14.800 --> 04:33:22.000
If pain or irritation persists, increase dosage to one tablespoon full. Do not give to children.

04:33:22.560 --> 04:33:26.320
Contains processed oleander leaves, salt, Peter, oil of peppermint,

04:33:26.320 --> 04:33:32.480
enosetal, Pia minifinal, zinc oxide, charcoal, cobalt chloride, caffeine, extract of digitalis,

04:33:32.480 --> 04:33:37.840
steroids and trace amounts, sodium citrate, ascorbic acid, artificial coloring and flavoring.

04:33:38.480 --> 04:33:43.200
Ubeck liver and kidney bomb is potent and effective if handled as per instructions.

04:33:43.200 --> 04:33:52.000
Imflammable. Use rubber gloves. Do not allow to get in eyes. Do not splash on skin. Do not

04:33:52.000 --> 04:34:00.320
inhale over long periods of time. Warning. Prolonged or excessive use may result in habituation.

04:34:01.040 --> 04:34:07.840
This is insane, Joe said to himself. He read the list of ingredients once more feeling growing

04:34:07.840 --> 04:34:13.760
baffled anger and a mounting helpless sensation that took root and spread through every part of him.

04:34:14.320 --> 04:34:20.080
I'm finished, he said to himself. This stuff isn't what Runciter advertised on TV. This is some

04:34:20.080 --> 04:34:27.600
arcane mixture of old time patent medicine, skin salves, pain killers, poisons, inert nothings,

04:34:28.240 --> 04:34:32.320
plus of all things cortisone, which didn't exist before World War II.

04:34:33.280 --> 04:34:36.960
Obviously, the Ubeck which he described to me in the tape-TV commercial,

04:34:37.520 --> 04:34:43.600
this sample of it anyhow, has reverted an irony that is just plain too much.

04:34:43.600 --> 04:34:49.120
The substance created to reverse the regressive change process has itself regressed. I should

04:34:49.120 --> 04:34:54.720
have known as soon as I saw the old purple three-cent stamps. He looked up and down the street

04:34:54.720 --> 04:34:59.440
and saw parked at the curb a classic museum piece surface car, a LaSalle.

04:34:59.440 --> 04:35:05.360
Can I get to Des Moines in a 1939 LaSalle automobile? he asked himself.

04:35:06.400 --> 04:35:12.480
Eventually, if it remains stable, perhaps a week from now, but by then it won't matter,

04:35:12.480 --> 04:35:17.600
and anyhow the car won't remain stable. Nothing, except maybe my front door will.

04:35:18.800 --> 04:35:22.240
However, he walked over to the LaSalle to examine it at close range.

04:35:23.200 --> 04:35:29.440
Maybe it's mine, he said to himself. Maybe one of my keys fits its ignition.

04:35:29.440 --> 04:35:33.520
Isn't that how surface cars operate? On the other hand, how am I going to drive it? I don't

04:35:33.520 --> 04:35:37.920
know how to pilot an old-time automobile, especially one with, what did they call it,

04:35:38.720 --> 04:35:44.560
manual transmission. He opened the door and slid onto the seat behind the driver's steering wheel.

04:35:45.280 --> 04:35:50.080
There he sat, plucking aimlessly at his lower lip and trying to think the situation through.

04:35:51.040 --> 04:35:56.480
Maybe I ought to drink down a tablespoon of ubeck liver and kidney bomb, he said to himself,

04:35:56.480 --> 04:36:02.800
grimly. With those ingredients it ought to kill me fairly thoroughly. But it did not strike him

04:36:02.800 --> 04:36:09.440
as the kind of death he could welcome. The cobalt chloride would do it very slowly and agonizingly,

04:36:09.440 --> 04:36:14.560
unless the digitalis managed it first. And there were, of course, the oleander leaves.

04:36:14.560 --> 04:36:20.640
They could hardly be overlooked. The whole combination would melt his bones into jelly inch

04:36:20.640 --> 04:36:30.400
by inch. Wait a minute, he thought. Air transportation existed in 1939. If I could get to the New York

04:36:30.400 --> 04:36:38.720
Airport, possibly in this car, I could charter a flight. Rent a Ford tri-motor plane complete

04:36:38.720 --> 04:36:45.200
with pilot, that would get me to Des Moines. He tried his various keys and, at last, found one which

04:36:45.200 --> 04:36:50.640
switched on the car's ignition. The starter motor cranked away and then the engine caught. With a

04:36:50.640 --> 04:36:57.040
healthy rumble, the engine continued to turn over and the sound of it pleased him. Like the genuine

04:36:57.040 --> 04:37:03.280
cow-hide wallet, this particular regression struck him as an improvement. Being completely silent,

04:37:03.280 --> 04:37:08.000
the transportation of his own time lacked this palpable touch of sturdy realism.

04:37:08.880 --> 04:37:15.760
Now the clutch, he said to himself, over on the left, with his foot he located it. Clutch down to

04:37:15.760 --> 04:37:24.000
the floor, then shift the lever into gear. He tried it and obtained a horrid clashing noise, metal

04:37:24.000 --> 04:37:29.360
whirring against metal. Evidently he had managed to let up on the clutch. He tried it again. This

04:37:29.360 --> 04:37:35.360
time he successfully got it into gear. Lurching, the car moved forward. It bucked and shuttered,

04:37:35.360 --> 04:37:41.520
but it moved. It limped erratically up the street and he felt within him a certain measured renewal

04:37:41.520 --> 04:37:47.280
of optimism. And now let's see if we can find the goddamn airfield, he said to himself, before

04:37:47.280 --> 04:37:52.880
it's too late, before we're back in the days of the gnome rotary engine with its revolving outside

04:37:52.880 --> 04:37:58.960
cylinders and its castor oil lubricant, good for fifty miles of hedge-hopping flight at seventy-five

04:37:58.960 --> 04:38:05.120
miles per hour. An hour later he arrived at the airfield, parked and surveyed the hangars, the

04:38:05.120 --> 04:38:11.120
windsock, the old bi-planes with their huge wooden props. What a sight, he reflected. An

04:38:11.120 --> 04:38:17.360
indistinct page out of history. Recreated remnants of another millennium lacking any connection with

04:38:17.360 --> 04:38:23.920
the familiar real world, a phantasm that had drifted into sight only momentarily, this too,

04:38:23.920 --> 04:38:30.800
would be gone soon. It would no more survive than had contemporary artifacts. The process of

04:38:30.800 --> 04:38:36.400
devolution would sweep this away like it had everything else. He got shakily from the LaSalle

04:38:36.400 --> 04:38:40.960
feeling acutely carcid and trudged toward the main buildings of the airfield.

04:38:41.040 --> 04:38:47.520
What can I charter with this, he asked, laying all his money out on the counter before the first

04:38:47.520 --> 04:38:51.920
official-looking person he caught sight of. I want to get to Des Moines as quickly as possible.

04:38:51.920 --> 04:38:58.560
I want to take off right away. The field official, bald-headed with a waxed mustache and small round

04:38:58.560 --> 04:39:01.440
gold-rimmed eyeglasses, inspected the bill silently.

04:39:02.640 --> 04:39:07.280
Hey, Sam! he called with a turn of his apple-like round head. Come here and look at this money.

04:39:08.000 --> 04:39:12.720
A second individual, wearing a striped shirt with billowing sleeves, shiny seersucker trousers,

04:39:12.720 --> 04:39:17.920
and canvas shoes, stumped over. Fake money, he said after he had taken his look.

04:39:18.480 --> 04:39:24.000
Play money, not George Washington and not Alexander Hamilton. Both officials scrutinized Joe.

04:39:25.120 --> 04:39:30.560
Joe said, I have a 39 LaSalle parked in the parking lot. I'll trade it for a one-way flight

04:39:30.560 --> 04:39:33.600
to Des Moines on any plane that'll get me there. Does that interest you?

04:39:33.680 --> 04:39:38.800
Presently the official with the little gold-rimmed glasses said meditatively,

04:39:39.440 --> 04:39:44.880
maybe Augie Brent would be interested. Brent, the official in the seersucker pants said,

04:39:44.880 --> 04:39:49.680
raising his eyebrows. You mean that Jenny of his that plane's over 20 years old wouldn't get to

04:39:49.680 --> 04:39:56.800
Philadelphia. How about McGee? Sure, but he's in Newark. Then maybe Sandy Jesperson. That Curtis

04:39:56.800 --> 04:40:02.400
right of his would make it to Iowa. Sooner or later. To Joe, the official said, go out by

04:40:02.400 --> 04:40:06.880
Hangar 3 and look for a red-and-white Curtis biplane. You'll see a little short guy sort of fat

04:40:06.880 --> 04:40:11.040
fiddling around with it. If he doesn't take you up on it, nobody here will, unless you want to

04:40:11.040 --> 04:40:17.120
wait till tomorrow for Ike McGee to come back here in his Focker trimotor. Thanks, Joe said.

04:40:17.120 --> 04:40:22.160
And left the building. He strode rapidly toward Hangar 3, already seeing what looked like a

04:40:22.160 --> 04:40:27.200
red-and-white Curtis right biplane. At least I won't be making the trip in a World War J. N.

04:40:27.200 --> 04:40:30.080
Training plane, he said to himself. And then he thought,

04:40:30.880 --> 04:40:34.560
how did I know that Jenny is a nickname for a J. N. Trainer?

04:40:35.520 --> 04:40:40.960
Good God, he thought. Elements of this period appear to be developing corresponding coordinates

04:40:40.960 --> 04:40:46.240
in my mind. No wonder I was able to drive the Lissalle. I'm beginning to phase mentally with

04:40:46.240 --> 04:40:52.400
this time continuum in earnest. A short fat man with red hair puttered with an oily rag at the

04:40:52.400 --> 04:40:55.520
wheels of his biplane. He glanced up as Joe approached.

04:40:56.240 --> 04:40:58.400
Are you Mr. Jesperson? Joe asked.

04:40:58.960 --> 04:41:04.720
That's right. The man surveyed him, obviously mystified by Joe's clothes, which had not reverted.

04:41:04.720 --> 04:41:07.040
What can I do for you? Joe told him.

04:41:07.680 --> 04:41:12.720
You want to trade a Lissalle? A new Lissalle for a one-way trip to Des Moines?

04:41:12.720 --> 04:41:18.560
Jesperson cogitated his brows knitting. Might as well be both ways. I gotta fly back here anyway.

04:41:19.520 --> 04:41:23.600
Okay, I'll take a look at it. But I'm not promising anything. I haven't made up my mind.

04:41:24.480 --> 04:41:26.480
Together they made their way to the parking lot.

04:41:27.040 --> 04:41:32.720
I don't see any 39 Lissalle, Jesperson said suspiciously. The man was right, the Lissalle

04:41:32.720 --> 04:41:39.920
had disappeared. In its place, Joe saw a fabric top Ford Coupe, a tinny and small car, very old,

04:41:39.920 --> 04:41:48.000
1929, he guessed. A black 1929 model A Ford, nearly worthless, he could tell that from Jesperson's

04:41:48.000 --> 04:41:54.720
expression. Obviously it was now hopeless. He would never get to Des Moines. And as Runceter

04:41:54.720 --> 04:42:01.360
had pointed out in his TV commercial, this meant death. The same death that had overtaken Wendy and

04:42:01.360 --> 04:42:09.280
Al. It would be only a matter of time. Better he thought to die another way. You, Bick, he thought.

04:42:09.840 --> 04:42:15.520
He opened the door of his Ford and got in. There on the seat beside him rested the bottle, which

04:42:15.520 --> 04:42:22.000
he had received in the mail. He picked it up and discovered something which did not really surprise

04:42:22.000 --> 04:42:30.320
him. The bottle, like the car, had again regressed. Seamless and flat with scratch marks on it.

04:42:30.320 --> 04:42:37.200
The kind of bottle made in a wooden mold, very old indeed. The cap appeared to be handmade.

04:42:37.200 --> 04:42:43.520
A soft tin screw type, dating from the late 19th century. The label too had changed. Holding the

04:42:43.520 --> 04:42:49.600
bottle up, he read the words printed on it. Elixir of Eubick guaranteed to restore lost manliness

04:42:49.600 --> 04:42:55.520
and to banish vapors of all known kinds, as well as to relieve reproductive complaints in both men

04:42:55.520 --> 04:43:04.000
and women. A beneficent aid to mankind when sedulously employed as indicated. And, in smaller

04:43:04.000 --> 04:43:09.520
type, a further inscription he had to squint in order to read the smudged, minute script.

04:43:10.480 --> 04:43:17.200
Don't do it, Joe. There's another way. Keep trying. You'll find it. Lots of luck.

04:43:18.720 --> 04:43:24.160
Ranseter, he realized. Still playing his sadistic cat and mouse games with us,

04:43:24.160 --> 04:43:30.000
goading us into keeping going a little longer, delaying the end as long as possible. God knows why.

04:43:31.120 --> 04:43:36.560
Maybe he thought Ranseter enjoys our torment. But that isn't like him. That's not the Glenn

04:43:36.560 --> 04:43:43.360
Ranseter I knew. However, Joe put the elixir of Eubick bottled down, abandoning the idea of making

04:43:43.360 --> 04:43:50.080
use of it, and wondered what Ranseter's elusive hinted at other way might be.

04:43:53.520 --> 04:43:54.000
11.

04:43:55.920 --> 04:44:00.880
Taken as directed, Eubick provides uninterrupted sleep without mourning after groggyness. You

04:44:00.960 --> 04:44:07.520
awaken fresh, ready to tackle all those little annoying problems facing you. Do not exceed

04:44:07.520 --> 04:44:08.800
recommended dosage.

04:44:10.400 --> 04:44:15.920
Hey, that bottle you have, Jesperson said. He peered into the car, an unusual note in his voice.

04:44:16.720 --> 04:44:22.320
Can I look at it? Joe Chip wordlessly passed the aviator the flat bottle of elixir of Eubick.

04:44:23.040 --> 04:44:28.000
My grandmother used to talk about this, Jesperson said, holding the bottle up to the light.

04:44:28.000 --> 04:44:31.680
Would you get it? They haven't made this since around the time of the Civil War.

04:44:32.560 --> 04:44:39.360
I inherited it, Joe said. You must have. Yeah, you don't see these handmade flasks anymore.

04:44:39.360 --> 04:44:43.920
The company never put out very many of these in the first place. This medicine was invented in

04:44:43.920 --> 04:44:49.600
San Francisco around 1850. Never sold in stores. The customers had to order it made up. It came

04:44:49.600 --> 04:44:54.960
in three strains. This, what you have here, this is the strongest of the three. The I, Joe.

04:44:55.840 --> 04:44:56.640
Do you know what's in this?

04:44:57.600 --> 04:45:03.760
Sure, Joe said. Oil of peppermint, zinc oxide, sodium citrate, charcoal. Let it go,

04:45:03.760 --> 04:45:09.120
Jesperson interrupted. Frowning, he appeared to be busily turning something over in his mind.

04:45:09.120 --> 04:45:12.320
Then, at last, his expression changed. He had come to a decision.

04:45:13.280 --> 04:45:17.600
I'll fly you to Des Moines in exchange for this flask of elixir of Eubick.

04:45:17.600 --> 04:45:20.560
Let's get started. I want to do as much of the flying as possible in daylight.

04:45:21.120 --> 04:45:24.080
He strode away from the twenty-nine-four, taking the bottle with him.

04:45:24.080 --> 04:45:30.240
Ten minutes later the Curtis Rye biplane had been gassed, the prop manually spun,

04:45:30.240 --> 04:45:36.880
and with Joe Chip and Jesperson aboard, it began weaving an erratic, sloppy path down the runway.

04:45:36.880 --> 04:45:41.360
Bouncing into the air and then collapsing back again, Joe gritted his teeth and hung on.

04:45:41.920 --> 04:45:47.040
We're carrying so much weight, Jesperson said without emotion. He did not seem alarmed.

04:45:47.600 --> 04:45:52.080
The plane at last wobbled up into the air, leaving the runway permanently behind.

04:45:52.560 --> 04:45:56.720
Noisily, it droned over the rooftops of buildings on its way west.

04:45:57.600 --> 04:46:00.480
Joe yelled, How long will it take to get there?

04:46:01.120 --> 04:46:07.200
Depends on how much tailwind we get. Hard to say. Probably around noon tomorrow, if our luck holds

04:46:07.200 --> 04:46:11.600
out. Will you tell me now, Joe yelled, What's in the bottle?

04:46:12.560 --> 04:46:18.000
Gold flakes suspended in a base composed mostly of mineral oil, the pilot yelled back.

04:46:18.880 --> 04:46:20.560
How much gold? Very much!

04:46:21.520 --> 04:46:26.800
Jesperson turned his head and grinned without answering. He did not have to say. It was obvious.

04:46:27.360 --> 04:46:32.320
The old Curtis Rye biplane blurbled on in the general direction of Iowa.

04:46:34.160 --> 04:46:38.400
At three in the afternoon the following day they reached the airfield at Des Moines.

04:46:38.400 --> 04:46:41.920
Having landed the plane, the pilot sauntered off for parts unknown,

04:46:41.920 --> 04:46:46.960
carrying his flask of gold flakes with him. With aching, cramped stiffness,

04:46:46.960 --> 04:46:51.520
Joe climbed from the plane, stood for a time rubbing his numb legs,

04:46:51.520 --> 04:46:56.400
and then unsteadily headed toward the airport office, as little of it as there was.

04:46:57.440 --> 04:47:01.760
Can I use your phone? he asked an elderly rustic official who sat hunched over a

04:47:01.760 --> 04:47:03.760
weather map absorbed in what he was doing.

04:47:04.560 --> 04:47:09.840
If you got a nickel, the official, with a jerk of his cowlick head, indicated the public phone.

04:47:10.640 --> 04:47:15.760
Joe sorted through his money, casting out all the coins which had Runciter's profile on them.

04:47:16.320 --> 04:47:20.960
At last he found an authentic buffalo nickel of the period and laid it before the elderly official.

04:47:22.560 --> 04:47:24.560
The official grunted without looking up.

04:47:25.600 --> 04:47:30.880
Locating the local phone book, Joe extracted from it the number of the simple shepherd mortuary.

04:47:30.880 --> 04:47:34.320
He gave the number to the operator and presently his party responded.

04:47:35.360 --> 04:47:38.640
Simple shepherd mortuary? Mr. Bliss speaking.

04:47:39.520 --> 04:47:44.240
I'm here to attend the services for Glen Runciter, Joe said. Am I too late?

04:47:44.240 --> 04:47:46.080
He prayed silently that he was not.

04:47:46.960 --> 04:47:50.960
Services for Mr. Runciter are in progress right now, Mr. Bliss said.

04:47:52.160 --> 04:47:56.160
Where are you, sir? Would you like us to send a vehicle to fetch you?

04:47:56.160 --> 04:47:58.080
He seemed fussily disapproving.

04:47:58.640 --> 04:48:00.480
I'm at the airport, Joe said.

04:48:00.480 --> 04:48:03.680
You should have arrived earlier, Mr. Bliss chided.

04:48:03.680 --> 04:48:06.400
I doubt very much if you'll be able to attend any of the service.

04:48:07.200 --> 04:48:12.160
However, Mr. Runciter will be lying in state for the balance of today and tomorrow morning.

04:48:12.160 --> 04:48:14.160
Watch for our car, Mr.—

04:48:15.040 --> 04:48:16.080
Chip, Joe said.

04:48:16.800 --> 04:48:19.280
Yes, you have been expected.

04:48:19.280 --> 04:48:22.800
Several of the bereaved have asked that we maintain a vigil for you,

04:48:22.800 --> 04:48:25.200
as well as for Mr. Hammond and a—

04:48:26.160 --> 04:48:26.800
He paused.

04:48:27.360 --> 04:48:29.280
A mis-right. Are they with you?

04:48:30.320 --> 04:48:31.440
No, Joe said.

04:48:32.080 --> 04:48:35.920
He hung up, then seated himself on a curved, polished wooden bench,

04:48:35.920 --> 04:48:38.160
where he could watch cars approaching the airport.

04:48:38.880 --> 04:48:42.400
Anyhow, he said to himself, I'm here in time to join the rest of the group.

04:48:42.400 --> 04:48:44.880
They haven't left town yet, and that's what matters.

04:48:45.840 --> 04:48:47.600
The elderly official called.

04:48:47.600 --> 04:48:49.360
Mr.—come over here, sec.

04:48:50.160 --> 04:48:52.160
Getting up, Joe crossed the waiting room.

04:48:52.160 --> 04:48:52.640
What's wrong?

04:48:53.520 --> 04:48:55.360
This nickel you gave me.

04:48:55.920 --> 04:48:58.160
The official had been scrutinizing it all this time.

04:48:59.600 --> 04:49:01.840
It's a buffalo nickel, Joe said.

04:49:01.840 --> 04:49:03.520
Isn't that the right coin for this period?

04:49:04.240 --> 04:49:07.200
This nickel is dated 1940.

04:49:07.760 --> 04:49:10.400
The elderly official eyed him, unblinkingly.

04:49:11.520 --> 04:49:15.840
With a groan, Joe got out his remaining coins, again sorted among them.

04:49:15.840 --> 04:49:20.000
At last he found a 1938 nickel and tossed it down before the official.

04:49:20.880 --> 04:49:22.720
Keep them both, he said.

04:49:23.600 --> 04:49:26.640
And once more seated himself on the polished curved bench.

04:49:27.520 --> 04:49:31.040
When he'd get counterfeit money every now and then, the official said.

04:49:31.920 --> 04:49:32.800
Joe said nothing.

04:49:33.280 --> 04:49:35.760
He turned his attention to the semi-high boy,

04:49:35.760 --> 04:49:39.680
Odiolla Radio, playing by itself off in a corner of the waiting room.

04:49:39.680 --> 04:49:42.880
The announcer was plugging a toothpaste called Ipana.

04:49:43.680 --> 04:49:46.880
I wonder how long I'm going to have to wait here, Joe asked himself.

04:49:46.880 --> 04:49:51.040
It made him nervous now that he had come so close physically to the inertials.

04:49:51.040 --> 04:49:54.480
I'd hate to make it this far, he thought, within a few miles, and then—

04:49:55.520 --> 04:49:58.480
He stopped his thoughts at that point, then simply sat.

04:49:58.720 --> 04:50:05.840
Half an hour later, in 1930, Willis Knight, 87, putt-putted onto the airfield's parking lot,

04:50:05.840 --> 04:50:10.640
a hempen, homespun individual wearing a conspicuously black suit,

04:50:10.640 --> 04:50:15.040
emerged and shaded his eyes with the flat of his hand in order to see into the waiting room.

04:50:15.840 --> 04:50:16.720
Joe approached him.

04:50:17.360 --> 04:50:18.800
Are you Mr. Bliss, he asked?

04:50:19.600 --> 04:50:20.320
Certainly I am.

04:50:20.960 --> 04:50:26.080
Bliss briefly shook hands with him, meanwhile emitting a strong smell of sen-sen,

04:50:26.080 --> 04:50:29.600
then got back at once into the Willis Knight and restarted the motor.

04:50:29.600 --> 04:50:31.600
Come along, Mr. Chair, please hurry.

04:50:31.600 --> 04:50:34.480
We may still be able to attend a part of the service.

04:50:34.480 --> 04:50:39.600
Father Abernathy generally speaks quite a while on such important occasions as this.

04:50:40.640 --> 04:50:43.200
Joe got into the front seat beside Mr. Bliss.

04:50:43.200 --> 04:50:47.120
A moment later they clanked onto the road leading to downtown Des Moines,

04:50:47.120 --> 04:50:51.120
rushing along at speeds sometimes reaching forty miles an hour.

04:50:52.240 --> 04:50:54.480
You're an employee of Mr. Rancis, sir?

04:50:54.480 --> 04:50:55.520
Bliss asked.

04:50:55.520 --> 04:50:56.480
Right, Joe said.

04:50:57.360 --> 04:51:03.360
Unusual line of business that Mr. Rancis was in, and I'm not quite sure I understand it.

04:51:04.240 --> 04:51:08.080
Bliss honked at a red setter which adventured onto the asphalt pavement,

04:51:08.080 --> 04:51:11.440
the dog retreated giving the Willis Knight its pompous right of way.

04:51:12.080 --> 04:51:14.400
What does psionic mean?

04:51:14.400 --> 04:51:17.280
Several of Mr. Rancis's employees have used the term.

04:51:18.000 --> 04:51:20.400
Parapsychological powers, Joe said.

04:51:20.960 --> 04:51:25.600
Mental force operating directly without any intervening physical agency.

04:51:26.400 --> 04:51:28.240
Mystical powers, you mean?

04:51:28.240 --> 04:51:29.680
Like knowing the future?

04:51:30.400 --> 04:51:35.680
The reason I ask that is that several of you people have talked about the futures if it already exists.

04:51:36.640 --> 04:51:37.520
Not to me.

04:51:37.520 --> 04:51:42.800
They didn't say anything about it except to each other, but I overheard, you know, how it is.

04:51:43.760 --> 04:51:46.480
Are you people mediums?

04:51:46.480 --> 04:51:47.120
Is that it?

04:51:48.080 --> 04:51:49.440
In a manner of speaking,

04:51:50.000 --> 04:51:52.080
what do you foresee about the war in Europe?

04:51:52.880 --> 04:51:59.200
Joe said Germany and Japan will lose, the United States will get into it on December 7, 1941.

04:52:00.000 --> 04:52:03.360
He lapsed into silence then, not feeling inclined to discuss it.

04:52:03.360 --> 04:52:06.320
He had his own problems to occupy his attention.

04:52:07.280 --> 04:52:09.920
I must shriner myself, Bliss said.

04:52:11.520 --> 04:52:14.320
What is the rest of the group experiencing, Joe wondered?

04:52:14.960 --> 04:52:18.400
This reality, the United States of 1939?

04:52:18.400 --> 04:52:23.520
Or when I rejoin them, will my regression be reversed, placing me at a later period?

04:52:23.520 --> 04:52:24.320
Good question.

04:52:25.120 --> 04:52:30.800
Because collectively they would have to find their way back 53 years to the reasonable and

04:52:30.800 --> 04:52:34.720
proper form constituents of contemporary unregressed time.

04:52:35.600 --> 04:52:39.760
If the group as a whole had experienced the same amount of regression as he had,

04:52:40.560 --> 04:52:44.720
then his joining them would not help him or them, except in one regard.

04:52:44.720 --> 04:52:48.000
He might be spared the ordeal of undergoing further world decay.

04:52:48.880 --> 04:52:53.120
On the other hand, this reality of 1939 seemed fairly stable.

04:52:53.120 --> 04:52:56.400
In the last 24 hours it had managed to remain virtually constant.

04:52:57.120 --> 04:53:00.640
But he reflected that might be due to my drawing nearer to the group.

04:53:01.760 --> 04:53:06.320
On the other hand, the 1939 jar of ubiquid liver and kidney bomb had reverted back an

04:53:06.320 --> 04:53:13.520
additional 80 odd years from a spray can to jar to wooden mold bottle within a few hours.

04:53:14.480 --> 04:53:19.520
Like the 1908 cage elevator which Al alone had seen, but that wasn't so.

04:53:20.320 --> 04:53:24.640
The short fat pilot, Sandy Gispersen, had also seen the wooden mold bottle,

04:53:24.640 --> 04:53:27.440
the elixir of ubiqu as it had become finally.

04:53:28.240 --> 04:53:30.640
This was not a private vision.

04:53:30.640 --> 04:53:33.440
It had, in fact, gotten him here to Des Moines.

04:53:34.240 --> 04:53:37.760
And the pilot had seen the reversion of the Lissal as well.

04:53:38.960 --> 04:53:42.560
Something entirely different had overtaken Al, it would seem.

04:53:42.640 --> 04:53:44.800
At least he hoped so, prayed so.

04:53:46.160 --> 04:53:49.200
Suppose he reflected we can't reverse our regression.

04:53:49.200 --> 04:53:53.040
Suppose we remain here, the balance of our lives.

04:53:55.040 --> 04:53:56.000
Is that so bad?

04:53:56.560 --> 04:54:00.960
We can get used to nine-tube screen-grid high-boy Philco radios,

04:54:01.600 --> 04:54:06.240
although they won't really be necessary in as much as the super-hetrodine circuit has

04:54:06.240 --> 04:54:09.920
already been invented, although I haven't as yet run across one.

04:54:10.640 --> 04:54:14.720
We could learn to drive American Austin motor-cars selling for $445.

04:54:16.080 --> 04:54:21.040
A sum that had popped into his mind seemingly at random, but which he intuited was correct.

04:54:21.840 --> 04:54:25.680
Once we get jobs and earn money of this period, he said to himself,

04:54:26.240 --> 04:54:29.760
we won't be traveling aboard antique Curtis Wright bi-planes.

04:54:30.400 --> 04:54:35.920
After all, four years ago, in 1935, Trans-Pacific Service by four engine China Clippers was

04:54:35.920 --> 04:54:42.960
inaugurated. The Ford Trimotor is an 11-year-old plane by now. To these people it's a relic,

04:54:42.960 --> 04:54:47.040
and the bi-plane I came here on is, even to them, a museum piece.

04:54:48.080 --> 04:54:53.120
That LaSalle I had before it reverted was a considerable piece of machinery. I felt

04:54:53.120 --> 04:54:54.800
real satisfaction driving it.

04:54:55.600 --> 04:55:02.480
What about Russia, Mr. Bliss was asking, in the war? I mean, do we wipe out those reds?

04:55:02.480 --> 04:55:03.680
Can you see that far ahead?

04:55:04.640 --> 04:55:08.640
Joe said, Russia will fight on the same side as the USA.

04:55:09.440 --> 04:55:13.760
And all the other objects and entities and artifacts of this world, he mulled.

04:55:14.560 --> 04:55:21.040
Medicine will be a major drawback. Let's see. Just about now they should be using the Sulfur drugs.

04:55:21.040 --> 04:55:23.200
Well, it's going to be serious for us when we become ill.

04:55:23.920 --> 04:55:27.200
And dental work isn't going to be much fun either.

04:55:27.200 --> 04:55:29.760
They're still working with hot drills and novocaine.

04:55:30.560 --> 04:55:35.040
Fluoride toothpaste's haven't even come into being. That's another 20 years in the future.

04:55:35.680 --> 04:55:41.280
On our side, Bliss sputtered, that communists? That's impossible. They've got that packed with the

04:55:41.280 --> 04:55:48.160
Nazis. Germany will violate that pack, Joe said. Hitler will attack the Soviet Union in June 1941.

04:55:48.160 --> 04:55:49.600
And wipe it out, I hope.

04:55:50.400 --> 04:55:54.720
Startled out of his preoccupations, Joe turned to look closely at Mr. Bliss,

04:55:54.720 --> 04:55:58.480
driving his nine-year-old Willis Knight. Bliss said,

04:55:58.480 --> 04:56:01.520
those communists are the real menace, not the Germans.

04:56:02.080 --> 04:56:07.680
Take the treatment of the Jews. You know who makes a lot out of that Jews in this country.

04:56:07.680 --> 04:56:12.080
A lot of them not citizens, but refugees, living on public welfare.

04:56:12.640 --> 04:56:16.880
I think the Nazis certainly have been a little extreme in some of the things they've done to

04:56:16.880 --> 04:56:24.400
the Jews. But basically, there's been the Jewish question for a long time. And something, although

04:56:24.400 --> 04:56:31.120
maybe not so vile as those concentration camps, had to be done about it. We have a similar problem

04:56:31.120 --> 04:56:35.440
here in the United States, both with Jews and with the niggers. Eventually we're going to have to do

04:56:35.440 --> 04:56:43.200
something about both. I never actually heard the term nigger used, Joe said, and found himself

04:56:43.200 --> 04:56:49.440
appraising this era a little differently all at once. I forgot about this, he realized.

04:56:50.400 --> 04:56:55.360
Lenberg is the one who's right about Germany, Bliss said. Have you ever listened to him speak?

04:56:55.360 --> 04:56:58.560
I don't mean what the newspapers write it up like, but actually,

04:56:59.200 --> 04:57:02.880
he slowed the car to a stop for a semaphore-style stop signal.

04:57:03.600 --> 04:57:08.480
Take Senator Bora and Senator Nye. If it wasn't for them, Roosevelt would be selling

04:57:08.480 --> 04:57:15.680
munitions to England and getting us into a war that's not our war. Roosevelt is so darn interested

04:57:15.680 --> 04:57:20.400
in repealing the arms embargo clause of the neutrality bill, he wants us to get into the war.

04:57:21.040 --> 04:57:25.440
American people aren't going to support him. American people aren't interested in fighting

04:57:25.440 --> 04:57:31.840
England's war or anybody else's war. The signal clanged and a green semaphore swung out.

04:57:32.400 --> 04:57:36.320
Bliss shifted into low gear and the Willis Knight bumbled forward,

04:57:36.320 --> 04:57:39.360
melding with downtown Des Moines midday traffic.

04:57:40.160 --> 04:57:43.440
You're not going to enjoy the next five years, Joe said.

04:57:43.440 --> 04:57:46.960
Why not? The whole state of Iowa is behind me in what I believe.

04:57:47.680 --> 04:57:52.160
You know what I think about you employees at Mr. Runceter? From what you've said and from what

04:57:52.160 --> 04:57:58.480
those others said what I overheard? I think you're professional agitators, Bliss glanced at Joe with

04:57:58.480 --> 04:58:05.440
uncowed bravado. Joe said nothing. He watched the old-time brick and wood and concrete buildings

04:58:05.520 --> 04:58:10.960
go by, the quaint cars, most of which appeared to be black, and wondered if he was the only one

04:58:10.960 --> 04:58:16.160
of the group who had been confronted by this particular aspect of the world of 1939.

04:58:17.360 --> 04:58:22.800
In New York, he told himself it'll be different. This is the Bible Belt, the isolationist Middle

04:58:22.800 --> 04:58:29.280
West. We won't be living here. We'll be on either the East Coast or the West. But instinctively,

04:58:29.280 --> 04:58:33.760
he sensed that a major problem for all of them had exposed itself just now.

04:58:34.560 --> 04:58:41.760
We know too much, he realized, to live comfortably in this time segment. If we had regressed 20 years

04:58:41.760 --> 04:58:48.160
or 30 years, we could probably make the psychological transition. It might not be interesting to once

04:58:48.160 --> 04:58:52.960
more live through the Gemini spacewalks and the creaking first Apollo flights, but at least it

04:58:52.960 --> 04:59:00.400
would be possible. But at this point in time, they're still listening to 10-inch 78 records of

04:59:00.400 --> 04:59:09.280
two black crows and Joe Penner and Mert and Marge. The depression is still going on. In our time,

04:59:09.280 --> 04:59:14.640
we maintain colonies on Mars, on Luna. We're perfecting workable interstellar flight.

04:59:15.440 --> 04:59:21.040
These people have not been able to cope with the dust bowl of Oklahoma. This is a world that lives

04:59:21.040 --> 04:59:26.800
in terms of William Jennings Bryan's oratory. The Scopes Monkey Trial is a vivid reality here.

04:59:27.440 --> 04:59:33.440
He thought, there is no way we can adapt to their viewpoint, their moral, political, sociological

04:59:33.440 --> 04:59:39.760
environment. To them, we're professional agitators, more alien than the Nazis, probably even more

04:59:39.760 --> 04:59:44.240
of a menace than the Communist Party. We're the most dangerous agitators that this time

04:59:44.240 --> 04:59:48.080
segment has yet had to deal with. Bliss is absolutely right.

04:59:49.040 --> 04:59:52.080
Where are you people from? Bliss was asking.

04:59:52.080 --> 04:59:54.400
Not from any part of the United States. Am I correct?

04:59:55.200 --> 04:59:59.040
Joe said, you're correct. We're from the North American Confederation.

05:00:00.080 --> 05:00:03.360
From his pocket, he brought forth a rancidur quarter which he handed to Bliss.

05:00:03.920 --> 05:00:09.360
Be my guest, he said. Glancing at the coin, Bliss gulped and quavered,

05:00:09.360 --> 05:00:15.680
the profile on this coin. This is the deceased. This is Mr. Rancidur. He took another look and

05:00:15.680 --> 05:00:19.600
blanched. And the date? 1990.

05:00:20.640 --> 05:00:23.280
Don't spend it all in one place, Joe said.

05:00:24.800 --> 05:00:28.720
When the Willis Knight reached the simple shepherd mortuary, the surface had already

05:00:28.720 --> 05:00:33.600
ended. On the wide, white, wooden steps of the two-story frame building, a group of people

05:00:33.600 --> 05:00:40.640
stood and Joe recognized all of them. There, at last, they were. Edidorn, Tippi Jackson,

05:00:40.640 --> 05:00:48.080
John Ild, Francie Spanish, Tito Apostos, Don Denny, Sammy Mundo, Fred Zafsky, and Pat.

05:00:49.200 --> 05:00:54.400
My wife, he said to himself, impressed once again by the sight of her, the dramatic dark hair,

05:00:54.400 --> 05:01:00.880
the intense coloring of her eyes and skin, all the powerful contrasts radiating from her.

05:01:02.000 --> 05:01:07.040
No, he said aloud as he stepped from the parked car. She's not my wife. She wiped that out.

05:01:07.840 --> 05:01:14.000
But he remembered she kept the ring, the unique rot-silver and jade wedding ring which she and I

05:01:14.000 --> 05:01:20.320
picked out. That's all that remains. But what a shock to see her again, to regain for an instant

05:01:20.320 --> 05:01:26.640
the ghostly shroud of a marriage that has been abolished, that had in fact never existed,

05:01:26.640 --> 05:01:31.360
except for this ring. And whenever she felt like it, she could obliterate the ring, too.

05:01:32.320 --> 05:01:38.800
Hi, Joe Chip, she said, in her cool, almost mocking voice, her intense eyes fixed on him,

05:01:38.800 --> 05:01:45.440
appraising him. Hello, he said awkwardly. The others greeted him, too, but that did not seem

05:01:45.440 --> 05:01:48.320
so important. Pat had snared his attention.

05:01:49.280 --> 05:01:55.680
No, Al Hammond, Don Denny asked. Joe said, Al's dead. Wendy Wright is dead.

05:01:56.400 --> 05:02:00.080
We know about Wendy, Pat said calmly.

05:02:00.080 --> 05:02:06.080
No, we didn't know, Don Denny said. We assumed, but we weren't sure. I wasn't sure.

05:02:06.720 --> 05:02:09.840
To Joe, he said, what happened to them? What killed them?

05:02:10.720 --> 05:02:12.480
They wore out, Joe said.

05:02:13.200 --> 05:02:17.760
Why? Tito Apostos said, hoarsely crowding into the circle of people surrounding Joe.

05:02:18.400 --> 05:02:24.080
Pat Conley said, Last thing you said to us, Joe Chip, back in New York before you went off with

05:02:24.080 --> 05:02:31.200
Hammond. I know what I said, Joe said. Pat continued, You said something about years. It had been

05:02:31.200 --> 05:02:34.960
too long, you said. What does that mean? Something about time.

05:02:36.080 --> 05:02:42.960
Mr. Chip, Edidorn said agitatedly, Since we came here to this place, this town has radically changed.

05:02:42.960 --> 05:02:46.080
None of us understand it. Do you see what we see?

05:02:46.080 --> 05:02:50.560
With her hand she indicated the mortuary building, then the street and the other buildings.

05:02:51.520 --> 05:02:54.240
I'm not sure, Joe said, What it is you see.

05:02:55.040 --> 05:03:00.160
Come on, ship, Tito Apostos said with anger, Don't mess around. Simply tell us for Christ's sake,

05:03:00.160 --> 05:03:04.400
What this place looks like to you. That vehicle, he gestured toward the Willis Knight.

05:03:04.400 --> 05:03:07.680
You arrived in that. Tell us what it is. Tell us what you arrived in.

05:03:08.480 --> 05:03:11.360
They all waited, all of them, Intently watching, Joe.

05:03:12.560 --> 05:03:19.360
Mr. Chip, Sammy Mundo stammered, That's a real old automobile. That's what it is, right?

05:03:19.360 --> 05:03:22.240
He giggled. How old is it, exactly?

05:03:23.280 --> 05:03:26.880
After pause, Joe said, 62 years old.

05:03:27.600 --> 05:03:31.920
That will make you 1930, tippy Jackson said to Don Denny,

05:03:31.920 --> 05:03:33.760
Which is pretty close to what we figured.

05:03:34.640 --> 05:03:39.600
We figured 1939, Don Denny said to Joe in a level voice,

05:03:39.600 --> 05:03:45.760
A moderate, detached, mature baritone voice, Without undue emotionality,

05:03:45.760 --> 05:03:47.280
Even under these circumstances,

05:03:49.360 --> 05:03:52.160
Joe said, It's fairly easy to establish that.

05:03:52.160 --> 05:03:56.720
I took a look at a newspaper at my con app back in New York, September 12th.

05:03:56.720 --> 05:04:00.400
So today is September 13, 1939.

05:04:01.120 --> 05:04:03.680
The French think they've reached the Siegfried line,

05:04:04.320 --> 05:04:07.680
Which in itself, John Hilt said, Is a million laughs.

05:04:08.720 --> 05:04:13.920
I hoped, Joe said, That you as a group were experiencing a later reality.

05:04:13.920 --> 05:04:16.880
Well, so it goes.

05:04:16.880 --> 05:04:23.200
If it's 1939, it's 1939, Fred Zafke said in a squeaky high-pitched voice.

05:04:23.200 --> 05:04:25.920
Naturally, we all experience it. What else can we do?

05:04:25.920 --> 05:04:28.240
He flacked his long arms energetically,

05:04:28.240 --> 05:04:30.080
Appealing to the others for their agreement.

05:04:30.880 --> 05:04:34.160
Flirt go off, Zafke, Tito Apostos said with annoyance.

05:04:34.960 --> 05:04:37.680
To Pat, Joe Chip said, What do you say about this?

05:04:38.480 --> 05:04:39.360
She shrugged.

05:04:39.360 --> 05:04:41.280
Don't shrug, he said, Answer.

05:04:42.160 --> 05:04:44.400
We've gone back in time, Pat said.

05:04:44.960 --> 05:04:46.080
Not really, Joe said.

05:04:46.880 --> 05:04:48.800
Then what have we done, Pat said?

05:04:48.800 --> 05:04:50.400
Gone forward in time, is that it?

05:04:51.280 --> 05:04:52.880
Joe said, We haven't gone anywhere.

05:04:52.880 --> 05:04:54.480
We're where we've always been.

05:04:54.480 --> 05:04:58.080
But for some reason, for one of several possible reasons,

05:04:58.080 --> 05:05:00.160
Reality has receded.

05:05:00.160 --> 05:05:03.680
It's lost its underlying support and its ebb back to previous forms.

05:05:03.680 --> 05:05:07.360
Forms it took 53 years ago. It may regress further.

05:05:08.240 --> 05:05:10.800
I'm more interested at this point in knowing if Runceter has

05:05:10.880 --> 05:05:12.160
manifested himself to you.

05:05:13.040 --> 05:05:16.720
Runceter, Don Denny said this time with undue emotionality,

05:05:16.720 --> 05:05:20.000
is lying inside this building in his casket dead as a herring.

05:05:20.000 --> 05:05:22.320
That's the only manifestation we've had of him.

05:05:22.320 --> 05:05:23.680
And that's the only one we're going to get.

05:05:24.560 --> 05:05:28.240
Does the word Yubic mean anything to you, Mr. Chip?

05:05:28.240 --> 05:05:29.520
Francesca Spanish said.

05:05:30.720 --> 05:05:33.200
It took him a moment to absorb what she had said.

05:05:34.400 --> 05:05:36.320
Jesus Christ, he said then.

05:05:36.320 --> 05:05:40.160
Can't you distinguish manifestations of fancy has dreams?

05:05:40.160 --> 05:05:42.960
Tippie Jackson said. She's always had them.

05:05:42.960 --> 05:05:44.880
Tell me a Yubic dream, Francie.

05:05:45.520 --> 05:05:48.880
To Joe, she said, Francie will not tell you her Yubic dream

05:05:48.880 --> 05:05:50.640
as she calls it. She had it last night.

05:05:51.680 --> 05:05:53.920
I could eat that because that's what it is.

05:05:53.920 --> 05:05:56.000
Francesca Spanish said fiercely.

05:05:56.000 --> 05:05:59.840
She clasped her hands together in a spasm of excited agitation.

05:05:59.840 --> 05:06:04.240
Listen, Mr. Chip, it wasn't like any dream I've ever had before.

05:06:04.240 --> 05:06:09.520
A great hand came down from the sky like the arm and hand of God.

05:06:09.520 --> 05:06:12.400
Enormous the size of a mountain.

05:06:12.400 --> 05:06:15.200
And I knew at the time how important it was.

05:06:15.200 --> 05:06:19.440
The hand was closed, made into a rock like fist.

05:06:19.440 --> 05:06:21.760
And I knew it contained something of value.

05:06:21.760 --> 05:06:26.320
So great that my life and the lives of everyone else on earth

05:06:26.320 --> 05:06:27.520
depended on it.

05:06:27.520 --> 05:06:29.680
And I waited for the fist to open.

05:06:29.680 --> 05:06:31.600
And it did open.

05:06:31.600 --> 05:06:34.000
And I saw what it contained.

05:06:34.640 --> 05:06:36.560
An aerosol spray can.

05:06:36.640 --> 05:06:38.000
Don Denny said dryly.

05:06:38.560 --> 05:06:41.520
On the spray can, Francesca Spanish continued,

05:06:41.520 --> 05:06:45.600
there was one word, great golden letters, glittering,

05:06:45.600 --> 05:06:50.080
golden fire, spelling out Yubic, nothing else.

05:06:50.080 --> 05:06:51.680
Just that strange word.

05:06:52.720 --> 05:06:56.320
And then the hand closed up again around the spray can

05:06:56.320 --> 05:06:58.480
and the hand and arm disappeared,

05:06:58.480 --> 05:07:01.520
drawn back up into a sort of gray overcast.

05:07:02.400 --> 05:07:05.200
Today, before the funeral services, I looked in the dictionary

05:07:05.200 --> 05:07:08.800
and I called the public library, but no one knew that word.

05:07:08.800 --> 05:07:10.640
Or even what language it is.

05:07:10.640 --> 05:07:12.080
And it isn't in the dictionary.

05:07:12.080 --> 05:07:14.480
It isn't English, the librarian told me.

05:07:14.480 --> 05:07:16.720
There's a Latin word very close to it.

05:07:17.280 --> 05:07:18.400
Ubiquay.

05:07:18.400 --> 05:07:20.720
It means everywhere, Joe said.

05:07:21.680 --> 05:07:23.440
Francesca Spanish nodded.

05:07:23.440 --> 05:07:24.800
That's what it means.

05:07:24.800 --> 05:07:26.080
But no Yubic.

05:07:26.080 --> 05:07:28.000
And that's how it was spelled in the dream.

05:07:28.800 --> 05:07:31.200
They're the same word, Joe said, just different spellings.

05:07:31.920 --> 05:07:33.200
How do you know that?

05:07:33.200 --> 05:07:35.040
Pat Conley said, archly.

05:07:35.840 --> 05:07:38.880
Ronseter appeared to me yesterday, Joe said,

05:07:38.880 --> 05:07:41.520
in a tape-TV commercial that he made before his death.

05:07:42.320 --> 05:07:43.600
He did not elaborate.

05:07:43.600 --> 05:07:47.280
It seemed too complex to explain, at least at this particular time.

05:07:48.240 --> 05:07:51.360
You miserable fool, Pat Conley said to him.

05:07:52.080 --> 05:07:55.840
Why, he asked, is that your idea of a manifestation of a dead man?

05:07:56.480 --> 05:07:59.120
You might as well consider letters he wrote before his death

05:07:59.120 --> 05:08:05.360
manifestations, or interoffice memos that he transcribed over the years, or even—

05:08:06.160 --> 05:08:09.360
Joe said, I'm going inside and take a last look at Ronseter.

05:08:10.000 --> 05:08:14.320
He departed from the group, leaving them standing there, and made his way up the wide

05:08:14.320 --> 05:08:18.640
board steps and into the dark, cool interior of the mortuary.

05:08:20.560 --> 05:08:21.200
Emptiness.

05:08:22.320 --> 05:08:27.840
He saw no one, only a large chamber with pew-like rows of seats, and at the far end

05:08:27.920 --> 05:08:29.840
a casket surrounded by flowers.

05:08:30.640 --> 05:08:35.680
Off in a small side room, an old-fashioned reed-pump organ, and a few wooden folding chairs.

05:08:36.240 --> 05:08:41.920
The mortuary smelled of dust and flowers, a sweet stale mixture that repelled him.

05:08:42.880 --> 05:08:48.240
Think of all the Iowans he thought who've embraced eternity in this listless room.

05:08:48.880 --> 05:08:52.480
Varnished floors, handkerchiefs, heavy, dark wool suits,

05:08:53.040 --> 05:08:59.200
everything but pennies placed over the dead eyes, and the organ playing symmetric little hymns.

05:09:00.560 --> 05:09:03.440
He reached the casket, hesitated, then looked down.

05:09:04.800 --> 05:09:11.520
A singed, dehydrated heap of bones lay at one end of the casket, culminating in a paper-like

05:09:11.520 --> 05:09:16.560
skull that leered up at him. The eyes recessed like dried grapes.

05:09:17.280 --> 05:09:22.320
Tatters of cloth with bristle-like woven spines had collected near the tiny body,

05:09:22.320 --> 05:09:28.320
as if blown there by wind, as if the body breathing had cluttered itself with them by its

05:09:28.320 --> 05:09:35.760
wheezing meager processes, inhalation and exhalation, which had now ceased. Nothing stirred.

05:09:36.640 --> 05:09:42.480
The mysterious change which had also degraded Wendy Wright and Al had reached its end.

05:09:43.040 --> 05:09:47.280
Evidently a long time ago, years ago, he thought remembering Wendy.

05:09:48.240 --> 05:09:52.320
Had the others in the group seen this, or had it happened since the services?

05:09:53.600 --> 05:09:59.200
Joe reached out, took hold of the oak lid of the casket, and shut it. The thump of wood

05:09:59.200 --> 05:10:03.760
against wood echoed throughout the empty mortuary, but no one heard it, no one appeared.

05:10:04.960 --> 05:10:09.760
Blinded by tears of fright, he made his way back out of the dust-stricken silent room,

05:10:09.760 --> 05:10:12.240
back into the weak sunlight of late afternoon.

05:10:13.120 --> 05:10:16.960
What's the matter, Don Denney asked him as he rejoined the group?

05:10:16.960 --> 05:10:18.720
Joe said, Nothing.

05:10:19.840 --> 05:10:23.840
You look scared out of your goony wits, Pat Connolly said acutely.

05:10:23.840 --> 05:10:28.080
Nothing! He stared at her with deep infuriated hostility.

05:10:28.880 --> 05:10:33.760
Tippi Jackson said to him, While you were in there, did you by any chance happen to see Edie

05:10:33.760 --> 05:10:38.000
Dorn? She's missing, John Ilde said by way of explanation.

05:10:38.800 --> 05:10:44.480
But she was just out here, Joe protested. All day she's been saying she felt terribly cold and

05:10:44.480 --> 05:10:49.760
tired. Don Denney said, It may be that she went back to the hotel. She said something about it

05:10:49.760 --> 05:10:55.200
earlier, that she wanted to lie down and take a nap right after the services. She's probably all right.

05:10:56.000 --> 05:11:02.720
Joe said, She's probably dead. To all of them, he said, I thought you understood.

05:11:03.440 --> 05:11:08.640
If any one of us gets separated from the group he won't survive, what happened to Wendy and Al

05:11:09.200 --> 05:11:15.040
and Runceter? He broke off. Runceter was killed in the blast, Don Denney said.

05:11:16.000 --> 05:11:22.320
We were all killed in the blast, Joe said. I know that because Runceter told me. He

05:11:22.320 --> 05:11:26.800
wrote it on the wall of the men's room back at our New York offices, and I saw it again on

05:11:26.880 --> 05:11:30.960
what you're saying is insane. Pat Connolly said sharply, interrupting him.

05:11:31.520 --> 05:11:36.080
Is Runceter dead or isn't he? Are we dead or aren't we? First you say one thing,

05:11:36.080 --> 05:11:41.520
then you say another. Can't you be consistent? Try to be consistent, John Ilde put in. The others,

05:11:41.520 --> 05:11:47.600
their faces pinched and creased with worry, nodded in mute agreement. Joe said, I can tell you what

05:11:47.600 --> 05:11:52.240
the graffiti said. I can tell you about the worn out tape recorder, the instructions that came with

05:11:52.720 --> 05:11:57.280
it. I can tell you about Runceter's TV commercial, the note in the carton of cigarettes in Baltimore.

05:11:57.280 --> 05:12:02.160
I can tell you about the label on the flask of elixir of Ubik, but I can't make it all add up.

05:12:03.760 --> 05:12:08.320
In any case, we have to get to your hotel to try to reach Edidorn before she withers away and

05:12:08.320 --> 05:12:14.000
invariably expires. Where can we get a taxi? The Marjory has provided us with a car to use while

05:12:14.000 --> 05:12:19.360
we're here, Don Denney said. That pierced arrow sitting over there, he pointed. They hurried

05:12:19.360 --> 05:12:24.880
toward it. We're not all of us going to be able to fit in, Tippi Jackson said,

05:12:24.880 --> 05:12:28.640
as Don Denney tugged the solid iron door open and got inside.

05:12:29.520 --> 05:12:34.000
Ask Bliss if we can take the Willis Knight, Joe said. He started up the engine of the pierce

05:12:34.000 --> 05:12:38.880
arrow, and as soon as everyone possible had gotten into the car drove out onto the busy

05:12:38.880 --> 05:12:44.320
main street of Des Moines. The Willis Knight followed close behind its horn honking dolefully

05:12:44.320 --> 05:12:45.680
to tell Joe it was there.

05:12:46.640 --> 05:12:49.440
12

05:12:51.520 --> 05:12:57.360
Pop tasty Ubik into your toaster, made only from fresh fruit and healthful all-vegetable

05:12:57.360 --> 05:13:04.320
shortening. Ubik makes breakfast of feast, put zing into your thing, safe when handled as directed.

05:13:06.720 --> 05:13:11.040
One by one, Joe Chip said to himself as he piloted the big car through traffic,

05:13:11.040 --> 05:13:17.600
we're succumbing. Something is wrong with my theory. Edie, by being with the group,

05:13:17.600 --> 05:13:24.720
should have been immune. And I—it should have been me, he thought, sometime during my slow

05:13:24.720 --> 05:13:30.640
flight from New York. What we'll have to do, he said to Don Denney, is make sure that anyone who

05:13:30.640 --> 05:13:36.880
feels tired—that seems to be the first warning—tells the rest of us, and isn't allowed to wander away.

05:13:37.840 --> 05:13:40.240
Twisting round to face those in the back seat, Don said,

05:13:40.800 --> 05:13:44.640
do you all hear that? As soon as any of you feels tired, even a little bit,

05:13:44.640 --> 05:13:48.640
report it to either Mr. Chip or myself. He turned back toward Joe.

05:13:49.200 --> 05:13:50.320
And then what, he asked.

05:13:51.040 --> 05:13:56.720
And then what, Joe? Pat Connolly echoed. What do we do then? Tell us how we do it, Joe, we're listening.

05:13:57.760 --> 05:14:03.200
Joe said to her, it seems strange to me that your talent isn't coming into play.

05:14:03.920 --> 05:14:08.320
This situation appears to me to be made for it. Why can't you go back fifteen minutes and

05:14:08.320 --> 05:14:13.360
compel Edie Dorn not to wander off? Do what you did when I first introduced you to Runceter.

05:14:14.480 --> 05:14:17.680
Gigi Ashwood introduced me to Mr. Runceter, Pat said.

05:14:18.480 --> 05:14:23.600
So, you're not going to do anything, Joe said. Sammy Mundo giggled and said,

05:14:24.320 --> 05:14:30.320
they had a fight last night while we were eating dinner. Ms. Connolly and Ms. Dorn—Ms. Connolly

05:14:30.320 --> 05:14:33.280
doesn't like her. That's why she won't help.

05:14:33.840 --> 05:14:39.040
I like Edie, Pat said. Do you have any reason for not making use of your talent?

05:14:39.040 --> 05:14:43.760
Don Denny asked her. Joe's right. It's very strange and difficult to understand,

05:14:43.760 --> 05:14:46.800
at least for me. Why exactly you don't try to help?

05:14:48.480 --> 05:14:56.160
After pause, Pat said, my talent doesn't work anymore. It hasn't since the bomb blast on Luna.

05:14:56.800 --> 05:15:02.800
Why didn't you say so, Joe said? Pat said, I didn't feel like saying so, goddamn it.

05:15:03.440 --> 05:15:08.720
Why should I volunteer information like that that I can't do anything? I keep trying,

05:15:08.720 --> 05:15:13.840
and it keeps not working. Nothing happens. And it's never been that way before. I've had the

05:15:13.840 --> 05:15:21.200
talent virtually my entire life. When did—? Joe began. With Runceter, Pat said, on Luna,

05:15:21.200 --> 05:15:22.640
right away, before you asked me.

05:15:23.760 --> 05:15:29.360
So you knew that long ago, Joe said. I tried again in New York after you showed up from Zurich,

05:15:29.360 --> 05:15:33.440
and it was obvious that something awful had happened to Wendy, and I've been trying now.

05:15:33.440 --> 05:15:38.480
I started as soon as you said Edie was probably dead. Maybe it's because we're back in this

05:15:38.480 --> 05:15:45.360
archaic time period. Maybe psionic talents don't work in 1939. But that wouldn't explain Luna.

05:15:46.160 --> 05:15:50.080
Unless we had already traveled back here and we didn't realize it.

05:15:51.200 --> 05:15:57.200
She lapsed into brooding, introverted silence. Dolly, she gazed out at the streets of Des Moines,

05:15:57.200 --> 05:16:00.080
the bitter expression on her potent, wild face.

05:16:01.120 --> 05:16:07.200
It fits in, Joe said to himself. Of course, her time-traveling talent no longer functions.

05:16:07.200 --> 05:16:15.200
This is not really 1939, and we are outside of time entirely. This proves that Al was right,

05:16:15.200 --> 05:16:20.640
the graffiti was right. This is half-life, as the couplets told us.

05:16:22.000 --> 05:16:25.200
He did not, however, say this to the others with him in the car.

05:16:25.200 --> 05:16:29.840
Why tell them it's hopeless, he said to himself. They're gonna find it out soon enough.

05:16:30.480 --> 05:16:34.640
The smarter ones, such as Denny, probably understand it already,

05:16:34.640 --> 05:16:38.000
based on what I've said and what they themselves have gone through.

05:16:39.600 --> 05:16:43.760
This really bothers you, Don Denny said to him, that our talent no longer works.

05:16:44.480 --> 05:16:48.320
Sure, he nodded. I hoped it might change the situation.

05:16:49.120 --> 05:16:56.400
There's more, Denny said with acute intuition. I can tell by your—he gestured—tone of voice,

05:16:56.400 --> 05:17:01.360
maybe. Anyhow, I know. This means something. It's important. It tells you something.

05:17:02.400 --> 05:17:07.360
Do I keep going straight here, Joe said, slowing the pierce arrow at an intersection?

05:17:07.840 --> 05:17:14.160
Turn right, Tippi Jackson said. Pat said, you'll see a brick building with a neon sign going up

05:17:14.160 --> 05:17:21.680
and down the Maramonte Hotel, it's called, a terrible place. One bathroom for every two rooms,

05:17:21.680 --> 05:17:28.480
and a tub instead of a shower, and the food—incredible. And the only drink they sell is something

05:17:28.480 --> 05:17:34.720
called knee-high. I like the food, Don Denny said. Genuine cow meat, rather than protein

05:17:34.800 --> 05:17:41.680
synthetics. Authentic salmon. Is your money good? Joe asked. And then he heard a high-pitched wine

05:17:41.680 --> 05:17:45.840
echoing up and down the street behind him. What's that mean? he asked Denny.

05:17:46.480 --> 05:17:53.680
I don't know, Denny said nervously. Sammy Mundo said, as a police siren. You didn't

05:17:53.680 --> 05:17:58.960
give a signal before you turn. How could I, Joe said? There's no lever on the steering column.

05:17:59.440 --> 05:18:05.440
You should have made a hand signal, Sammy said. The siren had become very close now. Joe turning

05:18:05.440 --> 05:18:10.960
his head saw a motorcycle pulling up a breast with him. He slowed the car, uncertain as to what he

05:18:10.960 --> 05:18:18.400
should do. Stop at the curb, Sammy advised him. Joe stopped the car at the curb. Stepping from

05:18:18.400 --> 05:18:24.480
his motorcycle, the cop strolled up to Joe, a young rat-faced man with hard, large eyes.

05:18:25.200 --> 05:18:28.960
He studied, Joe, and then said, Let me see your license, Mr.

05:18:30.000 --> 05:18:35.520
I don't have one, Joe said. Make out the ticket and let us go. He could see the hotel now. To

05:18:35.520 --> 05:18:41.200
Don Denny, he said, You better get over there, you and everyone else. The Willis night continued on

05:18:41.200 --> 05:18:46.160
toward it. Don Denny, Pat, Sammy Mundo, and Tippi Jackson abandoned the car. They trotted

05:18:46.160 --> 05:18:50.560
after the Willis night, which had begun to slow to a stop across from the hotel,

05:18:50.560 --> 05:18:56.880
leaving Joe to face the cop alone. The cop said to Joe, Yemeni, on identification,

05:18:57.520 --> 05:19:03.520
Joe handed him his wallet. With a purple indelible pencil, the cop rode out a ticket, tore it from

05:19:03.520 --> 05:19:09.440
his pad, and passed it to Joe. Earlier the signal, no operator's license, the citation tells where

05:19:09.440 --> 05:19:15.360
and when to appear. The cop slapped his ticket book shut, handed Joe his wallet, then sauntered back

05:19:15.360 --> 05:19:20.880
to his motorcycle. He revved up his motor and then zoomed out into traffic without looking back.

05:19:22.720 --> 05:19:28.160
For some obscure reason, Joe glanced over the citation before putting it away in his pocket

05:19:29.120 --> 05:19:36.320
and read it once again slowly. In purple indelible pencil, the familiar scrolled handwriting said,

05:19:37.200 --> 05:19:43.120
You are in much greater danger than I thought. What Pat Connolly said is,

05:19:43.440 --> 05:19:49.520
There the message ceased in the middle of a sentence. He wondered how it would have continued.

05:19:49.520 --> 05:19:54.880
Was there anything more on the citation? He turned it over, found nothing, returned again to the front

05:19:54.880 --> 05:20:01.680
side. No further handwriting. But in squirrel agate type at the bottom of the slip of paper,

05:20:01.680 --> 05:20:07.840
the following inscription, Try Archer's Drugstore for Reliable Household Remedies and Medicinal

05:20:08.800 --> 05:20:12.880
Preparations of Tried and Tested Value, Economically Priced.

05:20:14.000 --> 05:20:18.240
Not much to go on, Joe reflected, but still not what should have appeared at the bottom of

05:20:18.240 --> 05:20:23.760
a demoing traffic citation. It was clearly another manifestation, as was the purple handwriting above

05:20:23.760 --> 05:20:29.120
it. Getting out of the pier, Saron, he entered the nearest store of magazine, candy, and tobacco

05:20:29.120 --> 05:20:34.160
supply shop. May I use your phone book? He asked the broad-beamed middle-aged proprietor.

05:20:34.880 --> 05:20:38.560
In the rear, the proprietor said amably with a jerk of his heavy thumb.

05:20:39.360 --> 05:20:44.000
Joe found the phone book, and in the dim recesses of the dark little store looked up Archer's

05:20:44.000 --> 05:20:48.960
drugstore. He could not find it listed. Closing the phone book, he approached the proprietor,

05:20:48.960 --> 05:20:53.040
who at the moment was engaged in selling a roll of necko wafers to a boy.

05:20:53.920 --> 05:20:57.040
Do you know where I can find Archer's drugstore? Joe asked him.

05:20:57.680 --> 05:21:03.680
Nowhere, the proprietor said. At least not any more? Why not? It's been close for years.

05:21:04.320 --> 05:21:09.760
Joe said, tell me where it was. Anyhow, draw me a map.

05:21:09.760 --> 05:21:14.080
Oh, you don't need a map. I can tell you where it was. The big man leaned forward, pointing

05:21:14.080 --> 05:21:19.280
out the door of his shop. You see that barber pole there? Go over there, and then look north.

05:21:19.840 --> 05:21:26.080
That's north, he indicated the direction. You'll see an old building with gables, yellow in color.

05:21:26.080 --> 05:21:32.240
There's a couple of apartments over it still being used, but the store premises downstairs,

05:21:32.240 --> 05:21:37.120
they're abandoned. You'll be able to make out the sign, though, Archer's drugstore, so you'll

05:21:37.120 --> 05:21:43.360
know when you've found it. What happened is that Ed Archer came down with throat cancer and

05:21:43.360 --> 05:21:48.800
thanks, Joe said, and started out of the store back into the pale mid-afternoon sunlight.

05:21:48.800 --> 05:21:53.440
He walked rapidly across the street to the barber pole, and from that position looked new north.

05:21:54.160 --> 05:21:58.400
He could see the tall, peeling yellow building at the periphery of his range of vision,

05:21:59.200 --> 05:22:06.560
but something about it struck him as strange, a shimmer, an unsteadiness, as if the building

05:22:06.560 --> 05:22:12.960
faded forward into stability and then retreated into insubstantial uncertainty. An oscillation,

05:22:12.960 --> 05:22:19.360
each phase lasting a few seconds, and then blurring off into its opposite, a fairly regular

05:22:19.360 --> 05:22:26.000
variability, as if an organic pulsation underlay the structure, as if he thought it's alive.

05:22:26.080 --> 05:22:32.720
Maybe he thought I've come to the end. He began to walk toward the abandoned drugstore,

05:22:32.720 --> 05:22:39.360
not taking his eyes from it. He watched it pulse. He watched it change between its two states,

05:22:39.360 --> 05:22:43.920
and then as he got closer and closer to it, he discerned the nature of its alternate conditions.

05:22:44.640 --> 05:22:50.640
At the amplitude of greater stability, it became a retail home art outlet of his own time period,

05:22:50.640 --> 05:22:56.000
homeostatic in operation, a self-service enterprise selling 10,000 commodities for the

05:22:56.000 --> 05:23:01.600
modern conapt. He had patronized such highly functional computer-controlled pseudo-merchants

05:23:01.600 --> 05:23:08.880
throughout his adult life, and at the amplitude of insubstantiality, it resolved itself into a tiny

05:23:08.880 --> 05:23:16.720
anachronistic drugstore with rococo ornamentation. In its meager window displays, he saw hernia

05:23:16.720 --> 05:23:23.840
belts, rows of corrective eyeglasses, a mortar and pestle, jars of assorted tablets, a hand-printed

05:23:23.840 --> 05:23:31.200
sign reading leeches, huge glass-stopper bottles that contained a Pandora's heritage of patent

05:23:31.200 --> 05:23:37.680
medicines and placebo, and painted on a flat wood board running across the top of the windows,

05:23:37.680 --> 05:23:46.000
the words, archers, drugstore. No sign, whatever, of an empty, abandoned, closed-up store.

05:23:46.080 --> 05:23:55.520
Its 1939 stage had somehow been excluded. He thought, so, in entering it, I either revert

05:23:55.520 --> 05:24:04.480
further, or I find myself back roughly in my own time. And it's the further reversion, the pre-1939

05:24:04.480 --> 05:24:11.040
phase that I evidently need. Presently he stood before it, experiencing physically the tidal

05:24:11.040 --> 05:24:15.600
tug of the amplitudes. He felt himself drawn back, then ahead, then back again.

05:24:16.160 --> 05:24:21.680
Pedestrians clumped by, taking no notice. Obviously none of them saw what he saw.

05:24:21.680 --> 05:24:28.480
They perceived neither archers, drugstore, nor the 1992 home art outlet. That mystified him most of all.

05:24:29.600 --> 05:24:35.280
As the structure swung directly into its ancient phase, he stepped forward, crossed the threshold,

05:24:35.280 --> 05:24:40.880
and entered archers drugstore. To the right, a long marble-topped counter.

05:24:40.880 --> 05:24:46.800
Boxes on the shelves, dingy in color. The whole store had a black quality to it. Not merely in

05:24:46.800 --> 05:24:52.400
regard to the absence of light, but rather a protective coloration, as if it had been constructed

05:24:52.400 --> 05:24:59.920
to blend, to merge with shadows, to be, at all times, opaque. It had a heavy, dense quality.

05:24:59.920 --> 05:25:04.880
It pulled him down, weighing on him like something installed permanently on his back.

05:25:05.760 --> 05:25:10.720
And it had ceased to oscillate. At least for him, now that he had entered it.

05:25:10.720 --> 05:25:15.920
He wondered if he had made the right choice. Now, too late, he considered the alternative,

05:25:15.920 --> 05:25:22.080
what it might have meant, a return possibly to his own time. Out of this devolved world of

05:25:22.080 --> 05:25:27.520
constantly declining, time-binding capacity. Out, perhaps, forever.

05:25:28.480 --> 05:25:34.720
Well, he thought so it goes. He wandered about the drugstore, observing the brass and the wood,

05:25:34.720 --> 05:25:39.040
evidently walnut. He came at last to the prescription window at the rear.

05:25:39.840 --> 05:25:46.400
A wispy young man wearing a gray, many-button suit with vest appeared, and silently confronted him.

05:25:47.040 --> 05:25:50.880
For a long time, Joe and the man looked at each other, neither speaking.

05:25:50.880 --> 05:25:55.600
The only sound came from a wall-clock with Latin numerals on its round face.

05:25:55.600 --> 05:26:01.680
Its pendulum ticked back and forth inexorably, after the fashion of clocks everywhere.

05:26:03.040 --> 05:26:06.320
Joe said, I'd like a jar of ubeck.

05:26:07.840 --> 05:26:13.680
The sal, the drugist said. His lips did not seem properly synchronized with his words.

05:26:13.680 --> 05:26:16.720
First Joe saw the man's mouth open, the lips move,

05:26:16.720 --> 05:26:19.440
and then after a measurable interval he heard the words.

05:26:20.320 --> 05:26:24.000
Is it a sal, Joe said? I thought it was for internal use.

05:26:24.240 --> 05:26:30.000
The drugist did not respond for an interval, as if a golf separated the two of them an epoch of time.

05:26:30.000 --> 05:26:36.320
Then at last his mouth again opened, his lips again moved, and presently Joe heard words.

05:26:37.200 --> 05:26:41.760
Ubeck has undergone many alterations as the manufacturer has improved it.

05:26:41.760 --> 05:26:44.800
You may be familiar with the old ubeck rather than the new.

05:26:45.600 --> 05:26:49.920
The drugist turned to one side, and his movement had a stop-action quality. He

05:26:50.560 --> 05:26:56.560
flowed in a slow measured dance-like step, an aesthetically pleasing rhythm, but

05:26:56.560 --> 05:27:02.000
emotionally jolting. We had had a great deal of difficulty obtaining ubeck of late,

05:27:02.000 --> 05:27:07.920
he said, as he flowed back. In his right hand he held a flat-leaded tin, which he placed before

05:27:07.920 --> 05:27:13.520
Joe on the prescription counter. This comes in the form of a powder to which you add coal tar.

05:27:13.520 --> 05:27:18.880
The coal tar comes separate. I can supply that to you at very little cost. The ubeck powder,

05:27:18.880 --> 05:27:25.680
however, is dear, forty dollars. What's in it, Joe asked. The price chilled him.

05:27:26.480 --> 05:27:31.360
That is the manufacturer's secret. Joe picked up the sealed tin and held it to the light.

05:27:32.080 --> 05:27:34.800
Is it all right if I read the label? Of course.

05:27:35.920 --> 05:27:39.760
In the dim light entering from the street he at last managed to make out the printing

05:27:39.760 --> 05:27:45.920
on the label of the tin. It continued the handwritten message on the traffic citation,

05:27:45.920 --> 05:27:49.840
picking up at the exact point at which Runceter's writing had abruptly stopped.

05:27:50.880 --> 05:27:57.360
Absolutely untrue. She did not repeat not try to use her talent following the bomb blast.

05:27:57.360 --> 05:28:04.000
She did not try to restore Wendy Wright or Al Hammond or Edie Dorn. She's lying to you, Joe.

05:28:04.640 --> 05:28:09.440
And that makes me rethink the whole situation. I'll let you know as soon as I come to a conclusion.

05:28:10.240 --> 05:28:12.640
Meanwhile, be very careful.

05:28:14.000 --> 05:28:20.320
By the way, ubeck powder is of universal healing value if directions for use are rigorously and

05:28:20.320 --> 05:28:21.840
conscientiously followed.

05:28:23.440 --> 05:28:27.920
Can I make you out a check? Joe asked the drugist. I don't have forty dollars with me,

05:28:27.920 --> 05:28:32.400
and I need the ubeck badly. It's literally a matter hanging between life and death.

05:28:32.960 --> 05:28:35.280
He reached into his jacket pocket for his checkbook.

05:28:36.160 --> 05:28:40.720
You're not from Des Moines, are you? the drugist said. I can tell by your accent.

05:28:42.000 --> 05:28:47.200
No, I'd have to know you to take a check that large. We've had a whole rash of bad checks

05:28:47.200 --> 05:28:49.920
the last few weeks all by people from out of town.

05:28:50.960 --> 05:28:56.400
Credit card, then? the drugist said. What is a credit card?

05:28:58.320 --> 05:29:04.000
Laying down the tin of ubeck, Joe turned and walked wordlessly out of the drug store onto

05:29:04.000 --> 05:29:08.880
the sidewalk. He crossed the street, starting in the direction of the hotel, then paused to

05:29:08.880 --> 05:29:14.560
look back at the drug store. He saw only a dilapidated yellow building, curtains in its

05:29:14.560 --> 05:29:20.640
upstairs windows, the ground floor boarded up and deserted. Through the spaces between the

05:29:20.640 --> 05:29:25.920
boards he saw a gaping darkness, the cavity of a broken window, without life.

05:29:26.560 --> 05:29:35.520
And that is that, he realized. The opportunity to buy a tin of ubeck powder is gone,

05:29:35.520 --> 05:29:38.320
even if I were to find forty dollars lying on the pavement.

05:29:39.520 --> 05:29:44.720
But he thought I did get the rest of Runciter's warning for what it's worth. It may not even

05:29:44.720 --> 05:29:52.800
be true. It may be only a deformed and misguided opinion by a dying brain, or by a totally dead

05:29:52.880 --> 05:29:59.280
brain, as in the case of the TV commercial. Christ, he said to himself dismally, suppose it is true.

05:30:00.800 --> 05:30:04.400
Persons here and there on the sidewalk stared up, absorbitly, at the sky.

05:30:05.360 --> 05:30:10.880
Noticing them, Joe looked up too. Chilling his eyes against the slanting shafts of sun,

05:30:10.880 --> 05:30:17.120
he distinguished a dot exuding white trails of smoke, a high-flying monoplane industriously

05:30:17.120 --> 05:30:23.520
sky-writing. As he and the other pedestrians watched, the already dissipating streamer spilled

05:30:23.520 --> 05:30:32.320
out a message. Keep the old swisser up, Joe! Easy to say, Joe said to himself, easy enough to

05:30:32.320 --> 05:30:39.200
write out in the form of words. Hunched over with uneasy gloom and the first faint intimations of

05:30:39.200 --> 05:30:43.440
returning terror, he shuffled off in the direction of the Maramond Hotel.

05:30:44.160 --> 05:30:49.040
Don Denny met him in the high-ceiling provincial crimson carpeted lobby.

05:30:49.600 --> 05:30:55.440
We found her, he said. It's all over, for her, anyhow, and it wasn't pretty, not pretty at all.

05:30:55.440 --> 05:31:00.720
Now Fred Zafke is gone. I thought it was in the other car, and they thought he went along with us.

05:31:00.720 --> 05:31:04.160
Apparently he didn't get into either car. He must be back at the mortuary.

05:31:04.720 --> 05:31:10.240
It's happening faster now, Joe said. He wondered how much difference Ubeck dangled

05:31:10.240 --> 05:31:15.440
toward them again and again in countless different ways, but always out of reach would have made.

05:31:15.440 --> 05:31:17.600
I guess we'll never know, he decided.

05:31:18.640 --> 05:31:23.360
Can we get a drink here? he asked Don Denny. What about money, mine's worthless.

05:31:24.000 --> 05:31:27.360
The mortuary's paying for everything, Rumseter's instructions to them.

05:31:28.240 --> 05:31:33.360
The Hotel tab, too? It struck him as odd. How had that been managed?

05:31:34.320 --> 05:31:39.040
I want you to look at the citation, he said to Don Denny, while no one else is with us.

05:31:39.600 --> 05:31:43.600
He passed a slip of paper over to him. I have the rest of the message.

05:31:43.600 --> 05:31:49.920
That's where I've been, getting it. Then he read the citation, then re-read it, then slowly

05:31:49.920 --> 05:31:55.440
handed it back to Joe. Rumseter thinks Pat Connolly is lying, he said.

05:31:56.160 --> 05:31:56.960
Yes, Joe said.

05:31:57.920 --> 05:32:03.600
You realize what that would mean? His voice rose sharply. It means she could have nullified all

05:32:03.600 --> 05:32:06.480
this, everything that's happened to her, starting with Rumseter's death.

05:32:07.280 --> 05:32:09.840
Joe said it could mean more than that.

05:32:10.880 --> 05:32:17.600
Eyeing him, Denny said, you're right. Yes, you're absolutely right. He looked startled,

05:32:17.600 --> 05:32:23.680
and then acutely responsive, awareness glittered in his face of an unhappy, stricken kind.

05:32:25.120 --> 05:32:30.560
I don't particularly like thinking about it, Joe said. I don't like anything about it. It's

05:32:30.560 --> 05:32:35.520
worse, a lot worse than what I thought before, what Al Hammond believed, for example, which was

05:32:35.520 --> 05:32:42.160
bad enough. But this could be it, Denny said. Throughout all that's been happening, Joe said,

05:32:42.160 --> 05:32:46.000
I've kept trying to understand why. I was sure if I knew why.

05:32:47.200 --> 05:32:52.480
But Al never thought of this, he said to himself. Both of us let it drop out of our minds for good

05:32:52.480 --> 05:32:59.520
reason. Denny said, don't say anything to the rest of them. This may not be true, and even if it is,

05:32:59.520 --> 05:33:01.040
knowing it, isn't going to help them.

05:33:01.680 --> 05:33:07.440
Knowing what? Pat Conley said from behind them. What isn't going to help them?

05:33:08.240 --> 05:33:11.840
She came around in front of them now, her black, color-saturated eyes,

05:33:11.840 --> 05:33:14.240
wise and calm, serenely calm.

05:33:15.680 --> 05:33:21.920
It's a shame about Edie Dorn, she said, and Fred Zafsky, I guess he's gone, too.

05:33:22.800 --> 05:33:27.680
That doesn't really leave very many of us, does it? I wonder who'll be next?

05:33:28.640 --> 05:33:31.840
She seemed undisturbed, totally in control of herself.

05:33:32.720 --> 05:33:38.480
Tippi is lying down in her room. She didn't say she felt tired, but I think we must assume she is,

05:33:38.480 --> 05:33:42.080
don't you agree? After a pause, Don Denny said,

05:33:43.120 --> 05:33:44.320
Yes, I agree.

05:33:45.440 --> 05:33:49.840
How did you make out with your citation, Joe? Pat said. She held out her hand.

05:33:50.480 --> 05:33:56.960
Can I take a look at it? Joe passed it to her. The moment he thought has come.

05:33:58.080 --> 05:34:02.960
Everything is now rolled up into the present into one instant.

05:34:04.720 --> 05:34:09.360
How did the policeman know my name? Pat asked. After she had glanced over it,

05:34:09.360 --> 05:34:13.760
she raised her eyes, looked intently at Joe, and then at Don Denny.

05:34:14.560 --> 05:34:16.480
Why is there something here about me?

05:34:18.320 --> 05:34:21.360
She doesn't recognize the writing, Joe said to himself,

05:34:21.360 --> 05:34:24.240
because she's not familiar with it, as the rest of us are.

05:34:24.400 --> 05:34:27.040
Runceter, he said.

05:34:28.160 --> 05:34:33.600
You're doing it, aren't you, Pat? He said. It's you, your talent. We're here because of you.

05:34:34.560 --> 05:34:39.120
And you're killing us off, Don Denny said to her, one by one. But why?

05:34:40.000 --> 05:34:43.600
To Joe, he said, what reason could she have? She doesn't even know us, not really.

05:34:44.640 --> 05:34:50.320
Is this why you came to Runceter Associates? Joe asked her. He tried but failed to keep his voice

05:34:50.400 --> 05:34:54.640
steady. In his ears, it wavered and he felt abrupt contempt for himself.

05:34:55.440 --> 05:35:00.640
Gigi Ashwood scouted you and brought you in. Was he working for Hollis? Is that it?

05:35:01.200 --> 05:35:07.760
Is that what really happened to us? Not the bomb blast, but you? Pat smiled.

05:35:09.040 --> 05:35:12.400
And the lobby of the hotel blew up in Joe Chip's face.

05:35:15.840 --> 05:35:16.400
Thirteen.

05:35:17.360 --> 05:35:23.040
Lift your arms and be all at once curvier. New extra-gentle

05:35:23.040 --> 05:35:30.080
UBIC bra and long-line UBIC special bra mean lift your arms and be all at once curvier.

05:35:30.080 --> 05:35:35.840
Supplies firm, relaxing support to bosom all day long, when fitted as directed.

05:35:38.560 --> 05:35:44.240
Darkness hummed about him, clinging to him like coagulated damp warm wool.

05:35:45.200 --> 05:35:50.400
The terror he had felt as intimation fused with the darkness became whole and real.

05:35:51.120 --> 05:35:57.440
I wasn't careful, he realized. I didn't do what Runceter told me to do. I let her see the citation.

05:35:59.360 --> 05:36:03.520
What's the matter, Joe? Don Denney's voice edged with great worry.

05:36:03.520 --> 05:36:11.120
What's wrong? I'm okay. He could see a little now. The darkness had grown horizontal lines of gray,

05:36:11.200 --> 05:36:20.400
as if it had begun to decompose. I just feel tired, he said, and realized how really tired

05:36:20.400 --> 05:36:25.200
his body had become. He could not remember such fatigue never before in his life.

05:36:26.240 --> 05:36:31.920
Don Denney said, Let me help you to a chair. Joe felt his hand clamped over his shoulder.

05:36:31.920 --> 05:36:37.920
He felt Denney guiding him, and this made him afraid this need to be led. He pulled away.

05:36:38.560 --> 05:36:45.520
I'm okay, he repeated. The shape of Denney had started to form near him. He concentrated on it,

05:36:45.520 --> 05:36:50.400
then once again distinguished the turn of the century lobby with its ornate crystal chandelier

05:36:50.400 --> 05:36:58.080
and its complicated yellow light. Let me sit down, he said, and groping found a cane-bottom chair.

05:36:59.200 --> 05:37:02.640
To Pat, Don Denney said harshly, What did you do to him?

05:37:03.600 --> 05:37:10.880
She didn't do anything to me, Joe said, trying to make his voice firm, but it dipped shrilly with

05:37:10.880 --> 05:37:15.680
unnatural overtones as if it speeded up, he thought. High-pitched, not my own.

05:37:16.480 --> 05:37:23.920
That's right, Pat said. I didn't do anything to him or to anybody else. Joe said, I want to

05:37:23.920 --> 05:37:31.840
go upstairs and lie down. I'll get you a room, Don Denney said nervously. He hovered near Joe,

05:37:31.840 --> 05:37:38.400
appearing and then disappearing as the lights of the lobby ebbed. The light waned into dull red,

05:37:38.400 --> 05:37:45.120
then grew stronger, then waned once more. You stay there in that chair, Joe. I'll be right back.

05:37:45.120 --> 05:37:48.400
Denney hurried off in the direction of the desk. Pat remained.

05:37:49.600 --> 05:37:53.360
Anything I can do for you? Pat asked pleasantly.

05:37:54.320 --> 05:38:02.080
No, he said. It took vast effort, saying the word aloud, it clung to the internal cavern lodged

05:38:02.080 --> 05:38:05.440
in his heart, a hollowness which grew with each second.

05:38:08.000 --> 05:38:15.200
Cigarette, maybe, he said, and saying the full sentence exhausted him. He felt his heart labor.

05:38:15.200 --> 05:38:21.200
The difficult beating increased his burden. It was a further weight pressing down on him,

05:38:21.280 --> 05:38:23.200
a huge hand squeezing.

05:38:24.800 --> 05:38:30.720
Do you have one? he said, and managed to look up at her through the smoky red light,

05:38:30.720 --> 05:38:34.160
the fitful flickering glow of an unrobust reality.

05:38:34.960 --> 05:38:39.360
Sorry, Pat said. No, God. Joe said,

05:38:40.800 --> 05:38:43.440
What's the matter with me?

05:38:44.400 --> 05:38:46.640
Cardiac arrest, maybe, Pat said.

05:38:47.840 --> 05:38:54.640
Do you think there's a hotel doctor? He managed to say. I doubt it.

05:38:55.520 --> 05:39:04.080
You won't see. You won't look. Pat said, I think it's merely psychosomatic. You're not really sick.

05:39:04.080 --> 05:39:04.800
You'll recover.

05:39:05.920 --> 05:39:10.720
Returning, Don Denney said, I've got a room for you, Joe, on the second floor, room 203.

05:39:11.440 --> 05:39:17.360
He paused and Joe felt his scrutiny, the concern of his gaze. Joe, you look awful.

05:39:17.920 --> 05:39:23.280
Frail, like you're about to blow away. My God, Joe, you know what you look like.

05:39:23.280 --> 05:39:25.760
You look like Edie Dorn looked when we found her.

05:39:26.400 --> 05:39:33.040
Oh, nothing like that, Pat said. Edie Dorn is dead. Joe isn't dead. Are you, Joe?

05:39:33.120 --> 05:39:40.960
Joe said, I want to go upstairs. I want to lie down.

05:39:42.320 --> 05:39:48.080
Somehow he got to his feet. His heart, thudded, seemed to hesitate to not beat for a moment,

05:39:48.080 --> 05:39:54.640
and then it resumed, slamming like an upright iron ingot, crashing against cement. Each pulse

05:39:54.640 --> 05:40:00.160
of it made his whole body shudder. Where's the elevator? He said.

05:40:00.880 --> 05:40:05.280
I'll lead you over to it, Denney said. Again, his hand clamped over Joe's shoulder.

05:40:05.280 --> 05:40:09.120
You're like a feather, Denney said. What's happening to you, Joe?

05:40:09.120 --> 05:40:11.680
Can you say? Do you know? Try to tell me.

05:40:12.320 --> 05:40:18.400
He doesn't know, Pat said. I think he should have a doctor, Denney said, right away.

05:40:19.440 --> 05:40:26.640
No, Joe said. Lying down will help me, he said to himself. He felt an oceanic pull,

05:40:26.640 --> 05:40:34.000
an enormous tide tugging at him. It urged him to lie down. It compelled him toward one thing

05:40:34.000 --> 05:40:40.560
alone, to stretch out on his back alone, upstairs in his hotel room, where no one could see him.

05:40:41.120 --> 05:40:47.760
I have to get away, he said to himself. I've got to be by myself. Why? he wondered. He did not know.

05:40:47.760 --> 05:40:52.960
It had invaded him as an instinct, non-rational, impossible to understand or explain.

05:40:53.920 --> 05:40:58.080
I'll go get a doctor, Denney said. Pat, you stay here with him. Don't let him out of your sight.

05:40:58.080 --> 05:41:04.720
I'll be back as soon as I can. He started off. Joe dimly saw his retreating form.

05:41:04.720 --> 05:41:12.480
Denney appeared to shrink, to dwindle, and then he was entirely gone. Patricia Conley remained,

05:41:12.480 --> 05:41:17.440
but that did not make him feel less alone. His isolation, in spite of her physical presence,

05:41:17.520 --> 05:41:25.040
had become absolute. Well, Joe, she said, what do you want? What can I do for you? Just name it.

05:41:26.080 --> 05:41:33.040
The elevator, he said. You want me to lead you over to the elevator? I'll be glad to.

05:41:34.000 --> 05:41:38.320
She started off, and as best he could, he followed. It seemed to him that she walked

05:41:38.320 --> 05:41:43.840
unusually fast. She did not wait, and she did not look back. He found it almost impossible to keep

05:41:43.920 --> 05:41:50.960
her in sight. Is it my imagination, he asked himself, that she's moving so rapidly? It must be me.

05:41:51.680 --> 05:41:58.400
I'm slowed down, compressed by gravity. His world had assumed the attribute of pure mass.

05:41:58.400 --> 05:42:04.320
He perceived himself in one mode only, that of an object subjected to the pressure of weight,

05:42:04.320 --> 05:42:09.120
one quality, one attribute, and one experience, inertia.

05:42:10.080 --> 05:42:18.160
Not so fast, he said. He could not see her now. She had lightly trotted beyond his range of vision.

05:42:18.800 --> 05:42:24.000
Standing there, not able to move any farther, he panted. He felt his face drip, and his eyes

05:42:24.000 --> 05:42:31.760
sting from the salty moisture. Wait! he said. Pat reappeared. He distinguished her face as

05:42:31.840 --> 05:42:39.440
she bent to peer at him. Her perfect and tranquil expression, the disinterestedness of her attention,

05:42:39.440 --> 05:42:46.320
its scientific detachment. Want me to wipe your face? She asked. She brought out a handkerchief

05:42:46.320 --> 05:42:50.640
small and dainty and lace edged. She smiled the same smile as before.

05:42:51.920 --> 05:43:00.240
Just get me into the elevator! He compelled his body to move forward one step, two. Now he could

05:43:00.320 --> 05:43:04.560
make out the elevator with several persons waiting for it, the old-fashioned dial above

05:43:04.560 --> 05:43:11.040
the sliding doors with its clock hand, the hand, a baroque needle, wavered between three and four.

05:43:11.040 --> 05:43:16.240
It retired to the left, reaching the three, then wavered between three and two.

05:43:17.040 --> 05:43:22.320
It'll be here in a sec, Pat said. She got her cigarettes and lighter from her purse,

05:43:22.320 --> 05:43:25.920
lit up, exhaled trails of gray smoke from her nostrils.

05:43:26.880 --> 05:43:32.000
It's a very ancient kind of elevator, she said to him, her arms folded sedately.

05:43:32.640 --> 05:43:39.120
You know what I think? I think it's one of those old open iron cages. Do they scare you?

05:43:40.240 --> 05:43:47.360
The needle had passed, too. Now it hovered above one. Then plunge down firmly. The doors slid aside.

05:43:48.480 --> 05:43:53.760
Joe saw the grill of the cage, the latticework. He saw the uniformed attendant seated on a stool,

05:43:53.760 --> 05:43:55.680
his hand on the rotating control.

05:43:56.560 --> 05:44:00.080
Going up, the attendant said. Move to the back, please.

05:44:02.160 --> 05:44:04.960
I'm not going to get into it, Joe said.

05:44:05.680 --> 05:44:11.440
Why not, Pat said? Do you think the cable will break? Is that what frightens you? I can see you're

05:44:11.440 --> 05:44:16.480
frightened. This is what Al saw, he said.

05:44:17.520 --> 05:44:22.160
Well, Joe, Pat said, the only other way up to your room is the stairs,

05:44:22.160 --> 05:44:25.840
and you aren't going to be able to climb stairs, not in your condition.

05:44:27.120 --> 05:44:35.040
I'll go up by the stairs. He started away, seeking to locate the stairs. I can't see,

05:44:35.040 --> 05:44:40.640
he said to himself. I can't find them. The weight on him crushed his lungs, making it difficult and

05:44:40.640 --> 05:44:46.960
painful to breathe. He had to halt, concentrating on, getting air into him, that alone. If it is a

05:44:46.960 --> 05:44:53.120
heart attack, he thought. I can't go up the stairs, if it is. But the longing within him had grown

05:44:53.120 --> 05:44:59.520
even greater. The overpowering need to be alone, locked in an empty room, entirely unwitnessed,

05:44:59.520 --> 05:45:06.640
silent and supine, stretched out, not needing to speak, not needing to move, not required to cope

05:45:06.640 --> 05:45:14.000
with anyone or any problem. And no one will even know where I am, he told himself. That seemed

05:45:14.000 --> 05:45:21.520
unaccountably very important. He wanted to be unknown and invisible, to live unseen. Pat especially,

05:45:21.520 --> 05:45:28.400
he thought, not her. She can't be near me. There we are, Pat said. She guided him, turning him

05:45:28.400 --> 05:45:33.760
slightly to the left. Right in front of you, just take hold of the railing and go bump to

05:45:33.760 --> 05:45:39.600
bump upstairs to bed. See? She ascended skillfully, dancing and twinkling,

05:45:39.600 --> 05:45:43.120
poisoning herself, then scrambling weightlessly to the next step.

05:45:43.120 --> 05:45:45.600
Can you make it? Joe said.

05:45:46.560 --> 05:45:55.840
I don't want you to come with me. Oh, dear! She cluck-clucked with mocked dolefulness,

05:45:55.840 --> 05:46:02.880
her black eyes shone. Are you afraid I'll take advantage of your condition? Do something to

05:46:03.200 --> 05:46:13.440
you, something harmful? No, he shook his head. I just want to be alone.

05:46:14.800 --> 05:46:19.840
Gripping the rail, he managed to pull himself up onto the first step, halting there. He gazed

05:46:19.840 --> 05:46:24.880
up, trying to make out the top of the flight, trying to determine how far away it was, how many

05:46:24.880 --> 05:46:32.160
steps he had left. Mr. Denny asked me to stay with you. I can read to you or get you things.

05:46:32.160 --> 05:46:35.280
I can wait on you. He climbed another step.

05:46:36.160 --> 05:46:43.680
Alone, he gasped. Pat said, may I watch you climb? I'd like to see how long it takes you,

05:46:43.680 --> 05:46:51.200
assuming you make it at all. I'll make it! He placed his foot on the next step, gripped the railing,

05:46:51.200 --> 05:46:56.400
and hoisted himself up. His swollen heart choked off his throat. He shut his eyes and

05:46:56.400 --> 05:47:03.760
wheezed in strangled air. I wonder, Pat said, if this is what Wendy did. She was the first, right?

05:47:04.560 --> 05:47:14.960
Joe gasped. I was in love with her. Oh, I know. Gigi Ashwood told me. He read your mind. Gigi and I

05:47:14.960 --> 05:47:20.640
got to be very good friends. We spent a lot of time together. You might say we had an affair. Yes,

05:47:20.720 --> 05:47:27.600
you could say that. Our theory, Joe said, was right. He took a deeper breath.

05:47:29.120 --> 05:47:35.040
One. He succeeded in saying he ascended another step, and then with tremendous effort another.

05:47:36.080 --> 05:47:44.480
That you and Gigi worked it out with Ray Hollis to infiltrate.

05:47:45.120 --> 05:47:53.520
Quite right, Pat agreed. Our best inersals and Runciter wipe us all out. He made his way up one

05:47:53.520 --> 05:48:02.000
more step. We're not in half-life. We're not— Oh, you can die, Pat said. You're not dead, not you in

05:48:02.000 --> 05:48:08.080
particular, I mean, but you are dying off one by one. But why talk about it? Why bring it up again?

05:48:08.640 --> 05:48:14.320
You said it all a little while ago, and frankly, you bore me going over it again and again.

05:48:14.320 --> 05:48:20.480
You're really a very dull, pedantic person, Joe. Almost as dull as Wendy Wright. You two would have

05:48:20.480 --> 05:48:28.880
made a good pair. That's why Wendy died first, he said, not because she had separated from the group,

05:48:29.440 --> 05:48:37.120
but because— He cringed as the pain in his heart throbbed up violently. He had tried for another

05:48:37.120 --> 05:48:42.000
step, but this time he had missed. He stumbled, then found himself seated, huddled, like—

05:48:42.800 --> 05:48:49.200
Yes, he thought. Wendy, in the closet, huddled like this. Reaching out his hand, he took hold

05:48:49.200 --> 05:48:56.480
of the sleeve of his coat. He tugged. The fabric tore, dried, and starved. The material parted

05:48:56.480 --> 05:49:02.880
like cheap gray paper. It had no strength, like something fashioned by wasps. So there was no

05:49:02.880 --> 05:49:08.400
doubt about it. He would soon be leaving a trail behind him, bits of crumbled cloth, a trail of

05:49:08.400 --> 05:49:15.440
debris leading to a hotel room and yearn for isolation, his last laboured actions governed by

05:49:15.440 --> 05:49:23.280
atropism, an orientation urging him toward death, decay, and non-being. A dismal alchemy controlled

05:49:23.280 --> 05:49:31.040
him, culminating in the grave. He ascended another step. I'm going to make it, he realized. The force

05:49:31.040 --> 05:49:36.720
goading me on is feasting on my body. That's why Wendy and Al and Edie—and undoubtedly,

05:49:36.800 --> 05:49:42.560
Zafsky by now—deteriorated physically as they died, leaving only a discarded husk like

05:49:42.560 --> 05:49:48.800
weightless shell containing nothing, no essence, no juices, no substantial density. The force

05:49:48.800 --> 05:49:54.960
thrust itself against the weight of many gravities, and this is the cost, this using up of the waning

05:49:54.960 --> 05:50:01.520
body. But the body, as a source supply, will be enough to get me up there. A biological necessity

05:50:01.600 --> 05:50:06.800
is at work, and probably at this point not even Pat, who set it into motion, can abort it.

05:50:07.440 --> 05:50:14.160
He wondered how she felt now as she watched him climb. Did she admire him? Did she feel contempt?

05:50:14.720 --> 05:50:19.600
He raised his head, searched for her. He made her out, her vital face, with its several hues.

05:50:20.320 --> 05:50:28.480
Only interest there. No malevolence, a neutral expression. He did not feel surprise. Pat had

05:50:28.480 --> 05:50:33.280
made no move to hinder him and no move to help him. It seemed right, even to him.

05:50:34.400 --> 05:50:36.240
Feel any better? Pat asked.

05:50:37.360 --> 05:50:41.760
No, he said, and getting halfway up lunged onto the next step.

05:50:42.960 --> 05:50:48.960
You look different, not so upset. Joe said, because I can make it. I know that.

05:50:49.680 --> 05:50:51.600
It's not much further, Pat agreed.

05:50:52.160 --> 05:50:59.680
Father, he corrected. You're incredible, so trivial, so small. Even in your own death spasms,

05:51:00.720 --> 05:51:07.680
she corrected herself cat-like and clever. Or what probably seemed subjectively to you

05:51:07.680 --> 05:51:12.800
as death spasms. I shouldn't have used that term, death spasms. It might depress you.

05:51:12.800 --> 05:51:14.480
Try to be optimistic, OK?

05:51:15.360 --> 05:51:19.040
Just tell me, he said. How many steps left?

05:51:20.080 --> 05:51:24.880
Six. She slid away from him, gliding upward, noiselessly, effortlessly.

05:51:25.440 --> 05:51:29.680
No, sorry, ten. Or is it nine? I think it's nine.

05:51:30.800 --> 05:51:37.920
Again he climbed the step, then the next, and the next. He did not talk. He did not even try to see.

05:51:37.920 --> 05:51:44.080
Going by the hardness of the surface against which he rested, he crept snail-like from step to step,

05:51:44.080 --> 05:51:49.520
feeling a kind of skill develop in him, an ability to tell exactly how to exert himself,

05:51:49.520 --> 05:51:52.400
how to use his nearly bankrupt power.

05:51:53.120 --> 05:51:56.160
Almost there, Pat said cheerily from above him.

05:51:56.800 --> 05:52:02.480
What do you have to say, Joe? Any comments on your great climb, the greatest climb in the history of

05:52:02.480 --> 05:52:08.560
man? No, that's not true. Wendy and Al and Edie and Fred Zaske did it before you,

05:52:08.560 --> 05:52:11.840
but this is the only one I've actually watched. Joe said,

05:52:12.640 --> 05:52:19.840
Why me? I want to watch you, Joe, because of your low-class little scheme back in Zurich,

05:52:19.840 --> 05:52:23.840
of having Wendy Wright spend the night with you in your hotel room.

05:52:24.720 --> 05:52:28.320
Now, tonight, this will be different. You'll be alone.

05:52:29.360 --> 05:52:33.360
That night, too, Joe said, I was. Alone.

05:52:34.480 --> 05:52:40.320
Another step. He coughed convulsively, and out of him in drops hurled from his street face

05:52:40.320 --> 05:52:47.680
his remaining capacity expelled itself uselessly. She was there, not in your bed,

05:52:47.680 --> 05:52:52.800
but in the room somewhere. You slept through it, though, Pat laughed.

05:52:53.520 --> 05:52:59.840
I'm trying, Joe said, not to cough. He made it up two more steps and knew that he had almost

05:52:59.840 --> 05:53:04.480
reached the top. How long had he been on the stairs, he wondered, no way for him to tell.

05:53:05.200 --> 05:53:09.280
He discovered then with a shock that he had become cold as well as exhausted.

05:53:09.760 --> 05:53:15.760
When had this happened, he asked himself. Some time in the past it had infiltrated so

05:53:15.760 --> 05:53:22.480
gradually that before now he had not noticed it. Oh, God! he said to himself and shivered frantically.

05:53:22.480 --> 05:53:28.640
His bones seemed almost to quake. Worse than on Luna, far worse. Worse, too, than the chill

05:53:28.640 --> 05:53:32.640
which had hung over his hotel room in Zurich. Those had been harbingers.

05:53:33.360 --> 05:53:37.600
Metabolism, he reflected, is a burning process, an active furnace.

05:53:37.600 --> 05:53:39.840
When it ceases to function, life is over.

05:53:40.400 --> 05:53:46.240
They must be wrong about hell, he said to himself. Hell is cold. Everything there is cold.

05:53:47.040 --> 05:53:54.480
The body means weight and heat. Now, weight is a force which I'm succumbing to, and heat.

05:53:54.480 --> 05:53:59.920
My heat is slipping away, and unless I become reborn it will never return.

05:54:00.560 --> 05:54:06.240
This is the destiny of the universe. So, at least I won't be alone.

05:54:07.280 --> 05:54:13.680
But he felt alone. It's overtaking me too soon, he realized. The proper time hasn't come. Something

05:54:13.680 --> 05:54:20.160
has hurried this up. Some conniving thing has accelerated it out of malice and curiosity.

05:54:20.160 --> 05:54:26.880
A polymorphic, perverse agency which likes to watch an infantile, retarded entity which enjoys

05:54:26.880 --> 05:54:32.400
what's happening. It has crushed me like a bent-legged insect, he said to himself.

05:54:32.400 --> 05:54:37.920
A simple bug which does nothing but hug the earth, which can never fly or escape,

05:54:37.920 --> 05:54:44.560
can only descend step by step into what is deranged and foul. Into the world of the tomb,

05:54:44.560 --> 05:54:51.120
which a perverse entity surrounded by its own filth inhabits. The thing we call Pat.

05:54:51.920 --> 05:54:55.120
Do you have your key? Pat asked, to your room?

05:54:56.000 --> 05:55:01.680
Think how awful you'd feel to get up to the second floor and find you had lost your key

05:55:01.680 --> 05:55:09.200
and couldn't get into your room. I have it! he groped in his pockets. His coat ripped away,

05:55:09.200 --> 05:55:15.040
tattered, and in shreds it fell from him. And from its top pocket the key slid. It fell two steps

05:55:15.040 --> 05:55:21.840
down below him beyond reach. Pat said briskly, I'll get it for you. Daring by him she scooped

05:55:21.840 --> 05:55:27.760
up the key, held it to the light to examine it, then laid it at the top of the flight of stairs

05:55:27.760 --> 05:55:33.280
on the railing. Right up here, she said, well you can reach it when you're through climbing.

05:55:33.280 --> 05:55:40.240
Your reward. The room, I think, is to the left, about four doors down the hall. You'll have to

05:55:40.240 --> 05:55:44.960
move slowly but it'll be a lot easier once you're off the stairs once you don't have to climb.

05:55:45.040 --> 05:55:52.560
I can see, he said, the key and the top. I can see the top of the stairs.

05:55:53.600 --> 05:55:58.960
With both arms grasping the banister he dragged himself upward, ascended three steps in one

05:55:58.960 --> 05:56:05.920
agonizing expenditure of himself. He felt it deplete him. The weight on him grew, the cold

05:56:06.000 --> 05:56:13.120
grew, and the substantiality of himself waned. But he had reached the top.

05:56:14.160 --> 05:56:19.920
Goodbye, Joe. Pat said. She hovered over him kneeling slightly so that he could see her face.

05:56:21.040 --> 05:56:27.760
You don't want Don Denney bursting into you. A doctor won't be able to help you. So I'll tell

05:56:27.760 --> 05:56:33.120
him that I got the hotel people to call a cab and that you're on your way across town to a hospital.

05:56:33.120 --> 05:56:37.360
That way you won't be bothered. You can be entirely by yourself. Do you agree?

05:56:38.480 --> 05:56:46.160
Yes, he said. Here's the key. She pushed the cold metal thing into his hand, closed his fingers about

05:56:46.160 --> 05:56:52.960
it. Keep your chin up, as they say here in 39. Don't take any wooden nickels, they say that too.

05:56:54.320 --> 05:56:59.040
She slipped away then onto her feet. For an instant she stood there scrutinizing him.

05:56:59.520 --> 05:57:03.200
And then she darted off down the hall to the elevator. He saw her press the button.

05:57:03.200 --> 05:57:06.480
Wait. He saw the doors slide open, and then Pat disappeared.

05:57:08.080 --> 05:57:13.120
Gripping the key he rose lurchingly to a crouched position, he balanced himself against the far

05:57:13.120 --> 05:57:18.480
wall of the corridor, then turned to the left and began to walk step by step, still supporting

05:57:18.480 --> 05:57:25.360
himself by means of the wall. Darkness, he thought. It isn't lit. He squeezed his eyes shut,

05:57:25.360 --> 05:57:31.200
opened them, blinked. Sweat from his face still blinded him, still stung. He could not tell if

05:57:31.200 --> 05:57:37.200
the corridor were genuinely dark or whether his power of sight was fading out. By the time he

05:57:37.200 --> 05:57:41.520
reached the first door he had been reduced to crawling. He tilted his head up, sought for

05:57:41.520 --> 05:57:48.320
the number on the door. No, not this one. He crept on. When he found the proper door he had to

05:57:48.320 --> 05:57:54.080
stand direct, propped up to insert the key in the lock. The effort finished him. The key, still in

05:57:54.080 --> 05:57:59.760
his hand, he fell. His head struck the door, and he flopped back onto the dust-choke carpet,

05:57:59.760 --> 05:58:07.200
smelling the odor of age and wear and frigid death. I can't get in the room, he realized.

05:58:07.200 --> 05:58:12.960
I can't stand up any more. But he had to. Out here he could be seen.

05:58:14.000 --> 05:58:19.360
Gripping the knob with both hands he tugged himself onto his feet one more time. He rested

05:58:19.360 --> 05:58:25.440
his weight entirely against the door as he tremblingly poked the key in the direction of the knob and

05:58:25.440 --> 05:58:31.040
the lock. This way, once he had turned the key, the door would fall open and he would be inside.

05:58:31.040 --> 05:58:36.080
And then he thought, if I can close the door after me and if I can get to the bed, it'll be over.

05:58:37.200 --> 05:58:43.840
The lock grated. The metal unit hauled itself back. The door opened and he pitched forward, arms

05:58:43.840 --> 05:58:49.600
extended. The floor rose toward him and he made out shapes in the carpet, swirls and designs,

05:58:49.600 --> 05:58:55.360
and floral entities in red and gold, but worn into roughness and lusterlessness. The colors

05:58:55.360 --> 05:59:00.720
had dimmed, and as he struck the floor feeling little, if any, pain, he thought, this is very

05:59:00.720 --> 05:59:06.720
old, this room. When this place was first built they probably did use an open iron cage for an

05:59:06.720 --> 05:59:12.000
elevator. So I saw the actual elevator, he said to himself, the authentic original one.

05:59:13.920 --> 05:59:21.840
He lay for a time. And then as if called, summoned into motion stirred. He lifted himself up onto

05:59:21.840 --> 05:59:29.760
his knees, placed his hands flat before him. My hands! He thought, good God! Parchment hands,

05:59:29.760 --> 05:59:36.640
yellow and knobby, like the ass of a cooked, dried turkey, bristly skin, not like human skin,

05:59:36.640 --> 05:59:43.360
pin feathers. As if I've devolved back millions of years to something that flies and coasts,

05:59:43.360 --> 05:59:49.920
using its skin as a sail. Opening his eyes he searched for the bed, he strove to identify it,

05:59:49.920 --> 05:59:55.920
the fat, far window, emitting gray light through its web of curtains, a vanity table ugly with

05:59:55.920 --> 06:00:03.760
blank legs, then the bed with brass knobs capping its railed sides, bent and irregular as if years

06:00:03.760 --> 06:00:10.320
of use had twisted the railing's warp of varnished wooden headboards. I want to get on it even so,

06:00:10.320 --> 06:00:15.600
he said to himself. He reached toward it slid and dragged himself farther into the room,

06:00:16.160 --> 06:00:25.360
and saw then a figure seated in an overstuffed chair facing him, a spectator who had made no sound,

06:00:25.360 --> 06:00:27.920
but who now stood up and came rapidly toward him.

06:00:29.040 --> 06:00:30.000
Glenn Runciter.

06:00:31.120 --> 06:00:36.480
I couldn't help you climb the stairs, Runciter said, his heavy face stern. She would have seen me.

06:00:36.480 --> 06:00:40.000
Matter of fact, I was afraid she'd come all the way into the room with you, and then we'd be

06:00:40.000 --> 06:00:45.760
in trouble because she— He broke off, bent and hoisted Joe up to his feet as if Joe had no weight

06:00:45.760 --> 06:00:52.160
left in him, no remaining material constituents. We'll talk about that later. Here. He carried Joe

06:00:52.160 --> 06:00:56.400
under his arm across the room, not to the bed, but to the overstuffed chair in which he himself

06:00:56.400 --> 06:01:01.440
had been sitting. Can you hold on a few seconds longer? Runciter asked. I want to shut and lock

06:01:01.440 --> 06:01:08.000
the door in case she changes her mind. Yes, Joe said. Runciter strode in three big steps to the

06:01:08.000 --> 06:01:13.200
door, slammed it and bolted it, came at once back to Joe. Opening a drawer of the vanity table,

06:01:13.200 --> 06:01:18.320
he hastily brought out a spray can with bright stripes, balloons and lettering, glorifying

06:01:18.320 --> 06:01:23.760
its shiny surfaces. You, Bic, Runciter said, he shook the can mightily, then stood before Joe,

06:01:23.760 --> 06:01:30.720
aiming it at him. Don't thank me for this, he said, and sprayed prolongedly left and right.

06:01:30.720 --> 06:01:35.280
The air flickered and shimmered as if bright particles of light had been released,

06:01:35.360 --> 06:01:42.000
as if the sun's energy sparkled here in this worn out elderly hotel room. Feel better? It

06:01:42.000 --> 06:01:48.320
should work on you right away. You should already be getting a reaction. He eyed Joe with anxiety.

06:01:51.360 --> 06:01:58.560
14. It takes more than a bag to seal in food flavor. It takes UBIC plastic wrap,

06:01:58.560 --> 06:02:05.680
actually four layers in one, keeps freshness in, air and moisture out. Watch this simulated test.

06:02:07.440 --> 06:02:12.000
Do you have a cigarette, Joe said? His voice shook, but not from weariness,

06:02:12.000 --> 06:02:18.480
nor from cold, both had gone. I'm tense, he said to himself, but I'm not dying. That process has

06:02:18.480 --> 06:02:24.960
been stopped by the UBIC spray. As Runciter said it would, he remembered, in his take-TV commercial.

06:02:25.680 --> 06:02:31.120
If I could find it, I would be all right, Runciter promised that. But he thought somberly it took

06:02:31.120 --> 06:02:37.760
a long time, and I almost didn't get to it. No filter tips, Runciter said. They don't have

06:02:37.760 --> 06:02:43.760
filtration devices on their cigarettes, and there's backward no good time, period. He held a pack of

06:02:43.760 --> 06:02:50.800
camels toward Joe. I'll light it for you. He struck a match and extended it. It's fresh, Joe said.

06:02:50.880 --> 06:02:54.960
Oh, hell yes! Christ, I just now bought it downstairs at the tobacco counter.

06:02:55.600 --> 06:03:00.880
We're a long way into this. Well past the stage of clotted milk and stale cigarettes.

06:03:01.440 --> 06:03:05.760
He grinned starkly, his eyes determined and bleak, reflecting no light.

06:03:06.320 --> 06:03:11.680
In it, he said, not out of it. There's a difference. He lit a cigarette for himself, too.

06:03:11.680 --> 06:03:15.440
Leaning back, he smoked in silence, his expression still grim.

06:03:16.240 --> 06:03:21.280
And Joe decided tired, but not the kind of tiredness that he himself had undergone.

06:03:22.160 --> 06:03:28.160
Joe said, Can you help the rest of the group? I have exactly one can of this, you big, most of it.

06:03:28.160 --> 06:03:34.240
I had to use on you. He gestured with resentment, his fingers convulsed in a tremor of unresigned

06:03:34.240 --> 06:03:38.640
anger. My ability to alter things here is limited. I've done what I could.

06:03:39.600 --> 06:03:44.800
His head jerked as he raised his eyes to glare at Joe. I got through to you, all of you, every

06:03:44.800 --> 06:03:50.720
chance I could, every way I could. I did everything that I had the capacity to bring about. Damn little,

06:03:50.720 --> 06:03:55.280
almost nothing. He lapsed then into smoldering, brooding silence.

06:03:56.560 --> 06:04:03.600
The graffiti on the bathroom walls, Joe said. You wrote that we were dead and you were alive.

06:04:03.600 --> 06:04:08.320
I am alive, Runciter rasped. Are we dead, the rest of us?

06:04:09.280 --> 06:04:15.520
After a long pause, Runciter said, Yes. But in the tape-TV commercial,

06:04:15.520 --> 06:04:20.560
that was for the purpose of getting you to fight, to find Ubeck. It made you look and you kept on

06:04:20.560 --> 06:04:26.640
looking too. I kept trying to get it to you, but you know what went wrong. She kept drawing

06:04:26.640 --> 06:04:31.680
everyone into the past. She worked on us all with that talent of hers. Over and over again,

06:04:31.680 --> 06:04:37.680
she regressed it and made it worthless. Runciter added, Except for the fragmentary notes I managed

06:04:37.920 --> 06:04:43.120
to slip to you in conjunction with the stuff. Urgently, he pointed his heavy determined finger

06:04:43.120 --> 06:04:48.000
at Joe, gesturing with vigor. Look what I've been up against. The same thing that got all of you,

06:04:48.000 --> 06:04:53.280
that killed you off one by one. Frankly, it's amazing to me that I was able to do as much as I

06:04:53.280 --> 06:04:59.680
could. Joe said, When did you figure out what was taking place? Did you always know from the start?

06:05:00.720 --> 06:05:07.520
The start, Runciter said, Bitingly. What's that mean? It started months, or maybe even years

06:05:07.520 --> 06:05:13.120
ago. God knows how long Hollis and Mick and Pat Connolly and S. Doe Melopon and G. G. Ash would

06:05:13.120 --> 06:05:18.880
have been hatching it up, working it over and reworking it like Doe. Here's what happened.

06:05:19.680 --> 06:05:25.280
We got lured to Luna. We let Pat Connolly come with us, a woman we didn't know, a talent we

06:05:25.280 --> 06:05:31.360
didn't understand, but possibly even Hollis doesn't understand. An ability, anyhow, connected with

06:05:31.360 --> 06:05:37.680
time reversion, not strictly speaking the ability to travel through time. For instance,

06:05:37.680 --> 06:05:43.760
she can't go into the future. In a certain sense, she can't go into the past either. What she does,

06:05:43.760 --> 06:05:50.160
as near as I can comprehend it, is start a counter process that uncovers the prior stages inherent

06:05:50.160 --> 06:05:56.800
in configurations of matter. But you know that, you and Al figured it out. He ground his teeth

06:05:56.800 --> 06:06:04.240
with wrath. Al Hammond, what a loss. But I couldn't do anything. I couldn't break through then,

06:06:04.240 --> 06:06:12.240
as I've done now. Why were you able to now, Joe asked. Runciter said, Because this is as far back

06:06:12.240 --> 06:06:18.720
as she is able to carry us. Normal forward flow has already resumed. We're again flowing from

06:06:18.720 --> 06:06:24.880
past into present into future. She evidently stretched her ability to its limit. 1939, that's

06:06:24.880 --> 06:06:31.920
the limit. What she's done now is shut off her talent. Why not? She's accomplished what Ray Hollis

06:06:31.920 --> 06:06:38.160
sent her to us to do. How many people have been affected? Just the group of us who were on Luna

06:06:38.160 --> 06:06:44.800
there in that subsurface room. Not even so, were. Pat can circumscribe the range of the field she

06:06:44.800 --> 06:06:50.400
creates. As far as the rest of the world is concerned, a bunch of us took off for Luna and got blown up

06:06:50.400 --> 06:06:57.600
in an accidental explosion. We were put into cold pack by solicitor Stanton Mick, but no contact could

06:06:57.600 --> 06:07:03.520
be established. They didn't get us soon enough. Joe said, Why wouldn't the bomb blast be enough?

06:07:04.480 --> 06:07:12.640
Lifting an eyebrow, Runciter regarded him. Why use Pat Conley at all, Joe said. He sensed,

06:07:12.640 --> 06:07:20.160
even in his weary, shaken state, something wrong. There's no reason for all this reversion, machinery,

06:07:20.240 --> 06:07:25.760
this sinking us into a retrograde time momentum back here to 1939. It serves no purpose.

06:07:26.960 --> 06:07:33.440
That's an interesting point, Runciter said. He nodded slowly, a frown on his rugged, stony face.

06:07:34.240 --> 06:07:39.920
Now I have to think about it. Give me a little while. He walked to the window, stood gazing out

06:07:39.920 --> 06:07:46.720
at the stores across the street. It strikes me, Joe said, that what we appear to be faced with

06:07:46.720 --> 06:07:53.760
is a malignant rather than a purposeful force. Not so much someone trying to kill us or nullify us,

06:07:53.760 --> 06:08:00.000
someone trying to eliminate us from functioning as a prudent organization, but he pondered,

06:08:00.000 --> 06:08:08.880
he almost had it, an irresponsible entity that's enjoying what it's doing to us. The way it's

06:08:08.880 --> 06:08:14.320
killing us off one by one, it doesn't have to prolong all this. That doesn't sound to me like

06:08:14.320 --> 06:08:19.760
Ray Hollis. He deals in cold, practical murder. And from what I know about Stanton, Mick,

06:08:20.480 --> 06:08:24.160
Pat herself, Runciter interrupted brusquely. He turned away from the window.

06:08:24.800 --> 06:08:30.960
She's psychologically a sadistic person, like tearing wings off flies, playing with us.

06:08:31.680 --> 06:08:36.960
He watched for Joe's reaction. Joe said, that sounds to me more like a child.

06:08:36.960 --> 06:08:42.480
But look at Pat Connolly. She's spiteful and jealous. She got windy first because of emotional

06:08:42.480 --> 06:08:48.560
animosity. She followed you all the way up the stairs, just now, enjoying it, gloating over it,

06:08:48.560 --> 06:08:56.000
in fact. How do you know that? Joe said. You were waiting here in this room, he said to himself.

06:08:56.560 --> 06:09:03.760
You couldn't have seen it. And how had Runciter known he would come to this particular room?

06:09:05.760 --> 06:09:08.800
Letting out his breath in a ragged, noisy rush, Runciter said,

06:09:09.760 --> 06:09:14.960
I haven't told you all of it. As a matter of fact, he ceased speaking, chewed his lower lips

06:09:14.960 --> 06:09:21.360
savagely, then abruptly resumed. What I've said hasn't been strictly true. I don't hold the same

06:09:21.360 --> 06:09:26.400
relationship to this regressed world that the rest of you do. You're absolutely right. I know

06:09:26.400 --> 06:09:33.120
too much. It's because I enter it from outside, Joe. Manifestations, Joe said.

06:09:33.120 --> 06:09:40.160
Yeah. Thrust down into this world here and there at strategic points and times, like the traffic

06:09:40.160 --> 06:09:47.440
citation, like archers. You didn't tape that TV commercial, Joe said. That was live. Runciter,

06:09:47.440 --> 06:09:53.040
with reluctance, nodded. Why the difference, Joe said, between your situation and ours?

06:09:53.840 --> 06:09:59.600
You want me to say? Yes. He prepared himself already knowing what he would hear.

06:09:59.840 --> 06:10:07.840
I'm not dead, Joe. The graffiti told the truth. You're all in cold pack and I'm—

06:10:08.720 --> 06:10:11.840
Runciter spoke with difficulty, not looking directly at Joe.

06:10:12.720 --> 06:10:17.280
I'm sitting in a consultation lounge at the beloved Brethren Moratorium.

06:10:18.160 --> 06:10:23.520
All of you are interwired on my instructions, kept together as a group. I'm out here trying to reach

06:10:23.520 --> 06:10:29.520
you. That's where I am when I say I'm outside. That's why the manifestations, as you call them,

06:10:30.000 --> 06:10:34.000
are one week now. I've been trying to get you all functioning in Half-Life, but

06:10:34.640 --> 06:10:37.200
it isn't working. You're fading out one by one.

06:10:38.640 --> 06:10:45.440
After a pause, Joe said, what about Pat Conley? Yeah, she's with you in Half-Life,

06:10:45.440 --> 06:10:51.440
interwired to the rest of the group. Are the regressions due to her talent or to the normal

06:10:51.440 --> 06:10:58.960
decay of Half-Life? Tensely, he waited for Runciter's answer, everything as he saw it hung

06:10:59.040 --> 06:11:07.600
on this one question. Runciter snorted, grimaced, then said hoarsely, the normal decay. Ella

06:11:07.600 --> 06:11:11.200
experienced it. Everyone who enters Half-Life experiences it.

06:11:12.640 --> 06:11:20.960
You're lying to me, Joe said, and felt a knife shear through him. Staring at him, Runciter said,

06:11:20.960 --> 06:11:26.080
Joe, my God, I saved your life. I broke through to you enough just now to bring you back into full

06:11:26.080 --> 06:11:30.960
Half-Life functioning. You'll probably go on indefinitely now. If I hadn't been waiting here

06:11:30.960 --> 06:11:36.560
in this hotel room when you came crawling through that door, why, hell, hey, look,

06:11:36.560 --> 06:11:41.840
goddammit, you'd be lying on that rundown bed dead as a doornail by now if it wasn't for me.

06:11:42.400 --> 06:11:47.280
I'm Glenn Runciter. I'm your boss, and I'm the one fighting to save all your life. I'm the only

06:11:47.280 --> 06:11:54.000
one out here in the real world plugging for you. He continued to stare at Joe with heated indignation

06:11:54.000 --> 06:12:00.480
and surprise, a bewildered, injured surprise as if he could not fathom what was happening.

06:12:00.480 --> 06:12:06.800
That girl, Runciter said, that pat Connolly, she would have killed you like she killed—he broke

06:12:06.800 --> 06:12:15.040
off. Joe said like she killed Wendy and Al, Edie Dorn, Fred Zafsky, and maybe by now Tito Apostos.

06:12:16.320 --> 06:12:23.520
In a low but controlled voice, Runciter said, this situation is very complex, Joe.

06:12:23.520 --> 06:12:25.680
It doesn't admit to simple answers.

06:12:26.800 --> 06:12:33.520
You don't know the answers, Joe said. That's the problem. You made up answers. You had to

06:12:33.520 --> 06:12:39.200
invent them to explain your presence here, all your presences here, your so-called manifestations.

06:12:39.200 --> 06:12:43.680
I don't call them that. You and Al worked out that name. Don't blame me for what you do.

06:12:43.680 --> 06:12:49.040
You don't know any more than I do, Joe said, about what's happening to us and who's attacking us.

06:12:49.680 --> 06:12:53.520
Glenn, you can't say who we're up against because you don't know.

06:12:54.640 --> 06:12:58.880
Runciter said, I know I'm alive. I know I'm sitting out here in this

06:12:58.880 --> 06:13:00.720
consultation lounge at the moratorium.

06:13:01.600 --> 06:13:06.800
Your body in the coffin, Joe said, here at the simple shepherd mortuary. Did you look at it?

06:13:07.360 --> 06:13:10.160
No, Runciter said, but that isn't really—

06:13:10.160 --> 06:13:17.440
It had withered, Joe said, lost bulk, like Wendy's and Al's and Edie's, and in a little wild mine.

06:13:17.440 --> 06:13:19.680
Exactly the same for you. No better, no worse.

06:13:20.640 --> 06:13:22.480
In your case, I got ubiqu.

06:13:23.360 --> 06:13:28.000
Again, Runciter broke off. A difficult to decipher expression appeared on his face.

06:13:28.000 --> 06:13:31.520
A combination, perhaps, of insight, fear, and—

06:13:32.480 --> 06:13:33.680
But Joe couldn't tell.

06:13:34.800 --> 06:13:37.040
I got you the ubiqu. He finished.

06:13:37.920 --> 06:13:42.000
What is ubiqu, Joe said. There was no answer from Runciter.

06:13:42.720 --> 06:13:47.440
You don't know that, either, Joe said. You don't know what it is or why it works.

06:13:47.440 --> 06:13:49.040
You don't even know where it comes from.

06:13:50.800 --> 06:13:53.680
After a long agonized pause, Runciter said,

06:13:54.720 --> 06:13:57.760
You're right, Joe. Absolutely right.

06:13:58.800 --> 06:14:00.720
Fremulously, he lit another cigarette.

06:14:01.680 --> 06:14:04.400
But I wanted to save your life. That part's true.

06:14:05.040 --> 06:14:07.120
Hell, I'd like to save all your lives.

06:14:07.840 --> 06:14:11.360
The cigarette slipped from his fingers. It dropped to the floor, rolled away.

06:14:12.000 --> 06:14:15.600
With labored effort, Runciter bent over to grope for it.

06:14:15.600 --> 06:14:20.240
On his face showed extreme and clear cut on happiness, almost a despair.

06:14:21.680 --> 06:14:26.720
We're in this, Joe said. And you're sitting out there, out in the lounge.

06:14:26.720 --> 06:14:29.920
And you can't do it. You can't put a stop to the thing we're involved in.

06:14:30.560 --> 06:14:32.320
That's right, Runciter nodded.

06:14:33.440 --> 06:14:38.720
This is cold pack, Joe said. But there's something more, something

06:14:38.720 --> 06:14:45.120
not natural to people in half-life. There are two forces at work, as Al figured out.

06:14:45.120 --> 06:14:51.520
One helping us and one destroying us. You're working with the force or entity or person

06:14:51.520 --> 06:14:56.320
that's trying to help us. You got the u-beck from them. Yes. Joe said,

06:14:56.320 --> 06:14:59.840
So none of us know even yet who it is that's destroying us.

06:15:00.480 --> 06:15:05.360
And who it is that's protecting us. You outside don't know, and we in here don't know.

06:15:06.320 --> 06:15:10.400
Maybe it's Pat. I think it is, Runciter said. I think there's your enemy.

06:15:11.120 --> 06:15:18.320
Joe said, Almost. But I don't think so. I don't think he said to himself that we've met our

06:15:18.320 --> 06:15:24.560
enemy face to face, or our friend, either. He thought, But I think we will.

06:15:25.360 --> 06:15:28.080
Before long we will know who they both are.

06:15:28.480 --> 06:15:36.240
Are you sure, he asked Runciter. Absolutely sure that you're beyond out the only one who

06:15:36.240 --> 06:15:43.440
survived the blast. Think before you answer. Like I said, so were of us, Joe said. She's not here

06:15:43.440 --> 06:15:49.280
in this time segment with us. Pat Connelly, for example. Pat Connelly's chest was crushed.

06:15:49.840 --> 06:15:54.560
She died of shock and a collapsed lung with multiple internal injuries, including a damaged

06:15:54.560 --> 06:16:00.080
liver and the leg broken in three places. Physically speaking, she's about four feet away

06:16:00.080 --> 06:16:06.160
from you, her body, I mean. And it's the same for all the rest. They're all here in Colpac at the

06:16:06.160 --> 06:16:14.000
beloved brethren moratorium. Runciter said, With one exception, Sammy Mundo, he suffered massive

06:16:14.000 --> 06:16:19.920
brain damage and lapsed into a coma, out of which they say he'll never emerge, the cortical. Then

06:16:19.920 --> 06:16:27.600
he's alive. He's not in Colpac. He's not here. I wouldn't call it alive. They run encephalograms

06:16:27.600 --> 06:16:34.000
on him. No cortical activity at all. A vegetable, nothing more. No personality, no motion, no

06:16:34.000 --> 06:16:38.240
consciousness. There's nothing happening in Mundo's brain, nothing in the slightest.

06:16:39.280 --> 06:16:46.080
Joe said, So therefore you naturally didn't think to mention it. I mentioned it now. When I asked you,

06:16:46.880 --> 06:16:54.400
he reflected. How far is he from us in Zurich? We sat down here in Zurich. Yes, he's at the Carl

06:16:54.400 --> 06:17:00.720
Young Hospital about a quarter mile from this moratorium. Rent a telepath, Joe said, or use

06:17:00.720 --> 06:17:09.520
G.G. Ashwood, have him scanned. A boy, he said to himself, disorganized and immature, a cruel,

06:17:09.520 --> 06:17:15.520
unformed, peculiar personality. This may be it, he said to himself. It would fit in with what

06:17:15.520 --> 06:17:21.680
we're experiencing, the capricious contradictory happenings, the pulling off of our wings and

06:17:21.680 --> 06:17:27.440
then the putting back, the temporary restorations, as in just now with me here in this hotel room

06:17:27.440 --> 06:17:35.120
after my climb up the stairs. Runs to the side. We did that. In brain injury cases like this,

06:17:35.120 --> 06:17:41.360
it's a regular practice to try to reach the person telepathically. No results, nothing. No frontal lobe

06:17:41.360 --> 06:17:48.560
celebration of any sort. Sorry, Joe. He wagged his massive head in a sympathetic tick-like motion.

06:17:49.120 --> 06:17:56.720
Obviously, he shared Joe's disappointment. Removing the plastic disc from its place, its firm

06:17:56.720 --> 06:18:01.760
adhesion to his ear, Glenn Runceter said into the microphone, I'll talk to you again later.

06:18:02.560 --> 06:18:08.480
He now set down all the communications apparatus, rose stiffly from the chair and momentarily stood

06:18:08.480 --> 06:18:15.440
facing the misty, immobile, ice-bound shape of Joe Chip, resting within its transparent plastic

06:18:15.440 --> 06:18:22.160
casket, upright and silent as it would be for the rest of eternity. Did you ring for me, sir?

06:18:22.720 --> 06:18:26.880
Herbert, show in height one vocal song, scuttled into the consultation lounge,

06:18:26.880 --> 06:18:32.640
cringing like a medieval toadie. Shall I put Mr. Chip back with the others? You're done, sir?

06:18:33.520 --> 06:18:40.960
Runceter said, I'm done. Did you—yes, I got through all right. We could hear each other fine

06:18:40.960 --> 06:18:46.720
this time. He lit a cigarette. It had been hours since he had had one, had found a free moment.

06:18:47.600 --> 06:18:52.000
By now the arduous prolonged task of reaching Joe Chip had depleted him.

06:18:52.880 --> 06:18:58.480
You have an amphetamine dispenser nearby, he asked the moratorium owner. In the whore,

06:18:58.480 --> 06:19:02.240
outside the consultation lounge, the eager to please creature pointed.

06:19:03.040 --> 06:19:07.440
Leaving the lounge, Runceter made his way to the amphetamine dispenser. He inserted a coin,

06:19:07.440 --> 06:19:13.520
pushed the choice lever, and into the drop slot, a small, familiar object slid with a tinkling sound.

06:19:14.640 --> 06:19:19.760
The pill made him feel better, but then he thought about his appointment with Len Niggleman

06:19:19.760 --> 06:19:25.200
two hours from now and wondered if he could really make it. There's been too much going on,

06:19:25.200 --> 06:19:30.880
he decided, I'm not ready to make my formal report to this society. I'll have to vid Niggleman and

06:19:30.880 --> 06:19:36.000
ask for a postponement. Using a payphone, he called Niggleman back in the North American

06:19:36.000 --> 06:19:42.720
Confederation. Len, he said, I can't do any more today. I've spent the last twelve hours trying

06:19:42.720 --> 06:19:47.280
to get through to my people in Colpac, and I'm exhausted. Would tomorrow be okay?

06:19:48.080 --> 06:19:53.840
Niggleman said, the sooner you file your official formal statement with us, the sooner we can begin

06:19:53.840 --> 06:19:58.880
action against Hollis. My legal department says it's over in shot. They're chomping at the bit.

06:19:59.520 --> 06:20:04.640
They think they can make a civil charge stick. Civil and criminal. They've been talking to

06:20:04.640 --> 06:20:08.720
the New York District Attorney, but until you make a formal notarized report to us—

06:20:09.440 --> 06:20:15.600
Tomorrow, Runceter promised, after I get some sleep. This is damn near finished me off.

06:20:16.720 --> 06:20:20.720
This loss of all my best people, he said to himself, especially Joe Chip.

06:20:21.440 --> 06:20:26.720
My organization is depleted, and we won't be able to resume commercial operations for months,

06:20:26.720 --> 06:20:32.400
maybe years. God, he thought, where am I going to get inertials to replace those I've lost,

06:20:32.400 --> 06:20:38.080
and where am I going to find a tester like Joe? Niggleman said, sure, Glenn, get a good night's

06:20:38.080 --> 06:20:42.160
sleep, and then meet me in my office tomorrow, say, at ten o'clock our time.

06:20:42.800 --> 06:20:49.680
Thanks, Runceter said. He rang off, then threw himself heavily down on a pink plastic couch

06:20:49.680 --> 06:20:55.360
across the corridor from the phone. I can't find a tester like Joe, he said to himself.

06:20:56.160 --> 06:21:00.240
The fact of the matter is that Runceter Associates is finished.

06:21:01.600 --> 06:21:06.480
The moratorium owner came in, then, putting in another of his untimely appearances.

06:21:07.040 --> 06:21:12.080
Can I get you anything, Mr. Runceter, a cup of coffee? Another amphetamine? Perhaps a

06:21:12.080 --> 06:21:18.080
twelve-hour spanthule? In my office I have some twenty-four-hour spanthules. One of those would

06:21:18.080 --> 06:21:24.640
get you back up into action for hours, if not all night. All night, Runceter said, I intend to sleep.

06:21:25.280 --> 06:21:32.000
Then how about a flap away, Runceter grated. The moratorium owner scuttled off, leaving him alone.

06:21:32.960 --> 06:21:39.040
Why did I have to pick this place, Runceter asked himself. I guess because Ella's here,

06:21:39.040 --> 06:21:42.880
it is, after all, the best. That's why she's here, and hence why they're all here.

06:21:43.040 --> 06:21:49.760
Think of them, he reflected, so many who were so recently on this side of the casket,

06:21:49.760 --> 06:21:57.280
what a catastrophe. Ella, he said to himself, remembering, I better talk to her again for

06:21:57.280 --> 06:22:02.240
a moment to let her know how things are going. That's after all what I told her I'd do.

06:22:03.440 --> 06:22:06.720
Getting to his feet, he started off in search of the moratorium owner.

06:22:07.680 --> 06:22:11.840
Am I going to get that damn jury this time? He asked himself.

06:22:12.320 --> 06:22:15.840
Will I be able to keep Ella in focus long enough to tell her what Joe said?

06:22:15.840 --> 06:22:22.080
It's become so hard to hang on to her now, with Jory growing and expanding and feeding on her,

06:22:22.080 --> 06:22:27.360
and maybe on others over there in Half-Life. The moratorium should do something about him.

06:22:27.360 --> 06:22:32.320
Jory's a hazard to everyone here. Why did they let him go on? He asked himself.

06:22:33.280 --> 06:22:40.080
He thought, maybe because they can't stop him. Maybe there's never been anyone in Half-Life

06:22:40.080 --> 06:22:45.200
like Jory before. 15.

06:22:47.120 --> 06:22:51.840
Could it be that I have bad breath, Tom? Well, Ed, if you're worried about that,

06:22:51.840 --> 06:22:55.920
try today's new U-BIC with powerful germicidal foaming action,

06:22:55.920 --> 06:22:58.560
guaranteed safe when taken as directed.

06:22:58.800 --> 06:23:01.120
16.

06:23:01.120 --> 06:23:04.480
The door of the ancient hotel room swung open. Don Denny,

06:23:04.480 --> 06:23:09.120
accompanied by a middle-aged, responsible-looking man with neatly trimmed gray hair, entered.

06:23:09.760 --> 06:23:12.880
Denny, his face strained with apprehension, said,

06:23:12.880 --> 06:23:16.640
How are you, Joe? Why aren't you lying down? For Christ's sake, get on to the bed.

06:23:17.440 --> 06:23:22.720
Please lie down, Mr. Chip, the doctor said, as he set his medical bag on the vanity table

06:23:22.720 --> 06:23:28.080
and opened it up. Is there pain along with the innovation and the difficult respiration?

06:23:28.720 --> 06:23:32.800
He approached the bed with an old-fashioned stethoscope and cumbersome blood-pressure

06:23:32.800 --> 06:23:38.400
reading equipment. Do you have any history of cardiac involvement, Mr. Chip, or your

06:23:38.400 --> 06:23:43.360
mother or father? Unbutton your shirt, please. He drew up a wooden chair beside the bed,

06:23:43.360 --> 06:23:48.000
seated himself expectantly on it. Joe said, I'm okay now.

06:23:48.960 --> 06:23:51.440
Let him listen to your heart, Denny said, tersely.

06:23:52.160 --> 06:23:55.920
Okay. Joe stretched out on the bed and unbuttoned his shirt.

06:23:56.720 --> 06:23:59.600
Runseter managed to get through to me, he said to Denny.

06:24:00.240 --> 06:24:04.320
We're in cold pack. He's on the other side, trying to reach us.

06:24:05.120 --> 06:24:11.440
Someone else is trying to injure us. Pat didn't do it, or anyhow, she didn't do it alone. Neither

06:24:11.440 --> 06:24:16.320
she nor Runseter knows what's going on. When you opened the door, did you see Runseter?

06:24:17.040 --> 06:24:21.680
No, Denny said. He was sitting across the room from me, Joe said, two, three minutes ago.

06:24:22.400 --> 06:24:25.440
Sorry, Joe, he said, that was the last thing he said to me.

06:24:26.080 --> 06:24:30.400
And then he cut contact, stopped communicating, just cancelled himself out.

06:24:31.200 --> 06:24:34.000
Look on the vanity table and see if he left the spray can of Eubach.

06:24:34.880 --> 06:24:37.840
Denny searched, then held up the brightly illuminated can.

06:24:38.640 --> 06:24:41.360
Here it is, but it seems empty. Denny shook it.

06:24:42.080 --> 06:24:44.160
Almost empty, Joe said.

06:24:44.800 --> 06:24:48.720
Spray what's left on yourself. Go ahead. He gestured emphatically.

06:24:49.360 --> 06:24:53.520
Don't talk, Mr. Chip, the doctor said, listening to his stethoscope.

06:24:53.520 --> 06:24:57.920
He then rolled up Joe's sleeve and began winding inflatable rubber fabric around

06:24:57.920 --> 06:25:00.240
his arm in preparation for the blood pressure test.

06:25:01.280 --> 06:25:02.880
How's my heart, Joe asked.

06:25:03.440 --> 06:25:07.600
It appears normal, the doctor said, although slightly fast.

06:25:08.320 --> 06:25:10.640
See, Joe said to Don Denny, I've recovered.

06:25:11.440 --> 06:25:14.560
Denny said, the others are dying, Joe.

06:25:15.520 --> 06:25:17.600
Half sitting up, Joe said, all of them?

06:25:18.240 --> 06:25:21.520
Everyone that's left. He held the can, but did not use it.

06:25:22.480 --> 06:25:24.080
Pat too, Joe asked.

06:25:24.960 --> 06:25:28.320
When I got out of the elevator on the second floor here, I found her.

06:25:28.320 --> 06:25:31.600
It had just begun to hit her. She seemed terribly surprised.

06:25:31.600 --> 06:25:34.720
Apparently she couldn't believe it. He set the can down again.

06:25:35.440 --> 06:25:38.080
I guess she thought she was doing it, with her talent.

06:25:39.040 --> 06:25:41.120
Joe said, that's right, that's what she thought.

06:25:41.840 --> 06:25:43.120
Why won't she use the Eubach?

06:25:43.920 --> 06:25:46.720
Hell, Joe, we're going to die. You know it and I know it.

06:25:47.680 --> 06:25:50.640
He removed his horn-rimmed glasses and rubbed his eyes.

06:25:51.600 --> 06:25:56.720
After I saw Pat's condition, I went into the other rooms and that's when I saw the rest of them.

06:25:56.720 --> 06:26:01.360
Of us. That's why we took so long getting here. I had Dr. Taylor examine them.

06:26:02.000 --> 06:26:07.600
I couldn't believe they dwindle away so fast. The acceleration has been so goddamn great

06:26:07.600 --> 06:26:08.800
in just the last hour.

06:26:09.440 --> 06:26:12.000
Use the Eubach, Joe said, or I'll use it on you.

06:26:12.960 --> 06:26:17.200
Don Denny again picked up the can, again shook it, pointed the nozzle toward himself.

06:26:17.840 --> 06:26:22.800
All right, he said, if that's what you want, there really isn't any reason not to. This is the end,

06:26:22.800 --> 06:26:27.040
isn't it? I mean, they're all dead. Only you and I are left and the Eubach is going to wear

06:26:27.040 --> 06:26:30.800
off you in a few hours and you won't be able to get any more, which will leave me.

06:26:32.000 --> 06:26:35.120
His decision made Denny depress the button of the spray can.

06:26:35.680 --> 06:26:40.080
The shimmering, palpitating vapor filled with particles of metallic light that danced

06:26:40.080 --> 06:26:46.000
nimbly formed at once around him. Don Denny disappeared, concealed by the nimbus of radiant

06:26:46.000 --> 06:26:52.400
ergic excitement. Pausing in his task of reading Joe's blood pressure, Dr. Taylor twisted his

06:26:52.400 --> 06:26:57.840
head to see both he and Joe watched as the vapor now condensed, puddles of it glistened on the

06:26:57.840 --> 06:27:01.920
carpet and down the wall behind Denny it drizzled in bright streaks.

06:27:03.840 --> 06:27:09.920
The cloud concealing Denny evaporated. The person standing there, in the center

06:27:09.920 --> 06:27:16.400
of the vaporizing stain of Eubach that had saturated the worn and dingy carpet, was not Don Denny.

06:27:17.920 --> 06:27:23.600
An adolescent boy, mawkishly slender with irregular black button eyes beneath tangled

06:27:23.600 --> 06:27:30.480
brows. He wore an anachronistic costume, white drip dry shirt, jeans and laceless leather slippers,

06:27:31.040 --> 06:27:36.320
clothes from the middle of the century. On his elongated face Joe saw a smile, but it was a

06:27:36.320 --> 06:27:43.520
misshapen smile, a thwarted crease that became now almost a jeering lear. No two features matched,

06:27:43.520 --> 06:27:47.440
his ears had too many convolutions in them to fit with his chitinous eyes.

06:27:48.160 --> 06:27:54.400
His straight hair contradicted the interwoven curly bristles of his brows and his nose, Joe thought,

06:27:54.400 --> 06:28:00.160
too thin, too sharp, far too long. Even his chin failed to harmonize with the balance of his face.

06:28:00.720 --> 06:28:06.240
It had a deep chisel mark in it, a cleft, obviously penetrating far up into the bone,

06:28:06.480 --> 06:28:12.480
Joe thought as if at that point the manufacturer of this creature struck at a blow aimed at obliterating

06:28:12.480 --> 06:28:18.320
it. But the physical material, the base substance, had been too dense. The boy had not fractured and

06:28:18.320 --> 06:28:24.400
split apart. He existed in defiance of even the force that had constructed him. He jeered at

06:28:24.400 --> 06:28:33.440
everything else and it, too. Who are you? Joe said. The boy's fingers writhed, a twitch protecting

06:28:33.520 --> 06:28:39.840
him evidently from a stammer. Sometimes I call myself Matt and sometimes Bill, he said,

06:28:39.840 --> 06:28:48.880
but mostly I'm Jory. That's my real name, Jory. Gray, shabby teeth showed as he spoke, and a grubby tongue.

06:28:51.120 --> 06:28:56.400
After an interval, Joe said, where's Denny? He never came into this room did he?

06:28:57.360 --> 06:29:03.280
Dead, he thought, with the others. I ate Denny a long time ago. The boy, Jory, said,

06:29:03.520 --> 06:29:08.080
right at the beginning, before they came here from New York, first day, Wendy Wright, then he came second.

06:29:09.040 --> 06:29:15.360
Joe said, how do you mean eight? Literally, he wondered his flesh undulating with a version.

06:29:15.360 --> 06:29:20.400
The gross physical motion rolled through him and golfing him as if his body wanted to shrink away,

06:29:20.400 --> 06:29:26.240
however he managed more or less to conceal it. I did what I do, Jory said. It's hard to explain,

06:29:26.240 --> 06:29:31.440
but I've been doing it a long time to lots of half-life people. I eat their life, what remains

06:29:31.440 --> 06:29:36.240
of it. There's very little in each person, so I need a lot of them. I used to wait until they had

06:29:36.240 --> 06:29:40.800
been in half-life a while, but now I have to have them immediately if I'm going to be able to live

06:29:40.800 --> 06:29:46.480
myself. If you come close to me and listen, I'll hold my mouth open. You can hear their voices.

06:29:47.200 --> 06:29:50.560
Not all of them, but anyhow the last ones I ate, the ones you know.

06:29:51.520 --> 06:29:57.120
With his fingernail he picked at an upper incisor. His head tilted on one side as he regarded Joe,

06:29:57.120 --> 06:30:01.600
evidently waiting to hear his reaction. Don't you have anything to say? He said.

06:30:02.480 --> 06:30:08.640
It was you who started me dying down there in the lobby. Me and not Pat. I ate her out in the

06:30:08.640 --> 06:30:13.520
hall by the elevator, and then I ate the others. I thought you were dead. He rotated the can of

06:30:13.520 --> 06:30:19.040
Hubek, which he still held. I can't figure this out. What's in it? And where does Ranseter get it?

06:30:19.040 --> 06:30:24.800
He's scald. But Ranseter can't be doing it. You're right. He's on the outside. This originates from

06:30:24.800 --> 06:30:29.600
within our environment. It has to, because nothing can come in from outside except words.

06:30:30.560 --> 06:30:36.480
Joe said, So there's nothing you can do to me. You can't eat me because of the Hubek. I can't

06:30:36.480 --> 06:30:41.520
eat you for a while, but the Hubek will wear off. You don't know that. You don't even know what it is,

06:30:41.520 --> 06:30:49.280
or where it comes from. I wonder if I can kill you, he thought. The boy, Jory, seemed delicate.

06:30:50.000 --> 06:30:54.480
This is the thing that got Wendy, he said to himself. I'm seeing it, face to face,

06:30:54.480 --> 06:31:00.240
as I knew I eventually would. Wendy, Al, the real Don Denny, all the rest of them.

06:31:00.240 --> 06:31:04.560
It even ate Ranseter's corpse as it lay in the casket at the mortuary. There must have been a

06:31:04.560 --> 06:31:09.680
flicker of residual proto-phasic activity in or near it or something, anyhow, which attracted him.

06:31:10.480 --> 06:31:15.440
The doctor said, Mr. Chip, I didn't have a chance to finish taking your blood pressure.

06:31:15.440 --> 06:31:19.440
Please lie back down. Joe stared at him, then said,

06:31:20.400 --> 06:31:23.520
Didn't he see you change, Jory? Hasn't he heard what you've been saying?

06:31:24.240 --> 06:31:29.440
Dr. Taylor is a product of my mind, Jory said, like every other fixture in this pseudo-world.

06:31:30.320 --> 06:31:34.000
I don't believe it, Joe said. To the doctor, he said,

06:31:34.000 --> 06:31:40.480
You heard what he's been saying, didn't you? With a hollow whistling pop, the doctor disappeared.

06:31:41.280 --> 06:31:43.440
See? Jory said, pleased.

06:31:44.480 --> 06:31:47.440
What are you going to do when I'm killed off? Joe asked the boy.

06:31:47.440 --> 06:31:52.080
Will you keep on maintaining this 1939 world, this pseudo-world, as you call it?

06:31:52.080 --> 06:31:57.840
Of course not. There'd be no reason to. Then it's all for me. Just for me, this entire world.

06:31:59.040 --> 06:32:03.760
Jory said, It's not very large. One hotel in Des Moines, and a street outside the window with a

06:32:03.760 --> 06:32:07.920
few people and cars, and maybe a couple of other buildings thrown in, stores across the street

06:32:07.920 --> 06:32:13.680
for you to look at when you happen to see out. So you're not maintaining any New York or Zurich,

06:32:13.680 --> 06:32:17.600
or why should I? No one's there. Wherever you and the others of the group went,

06:32:17.600 --> 06:32:21.360
I constructed a tangible reality corresponding to their minimal expectations.

06:32:22.240 --> 06:32:26.720
When you flew here from New York, I created hundreds of miles of countryside, town after town.

06:32:27.680 --> 06:32:31.840
I found that very exhausting. I had to eat a great deal to make up for that. In fact,

06:32:31.840 --> 06:32:35.920
that's the reason I had to finish off the others so soon after you got here. I needed to replenish

06:32:35.920 --> 06:32:45.440
myself. Joe said, Why 1939? Why not our own contemporary world, 1992? The effort! I can't

06:32:45.440 --> 06:32:52.000
keep objects from regressing. Doing it all alone, it was too much for me. I created 1992 at first,

06:32:52.000 --> 06:32:57.600
but then things began to break down. The coins, the cream, the cigarettes, all those phenomena

06:32:57.600 --> 06:33:01.120
that you noticed, and then runs to the keep breaking through from outside. That made it

06:33:01.120 --> 06:33:04.800
even harder for me. Actually, it would have been better if he hadn't interfered.

06:33:05.600 --> 06:33:11.920
Jory grin slighly. But I didn't worry about the reversion. I knew you'd figure it was Pat Conley.

06:33:12.480 --> 06:33:16.880
It would seem like her talent because it's sort of like what her talent does. I thought maybe the

06:33:16.880 --> 06:33:21.120
rest of you would kill her. I would enjoy that. His grin increased.

06:33:22.080 --> 06:33:27.040
What's the point of keeping this hotel and the street outside going for me now? Joe said.

06:33:27.840 --> 06:33:32.720
Now that I know. But I always do it this way. Jory's eyes widened.

06:33:32.960 --> 06:33:41.120
Joe said, I'm going to kill you. He stepped toward Jory in an uncoordinated half-falling motion.

06:33:41.120 --> 06:33:45.280
Raising his open hands, he plunged against the boy, trying to capture the neck, searching for

06:33:45.280 --> 06:33:51.840
the bent pipe stem windpipe with all his fingers. Snarling, Jory bit him. The great shoveled teeth

06:33:51.840 --> 06:33:56.240
fastened deep into Joe's right hand. They hung on as meanwhile Jory raised his head,

06:33:56.240 --> 06:34:02.080
lifting Joe's hand with his jaw. Jory stared at him with unwinking eyes, snoring wetly as he

06:34:02.080 --> 06:34:07.040
tried to close his jaws. The teeth sank deeper and Joe felt the pain of it throughout him.

06:34:07.040 --> 06:34:13.200
He's eating me, he realized. You can't, he said aloud. He hit Jory on the snout, punching again

06:34:13.200 --> 06:34:18.800
and again. You bit keeps you away, he said, as he cuffed Jory's jeering eyes. You can't do it to me.

06:34:20.720 --> 06:34:26.080
Jory bubbled, working his jaws sideways like a sheep's, grinding Joe's hand until the pain

06:34:26.080 --> 06:34:31.680
became too much for Joe to stand. He kicked Jory. The teeth released his hand. He crept backward,

06:34:31.760 --> 06:34:35.200
looking at the blood rising from the punctures made by the troll teeth.

06:34:35.200 --> 06:34:41.200
Jesus, he said to himself, appalled. You can't do to me, Joe said, what you did to them.

06:34:41.920 --> 06:34:45.680
Locating the spray can of Eubach, he pointed the nozzle toward the bleeding wound which

06:34:45.680 --> 06:34:51.040
his hand had become. He pressed the red plastic stud and a weak stream of particles emerged and

06:34:51.040 --> 06:34:57.120
settled in a film over the chewed torn flesh. The pain immediately departed before his eyes,

06:34:57.120 --> 06:35:02.160
the wound healed. And you can't kill me, Jory said. He still grinned.

06:35:03.200 --> 06:35:09.360
Joe said, I'm going downstairs. He walked unsteadily to the door of the room and opened it.

06:35:09.360 --> 06:35:15.520
Outside lay the dingy hall. He started forward, step by step treading carefully. The floor,

06:35:15.520 --> 06:35:19.360
however, seemed substantial, not a quasi or a real world at all.

06:35:20.080 --> 06:35:25.040
Don't go too far, Jory said from behind him. I can't keep too great an area going. Like,

06:35:25.040 --> 06:35:28.640
if you were going to get into one of those cars and drive for miles, eventually you'd reach a

06:35:28.640 --> 06:35:32.000
point where it breaks down and you wouldn't like that any better than I do.

06:35:32.640 --> 06:35:37.200
I don't see what I have to lose. Joe reached the elevator, pressed the down button.

06:35:37.200 --> 06:35:40.720
Jory called after him. I have trouble with elevators. They're complicated. Maybe you should

06:35:40.720 --> 06:35:47.200
take the stairs. After waiting a little longer, Joe gave up. As Jory had advised, he descended

06:35:47.200 --> 06:35:53.120
by the stairs, the same flight up which he had so recently come step by step in an agony of effort.

06:35:53.360 --> 06:36:01.200
Well, he thought. That's one of the two agencies who are at work. Jory is the one who's destroying

06:36:01.200 --> 06:36:07.120
us, has destroyed us, except for me. Behind Jory there is nothing. He is the end.

06:36:08.000 --> 06:36:13.840
Will I meet the other? Probably not soon enough for it to matter, he decided. He looked once more

06:36:13.840 --> 06:36:18.560
at his hand completely well. Reaching the lobby, he gazed around him at the people, the great

06:36:18.640 --> 06:36:24.800
chandelier overhead. Jory, in many respects, had done a good job, despite the reversion to these

06:36:24.800 --> 06:36:30.560
older forms. Real, he thought, experiencing the floor beneath his feet. I can't get over it.

06:36:32.080 --> 06:36:37.120
He thought, Jory must have had experience. He must have done this many times before.

06:36:38.000 --> 06:36:40.000
Going to the hotel desk, he said to the clerk,

06:36:40.640 --> 06:36:42.800
You have a restaurant that you'd recommend?

06:36:43.440 --> 06:36:47.440
Down the street, the clerk said, pausing in his task of sorting mail.

06:36:47.440 --> 06:36:50.720
To your right, the matador, you'll find it excellent, sir.

06:36:52.080 --> 06:36:58.000
I'm lonely, Joe said on impulse. Does the hotel have any source of supply, any girls?

06:36:58.800 --> 06:37:04.320
The clerk said in a clipped disapproving voice, Not this hotel, sir. This hotel does not pander.

06:37:05.040 --> 06:37:09.520
You keep a good clean family, hotel, Joe said. We like to think so, sir.

06:37:10.080 --> 06:37:15.200
I was just testing you, Joe said. I wanted to be sure what kind of hotel I was staying in.

06:37:15.920 --> 06:37:20.000
He left the counter, recrossed the lobby, made his way down the wide marble stairs,

06:37:20.000 --> 06:37:23.200
through the revolving door, and onto the pavement outside.

06:37:26.480 --> 06:37:32.960
16. Wake up to a hearty, lip-smacking bowl full of nutritious, nourishing,

06:37:32.960 --> 06:37:39.200
ubic toasted flakes, the adult cereal that's more crunchy, more tasty, more mmmish,

06:37:39.760 --> 06:37:46.320
ubic breakfast cereal, the whole bowl taste treat, do not exceed recommended portion at any one meal.

06:37:48.560 --> 06:37:54.400
The diversity of cars impressed him. Many years represented many makes and many models.

06:37:54.960 --> 06:37:59.360
The fact that they mostly came in black could not be laid at Jory's door. This detail was authentic.

06:38:00.240 --> 06:38:08.720
But how did Jory know it? That's peculiar, he thought. Jory's knowledge of the minutiae of 1939,

06:38:08.720 --> 06:38:15.280
a period in which none of us lived, except Glenn Runceter. Then all at once he realized why.

06:38:16.160 --> 06:38:22.880
Jory had told the truth. He had constructed not this world, but the world, or rather its

06:38:22.880 --> 06:38:29.520
phantasmagoric counterpart of their own time. Decomposition back to these forms was not of

06:38:29.520 --> 06:38:36.080
his doing. They happened despite his efforts. These are natural atavisms, Joe realized,

06:38:36.080 --> 06:38:42.160
happening mechanically as Jory's strength wanes. As the boy says, it's an enormous effort.

06:38:42.160 --> 06:38:47.520
This is perhaps the first time he has created a world this diverse for so many people at once.

06:38:47.520 --> 06:38:50.400
It isn't usual for so many half-lifers to be interwired.

06:38:51.280 --> 06:38:56.560
We have put an abnormal strain on Jory, he said to himself, and we paid for it.

06:38:57.600 --> 06:39:02.960
A square old dodged taxi, spotted past Joe, waved at it, and the cab floundered noisily to the curb.

06:39:03.760 --> 06:39:09.920
Let's test out what Jory said, he said to himself, as to the early boundary of this quasi-world now.

06:39:10.720 --> 06:39:11.760
To the driver, he said,

06:39:12.720 --> 06:39:16.800
Take me for a ride through town, go anywhere you want. I'd like to see as many streets and

06:39:16.800 --> 06:39:21.120
buildings and people as possible. And then when you've driven through all of Des Moines,

06:39:21.120 --> 06:39:24.000
I want you to drive me to the next town, and we'll see that.

06:39:24.720 --> 06:39:29.680
I don't go between towns, Mr. the driver said, holding the door open for Joe,

06:39:29.680 --> 06:39:35.280
but I'll be glad to drive you around Des Moines. It's a nice city, sir. You've not stayed, aren't you?

06:39:35.840 --> 06:39:40.640
New York, Joe said, getting inside the cab. The cab rolled back out into traffic.

06:39:42.160 --> 06:39:47.760
How did they feel about the war back in New York, the driver asked presently. Do you think we'll

06:39:47.760 --> 06:39:54.320
be getting into it? Rosa wants to get us. I don't care to discuss politics or the war, Joe said harshly.

06:39:55.280 --> 06:40:00.640
They drove for a time in silence. Watching the buildings, people, and cars go by,

06:40:00.640 --> 06:40:06.000
Joe asked himself again how Jory could maintain it all so many details, he marveled.

06:40:06.720 --> 06:40:10.160
I should be coming to the edge of it soon. It has to be just about now.

06:40:10.320 --> 06:40:15.520
"'Driver,' he said, are there any houses of prostitution here in Des Moines?'

06:40:16.080 --> 06:40:17.520
"'No,' the driver said.

06:40:18.480 --> 06:40:24.000
Maybe Jory can't manage that, Joe reflected, because of his youth, or maybe he disapproves.

06:40:24.880 --> 06:40:26.720
He felt all at once tired.

06:40:27.520 --> 06:40:30.240
"'Where am I going?' he asked himself, and what for?'

06:40:30.960 --> 06:40:36.400
To prove to myself that what Jory told me is true. I already know it's true. I saw the doctor wink out.

06:40:36.960 --> 06:40:40.480
I saw Jory emerge from inside Don Denny. That should have been enough.

06:40:41.040 --> 06:40:45.760
All I'm doing this way is putting more of a load on Jory, which will increase his appetite.

06:40:46.480 --> 06:40:49.120
"'I'd better give up,' he decided. This is pointless.'

06:40:50.560 --> 06:40:54.000
And, as Jory had said, the uber would be wearing off anyhow.

06:40:54.720 --> 06:40:59.600
This driving around Des Moines is not the way I want to spend my last minutes or hours of life.

06:40:59.600 --> 06:41:01.040
There must be something else.'

06:41:02.000 --> 06:41:07.760
Along the sidewalk a girl moved in a slow, easy gate. She seemed to be window-shopping,

06:41:07.760 --> 06:41:12.960
a pretty girl, with gay blonde pigtails, wearing an unbuttoned sweater over her blouse,

06:41:12.960 --> 06:41:15.520
a bright red skirt, and high-heeled little shoes.

06:41:16.400 --> 06:41:20.640
"'Slow the cab,' he instructed the driver. There, by that girl with the pigtails.

06:41:21.200 --> 06:41:23.360
"'She won't talk to you,' the driver said.

06:41:23.360 --> 06:41:25.280
"'She'll call a cop.' Joe said.

06:41:25.840 --> 06:41:28.560
"'I don't care.' It hardly mattered at this point.

06:41:29.280 --> 06:41:32.000
Slowing the old dodge bumbled its way to the curb.

06:41:32.000 --> 06:41:36.000
Its tires protested as they rubbed against the curb. The girl glanced up.

06:41:36.720 --> 06:41:38.320
"'Hi, Miss,' Joe said.

06:41:39.280 --> 06:41:44.720
She regarded him with curiosity. Her warm, intelligent blue eyes widened a little,

06:41:44.720 --> 06:41:49.360
but they showed no aversion or alarm. Rather, she seemed slightly amused at him,

06:41:49.360 --> 06:41:50.480
but in a friendly way.

06:41:51.360 --> 06:41:52.640
"'Yes,' she said.

06:41:53.600 --> 06:41:55.840
"'I'm going to die,' Joe said.

06:41:56.560 --> 06:41:59.040
"'Oh, dear,' the girl said with concern.

06:41:59.680 --> 06:42:00.400
"'Are you—'

06:42:00.400 --> 06:42:02.800
"'He's not sick,' the driver put in.

06:42:02.800 --> 06:42:05.200
He's been asking after girls. He just wants to pick you up.'

06:42:06.000 --> 06:42:10.400
The girl laughed, without hostility, and she did not depart.

06:42:11.680 --> 06:42:14.880
"'It's almost dinner time,' Joe said to her.

06:42:14.880 --> 06:42:18.720
"'Let me take you to a restaurant. The matador, I understand that's nice.'

06:42:19.680 --> 06:42:23.360
His tiredness now had increased. He felt the weight of it on him.

06:42:23.920 --> 06:42:29.280
And then he realized, with muted, weary horror, that it consisted of the same fatigue

06:42:29.280 --> 06:42:33.520
which had attacked him in the hotel lobby after he had shown the police citation to Pat.

06:42:34.400 --> 06:42:35.520
And the cold—'

06:42:36.480 --> 06:42:41.040
Stealthily, the physical experience of the cold pack surrounding him had come back.

06:42:41.680 --> 06:42:44.560
The u-bick is beginning to wear off,' he realized.

06:42:45.120 --> 06:42:46.160
"'I don't have much longer.'

06:42:46.240 --> 06:42:51.360
Something must have showed in his face. The girl walked toward him up to the window of the cab.

06:42:51.360 --> 06:42:53.520
"'Are you all right?' she asked.

06:42:54.160 --> 06:42:55.440
Joe said with effort.

06:42:56.320 --> 06:42:57.920
"'I'm dying, miss.'

06:42:59.040 --> 06:43:02.880
The wound on his hand, the teeth marks, had begun to throb once more,

06:43:02.880 --> 06:43:07.520
and were again becoming visible. This alone would have been enough to fill him with dread.

06:43:08.480 --> 06:43:11.200
"'Have the driver take you to the hospital,' the girl said.

06:43:12.240 --> 06:43:15.120
"'Can we have dinner together?' Joe asked her.

06:43:16.240 --> 06:43:18.640
"'Is that what you want to do?' she said.

06:43:18.640 --> 06:43:19.680
"'When you're—'

06:43:19.680 --> 06:43:23.840
"'Whatever it is, sick? Are you sick?' she opened the door of the cab.

06:43:23.840 --> 06:43:24.000
Then.

06:43:24.880 --> 06:43:27.440
"'Do you want me to go with you to the hospital? Is that it?'

06:43:28.480 --> 06:43:30.240
"'To the matador,' Joe said.

06:43:30.800 --> 06:43:33.360
"'We'll have braised fillet of mushroom-mull cricket.'

06:43:34.240 --> 06:43:38.800
He remembered, then, that imported delicacy did not exist in this time period.

06:43:39.680 --> 06:43:41.040
"'Market steak,' he said.

06:43:41.680 --> 06:43:43.440
"'Beef. Do you like beef?'

06:43:44.400 --> 06:43:46.720
Getting into the cab, the girl said to the driver,

06:43:46.720 --> 06:43:48.160
"'He wants to go to the matador.'

06:43:48.880 --> 06:43:50.560
"'Okay, miss,' the driver said.

06:43:51.120 --> 06:43:53.760
The cab rolled out into traffic once more.

06:43:53.760 --> 06:43:56.480
At the next intersection, the driver made a U-turn.

06:43:56.480 --> 06:43:59.680
"'Now,' Joe realized, we are on our way to the restaurant.

06:43:59.680 --> 06:44:01.120
"'I wonder if I'll make it there.'

06:44:01.840 --> 06:44:05.280
Fatigue and cold had invaded him completely.

06:44:05.280 --> 06:44:09.280
He felt his body processes beginning to close down one by one.

06:44:09.280 --> 06:44:11.120
Organs that had no future.

06:44:11.120 --> 06:44:13.840
The liver did not need to make red blood cells.

06:44:13.840 --> 06:44:16.640
The kidneys did not need to excrete wastes.

06:44:16.640 --> 06:44:19.200
The intestines no longer served any purpose.

06:44:19.840 --> 06:44:21.840
Only the heart laboring on.

06:44:22.480 --> 06:44:25.120
And the increasingly difficult breathing.

06:44:25.120 --> 06:44:29.280
Each time he drew air into his lungs, he sensed the concrete block

06:44:29.280 --> 06:44:31.360
that had situated itself on his chest.

06:44:32.080 --> 06:44:34.320
"'My gravestone,' he decided.

06:44:35.120 --> 06:44:37.360
His hand, he saw, was bleeding again.

06:44:37.360 --> 06:44:39.920
Thick, slow blood appeared, drop by drop.

06:44:40.720 --> 06:44:43.360
"'Care for Lucky Strike?' the girl asked him,

06:44:43.360 --> 06:44:44.960
extending her pack toward him.

06:44:45.520 --> 06:44:48.240
"'They're toasted,' as the slogan goes.

06:44:48.240 --> 06:44:51.440
The phrase LSMFT won't come into existence until—'

06:44:52.240 --> 06:44:52.800
Joe said,

06:44:53.680 --> 06:44:54.960
"'My name is Joe Chipp.

06:44:55.680 --> 06:44:56.960
Do you want me to tell you my name?'

06:44:58.000 --> 06:45:00.320
"'Yes,' he grated and shut his eyes.

06:45:00.320 --> 06:45:02.720
He couldn't speak any further for a time anyhow.

06:45:02.720 --> 06:45:06.000
"'Do you like Des Moines?' he asked her,

06:45:06.000 --> 06:45:07.920
presently concealing his hand from her.

06:45:08.800 --> 06:45:11.360
"'Have you lived here a long time?'

06:45:12.240 --> 06:45:15.280
"'You sound very tired, Mr. Chipp.' the girl said.

06:45:16.080 --> 06:45:18.800
"'Oh, hell,' he said, gesturing.

06:45:19.360 --> 06:45:20.160
"'It doesn't matter.'

06:45:21.360 --> 06:45:22.080
"'Yes, it does.'

06:45:23.120 --> 06:45:25.760
The girl opened her purse, rummaged briskly, within it.

06:45:26.800 --> 06:45:28.880
"'I'm not a deformation of juries.

06:45:28.880 --> 06:45:31.760
I'm not like him,' she indicated the driver.

06:45:32.400 --> 06:45:36.400
"'Or like these little old stores and houses and this dingy street—

06:45:36.400 --> 06:45:38.880
all these people and their neolithic cars.

06:45:38.880 --> 06:45:40.080
"'Here, Mr. Chipp.'

06:45:40.880 --> 06:45:44.000
From her purse she brought an envelope which she passed to him.

06:45:44.000 --> 06:45:45.120
"'This is for you.

06:45:45.120 --> 06:45:46.080
Open it right away.

06:45:46.080 --> 06:45:48.560
I don't think either of us should have delayed so long.'

06:45:49.760 --> 06:45:53.120
With leaden fingers he tore open the envelope.

06:45:53.760 --> 06:45:56.720
In it he found a certificate stately and ornamented.

06:45:57.280 --> 06:45:59.680
The printing on it, however, swam.

06:45:59.680 --> 06:46:01.200
He was too weary now to read.

06:46:02.240 --> 06:46:06.240
"'What say?' he asked her, laying it down on his lap.

06:46:07.280 --> 06:46:10.720
"'From the company that manufactures you, Bick,' the girl said.

06:46:10.720 --> 06:46:14.080
"'It's a guarantee, Mr. Chipp, of a free lifetime supply.

06:46:14.720 --> 06:46:19.520
Free because I know your problem regarding money—your, shall we say, idiosyncrasy—

06:46:20.160 --> 06:46:22.960
and a list on the reverse of all the drugstores which carry it.

06:46:23.600 --> 06:46:27.200
Two drugstores and not abandoned ones in Des Moines.'

06:46:27.200 --> 06:46:28.000
The list did.

06:46:28.000 --> 06:46:30.880
I suggest we go to one first before we eat dinner.

06:46:30.880 --> 06:46:32.400
Here, driver—'

06:46:32.400 --> 06:46:36.160
She leaned forward and handed the driver a slip of paper already written out.

06:46:36.160 --> 06:46:38.240
Take us to this address, and hurry.

06:46:38.240 --> 06:46:39.360
They'll be closing soon.'

06:46:40.480 --> 06:46:43.600
Joe lay back against the seed panting for breath.

06:46:44.560 --> 06:46:48.400
"'We'll make it to the drugstore,' the girl said, and patted his arm reassuringly.

06:46:49.600 --> 06:46:52.400
"'Who are you?' Joe asked her.

06:46:53.120 --> 06:46:56.640
"'My name is Ella—Ella Hyde Runceter, your employer's wife.'

06:46:57.600 --> 06:47:01.680
"'You're here with us,' Joe said.

06:47:01.680 --> 06:47:04.400
"'On this side you're in cold pack.'

06:47:04.400 --> 06:47:08.720
"'As you well know, I have been for some time,' Ella Runceter said.

06:47:08.720 --> 06:47:13.840
"'Fairly soon I'll be reborn into another womb, I think—at least Glenn says so.

06:47:14.400 --> 06:47:19.760
I keep dreaming about a smoky red light, and that's bad—that's not a morally proper womb

06:47:19.760 --> 06:47:20.720
to be born into.'

06:47:21.840 --> 06:47:23.920
She laughed a rich, warm laugh.

06:47:24.880 --> 06:47:27.120
"'You're the other one,' Joe said.

06:47:28.000 --> 06:47:30.400
"'Joy destroying us—you trying to help us.

06:47:31.520 --> 06:47:35.680
Behind you there's no one, just as there's no one behind Jory.

06:47:35.680 --> 06:47:38.080
I've reached the last entities involved.'

06:47:39.280 --> 06:47:40.800
Ella said costically,

06:47:40.800 --> 06:47:42.720
"'I don't think of myself as an entity.

06:47:43.440 --> 06:47:45.760
I usually think of myself as Ella Runceter.'

06:47:46.640 --> 06:47:48.960
"'But it's true,' Joe said.

06:47:49.760 --> 06:47:50.080
"'Yes.'

06:47:50.800 --> 06:47:52.160
Sombrily she nodded.

06:47:53.120 --> 06:47:55.520
"'Why are you working against Jory?'

06:47:56.240 --> 06:47:57.920
"'Because Jory invaded me.'

06:47:58.560 --> 06:47:59.440
Ella said.

06:47:59.440 --> 06:48:02.000
He menaced me in the same way he's menaced you.

06:48:02.720 --> 06:48:04.080
We both know what he does.

06:48:04.080 --> 06:48:06.560
He told you himself in your hotel room.

06:48:06.560 --> 06:48:08.480
Sometimes he becomes very powerful.

06:48:08.480 --> 06:48:12.240
On occasion he manages to supplant me when I'm active and trying to talk to Glenn.

06:48:12.880 --> 06:48:16.240
But I seem to be able to cope with him better than most half-lifers,

06:48:16.240 --> 06:48:18.000
with or without you, Vic.

06:48:18.000 --> 06:48:21.120
Better, for instance, than your group, even acting as a collective.'

06:48:22.160 --> 06:48:23.440
"'Yes,' Joe said.

06:48:24.080 --> 06:48:25.920
It certainly was true, well-proved.'

06:48:26.640 --> 06:48:28.720
"'But I'm reborn,' Ella said.

06:48:28.720 --> 06:48:31.120
Glenn won't be able to consult with me any more.

06:48:31.840 --> 06:48:35.280
"'I have a very selfish, practical reason for assisting you, Mr. Chip.

06:48:35.280 --> 06:48:36.960
I want you to replace me.

06:48:37.600 --> 06:48:41.520
I want to have someone whom Glenn can ask for advice and assistance,

06:48:41.520 --> 06:48:42.640
whom he can lean on.

06:48:43.360 --> 06:48:44.800
You will be ideal.

06:48:44.800 --> 06:48:47.360
You'll be doing in half-life what you did in full life.

06:48:47.920 --> 06:48:50.880
So in a sense I'm not motivated by noble sentiments.

06:48:50.880 --> 06:48:55.200
I saved you from Jory for a good common sense reason,' she added,

06:48:55.200 --> 06:48:57.520
and God knows I detest Jory.'

06:48:58.800 --> 06:49:01.200
"'After you're reborn,' Joe said.

06:49:01.840 --> 06:49:03.040
I won't succumb.

06:49:03.760 --> 06:49:08.160
You have your lifetime supply of you, Vic, as it says on the certificate I gave you.'

06:49:09.200 --> 06:49:09.680
Joe said,

06:49:10.560 --> 06:49:12.640
"'Maybe I can defeat Jory.'

06:49:13.280 --> 06:49:14.800
"'Destroy him, you mean?'

06:49:15.520 --> 06:49:16.480
Ella pondered.

06:49:17.120 --> 06:49:18.880
He is not invulnerable.

06:49:18.880 --> 06:49:22.160
Maybe in time you can learn ways to nullify him.

06:49:22.160 --> 06:49:24.480
I think that's really the best you can hope to do.

06:49:24.480 --> 06:49:28.000
I doubt if you can truly destroy him, in other words, consume him,

06:49:28.000 --> 06:49:31.360
as he does to half-lifers placed near him at the moratorium.'

06:49:32.240 --> 06:49:33.840
"'Hell,' Joe said.

06:49:33.840 --> 06:49:39.760
I'll tell Glenn Runceter the situation, and have him move Jory out of the moratorium entirely.'

06:49:40.320 --> 06:49:42.240
"'Oh, Glenn has no authority to do that.'

06:49:43.440 --> 06:49:45.680
"'Won't Sean Hyde von Vogel sing?'

06:49:46.640 --> 06:49:47.280
Ella said,

06:49:47.840 --> 06:49:52.560
"'Herbits paid a great deal of money annually by Jory's family to keep him with the others,

06:49:52.560 --> 06:49:55.680
and to think up plausible reasons for doing so.

06:49:56.720 --> 06:50:00.400
And there are Jories in every moratorium.

06:50:00.400 --> 06:50:03.040
This battle goes on wherever you have half-lifers.

06:50:03.600 --> 06:50:07.040
It's a verity, a rule of our kind of existence.'

06:50:07.920 --> 06:50:13.360
She lapsed into silence, then, for the first time he saw in her face an expression of anger,

06:50:13.360 --> 06:50:16.720
a ruffled, taut look that disturbed her tranquillity.

06:50:17.440 --> 06:50:21.360
"'It has to be fought on our side of the glass,' Ella said,

06:50:21.360 --> 06:50:24.640
by those of us in half-life, those that Jory prays on.

06:50:25.200 --> 06:50:27.840
"'You'll have to take charge, Mr. Chip, after I'm reborn.

06:50:27.840 --> 06:50:29.520
Do you think you can do that?

06:50:29.520 --> 06:50:30.320
It'll be hard.

06:50:30.880 --> 06:50:35.280
Jory'll be sapping your strength always, putting a burden on you that you'll feel as,'

06:50:36.080 --> 06:50:36.880
she hesitated,

06:50:37.440 --> 06:50:43.920
the approach of death, which it will be, because in half-life we diminish constantly anyhow.

06:50:44.480 --> 06:50:46.000
Jory only speeds it up.

06:50:46.560 --> 06:50:50.640
The weariness and cooling off come anyhow, but not so soon.'

06:50:51.920 --> 06:50:53.200
To himself, Joe thought,

06:50:53.760 --> 06:50:55.840
"'I can remember what he did to Wendy.

06:50:55.840 --> 06:50:57.680
That'll keep me going, that alone.'

06:50:58.960 --> 06:51:01.680
"'Here's their drugstore, Miss,' the driver said.

06:51:01.680 --> 06:51:04.720
The square upright old dodge wheezed the curb and parked.

06:51:05.440 --> 06:51:10.960
"'I won't go in with you,' Ella Ronson said to Joe as he opened the door and crept shakily out.

06:51:10.960 --> 06:51:13.840
"'Good-bye. Thanks for your loyalty to Glenn.

06:51:13.840 --> 06:51:16.240
Thanks for what you're going to be doing for him.'

06:51:17.040 --> 06:51:19.520
She leaned toward him, kissed him on the cheek.

06:51:19.520 --> 06:51:22.160
Her lips seemed to him ripe with life.

06:51:22.960 --> 06:51:24.720
And some of it was conveyed to him.

06:51:24.720 --> 06:51:26.160
He felt slightly stronger.

06:51:26.800 --> 06:51:27.760
"'Good luck with Jory!'

06:51:28.400 --> 06:51:32.000
She settled back, composed herself sedately, her purse on her lap.

06:51:32.960 --> 06:51:37.680
Joe shut the cab door, stood, then made his way haltingly into the drugstore.

06:51:37.680 --> 06:51:39.840
Behind him the cab thub-thub-dough.

06:51:40.400 --> 06:51:42.080
He heard but did not see it go.

06:51:43.360 --> 06:51:46.480
Within the solemn, lamplet interior of the drugstore,

06:51:46.480 --> 06:51:48.960
a bald pharmacist wearing a formal dark vest,

06:51:48.960 --> 06:51:52.400
bow tie, and sharply pressed shark-skin trousers approached him.

06:51:53.200 --> 06:51:56.560
"'Afraid we're closing, sir. I was just coming to lock the door.'

06:51:56.560 --> 06:51:59.280
"'But I'm in,' Joe said, and I want to be weighted on.

06:51:59.920 --> 06:52:03.200
He showed the pharmacist the certificate which Ella had given him,

06:52:03.200 --> 06:52:08.320
squinting through his round rimless glasses the pharmacist labored over the gothic printing.

06:52:09.200 --> 06:52:11.040
"'Are you going to wait on me?' Joe asked.

06:52:12.000 --> 06:52:13.760
"'You beck,' the pharmacist said.

06:52:14.400 --> 06:52:18.240
"'I believe I'm out of that. Let me check and see.' He started off.'

06:52:19.600 --> 06:52:21.040
"'Jory?' Joe said.

06:52:21.840 --> 06:52:23.280
Turning his head, the pharmacist said.

06:52:23.840 --> 06:52:24.080
"'Sir?'

06:52:25.040 --> 06:52:26.880
"'Your jury,' Joe said.

06:52:26.880 --> 06:52:28.800
"'I can tell now,' he said to himself.

06:52:28.800 --> 06:52:30.640
"'I'm learning how to know him when I encounter him.'

06:52:31.360 --> 06:52:36.000
"'You invented this drugstore,' he said, and everything in it except for the spray cans of

06:52:36.000 --> 06:52:40.000
Ubeck. You have no authority over Ubeck. That comes from Ella.'

06:52:40.640 --> 06:52:42.080
He forced himself into motion.

06:52:42.080 --> 06:52:45.840
Step by step he edged his way behind the counter to the shelves of medical supplies,

06:52:46.400 --> 06:52:48.560
peering in the gloom over one shelf after the other.

06:52:48.560 --> 06:52:50.160
He tried to locate the Ubeck.

06:52:50.160 --> 06:52:52.080
The lighting of the store had dimmed.

06:52:52.080 --> 06:52:54.000
The antique fixtures were fading.

06:52:54.960 --> 06:52:58.800
"'I've regressed all the Ubeck in this store,' the pharmacist said in a youthful

06:52:58.800 --> 06:53:00.480
high-pitched jury voice.

06:53:00.480 --> 06:53:02.800
"'Back to the liver and kidney bomb. It's no good now.'

06:53:03.760 --> 06:53:06.640
"'I'll go to the other drugstore that has it,' Joe said.

06:53:07.200 --> 06:53:11.440
He leaned against the counter painfully drawing in slow irregular gulps of air.

06:53:12.240 --> 06:53:15.200
"'Jory from within the balding pharmacist said,

06:53:15.200 --> 06:53:16.080
"'It'll be closed.'

06:53:17.120 --> 06:53:18.960
"'Tomorrow,' Joe said.

06:53:18.960 --> 06:53:21.520
"'I can hold out until tomorrow morning.'

06:53:21.520 --> 06:53:23.440
"'You can,' Jory said.

06:53:23.440 --> 06:53:26.080
"'And anyhow the Ubeck at that drugstore will be regressed too.'

06:53:26.960 --> 06:53:29.120
"'Another town,' Joe said.

06:53:29.120 --> 06:53:31.120
"'Wherever you go it'll be regressed.

06:53:31.120 --> 06:53:34.800
Back to the salve, or back to the powder, or back to the elixir,

06:53:34.800 --> 06:53:37.920
or back to the bomb. You'll never see a spray can of it, Joe Chipp.'

06:53:38.720 --> 06:53:43.200
Jory, in the form of the bald-headed pharmacist's smile showing celluloid-like

06:53:43.200 --> 06:53:49.840
dentures. "'I can,' he broke off, gathering his meager vitality to him,

06:53:49.840 --> 06:53:53.920
trying by his own strength to warm his stiffening cold-numbed body.

06:53:55.040 --> 06:53:59.120
"'Bring it up to the present,' he said, to 1992.'

06:54:00.320 --> 06:54:05.360
"'Can you, Mr. Chipp?' the pharmacist handed Joe a square paste-board container.

06:54:05.360 --> 06:54:07.360
"'Here you are. Open it, and you'll see.'

06:54:08.320 --> 06:54:09.120
Joe said.

06:54:09.120 --> 06:54:10.080
"'I know what I'll see.'

06:54:11.040 --> 06:54:14.720
He concentrated on the blue jar of liver and kidney-bomb.

06:54:14.720 --> 06:54:18.720
"'Evolve forward,' he said to it, flooding it with his need.

06:54:18.720 --> 06:54:22.000
He poured whatever energy he had left into the container.

06:54:22.800 --> 06:54:23.840
"'It did not change.'

06:54:24.560 --> 06:54:27.040
"'This is the regular world,' he said to it.

06:54:27.040 --> 06:54:30.560
"'Spray can,' he said aloud, he shut his eyes, resting.

06:54:30.560 --> 06:54:33.120
"'It's not a spray can, Mr. Chipp,' the pharmacist said.

06:54:33.760 --> 06:54:36.640
Going here and there in the drugstore he shut off lights.

06:54:36.640 --> 06:54:39.840
At the cash register he punched a key and the drawer rattled open.

06:54:39.840 --> 06:54:43.280
Expertly the pharmacist transferred the bills and changed from the drawer

06:54:43.280 --> 06:54:45.040
into a metal box with a lock on it.

06:54:46.160 --> 06:54:50.480
"'You are a spray can,' Joe said to the paste-board container,

06:54:50.480 --> 06:54:51.520
which he held in his hand.

06:54:52.160 --> 06:54:58.800
"'This is 1992,' he said, and tried to exert everything he put the entirety of himself

06:54:58.800 --> 06:55:03.440
into the effort. The last light blinked out, turned off by the pseudo-pharmacist.

06:55:04.000 --> 06:55:08.080
A dull gleam shone into the drugstore from the street lamp outside.

06:55:08.080 --> 06:55:12.800
By it Joe could make out the shape of the object in his hand, its box-like lines.

06:55:13.360 --> 06:55:15.120
Opening the door the pharmacist said,

06:55:15.120 --> 06:55:17.040
"'Come on, Mr. Chipp, time to go home.'

06:55:17.040 --> 06:55:18.240
She was wrong, wasn't she?

06:55:18.240 --> 06:55:21.520
And you won't see her again because she's so far on the road to being reborn.

06:55:21.520 --> 06:55:24.640
She's not thinking about you anymore, or me, or Runceter.

06:55:24.640 --> 06:55:28.960
Would L.A.C.'s now or various lights, red and dingy, then maybe bright orange?'

06:55:29.680 --> 06:55:34.240
"'What I hold here,' Joe said, "'is a spray can.'"

06:55:34.960 --> 06:55:36.640
"'Nope,' the pharmacist said.

06:55:36.640 --> 06:55:38.880
"'I'm sorry, Mr. Chipp, I really am, but it's not.'"

06:55:40.800 --> 06:55:44.240
Joe set the paste-board container down on a nearby counter.

06:55:44.240 --> 06:55:50.560
He turned with dignity, and began the long, slow journey across the drugstore to the front door,

06:55:50.560 --> 06:55:55.600
which the pharmacist held open for him. Neither of them spoke until Joe at last

06:55:55.600 --> 06:55:59.120
passed through the doorway and out onto the nocturnal sidewalk.

06:55:59.920 --> 06:56:04.400
Behind him the pharmacist emerged to. He bent and locked the door after the two of them.

06:56:05.200 --> 06:56:08.800
"'I think I'll complain to the manufacturer,' Joe said.

06:56:08.800 --> 06:56:09.520
"'About the—'

06:56:10.240 --> 06:56:13.600
He ceased, talking something constricted his throat.

06:56:13.600 --> 06:56:15.680
He could not breathe, and he could not speak.

06:56:16.480 --> 06:56:18.320
Then temporarily the blockage abated.

06:56:19.280 --> 06:56:21.840
"'Your regressed drugstore,' he finished.

06:56:22.480 --> 06:56:24.240
"'Good night,' the pharmacist said.

06:56:24.800 --> 06:56:27.840
He remained for a moment, eyeing Joe in the evening gloom,

06:56:27.840 --> 06:56:29.520
then shrugging, he started off.

06:56:30.880 --> 06:56:35.280
To his left Joe made out the dark shape of a bench where people waited for a streetcar.

06:56:35.280 --> 06:56:37.600
He managed to reach it to seat himself.

06:56:38.240 --> 06:56:42.640
The other persons, two or three, whichever it was, squeezed away from him,

06:56:42.640 --> 06:56:46.960
either out of aversion or to give him room he could not tell which, and he didn't care.

06:56:47.520 --> 06:56:50.560
All he felt was the support of the bench beneath him,

06:56:50.560 --> 06:56:53.520
the release of some of his vast inertial weight.

06:56:54.400 --> 06:56:56.960
"'A few more minutes,' he said to himself.

06:56:56.960 --> 06:56:58.240
"'If I remember right—'

06:56:59.280 --> 06:57:04.240
Christ, what a thing to have to go through,' he said to himself for the second time.

06:57:05.280 --> 06:57:10.720
Anyhow, we tried,' he thought as he watched the yellow flickering lights and neon signs,

06:57:10.720 --> 06:57:14.240
the flow of cars going in both directions directly before his eyes.

06:57:15.200 --> 06:57:18.320
He thought to himself, runse to the kit and struggled.

06:57:18.320 --> 06:57:22.400
Ella has been scratching and biting and gouging for a long time,

06:57:22.400 --> 06:57:27.200
and he thought, I damn near evolved the jar of ubeck liver and kidney bomb back to the present.

06:57:27.200 --> 06:57:31.600
I almost succeeded. There was something in knowing that,

06:57:31.600 --> 06:57:36.480
an awareness of his own great strength, his final transcendental attempt.'

06:57:37.760 --> 06:57:43.040
The streetcar, a clanging metal enormity, came to a grating halt before the bench.

06:57:43.040 --> 06:57:47.200
The several people beside Joe rose and hurried out to board it by its rear platform.

06:57:47.840 --> 06:57:50.240
"'Aye, mister,' the conductor yelled to Joe.

06:57:50.240 --> 06:57:53.600
"'Are you coming or aren't you?' Joe said nothing.

06:57:54.160 --> 06:57:57.280
The conductor waited. Then jerked his signal cord.

06:57:57.280 --> 06:58:00.960
Noisily the streetcar started up. It continued on,

06:58:00.960 --> 06:58:03.840
and then at last disappeared beyond his range of vision.

06:58:04.720 --> 06:58:09.680
"'Lots of luck,' Joe said to himself, as he heard the racket of the streetcar's wheels die away.

06:58:10.320 --> 06:58:14.800
And so long.' He leaned back, closed his eyes.

06:58:15.680 --> 06:58:17.520
"'Excuse me?'

06:58:18.800 --> 06:58:23.040
Bending over him in the darkness a girl in a synthetic ostrich leather coat,

06:58:23.680 --> 06:58:25.760
he looked up at her jarred into awareness.

06:58:26.640 --> 06:58:28.160
"'Mr. Chip,' she said.

06:58:29.040 --> 06:58:32.240
Pretty and slender, dressed in hat, gloves, suit, and high heels.

06:58:32.800 --> 06:58:35.600
She held something in her hand. He saw the outlines of a package.

06:58:36.160 --> 06:58:40.560
Of New York? Of Runciter Associates? I don't want to give this to the wrong person.'

06:58:40.640 --> 06:58:43.840
"'I'm Joe Chip,' he said.

06:58:44.800 --> 06:58:48.960
For a moment he thought the girl might be Ella Runciter, but he had never seen her before.

06:58:49.840 --> 06:58:51.920
"'Who sent you?' he said.

06:58:52.800 --> 06:58:55.040
"'Dr. Sunderbar,' the girl said.

06:58:55.040 --> 06:58:58.640
The younger Dr. Sunderbar, son of Dr. Sunderbar the founder.

06:58:59.840 --> 06:59:00.720
"'Who's that?'

06:59:01.600 --> 06:59:05.040
The name meant nothing to him, and then he remembered where he had seen it.

06:59:05.600 --> 06:59:08.160
The liver and kidney man,' he said.

06:59:08.880 --> 06:59:14.560
"'Processed oleander leaves, oil of peppermint, charcoal, cobalt, chloride, zinc oxide.'

06:59:15.280 --> 06:59:17.440
Wearing this overcame him, he stopped talking.

06:59:18.480 --> 06:59:19.200
The girl said,

06:59:19.920 --> 06:59:23.680
"'By making use of the most advanced techniques of modern-day science,

06:59:23.680 --> 06:59:29.600
the reversion of matter to earlier forms can be reversed, and at a price any conept owner can

06:59:29.600 --> 06:59:34.080
afford. UBIC is sold by leading home-art stores throughout earth,

06:59:34.080 --> 06:59:36.400
so look for it at the place you shop, Mr. Chip.'"

06:59:37.680 --> 06:59:39.120
Fully conscious now he said,

06:59:40.000 --> 06:59:44.400
"'Look for it where?' he struggled to his feet, stood inexperently swaying.

06:59:44.960 --> 06:59:49.040
"'You're from 1992, what you said came from Runciter's TV commercial.'

06:59:49.920 --> 06:59:54.240
An evening wind rustled at him, and he felt a tug at him, drawing him away with it.

06:59:54.240 --> 06:59:59.440
He seemed to be like some ragged bundle of webs and cloth barely holding together.

07:00:00.240 --> 07:00:02.960
"'Yes, Mr. Chip,' the girl handed him a package.

07:00:03.600 --> 07:00:08.240
"'You brought me from the future. By what you did there inside the drug-store a few moments ago,

07:00:08.240 --> 07:00:10.240
you summoned me directly from the factory.

07:00:11.040 --> 07:00:14.720
Mr. Chip, I could spray it on you if you're too weak to, shall I?

07:00:14.720 --> 07:00:19.440
I'm an official factory representative and technical consultant. I know how to apply it.'

07:00:20.160 --> 07:00:23.760
She took the package swiftly back from his trembling hands, tearing it open.

07:00:23.760 --> 07:00:25.680
She immediately sprayed him with UBIC.

07:00:26.320 --> 07:00:30.720
In the dusk he saw the spray can glint, he saw the happy, colored lettering.

07:00:32.160 --> 07:00:37.360
"'Thanks,' he said after a time, after he felt better and warmer.

07:00:38.480 --> 07:00:42.640
The girl said, "'You didn't need as much this time as you did in the hotel room.

07:00:42.640 --> 07:00:47.520
You must be stronger than before. Here, take the can of it. You might need it before morning.'

07:00:48.800 --> 07:00:51.680
"'Can I get more?' Joe said, when this runs out.'

07:00:52.640 --> 07:00:57.760
"'Evidently so. If you got me here once, I would assume you can get me here again the same way.'

07:00:58.560 --> 07:01:04.160
She moved away from him, merging with the shadows created by the dense walls of closed-up nearby

07:01:04.160 --> 07:01:09.120
stores. "'What is UBIC?' Joe said, wanting her to stay.'

07:01:09.680 --> 07:01:12.160
"'A spray can of UBIC,' the girl answered,

07:01:12.160 --> 07:01:16.480
is a portable negative ionizer with a self-contained high-voltage low-amp unit

07:01:16.480 --> 07:01:22.880
powered by a peak-gain helium battery of 25 kV. The negative ions are given a counterclockwise

07:01:22.880 --> 07:01:29.440
spin by a radically biased acceleration chamber, which creates a centripetal tendency to them

07:01:29.440 --> 07:01:34.720
so that they cohere rather than dissipate. A negative ion field diminishes the velocity

07:01:34.720 --> 07:01:40.000
of antiproto-phasons normally present in the atmosphere. As soon as their velocity falls,

07:01:40.000 --> 07:01:45.440
they cease to be antiproto-phasons, and under the principle of parity no longer can unite

07:01:45.440 --> 07:01:51.200
with the proto-phasons radiated from persons frozen in coal-pack, that is, those in half-life.

07:01:51.200 --> 07:01:57.840
The end result is that the proportion of proto-phasons not cancelled by antiproto-phasons increases,

07:01:57.840 --> 07:02:04.160
which means, for a specific time anyhow, an increment in the net put forth field of proto-phasonic

07:02:04.160 --> 07:02:10.480
activity, which the affected half-liver experiences as greater vitality, plus a lowering of the

07:02:10.480 --> 07:02:16.240
experience of low coal-pack temperatures, so you can see why regressed forms of ubiquic fail to—

07:02:17.040 --> 07:02:22.320
Joe said reflexively, to say negative ions is redundant, all ions are negative.

07:02:23.680 --> 07:02:25.120
Again the girl moved away.

07:02:26.000 --> 07:02:31.760
Maybe I'll see you again, she said gently. It was rewarding to bring you the spray can.

07:02:31.760 --> 07:02:32.560
Maybe next time—

07:02:33.280 --> 07:02:38.000
Maybe we can have dinner together, Joe said. I look forward to it.

07:02:38.000 --> 07:02:40.000
She ebbed farther and farther away.

07:02:40.800 --> 07:02:46.960
Who invented, Eubrick, Joe asked? A number of responsible half-lifers whom Jory threatened,

07:02:46.960 --> 07:02:53.040
but principally by Ella Runceter. It took her and them working together a long, long time,

07:02:53.040 --> 07:02:55.440
and there still isn't very much of it available as yet.

07:02:56.240 --> 07:03:03.440
Ebbing from him in her trim covert way she continued to retreat, and then, by degrees, was gone.

07:03:04.400 --> 07:03:10.480
At the matador, Joe called after her. I understand Jory did a good job materializing it,

07:03:11.280 --> 07:03:17.760
or regressing it just right, whatever it is he does. He listened, but the girl did not answer.

07:03:19.280 --> 07:03:24.080
Carefully carrying the spray can of Eubrick, Joe Chipp walked out to greet the evening traffic,

07:03:24.080 --> 07:03:28.640
searching for a cab. Under a street light he held up the spray can of Eubrick,

07:03:28.640 --> 07:03:29.920
read the printing on the label.

07:03:29.920 --> 07:03:37.520
I think her name is Myra Laney. Look on reverse side of container for address and phone number.

07:03:38.640 --> 07:03:45.360
Thanks, Joe said to the spray can. We are served by organic ghosts, he thought,

07:03:45.920 --> 07:03:49.840
who, speaking and writing, pass through this our new environment,

07:03:50.400 --> 07:03:56.720
watching wise physical ghosts from the full life world, elements of which have become for us

07:03:56.800 --> 07:04:01.600
invading but agreeable splinters of a substance that pulsates like a former heart.

07:04:02.560 --> 07:04:08.000
And of all of them, he thought, thanks to Glenn Runciter, in particular, the writer of

07:04:08.000 --> 07:04:15.120
instructions, labels, and notes, valuable notes. He raised his arm to slow to a grumpy halt,

07:04:15.120 --> 07:04:21.840
a passing 1936 Graham cab. 17.

07:04:22.720 --> 07:04:31.440
I am Eubick. Before the universe was, I am. I made the suns, I made the worlds,

07:04:31.440 --> 07:04:37.760
I created the lives and the places they inhabit. I move them here, I put them there,

07:04:37.760 --> 07:04:44.240
they go as I say, they do as I tell them. I am the word and my name is never spoken,

07:04:44.240 --> 07:04:51.120
the name which no one knows. I am called Eubick, but that is not my name. I am.

07:04:51.840 --> 07:04:53.440
I shall always be. 17.

07:04:56.160 --> 07:04:58.640
Glenn Runciter could not find the moratorium owner.

07:04:59.200 --> 07:05:04.640
Are you sure you don't know where he is? Runciter asked Miss Beeson, the moratorium owner's secretary.

07:05:04.640 --> 07:05:06.880
It's essential that I talk to Ella again.

07:05:06.880 --> 07:05:10.400
18. I'll have her brought out, Ms. Beeson said.

07:05:10.960 --> 07:05:16.640
You may use Office 4B. Please wait there, Mr. Runciter. I will have your wife for you in a

07:05:16.640 --> 07:05:18.960
very short time. Try to make yourself comfortable.

07:05:18.960 --> 07:05:25.840
19. Locating Office 4B, Runciter paced about restlessly. At last a moratorium attendant appeared,

07:05:25.840 --> 07:05:28.080
wheeling in Ella's casket on a hand truck.

07:05:28.080 --> 07:05:31.280
20. Sorry to keep you waiting, the attendant said.

07:05:31.280 --> 07:05:36.720
He began at once to set up the electronic communing mechanism, humming happily as he worked.

07:05:36.720 --> 07:05:41.040
In short order, the task was completed. The attendant checked the circuit one last time,

07:05:41.040 --> 07:05:44.320
knotted in satisfaction, then started to leave the office.

07:05:44.960 --> 07:05:49.520
This is for you, Runciter said, and handed him several fifty-cent pieces, which he had

07:05:49.520 --> 07:05:55.280
scrounged from his various pockets. I appreciate the rapidity with which you accomplished the job.

07:05:56.080 --> 07:06:01.360
Thank you, Mr. Runciter, the attendant said. He glanced at the coins, then frowned.

07:06:02.160 --> 07:06:08.560
What kind of money is this, he said. Runciter took a good long look at the fifty-cent pieces.

07:06:08.640 --> 07:06:12.400
20. He saw at once what the attendant meant.

07:06:12.400 --> 07:06:15.920
21. Very definitely the coins were not as they should be.

07:06:15.920 --> 07:06:22.560
Whose profile is this, he asked himself. Who's this on all three coins? Not the right person at all.

07:06:23.200 --> 07:06:26.880
And yet he's familiar. I know him.

07:06:26.880 --> 07:06:30.240
21. And then he recognized the profile.

07:06:30.240 --> 07:06:34.160
22. I wonder what this means, he asked himself.

07:06:34.160 --> 07:06:37.040
23. Strangest thing I've ever seen.

07:06:38.000 --> 07:06:44.720
Most things in life eventually can be explained, but... Joe Chip on a fifty-cent piece?

07:06:46.320 --> 07:06:49.120
It was the first Joe Chip money he had ever seen.

07:06:50.400 --> 07:06:55.520
He had an intuition, chillingly, that if he searched his pockets and his billfold,

07:06:55.520 --> 07:07:00.080
he would find more. This was just the beginning.

07:07:00.080 --> 07:07:10.800
21. This concludes the reading of UBIK by Philip K. Dick.

